<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS USUAL, YANKEES FEEL AT HOME IN INDIANS' PARK
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Laughter echoed from the other half of the New York
Yankees' clubhouse before tonight's game. ``Look at Knoblauch,''
David Cone said, pausing in his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch was doing an impression of his teammate Jim
Leyritz: a miniature Yankees jersey jammed into his waistband with
the fabric stretched tautly over his torso, a No. 13 taped on his
back, and he was bent forward, bat waggling. Leyritz watched, his
smile cockeyed, and Knoblauch cackled gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch and the rest of the Yankees are much more relaxed now
that they have resumed hitting, scoring and winning. Friday night
they pounded the Indians, 11-7, for their fourth consecutive
victory against Cleveland here this year and their 25th in 34
regular-season games at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill had a single, a double and a home run, and Bernie
Williams drove in three runs for the Yankees (24-14), who have 20
runs and 29 hits in their last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just pleased we were able to keep coming back at them,''
manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees placed shortstop Derek Jeter on the 15-day disabled
list with an abdominal strain and promoted the top prospect Alfonso
Soriano to play in his place. Soriano was used at third base in
April and was atrocious defensively, clearly uncomfortable playing
a position besides shortstop. Even while playing his natural
position Friday night, however, Soriano fumbled a couple of balls
anxiously before making plays and committing a throwing error that
led to three unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Soriano flew here from Rochester, N.Y. and did not share in the
Yankees' harrowing flight Thursday night. Bad weather kept their
flight on the ground in Newark for about three hours. And after
finally taking off and approaching the Cleveland area, the players
said, the plane circled repeatedly through lightning. ``I knew it
was bad when I saw the flight attendant start to panic,'' said
Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher.
</P>
<P>
   They landed with all but their psyches unscathed; this certainly
ranked among his worst flights ever, Posada said. And the weather
continued to haunt. The pitchers could not control the baseball.
Knoblauch drew a walk leading off the game, the first of 15 issued
by the teams.
</P>
<P>
   The walks led to many rallies and runs and an incredibly long
and slow game _ the first five innings lasted 2 hours 23 minutes _
and Knoblauch was often in the middle of what the Yankees' hitters
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knobby had some big at-bats, a couple of base hits,'' Torre
said. ``He's looked as comfortable as he has all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trailed, 2-1, in the top of the fifth inning, and
after Shane Spencer and Ricky Ledee reached second and third with
nobody out, Cleveland's Dave Burba struck out Scott Brosius and
retired Soriano on a grounder. Knoblauch fell behind, no balls and
two strikes, and the rally appeared finished.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch worked his way back against Burba, taking a ball,
fouling off a pitch, taking two more balls, fouling off three more
pitches, and on the 10th pitch of the at-bat, Burba walked
Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   If Burba was exhausted, there was good reason _ by the end of
Knoblauch's at-bat, he had thrown 76 pitches in less than four
innings. Only a few knockout blows were needed to finish him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really big, and it didn't surprise me,'' Torre said
of Knoblauch's lengthy at-bat. ``When he's fouling balls over our
dugout, you know he's waiting on the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, batting in the No. 2 slot again, followed Knoblauch's
walk with a three-run double. O'Neill doubled home Williams and
scored when Tino Martinez singled. Posada singled, finishing Burba;
the Yankees led, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees had more work to do. Wiping his nose with his
sleeve time and again, Andy Pettitte was miserable, and he allowed
four runs in the fourth, the last three on Manny Ramirez's homer.
Knoblauch singled home the go-ahead run against Scott Kamieniecki
in the fifth, however, and two batters later, O'Neill clubbed a
two-run homer. Ledee blistered a two-run homer in the sixth,
increasing the Yankees' lead to 11-7.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, who relieved Pettitte in the fifth and pitched 2
2/3 innings, improved his record to 4-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
