<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MONEY-ADVISORY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star will publish a two-part series, with
sidebars and graphics, on Sunday and Monday, May 21 and 22, about
police nationwide circumventing state laws in order to keep drug
money they seize.
</P>
<P>
   The stories, with a home slug of DRUG-MONEY, are available for
use by clients of The New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that while the stories are long, they are rich in
detail from cases around the country. For this reason, the stories
will have trim indicators, enabling clients to excise material of
less interest to readers in their region.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, The Star is offering a shorter version of the
DRUG-MONEY-I story, slugged DRUG-MONEY-SHORT.
</P>
<P>
   First-day package:
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MONEY-I Kansas City -- Local and state police nationwide
work with federal agencies to keep drug money they seize even
though many state laws clearly intend the money to go education or
other public funds. In fact, little-known provisions in most state
laws would block the way the police/federal partnership now works.
The police practice leads to aggressive searches and a loss of
civil liberties, critics say. By Karen Dillon. 3400 words.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MONEY-SHORT -- A shorter version of DRUG-MONEY-I. 1,500
words.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MONEY-SCHOOLS -- At least eight states want seized drug
money sent to public education. Others have other plans. But it
doesn't matter because police widely ignore the laws. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   Graphics: A graphic explaining how states want police to act and
what they actually do, plus a national map depicting states with
tough laws that are often being ignored by police.
</P>
<P>
   These are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   Second-day package:
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MONEY-II Kansas City -- A few states have tried
unsuccessfully to prohibit police from circumventing their own
laws, making it clear the solution must come from Washington. But
the Justice Department won't address the problem and Congress just
lost its best chance in a decade. By Karen Dillon. (2600 words).
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MONEY-REFORM -- A news analysis: The federal forfeiture
reform law passed by Congress in April does not match its
advertising. (1500 words).
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MONEY-FEDS -- It may be the police who evade their state
laws, but it's the Justice Department that invented the system
allowing that evasion and taught police how to use it. (1000
words).
</P>
<P>
   Graphic: A diagram showing how the Justice Department has
battled Congress since 1984 over the police/federal partnership --
and won.
</P>
<P>
   This is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.
</P>
</TEXT>
