<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER WEST FINALS, IS IT A BREEZE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ There is an unofficial movement afoot to
drop the ``Western Conference'' label from the Western Conference
Finals that open today at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers had the NBA's best record this season,
67-15. The Portland Trail Blazers were second best, at 59-23. And
the watered-down East is an afterthought, so the argument goes;
this series is the de facto finals.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson doesn't endorse that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, these have been the two best teams in basketball this
season, there's no doubt about that,'' Jackson said, ``but will
they be the two best teams all the way through this? You don't
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's a funny thing, that you'll see in retrospect
going back in a championship year, that `X' team played the best
series against the championship team way back when. And they didn't
get challenged all the way through the rest of them. Or maybe
Sacramento will have played the best series against us if we were
able to go on and by good fortune win a championship. And would
people look back and say, `Hey, the best series they had was
Sacramento'? So what does that mean? . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you get to the finals against any of the teams that are
left out there in the East, they're going to provide the challenge
for you at that time. So it's not like whoever wins the West is a
shoo-in. Althoughby all intents and purposes, that's what people
want to make of it, that's not the reality of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Games coaches play: Jackson was dismissive when asked if he
was concerned about Portland coach Mike Dunleavy's assertion that
Shaquille O'Neal got away with illegal defense 57 times in the
Phoenix series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that Mike's concerned about the officiating,''
Jackson said wryly, ``and that Mike's concerned about counting
illegal defenses. That bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a coaching ploy to get the officials' attention?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got to play a series in hopes that the officiating
is in your favor or sees things your way, then I think we've
misconstrued what the game's all about,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy, meanwhile, took umbrage at assertions that the Lakers
were the underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's falling for that,'' Dunleavy said. ``I mean, they won
67 games. They're going to have two first-team All-NBA players in
Shaq and Kobe. . . . They're the favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Defensive: At times, this series might well resemble an
Eastern Conference duel, a la Miami and New York. The Lakers scored
100.8 points a game this season but only 89.0 against Portland. The
Blazers averaged 97.5 this season but just 89.8 against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams are very good defensive teams,'' Ron Harper said.
``They are a very great defensive team. They've got speed, size and
they all know how to use the team thing, too. I think we're a good
defensive team because we've got Shaq behind us. Hard not be a good
defensive team when you've got Shaq behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper seemed unconcerned about Portland's speed and
athleticism, even though the Lakers had trouble containing the
speed and athleticism of the Kings and Suns in the prior two
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Harper said, ``they're both at home right now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Film school: A new playoff round has brought a new intrigue
to the Lakers' film sessions. Jackson had been splicing scenes from
``American History X'' between basketball sequences. He's now using
``The Green Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just getting started, so I can't really give you a
summary of what's going on right now,'' Derek Fisher said. ``But
hopefully as this postseason continues, I'll be able to give you
more insight into what's going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
