<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ROLL A SEVEN, SENDING THE SERIES TO MIAMI FOR A FINAL GAME
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Somewhere along a seemingly doomed path, the New York
Knicks found healing powers from their pride to recover from an
18-point second-quarter deficit Friday night and extend their
second-round series with the Miami Heat to a deciding Game 7 Sunday
by taking Game 6, 72-70.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston, fouled by Dan Majerle, made two free throws with
17.6 seconds left to pull the Knicks ahead at last. And when
Miami's Anthony Carter missed a 3-pointer just before the final
buzzer, the Knicks had found a way to send the series back to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with elimination, and down by 18 points in the first half,
the Knicks managed to unearth the kind of desperate attitude that
served them so well in their improbable run to the finals last
season. Now, they have set themselves up to poke a hole in the
hearts of the Heat once more and give coach Pat Riley yet another
Knicks demon to jolt him from his sleep. The possibility must make
him shudder just a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the Knicks have arrived in Miami for a
series-deciding game and left strutting to the next round. Now, the
pressure is on a Heat team Riley has threatened to dismantle if
they cannot get by their playoff ghosts. Although neither team has
come up with back-to-back victories in two years of playoff games,
the Knicks are often at their best when they can manufacture an
us-against-the-world mentality. And Game 7 in Miami Sunday
afternoon is the perfect setting to start building an edge that has
been missing in the Knicks at times this season.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Game 6, Houston admitted that he had detected a
missing ingredient in his team so far in their playoff run: hunger.
After last year's finals path carved against the odds by the
Knicks, this team has been in constant search of something to prove
this season, something to prod their pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you constantly have to prove yourself in this
league,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said before the game. ``I don't care
if it's a player, a coach or management. If it's true that we don't
think we have anything to prove _ and I don't believe that's the
case _ then it's a critical mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of urgency that should have motivated the Knicks was
not horribly apparent as the more aggressive and far crisper Heat
surged out to a shocking 43-25 lead with two minutes left in the
second quarter. During one stretch, the Knicks were 2 for 14
shooting under the pressure the Heat applied on defense. To make it
worse, there were plays like this: On a missed jumper by Carter,
the bulky Clarence Weatherspoon leaped above three Knicks and
retrieved the rebound. Then he was fouled.
</P>
<P>
   The boos quickly came down in buckets. When the Knicks closed
the score to within 45-30 at the half, they received a handful of
sarcastic cheers. As the Knicks exited at halftime, they were
shooting 27.5 percent and had turned the ball over nine times. The
Heat, led by Mourning's 13 points, were hitting only 34.3 percent
but had just three turnovers. They also were rewarded for their
assertiveness with 21 free-throw attempts; the Knicks had just
seven.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, Chris Childs' pre-game guarantee seemed both
ridiculous and another sign of the arrogance that has made the
Knicks seem dangerously overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee a win,'' Childs boasted in the locker room an hour
before tip-off. ``Y'all go out and book your flight to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat made no such grandiose statements. They just went out
and played hard with as few mistakes as possible. Hardaway and then
Carter broke down the Knicks' guards by dribbling into the paint,
sucking a slow-reacting defense inside and then hitting the open
man for uncontested jumpers. Mourning bulled his way into the paint
against Patrick Ewing and either scored or took a trip to the
free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Knicks turned the ball over, the Heat ran out on
the break and finished strong. The Knicks just kept backing down.
And for once, rebounding was not an issue. It was the Knicks'
panicked execution in the face of the Heat's defense. A harried
Houston (3 for 9) continued to be invisible, while Latrell Sprewell
(2 for 6) rushed his shots. Once again, the bench play of Marcus
Camby and Kurt Thomas was less than spectacular. The two combined
for two points and five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   With so much going wrong, Van Gundy needed a halftime speech to
resurrect his team's hopes. They weren't out of it. A 15-point lead
wasn't insurmountable even at their slow offensive pace.
</P>
<P>
   And in an instant, a supercharged group of Knicks started
flaunting their talent edge over the Heat. Using dribble
penetration by Charlie Ward to create open shots for Houston and
seizing the moment off a series of Heat misses from the perimeter,
the Knicks went on a blistering 11-2 run to close to within 47-41
with nine minutes left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game again. Suddenly, the Heat's 18-point
second-quarter lead was down to a manageable margin. A very sharp
Houston was not only scoring but making plays for his teammates by
passing off the drive. An energized Sprewell scored four straight
points to cut the Heat's lead to 50-45.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams then blew opportunities with missed free throws and
turnovers. Sprewell rushed several shots that went awry, Ewing
missed two jumpers, but the Knicks did cut the Heat's lead to four
points before they allowed Carter to hit a gutsy 3-pointer at the
shot-clock buzzer with 30 seconds left in the third. After a jumper
by Houston, the Knicks were down, 58-53, entering the fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
