<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-BABY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR AND HIS WIFE HAVE A NEW SON, THEIR 4TH CHILD
</HEADLINE>
  By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Cherie Blair, 45, the wife of Prime Minister Tony
Blair, 47, gave birth to a baby boy at a London hospital early
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both mother and baby are doing well,'' a 10 Downing Street
spokesman said in a brief statement. ``Both the prime minister and
Mrs. Blair are delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Blair went to the Chelsea and Westminster Hospital on
Friday morning, and Mr. Blair followed in the late afternoon. There
was no word of a name for the baby, who due date was May 24.
</P>
<P>
   The baby is the couple's fourth child and the first to be born
to a sitting prime minister in 152 years. Their other children are
Euan, 16, Nicky, 14, and Kathryn, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Blair, a prominent employment rights lawyer, worked up
until the last few days, appearing on Tuesday in the High Court to
argue a case for the Trade Unions Congress that challenged the way
Mr. Blair's government has introduced parental leave benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, modeled on a European Union directive, gives
parents the right to take 13 weeks off during the first five years
of their child's life, but the Blair government has restricted the
benefit to parents of children born after Dec. 15, 1999. Mrs.
Blair, who practices under her unmarried name, Cherie Booth, told
the justices that the limit unlawfully excluded 2.7 million people
who were already parents of children under 5.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of parental leave became an issue for the Blairs when
she noted in a speech to a legal group in London the experience of
the Finnish prime minister, Paavo Lipponen, 59, who took a week out
of the office to spend with his newborn daughter in March. Mrs.
Blair pointedly encouraged the ``widespread adoption'' of
Lipponen's ``fine example.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention turned to the prime minister, who let his decision on
how he would react be known in an interview in last Sunday's New
York Times Magazine. ``I know what people want me to say,'' he
said, ``but the truth is if I went away and stopped taking calls or
having any conversations, it just wouldn't be real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take more time off,'' he said. ``I'll try to cut down on
official things. You've got to have some common sense about it _
you want to spend more time with your baby, but you don't give up
the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
