<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DC UNITED HAVING PROBLEMS; HERNANDEZ SET FOR DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PASADENA, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Galaxy might have its hands
full integrating newly acquired Mexican striker Luis Hernandez
while at the same time adjusting to a new lineup after losing three
starters _ Joey Franchino, Roy Myers and Clint Mathis _ to make
room for ``El Matador.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's nothing in comparison to the disaster three-time MLS
champion D.C. United is going through.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer's proud dynasty has taken a number of
punishing blows this season. A couple more big punches could send
United sprawling to the canvas for good.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the focus will certainly be on Hernandez's MLS
debut when the Galaxy (5-0-5) plays host to United tonight at the
Rose Bowl, United (2-8-1), with the worst record in the MLS, needs
a victory like a heart needs a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final third, we've not executed from day one,'' United
coach Thomas Rongen said. ``If we can get somebody who's willing to
step up and put the ball in the back of the net, we're looking at a
completely different scenario right now. That will come.''
</P>
<P>
   United hasn't played poorly, despite losing striker Roy Lassiter
to Miami as well as dealing with nagging injuries. But it seems a
wealth of good fortune in the past has suddenly turned. Even in
games in which it has looked dominant, it ends up walking away with
nothing to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting tired of it,'' United defender Jeff Agoos said.
``I would love to play absolutely poorly and win a game. We've been
playing great for eight or nine games, but it hasn't meant anything
on the scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid isn't convinced that
United's dynasty is through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their record is a surprise, but if you look at their games,
the results are really unfortunate,'' Schmid said. ``I think the
ball is bouncing against them a bit, but by no means do I
underestimate them as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not all of a sudden a bad team. They're a good team
going through a bad patch, which is a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take a few more beatings to convince Galaxy defender
Danny Pena that United is a team in danger of missing the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to count them out,'' Pena said. ``I still think
at the end of the day they're going to be exactly where they want
to be. It's going to take at least three more losses to convince me
they're in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the (East) conference isn't really an issue for them.
If they can get into the playoffs and gain some momentum, you're
going to see what you saw last year, which is the dominant team
they have been since day one.''
</P>
<P>
   United defeated the Galaxy 2-0 in November to claim their third
MLS title. In their only meeting earlier this year at RFK Stadium,
the Galaxy returned the favor with a 4-0 thumping, the worst loss
in United history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they want to come out and return some favors,''
Schmid said. ``I expect them to be highly attentive to marking some
of our guys tightly. I would not be surprised if the game is very
physical in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy officials have looked forward to this meeting with United
from day one, hoping to lure more fans by handing out a free cap
for tonight's match. Adding Hernandez to the mix adds a welcomed
boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes for an even grandeur event,'' Schmid said.
``This is what you become a professional athlete for, to play in
these kind of events. There will be a buzz going into this game,
maybe the biggest we have have had in a few years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
