<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCAM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY FINED FOR FAILING TO DELIVER ON ITS PROMISE OF FREE AIRLINE
TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY TONY RIZZO, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Branson company that falsely promised free
airline tickets as part of a travel promotion will pay $30,000 to
Johnson County, Kan., residents, according to a court settlement
reached Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Surrey Vacation Resorts Inc. also will pay a $10,000 civil
penalty and $7,500 in investigative costs, under terms of the
agreement filed in Johnson County District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged that customers reached by telephone were
promised four free tickets for attending a 90-minute presentation
at the company's Overland Park, Kan., office.
</P>
<P>
   One of those called was Tyler Garretson, an assistant district
attorney who handles consumer fraud cases.
</P>
<P>
   Garretson and others were told that the airline ticket offer
came with ``no strings attached,'' according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tickets, however, people who attended the
presentation received a piece of paper labeled as a ``Fly America''
vacation voucher.
</P>
<P>
   When the vouchers were mailed to an address supplied by the
company, a brochure was mailed back listing prices for hotel rooms
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers had to book minimum five- or 10-day stays at hotels
with prices ranging from $69 to $425 per night to get their airline
tickets, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged that failing to deliver the free tickets as
promised violated the Kansas Consumer Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the subsequent investigation, the Johnson County district
attorney's office found 60 individuals or couples who said they
were promised, but did not receive, the four free airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the $30,000 settlement Friday, each of those
60 customers will receive $500.
</P>
<P>
   The company also must give copies of its sales pitches to the
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The company's local attorney, Scott Gyllenborg, who signed the
agreement, declined to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman did not respond to a telephone message left
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
