<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MAKE LATE MAGIC AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Los Angeles Dodgers are getting hits in situations
they didn't last year. They're jumping on opponents' mistakes, and
the bullpen is holding leads.
</P>
<P>
   So many things are different about the Dodgers now than they
were, and that Mark Kotsay's ball stayed in Pro Player Stadium
instead of going out might say the most. Things are certainly going
the Dodgers' way.
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight game, the Dodgers rallied from a deficit
in the eighth inning to win, and for the third time, Jeff Shaw
closed it out as the Dodgers beat the Florida Marlins 5-3 Friday in
the opener of a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre delivered the big hit, a two-run
double in the eighth to transform a 3-2 deficit into a 4-3 lead.
Chad Kreuter added an RBI single as the Dodgers won for the fifth
time in six games. They are 5-4 with two games remaining on a
difficult four-city road trip that brings an end to a torturous
beginning of the season in which the Dodgers were rarely home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a momentum-turner right there,'' Shaw said. ``We didn't
seem to get the big hit last year like we are now. Adrian had the
big one. The big hit is coming in the sixth, seventh, eighth inning
every night. And it's a different guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre's double provided the lead, but there were some skipped
heartbeats in the bottom of the inning when the Marlins had two
runners in scoring position and Mark Kotsay was batting.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kotsay hit Shaw's first pitch deep to right field, only to
have Shawn Green catch it a step in front of the fence to end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was gone,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who also doubled in the fourth inning, had similar
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   `Man, it was freakin' me out because I thought it was going to
go out,'' Beltre said. ``That's what I told Shawn Green after (the
game) when I saw him. I thought it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers continue to win games when the bullpen
keeps them close and the offense jumps on a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   After starter Chan Ho Park allowed three runs in six solid
innings, Matt Herges (2-0) held the Dodgers close for an inning
before they could rally off reliever Braden Looper (0-1). Gary
Sheffield started the inning with a double, Green was intentionally
walked and Karros grounded to third to move the runners into
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre thought the Marlins would intentionally walk him, but
Looper pitched and Beltre slammed a double high off the left-center
field fence to give the Dodgers the lead. They went on to win after
trailing entering the eighth inning for the fifth time in 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a clutch hitter,'' Sheffield said. ``A lot of teams
forget about him and guys pitch around (Karros) and Shawn Green and
face him. The whole team respects each other. We know who our
Golden Boy is. He's the future. You have to take care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Set-up man Terry Adams is apparently over the problem that
plagued him during his first few outings of the road trip, and is
pitching well in place of injured set-up man Mike Fetters.
</P>
<P>
   Adams pitched a scoreless eighth, though it wasn't without a
threat. Preston Wilson and David Berg singled with two outs, but
Brant Brown popped out to third. Shaw then recorded his 11th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the feeling is, especially with the bullpen, as long
as we stay close, we're going to get to them,'' Johnson said.
``Jeff Shaw, he's a consummate professional. He's going to make
them hit his pitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
