<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GASOLINE PRICES IN KC AHEAD OF THE NATIONAL AVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 PRICES -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE EVERLY, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, _ Mo. For the first time, many Kansas City service
stations are posting prices of $1.50 or more for a gallon of
unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, gasoline prices are up again, with the national average
climbing to $1.49 for unleaded. And for once the Midwest, often the
home of the country's cheapest gasoline, is ahead of that average.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of months ago, in March, gasoline prices were on
the way down, thanks to the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting
Countries' agreeing to produce more crude oil. Randall Espeland
recalls breathing a sigh of relief when he heard that news.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday the Kansas City resident could hardly believe the
$1.50 sign at an area gas station. ``I don't know what happened,''
he said. ``But this is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   So volatile have gasoline prices become recently that it's hard
to keep track. Earlier this week, AAA Automobile Club of Missouri
completed its survey of Kansas City area prices, and on Friday it
reported an average price at $1.42 a gallon for unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   But by Friday morning, area service stations had raised prices
to at least $1.50. That's more than gas cost during the oil embargo
in the early 1980s or during the 1991 Persian Gulf War, when
unleaded hit $1.25. The previous high this year was $1.46 in March.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation, the prices are not historically high.
Nevertheless, motorists are getting sticker shock. And for once the
Midwest isn't relatively well-off.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Energy Information Administration this week said the
average price for several Midwestern states was $1.50 a gallon.
That made it the second-most-expensive region in the agency's
survey. Typically, the Midwest has had some of the cheaper gas in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast, where taxes are higher and Californians must use
cleaner-burning gas that costs more, was the only region where
prices topped those in the Midwest. Motorists there paid an average
$1.60 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The usual suspects for higher gasoline prices are being blamed:
supply and demand. OPEC indicated this week that it had no
intention of further increasing oil production. Crude oil prices
have hovered at $30 a barrel, near their March highs, and demand
has increased as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old story,'' said Karen DesJarlais, a
spokeswoman for the Phillips Petroleum Co. in Bartlesville, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   John Felmy, director of policy analysis for the American
Petroleum Institute in Washington, said problems also had been
caused by a change in the formula for cleaner-burning fuel _ such
as that used in St. Louis _ that takes effect in June. The
situation in the Midwest has been aggravated by temporary outages
at some refineries.
</P>
<P>
   But is more afoot? Gasoline stockpiles are down about 7 percent
from a year ago, making prices sensitive to reports that supplies
are tight or demand is up.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Right, a spokesman for the Missouri AAA, said the tighter
supply had been caused in part by ``capacity utilization'' _ the
percentage of refinery capacity used to produce gasoline _ being
down from a year ago. Felmy, however, said the percentage figures
were misleading and that more gasoline was being produced than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is also evidence that refineries are boosting profit
margins, particularly in the Midwest. Paul Ting, an analyst for
Salomon Smith Barney, said making gasoline had become more
profitable for U.S. refineries.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true for refineries in the Midwest that are
making $5 a barrel more than they were in the second quarter of
last year, he said. A barrel contains 42 gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   And with demand expected to increase to 130,000 barrels a day
this summer, consumers will hardly be in a position to bargain. The
use of gasoline this summer is expected to set a record, according
to the Energy Information Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency is forecasting ``extraordinarily'' tight
supplies until September, or when summer vacations are wrapped up,
so further price spikes are likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they got it and we want it, they'll charge what the market
will pay,'' said Todd Spencer, executive vice president of the
Owner-Operator Independent Drivers Association in Grain Valley.
``This is going to go on for awhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0817 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ID-KAN &LR;      05-20 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ID-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY KEVIN MURPHY, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 FAKE CONGRESS LOOKS INTO PROBLEM OF FAKE IDs SOLD ON WEB   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Getting a driver's license from the state of
Florida was easy for Susan Collins. So was securing a U.S. Army
Reserves identification card and a Boston University student ID.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins is a U.S. senator from Maine, not from Florida. She
isn't in the reserves and never attended Boston University. Collins
got the bogus credentials off the Internet to prove a point:
Anybody can do it and more people are doing it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   A five-month investigation by Collins' Senate staff uncovered
some 60 Web sites that either sell fake documents or the kits to
make them. Three sites _ including fakeidzone.com, traced to a
Lawrence man _ were used to illustrate how the system works.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations held a
hearing Friday on fake documents, which senators and witnesses said
are a disturbing byproduct of the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a growing and vastly underpublicized problem,'' said Sen.
Daniel Akaka, a Hawaii Democrat and subcommittee member. ``The
number of Web sites for making false IDs and documents is really
striking.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the documents reproduced using Internet capability and
computer technology include passports, green cards, bank loan
authorizations, Social Security cards, diplomas, birth certificates
and press credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who is chairwoman of the subcommittee, said she is most
concerned about how easy it is to create identifications that
falsely present someone as a police officer, FBI agent or other
government official.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wide-scale availability of false identifications and
credentials on the Internet poses a serious new threat to
government and the integrity of government operations,'' Collins
said. ``I'm more convinced than ever that we need a crackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins would like to pass a law that clearly makes it illegal
to sell fake identification kits, just as it is illegal to sell and
use IDs themselves for unauthorized purposes. Current laws are
being skirted by promoting the IDs as ``novelty'' items, Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   States have various laws on false identifications and are having
a hard time keeping up with methods people can use to re-create
documents, said David C. Myers, identification fraud coordinator
for the Florida Department of Business and Professional Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said 30 percent of the fake IDs that authorities now see
in Florida are produced on the Internet, up from 5 percent last
year and 1 percent two years ago. Some sites selling IDs get 10,000
inquiries a day and can generate $1 million in sales annually, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   K. Lee Blalack II, chief counsel and staff director of the
Collins subcommittee, testified Friday that it is almost impossible
to tell fake documents from real ones in many cases and that ``some
of these sites offer phony documents of a shockingly high
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Blalack and his staff issued 11 subpoenas for documents and
depositions and interviewed 40 witnesses. Among people subpoenaed
was Tim Catron of Lawrence, who Blalack said had the Web site
called fakeidzone.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site advertisement tried to sell kits to make ``novelty
IDs,'' such as driver's licenses, birth certificates, college
transcripts, diplomas and Social Security cards. Disks were
available for $19.95 on the site, which Blalack said is now closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide you with templates and step-by-step instructions on
what you need to create fake IDs so real you could fool your own
mother,'' the ad said.
</P>
<P>
   Catron declined to give a deposition to the committee on the
grounds it might incriminate him, Blalack said. Catron was not
accused of a crime by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Catron wouldn't comment when reached by a reporter. His lawyer,
Keith White of Lawrence, also wouldn't comment but said he is not
aware of any ongoing investigation of Catron by authorities and
that he has not been charged with any related offense.
</P>
<P>
   Blalack said billing records obtained by the committee found
that Catron received 652 orders and generated more than $12,000 in
revenue during a two-month period in late 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Blalack said Catron attempted to disguise the real location of
his Web site by registering it to an address and phone number in
the Philippines and an e-mail address originating in another small
country in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Payments were directed instead to an address in Pittsburg, Kan.,
and Catron was finally served with a subpoena by U.S. marshals in
Lawrence, Blalack said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Catron's tactics...allowed him to market his products to a
wide audience with very little overhead cost and minimal risk of
criminal exposure,'' Blalack said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian L. Stafford, director of the U.S. Secret Service, said use
of false identifications to open bank accounts, pass checks, get
credit cards and obtain loans is rising rapidly and creating a
major challenge for his agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``False identification provides criminals with the anonymity
needed to perpetuate a myriad of fraud schemes,'' Stafford told the
subcommittee. Stafford and Myers said better fraud identification
training and strict enforcement of laws are two ways to address the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Williams, U.S. attorney for the Kansas District, said a
state and federal task force is being formed to study use of the
Internet for illegal purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
