<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BARK-KAN &LR;      05-20 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGS  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN  
 MU VETERINARIAN ENVISIONS A RONALD MCDONALD-tYPE HOUSE FOR SICK (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY LEE HILL KAVANAUGH, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ ``Big Dog,'' a German shepherd mix, strides into
the veterinary school. Her owner, Ed Shipman, reaches down and
gives Big Dog an affectionate rub on her belly, then a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dog, 13, smiles back in her doggy way, her pink tongue
hanging out. She is happy.
</P>
<P>
   But Big Dog has no idea how sick she is.
</P>
<P>
   She has cancer. Shipman and his wife, Anita, have driven more
than two hours from Kansas City to bring Big Dog to the College of
Veterinary Medicine at the University of Missouri-Columbia. Their
hope is that modern medical procedures like radiation and
chemotherapy might eradicate the cancer in Big Dog's body. Or at
least give them a little more time together.
</P>
<P>
   Time is precious to people whose pets are fighting serious
illness.
</P>
<P>
   But driving hours to and from Columbia to meet the needs of an
ailing pet can add more stress to an already difficult time. The
option of spending the night while a pet recovers from a medical
procedure can be nearly impossible if there is a football game or a
convention filling hotel rooms. And many hotels do not permit pets
at all.
</P>
<P>
   But pet owners may have another option if an idea from
veterinarian//oncologist Carolyn Henry becomes a reality. Barkley
House is envisioned as a homey place located within steps of the
veterinary school, where pets and their owners could stay during
treatments, especially radiation treatments that often require
daily doses.
</P>
<P>
   The house would be a Ronald McDonald-style home, perhaps even a
hospice center where dying pets and owners could visit together one
last time in privacy.
</P>
<P>
   To many people, pets are family, and owners will help them as
much as possible. A typical treatment regimen for cancer costs
between $1,200 and $2,200. But sometimes, costs for a cancer
treatment are met by anonymous donors or waived if the pet is
participating in a clinical trial to help animals and perhaps even
humans.
</P>
<P>
   Although pets do not suffer as much as people from the side
effects of chemotherapy and radiation treatments, they do suffer
anxiety when their owners are not nearby. That's why Barkley House
is needed, Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If owners could stay with their pets throughout the process,
both the pets and the owners would do better in the treatments,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are people who view this as extravagant. I tell
people if you go down to the lake and spend $20,000 on a boat
because it makes you happy, why couldn't someone else spend money
on a pet that makes them happy every day?''
</P>
<P>
   The idea came to Henry in December, after she heard about a
similar house and a favorite patient died: an 8-year-old Great
Pyrenees, weighing 155 pounds and named Barkley. His owner, Sally
Truscheit of Kansas City, drove Barkley to the veterinary clinic in
Columbia for most of his treatments, but one month she broke her
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, I was able to get a friend to take him'' to Columbia,
Truscheit said. ``It was such a comfort to talk with others in the
waiting room there, and learn that there are all these other people
going through the same thing. It was nice to be around people who
understand what you feel, that yes, you love this dog and you'll do
whatever it takes to make them feel better or more comfortable.
Being with others helped with the grief process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barkley lived for almost a year instead of dying in a few
weeks because of his treatments. I loved him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates to create Barkley House approach $250,000 to find the
property and build the house. But just the mention of the idea has
already garnered more than $11,000 in donations from pet lovers.
Although the veterinary school itself is not sponsoring the house,
the school has endorsed it.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 12,000 animals were treated at the school.
Owners who must leave their pets are called twice daily with
medical updates. Veterinarians also are compassionate with owners'
grief and conscientious of a pet's quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to talk with owners as much as possible, especially
with those whose pets die,'' Henry said. ``But sometimes we get too
busy to talk as much as we'd like. If there was a place for owners
to stay with their animals, they'd be around others who are also
going through the same grief of helping a terminally ill pet.
They'd be around people who understand and who don't judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley House would not be the first boarding house for sick
pets. In Pullman, Wash., Carmel Travis founded Lucas House in
September. She turned one floor of her house into four units where
pets can stay with their owners at night. During the day, the pets
receive medical care at the Washington State University Veterinary
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up with the idea based on what I would have wanted if I
were going through this,'' said Travis, whose dog Lucas died but
was treated near her home. ``I've been hoping the concept would
catch on around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis said she didn't know of any other homes yet, but there
are several teaching veterinary hospitals around the country. The
need is there.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Columbia, another family arrives at the veterinary
school after driving three hours from St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy'' bounces into the waiting room, her four paws clicking
on the linoleum floor. She is a 10-year-old cocker spaniel, a
fluffball of orange curls and brown liquid eyes. A wagging stub of
a tail makes her whole body wiggle, and her people, the Nold
family, smile from ear to ear.
</P>
<P>
   But Sandy is sick. She has lung cancer. Thursday she received
her third chemotherapy dose. So far, her cancer treatment is
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was first diagnosed by her home vet, they told me
she'd live maybe two weeks,'' said Jane Nold, a nurse. ``The cancer
has spread to her lymph nodes but she's doing excellently.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy insists on kissing Jane Nold and her husband, Greg, as
Jane talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they treat Sandy as if she's my child instead of a
dog,'' Nold said. ``Everyone at work thought we were crazy for
spending money to treat her. I just decided she was worth more than
my kitchen floor that we were going to buy. The driving does get
hard because we have to stop a lot to let her go to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``But seeing her now, here, as she jumps around, this is a treat
for us. Every day that we have together is a gift. When she chases
a squirrel, or jumps after a ball, I never dreamed she could bounce
back from surgery so quickly. She's not in any pain. She eats well.
Yeah, we may be doing this treatment for us, but the quality of
life for Sandy is worth it too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's given a lot to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have her around a little longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
