<SLUG> BC-HERO-KID-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV TIPS HELP GIRL SAVE LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Who says TV is bad for your health?
</P>
<P>
   Eight-year-old Francesca Valencia learned the Heimlich maneuver
from a cartoon show, just in time to save a friend who was choking
on a jawbreaker that got stuck in her throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so grateful for that show being on,'' the hero's mother,
Elena Valencia, said Friday. ``I don't think my child would have
known about that had she not seen it on TV. I can appreciate the
fact that there are good programs out there that teach the children
as well as entertain them.''
</P>
<P>
   It all happened Monday when a group of kids were playing
handball and sucking on jawbreakers in front of Jessenia Lopez's
home. A piece of the hard candy suddenly slipped down the child's
throat. The Fremont Elementary School third-grader couldn't talk,
couldn't breathe - and thought she was going to die.
</P>
<P>
   As several girls ran for help, Francesca remained calm and
thought back to a cartoon on which a character did the Heimlich
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Six quick pumps of Jessenia's abdomen forced a gnarled
jawbreaker out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for her, I'd probably be dead,'' Jessenia said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mom also hailed the third-grader as a hero for the save.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other words to say but: It's amazing,'' said
Jessenia's mother, Yvette Lopez, 34. ``We praised Francesca, and
wonder how she was able to stay there and not panic. We ran out
there, and we didn't know what we were going to do. She's
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters gave Francesca an atta-girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite amazing,'' said Los Angeles Fire Department
spokesman Bob Collis. ``It's unusual for someone that young to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Francesca brushes aside the praise, and instead casually walks
through her grace-under-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing on the corner, and she started choking, and I
ran up behind her, grabbed her, and did Heimlich on her,'' said
Francesca, who herself is barred from sucking on jawbreakers due to
a filling.
</P>
<P>
   She learned the Heimlich from an episode of the television
cartoon ``Hey Arnold,'' in which a character with all the bad luck
gets a hot dog stuck in his throat.
</P>
<P>
   In the cartoon, a friend reads about the Heimlich maneuver - Dr.
H.J. Heimlich's emergency technique involving short thrusts against
the abdomen just below the rib cage, forcing air up the windpipe to
dislodge an object stuck in the throat - and helps his friend. It
may have been funny in the cartoon when the hot dog shot out of the
character's mouth, but for Francesca, the horrific event was all
too real. Afterward, she thanked her guardian angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking that maybe if it doesn't work, she's not going
to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessenia, too, is shaken by the incident. She vowed never to
suck on jawbreakers again, and thanked her friend for saving her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that she saved me, and that she was there, and that
she thought of it,'' Jessenia said.
</P>
<P>
   Mom, meanwhile, realizes that maybe it wasn't such a good idea
to get jawbreakers just before the kids went out to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was against my better judgment,'' she said. ``But all the
kids wanted them, and I go and get change, and I gave quarters to
all the kids. Then 10 minutes later, she's choking on a jawbreaker
at home. We were so shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
