<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CLAIM NEEDED LEFTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After three months of looking the Los Angeles Dodgers
found a situational lefty for their bullpen. How long he lasts,
however, is the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The club claimed lefty Trever Miller off waivers from the
Philadelphia Phillies on Friday. He will join the Dodgers when the
club returns to Los Angeles to open a three-game series against
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a guy who can get left-handers out and he's had some
success,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``He should
complement our bullpen. We've been looking for a left-hander since
spring training, really. Hopefully, he's the answer''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will be Miller's fourth major-league team (Phillies,
Houston, Detroit), and he'll try to fill the situational-lefty
void. Lefties are hitting .258 (46 for 178) against Miller in his
four-year career and they were batting .261 (6 for 23) this season.
</P>
<P>
   But during the past three seasons, Miller was slightly better.
Lefties hit .228 with three homers and 19 RBI in 316 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (manager) Davey (Johnson) would use him against some
tough left-handers,'' Malone said. ``We like the guy and we've been
searching hard for one.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 26, was 0-0 with an 8.36 ERA in 14 games for the
Phillies before being placed on waivers and became expendable when
Jeff Brantley was activated. The Dodgers are pinning their hopes on
more consistency from Miller since he didn't allow a run in 10 of
his appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers paid $25,000 to acquire Mille and will pay the
prorated portion of the $280,000 he'll make this season.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Miller on the 40-man roster, the Dodgers
transferred ailing right-handed reliever Gregg Olson from the
15-day to the 60-day disabled list, retroactive to April 9.
</P>
<P>
   When Miller is activated Monday, it's likely lefty Onan Masaoka
will be sent to Triple-A Albuquerque if the Dodgers can't work out
a trade to ease the logjam of right-handers in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has spoken repeatedly with the Cubs about dealing one of
L.A.'s right-handed relievers to Chicago, but so far a match hasn't
been found. Meanwhile, Johnson spoke with Masaoka about better
understanding the type of pitcher the 22-year-old needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to use his legs, come over the top a little more,''
Johnson said. ``I don't want him throwing darts and getting by. I
want him to be the complete pitcher he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Investigation presses on: While the commissioner's office
continued its investigation into Tuesday's fight between the
Dodgers and fans at Wrigley Field, the players' association is
doing its own fact-finding in preparation of appeals to possible,
if not imminent, suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Several representatives from the players' association met with
numerous Dodgers to talk about what they saw during the
altercation. Many baseball and Dodgers officials believe heavy
fines and suspensions are coming for catcher Chad Kreuter and
potentially bullpen coach Rick Dempsey for their roles in the
melee. Many other Dodgers are expected to be fined, and more
suspensions are possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy Alderson (executive vice president of baseball
operations) already has spoken out and made it seem that's he's
going to do that,'' said Phil Bradley, special assistant to the
executive director for the players' association. ``That's all we
can do (is gather facts). You're dealing with (potential) civil
lawsuits from the fans and discipline from the commissioner's
office.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Elster delayed? Because of bad weather, the Dodgers didn't
get to their hotel in Florida until 3 a.m., so they canceled a
simulated game in which shortstop Kevin Elster was supposed to test
his right groin.
</P>
<P>
   Elster was to bat against Orel Hershiser, play the field and run
the bases. Instead, he just ran the bases and reported no problem.
The plan is to have Elster participate in the simulated game today
and be activated Sunday. Shortstop Alex Cora is expected to be sent
to Triple-A Albuquerque when Elster's ready.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally: Tom Lasorda, Dodgers senior vice president and
U.S. Olympic coach, was in the clubhouse before the game with
former Dodgers executive Ralph Avila, who was suspended from
baseball for one year for his dealings in the underage signing of
Adrian Beltre. Avila is retired, but if he returns to baseball he
must first serve his suspension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
