<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKSON BACK ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Add Jason Dickson to the growing list of
starting pitchers knocked out of the Anaheim Angels rotation
because of injury. Dickson, who made one start after missing two
weeks with a strained left hip flexor, went back to the disabled
list Friday, retroactive to May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson lasted only 1 innings in his start last Sunday when the
Rangers got him for four runs. Dickson was favoring the still-sore
hip and it affected his mechanics, which is the last thing the
Angels want for a pitcher coming off shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt fine but he wasn't as far along as we hoped,'' manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``We want to err on the side of caution. We
gave it a good amount of time but it wasn't healed. Obviously he
needs more time. He's too valuable a pitcher for us to not step
back and make sure he's 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two starters that were in the rotation at the beginning of
the season are still there now _ Kent Bottenfield and Scott
Schoeneweis. Ken Hill and Dickson are on the DL and Ramon Ortiz is
back in the minors. Also, Kent Mercker, who made two starts, is in
the hospital recovering from a brain hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the strengths of the club throughout the organization
was depth in our starting pitcher, but that's being tested,''
Scioscia said. ``We've still got some good arms in the minor
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hinchliffe was called up from Triple-A Edmonton to take
Dickson's spot on the roster. In order to make room for Hinchliffe
on the 40-man roster, Tim Belcher was transferred from the 15-day
DL to the 60-day DL.
</P>
<P>
   __ More starters: The Angels will need yet another starter
sometime next week, at which point they might go to the minor
leagues for help, but it won't be Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said Brian Cooper and Seth Etherton have been pitching
particularly well, and one of the two likely will be called up to
start either Thursday against Minnesota or next Saturday against
Kansas City. Another possibility is Hinchliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz is not an option, Scioscia said, because it would defeat
the purpose of sending him down in the first place. Also, Ortiz
suffered a slightly strained back in his last start for the
Trappers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ortiz needed to work on things, he needs to pitch on a regular
basis to find his command,'' Scioscia said. ''When Ramon has his
command again, he'll force his way into any rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Lineup swaps: The Angels have considered flip-flopping No. 3
hitter Mo Vaughn and No. 4 hitter Tim Salmon in the lineup in an
effort to get Salmon's bat going. Salmon is hitting .245, but he's
get better pitches to hit with Vaughn hitting behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible change is flip-flopping No. 5 hitter Garret
Anderson with No. 6 hitter Troy Glaus to get Anderson (.236) going,
but for now Scioscia will keep the lineup as is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel offense is our problem,'' Scioscia said. ``We've
been doing fine without the normal production of Tim and Garret.
We're going to be patient with those guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
