<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS     05-20 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES ENDS YEAR'S DROUGHT AGAINST DIAMONDBACKS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It had been 13 months since Bobby J. Jones' last
victory, and holding runners was not a priority. The New York Mets
right-hander sat out most of last season with a shoulder injury,
and he went down with a calf strain after three forgettable starts
this year. The game plan Friday night was simple: hold runners on
as well as possible, but concentrate on making quality pitches.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones was a bit slower to home plate _ 1.5 seconds, instead
of his usual 1.2, by manager Bobby Valentine's estimation _ and the
Arizona Diamondbacks easily got the first four of their club-record
seven stolen bases while he was pitching Friday night at Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some of the throws from catcher Mike Piazza were far
from accurate. When Tony Womack stole second after leading off the
game with a single, Piazza bounced his throw off the pitcher's
mound. Piazza rolled his shoulders _ he has been bothered by
discomfort in his back since mid-April _ and sounded discouraged
about his throwing afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, none of it mattered. These days, games are won by
homers, not steals, and Piazza's two-run shot in the fifth inning
was the decisive blow in a 4-3 Mets victory. Jones worked six
innings, allowing three runs on six hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy right now _ very, very happy,'' Jones said.
``It's been a long time since I've pitched well, and I also got a
victory out of it. I felt good out there. It's good to know I can
still go out there and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had command of all four of his pitches, including the
slider he worked on in two rehab starts for Triple-A Norfolk. In
his first three outings, he was throwing too many fastballs, acting
like a power pitcher _ ``That's not going to work for me,'' he said
_ and lacking confidence in his off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He knew things were different in the first inning Friday night,
when he fell behind Steve Finley, 2-0, with runners on first and
second and two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't have the confidence or command of all of my
pitches, I've got to go to the fastball there,'' Jones said. ``I
threw a good changeup, he rolled over it and grounded it to
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The inning was over, and although the Diamondbacks would score
twice in the second after stealing three bases, including a double
steal while pitcher Todd Stottlemyre was trying to bunt, Jones was
on his way to a quality performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have good games; I'm going to have games that are
poor,'' said Jones, whose last victory came last April 17. ``But
every time I go out there, if I can take four pitches with me and
keep my team in the game, then good things are going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza gave Jones the lead with the homer, which he sent down
the left-field line _ the only place a ball could have gotten out
on a night where the wind was blowing straight in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He protected the lead in the seventh, when Womack tried to score
on a double by Jay Bell off Turk Wendell. Jon Nunnally threw to Rey
Ordonez, whose relay bounced several feet up the line. Piazza
pounced on it, recovered and swiped the tag on Womack, ending the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike made one of the best plays I've ever seen,'' Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is working with a new catching coach, John Stearns, but
he has still had trouble throwing out runners. Coming into Friday
night's game, Piazza had thrown out only 4 of 32 runners trying to
steal. (Mets pitchers also have three pickoffs, which count as
caught stealing.) Only Houston's Mitch Meluskey (2 of 23, for 8.7
percent) had a worse percentage among National League catchers than
Piazza's 12.5.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza takes pride in his defense, and he admitted he was
``throwing the ball pretty poorly'' Friday night, saying he was
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to just try to stay composed and not feel I can make up
for a good jump,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' final two stolen bases came in the ninth
inning, when Armando Benitez recorded his 10th save. Benitez, whose
velocity has fluctuated greatly at times this season, was throwing
hard, and keeping his pitches below the belt. His last pitch was a
backdoor slider to Womack, who struck out with Lenny Harris on
third to end the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
