<P>
   BRITAIN-GERMANY-MARKETS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The pioneering
merger of the London and Frankfurt stock exchanges is running into
heavy resistance in both cities. In Germany, regulators and the
nation's state-owned banks fear that Frankfurt will lose control
over the market for small growth companies, which has been a huge
success here in the last three years. In Britain, the fear is that
Frankfurt will grab all the good business and that London traders
will be left with little except the costs of switching over to
Frankfurt's system for electronic trading. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MARKET (Seoul, South Korea) _ Members of Korea's
securities industry union are angry over the the Korea Stock
Exchange's stock exchange plan to abolish the lunch hour break in
trading, saying that it will destroy a Korean tradition. The
30,000-member union threatens to strike on Monday, when the new
hours take effect. By Samuel Len.
