<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FIND A WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was a typical night in Anaheim on Friday,
with another Angels pitcher going to the disabled list and the
offense slamming four home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, though, was the performance by starting pitcher
Jarrod Washburn in the Anaheim Angels' 6-4 victory over the Kansas
City Royals before 26,561 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Dickson was the latest pitcher to land on the disabled
list, making his second trip there because of a strained left hip.
Troy Glaus hit two homers, and Garret Anderson and Tim Salmon each
hit one.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival pitched the ninth for his 11th save, but it was
all set up by Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn (1-1) gave up four runs (three earned) in 6 innings. It
was significant because it was the first quality start (six or more
innings, three earned runs or fewer) by a starter other than Kent
Bottenfield since April 26.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Bottenfield, the Angels rotation has been a mess, as
injuries have torn the staff apart. Ken Hill, Kent Mercker and now
Dickson are on the DL. Ramon Ortiz is in the minors trying to find
his command.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got a big boost from the bullpen as well Friday.
Shigetoshi Hasegawa retired all five batters he faced, and Percival
got the save despite giving up two hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a 3-0 lead, getting two runs in the second
inning when Anderson tripled and glaus followed with his 12th homer
of the season. Anderson made it 3-0 with a solo homer (No. 9) in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Washburn had everything working early, retiring the
first 10 batters he faced before Jeff Reboulet's one-out single in
the fourth inning. Washburn worked his way out of that inning
unscathed, but he wasn't so fortunate in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Beltran led off with a homer and Mark Quinn singled. One
out later, Rey Sanchez singled Quinn to third, and Quinn scored on
Johnny Damon's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez moved second on a walk to Reboulet, then scored on Mark
Sweeney's single to tie the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Washburn was hurt by shortstop Benji Gil's
error. Instead of what should have been a routine double play, Gil
booted Beltran's grounder and the Royals had runners on first and
second with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn followed with a fly ball into the right-field corner,
where Tim Salmon made the catch. Joe Randa tagged and reached third
on the play, but Beltran slid past the bag trying to go from first
to second and was tagged out for a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn, though, yielded a two-out single to Brian Johnson,
scoring Randa for a 4-3 Royals advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals lead lasted only until the bottom of the sixth, when
Salmon followed a single by Vaughn with a home run just inside the
left-field foul pole to give the Angels a 5-4 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0838 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-HERNANDZ-LADN-(SL     05-20 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-HERNANDZ-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ SET TO CONQUER U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Luis Hernandez is easily distinguished from
the other great soccer players who have worn Mexico's famed green
national team jersey.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is his long, flowing blond hair. Then there is his
trademark headband.
</P>
<P>
   But neither his hair nor his headband explain why Hernandez _
known as ``El Matador'' _ is adored by his countrymen. Simply put,
it's because Hernandez is what you call a Mexican's Mexican. To
him, wearing the red, white and green colors of Mexico is more a
matter of pride than responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He IS Mexican soccer at the moment,'' said Rigoberto
Cervantes, who covers soccer for Los Angeles' most popular
Spanish-language newspaper, La Opinion. ``The media from Mexico
that will follow him here is enormous. Luis is world-known, there
is a lot of pride with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer officials are proud to have landed
Hernandez, who will make his debut for the Los Angeles Galaxy at 6
p.m. tonight at the Rose Bowl against D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was introduced to his new teammates Friday at Staples
Center. Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid was asked if Hernandez would start
tonight. Schmid then turned the question over to Hernandez: ``Are
you ready?'' Schmid asked Hernandez. ``Yes,'' replied Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is familiar with Galaxy players Cobi Jones and Robin
Fraser, who he has competed against during international games. He
even joked about defender Paul Caligiuri taking a few whacks at
him.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked why he's here, and what he hopes to accomplish,
he made it clear why he's making the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accomplished and achieved everything I wanted to in
Mexico,'' Hernandez said. ``As a man I'm looking forward to a new
challenge, to help soccer in the United States and hopefully win a
champions As for the future: ``After a year, I will have options to
play in Europe, but we will take that one step at a time,''
Hernandez said. ``My contract is with the Galaxy and that's where
my concentration is. I'm looking forward to playing with my new
teammates and learning brand of soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez signed a three-year contract with MLS on Tuesday and
was assigned to the Galaxy after the league purchased his contract
Monterrey Tigres for nearly $5 million. MLS forced the Galaxy to
part with three starters. Striker Clint Mathis and midfielder Roy M
to New York/New Jersey and defender Joey Franchino went to New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans love Hernandez for the same reason they love fighters
who duke it out: He has the same grit. The 31-year-old striker ear
Hernandez is only 5-foot-7 and 160 pounds, but he's Mexico's
heavyweight, its biggest star. He's tireless, demands attention and
has what you call a striker's nose for the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch his playing style, he's not someone who stands
around and waits for the ball,'' Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said.
``He's not the kind who says: `Hey, I'm here, you have to play the
ball to me.' He's the kind of player who's busy, active and rolls
up his sleeves.''
</P>
<P>
   League and Galaxy officials are hoping Hernandez can be the
franchise player that will lead the team to an MLS championship,
something no other foreign star has done. The Galaxy has made two
appearances in the championship match, but lost to D.C. United both
times, in 1996 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's credentials are impressive. He won two Mexican
League championships with Necaxa (1994-95, 1995-96), a CONCACAF
Champions Cup title with Monterrey (1992-93) and was named the
Mexican Player of the Year in 1997 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   He made a global impact in the 1998 World Cup in France, proving
he could score in clutch situations. He tallied four of Mexico's
eight goals in the tournament, and scored in injury time to help
Mexico tie Holland, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   His four goals earned him a tie for fourth place among the World
Cup scoring leaders with Brazil's Ronaldo and Chile's Marcelo
Salas.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is different from all the other Mexican players who
have ventured to Major League Soccer. Two of the most well known,
Jorge Campos and Carlos Hermosillo, previously played for the
Galaxy. Other notable Mexican players, Damien Alvarez, Hugo Sanchez
and Francisco Uribe, have played with Dallas (Alvarez and Sanchez)
and San Jose (Uribe).
</P>
<P>
   Campos arrived in his prime in 1996. He was flashy, personable
and had some great games, but he was a goalkeeper, not a scorer.
Campos was traded to Chicago after the 1997 season, never beat out
Fire keeper Zach Thornton, so he bolted to Mexico during the 1998
playoffs, missing out when Chicago won the MLS title.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo arrived in Los Angeles in 1998, but the speed in the
MLS overwhelmed him. He never fit in with the Galaxy, but he
managed 14 goals and 15 assists in 34 games. He left MLS to join
Club America of Mexico after the Galaxy's 2-0 title loss to D.C.
United this past November.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, big-name Mexicans have played in the United States, but
they haven't taken over MLS the way Marco Etcheverry (Bolivia),
Carlos Valderrama (Colombia) or Jaime Moreno (Bolivia) have.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadoran striker Eduardo Hurtado helped lead the Galaxy to the
1996 MLS title match, but he disappointed in 1997 and was
subsequently sent to New York/New Jersey. Thursday, New England
sold his rights to an Ecuadoran team.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez is different than all of them. He's MLS' biggest
foreign allocation and Mexico's biggest name.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, who met Hernandez for the first time Friday, says it's
not a question of will he or won't he work out. Schmid said
Hernandez is without peer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare Luis to some of the other Mexican players
that have come here, I don't think you can,'' said Schmid.
``There's never been a Mexican player of the quality of Luis
Hernandez in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Hernandez having a major impact on this team and a major
impact in this league. He's not a player who's not going to live up
to his promise. He's going to live up to it and exceed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez draws comparisons to other legendary soccer players
who previously played in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, Northern Ireland's George Best, who earned
fame with England's Manchester United, played for the Los Angeles
Aztecs of the North American Soccer League.
</P>
<P>
   The Aztecs also landed Johan Cruyff, a member of Holland's famed
``Clockwork Orange'' national team. Cruyff came to Los Angeles
after a brilliant career with Ajax of Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think us getting Hernandez is bigger than those two,'' said
Schmid. ``Cruyff was a name and recognition and so was Best, b
we're dealing with the biggest ethnic population in Southern
California, which are the Mexican-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Luis Hernandez, that's a much bigger
impression for them than a Best or Cruyff. Plus, you have to
remember back in the days of Best and Cruyff, there wasn't Internet
or satellite television, so it was difficult for people in the U.S.
to see Best or Cruyff play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's nobody who doesn't follow soccer in the U.S.,
whether they're American, Mexican, Iranian, English or whatever,
that hasn't seen Luis Hernandez play. And those who have seen him
play appreciate his style because he's very industrious.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid believes Hernandez's skills and work ethic can only lead
to success for the Galaxy. Galaxy fans and all of Mexico will be
watching to see how he works out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be some bumps along the road as we move forward
and until the timing and coordination gets down, but I'm very
confident it will work out,'' said Schmid. ``For it to work out is
just a matter of our attitude as a team and our attitude as a
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's a matter of Luis' attitude, and everything I've heard
about Luis is he's a great person. And if his playing style is
anything like his personality, there won't be any problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
