<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-20 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN ODD YEAR YIELDS STRANGE FRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the wee hours of a new day, a large throng milled
around the stands at Madison Square Garden, trying to get a peek at
the hero of Game 6, maybe even give a cheer. Patrick Ewing does not
get many ovations these days. But now, in the joy of the moment,
after the New York Knicks' 37-year-old center had so clearly been
the one to keep the Knicks' season from expiring, there were all
these Knicks fans who felt they had to linger and watch Ewing being
interviewed on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing sparked one of the more incredible comebacks in Knicks
playoff history Friday night. He refused to let the Knicks truly
hit bottom in the first half, when they trailed by as many as 18
points, and then he carried them to a 72-70 victory in the second.
And now, for the fourth time in four years, the Knicks are headed
to Miami for another deciding game against the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that I'm glad we won this game and we're
playing Game 7,'' Ewing said, after he had willed the Knicks to
survive. ``Anything can happen in Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no chants of ``Patrick! Patrick!'' as Ewing left the
floor at the end of Friday night's game. He's been around too long,
crossed too many bridges, for that type of giddy show of
appreciation. There was even that bittersweet mixture of groans and
cheers in the first half whenever he touched the ball. Although _
and this happens a lot with Ewing _ when the fans realized that
Ewing was the only Knick who wasn't waving the white flag in the
first two quarters, he drew a salute of respectful cheers and
applause whenever he came out the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ewing played 42 minutes Friday night, more than any
other player on either team except Latrell Sprewell. He scored 15
points, he grabbed 18 rebounds. More than any other Knick, he kept
his team alive. ``Jeff really didn't say too much at halftime,''
Ewing said, looking back to a moment when the Knicks were trailing
by 15. ``The guys just came together and said: `Look, we're not
ready to go on vacation. We have another half to play.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, halftime was one final chance
to exhort his players, to underline the message he had preached to
them 10 hours before as they went through a morning shoot-around.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy sat on a table after the shoot-around, talking to
reporters and trying to be positive with his team one defeat from
elimination. Someone asked him about the Knicks' backs being
against the wall; someone else about the Knicks' sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy was in no mood for cliches. ``I'm cliched out,''
he said. ``Forget desperate, urgent, us against them. We can make
it a cliche thing or we can make it a rebounding thing. What we
need to do is win one home game to get to the ultimate game.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything between these teams has seemed to rest on the slender
thread of a single shot. Allan Houston's last-second shot against
the Heat last May, Tim Hardaway's last-second miracle shot against
the Knicks last month, Anthony Carter's last-second miracle shot
against the Knicks in Game 3's overtime. And perhaps a last-second
shot Sunday, in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   What was on Van Gundy's mind Friday morning weren't any of those
shots, but the recurring problems that underlined a lack of will,
not luck, on the part of the Knicks: a block-out problem on P.J.
Brown, a toughness problem going after loose balls, a team
rebounding problem.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy related how just an hour before he had addressed his
players and turned preacher. ``We need some people to set the
proper tone,'' Van Gundy said, his voice rising, as he recounted
what he told his team. ``This is how you rebound to win a big game.
This is how you guard to win a big game. This is how you pass to
win a big game. It starts with our starting lineup. Some guys have
been setting a good tone, some other guys in critical areas have
not been setting the tone we need. We're either going to do it
tonight, or we're going to be talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Van Gundy said, he put a pointed question to his
players. He wondered who, in their heart of hearts, really wanted a
Game 7 Sunday. ``Do you want the pressure of going back down there
for another ultimate game?'' Van Gundy asked. ``If you do, it will
be reflected in how we play tonight. If you sort of want to slide
off into vacation, that will also be reflected in how we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, more than any other Knick, answered Van Gundy's question.
He wanted a Game 7, and now he has it. And if Ewing has his way,
Van Gundy will be exhorting his team in next week's shoot-arounds
in the conference finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
