<SLUG> BC-FBO-AVENGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVENGERS CONTINUE LOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just in case anyone needed a reminder that this is
not the NFL, Avengers quarterback Todd Marinovich found out a new
drawback to playing in the Arena Football League on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   While running out to the field, Marinovich was hit in the eye by
a piece of debris from the pregame fireworks display at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see until the second half,'' Marinovich said.
``That was (difficult). They just have to quit those fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident was just the latest woe to strike the hapless
Avengers, who lost to the Houston ThunderBears 51-36 before 10,781.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers (0-6) are still far from having to worry about
setting a league record for futility. The now-defunct Memphis
franchise lost 14 games to start the 1996 season, so they are quite
a ways off from worrying about that mark.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean they have much to be proud of six weeks
into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid mistakes. Turnovers. Stupid penalties,'' Avengers coach
Stan Brock said. ``We have different people but it's the same
story. We just have to keep working on things. That's all we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was rough night for Marinovich all around. Although he
completed 21 of 35 passes for 235 yards, he threw only two
touchdown passes with two interceptions. He also had at least four
passes dropped by Houston cornerbacks that easily could have been
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   His final interception was the costliest. Marinovich threw the
ball right into the hands of Houston's Ed Howard with 2:05 left
that ended any chance of an Avengers comeback. On the next play,
Hall found Ben Bronsonon a 18-yard touchdown pass to put the game
away, giving Houston a 45-29 lead with 1:51 left.
</P>
<P>
   Hall finished 23 for 35 for 228 yards and six touchdowns with no
interceptions. The real star, though, might have been Houston's
defense, considering it was giving up 58 points per game and
allowed 73 last week in aloss to Iowa. Or maybe it was just the
ineptness of the Avengers' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Another season-long weak spot _ the secondary _ continued to be
a nemesis. Houston wide receiver Bronson caught 12 passes for 164
yards and three touchdowns. The Avengers also continued to have
penalty problems, with 11 for 57 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A final lingering problem was the kicking game, as kicker Kyle
Pooler had an extra point blocked because of a bad snap, and a
50-yard field goal blocked as the first half ended.
</P>
<P>
   Pooler also missed a critical extra point in the fourth quarter
after the Avengers scored a touchdown to cut Houston's lead to
35-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a protection problem (with our kicks),'' Brock
said. ``There's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first half was close, but the Avengers were burned late. The
ThunderBears made a huge play with 44 seconds left in the half, as
Hall hit Bronson on a 33-yard touchdown pass that gave Houston a
28-16 halftime advantage. Bronson had a big first-half, with eight
receptions for 95 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Former USC wide receiver Travis Hannah made his debut,
and caught five passes for 41 yards. Another newly signed player,
wide receiver Shannon Culver, caught four passes for 33 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
