<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BLANK TIGERS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Stanley swears his calendar was off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sure when I left for the ballpark it was May 19th,''
said the Red Sox first baseman. ``But when I got to the ballpark,
it was April 19th.''
</P>
<P>
   A raw, brutal wind from the East dropped the temperature to the
40s, the wind chill to the 30s, and reduced driven baseballs to
cans of corn Friday night at Fenway Park, but the weather couldn't
chill Boston's white-hot pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The weather was wrong, but the calendar was right. Red Sox
pitchers have been nearly invincible in May, and Friday night Jeff
Fassero (5-1) featured a marvelous split-finger pitch in hurling
seven scoreless innings as the first-place Red Sox whitewashed the
Tigers, 3-0, at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The shutout (with one helpful relief inning each from Rich
Garces and Derek Lowe) was the second consecutive by the Boston
staff and its third in the last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   And last Monday in Toronto, Pete Schourek only gave up an
unearned run in an 8-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing in, so make 'em try to hit it over the
triangle,'' said catcher Jason Varitek of his pitch-calling in the
breezy conditions. ``Maybe a guy hits a fastball away well, but
he's really got to `tater' it to hit it out to right-center. So you
say, `Hey, try to hit it out over the triangle right now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, for one, was sure no ball could be hit out against
the headwind when he smashed a ball in the fourth inning off
Detroit starter Brian Moehler (1-2) that seemed destined to clear
the bullpens. But right fielder Juan Gonzalez backed to the wall
and patiently waited for the wind to knock down Everett's drive
before hauling it in.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, as usual, had an interesting take
on Everett's drive. The wind, yes, ``but they have a tall right
fielder, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had all of it,'' said Everett. ``But it was high
and the wind was able to get to it. Plus Gonzo (Gonzalez) is out
there with those long arms of his. If it's (Luis) Polonia out
there, it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now fast-forward two innings to the sixth. The game is still a
tidy 0-0. The inning began with an unusual ``4-5'' scorebook
notation when Tigers second baseman Jose Macias made a quick,
heady, and daring decision on a hard grounder by Trot Nixon with
none out and Donnie Sadler on second.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all second basemen would have routinely thrown to
first on the play, especially with a runner as quick as Sadler, but
Macias fired to third baseman Dean Palmer to nail the sliding
Sadler. ``The kid made a heck of a play,'' said Williams.
``Especially with Sadler the runner. You don't see many second
basemen do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Nixon on first and one out, Brian Daubach struck out. That
brought up Everett, the wind still gusting straight into his face.
This time, though, on a 3-2 pitch from Moehler, Everett lashed a
screamer that even the wind couldn't prevent from clearing the
Detroit bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I hit the second one harder than the first one,'' said
Everett of his 13th homer. ``And I hit it lower, so the wind
couldn't do as much with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who also made a dazzling snag of a Bobby Higginson
smash at first base, closed out the scoring by hitting a low laser
into the screen in left-center to lead off the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Red Sox pitching that deserved most of the
accolades. Friday night's shutout _ the team's first at Fenway this
season _ was Boston's sixth of the season and continued one of the
more remarkable streaks of pitching in recent years. The Boston
staff has now allowed one earned run or fewer in six of its last
seven games, going 6-1 with a 1.30 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitching has just been tremendous,'' said Stanley. ``What
a great feeling it is as a hitter and defensive player to know that
your pitching staff is doing that well and you just have to scratch
and crawl and try to get a few runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more, the Red Sox' team ERA is down to an outstanding 3.28,
the best in the majors, and nearly three-quarters of a run lower
than the second-best staff in the league, the Yankees. And Fassero,
a reclamation project six weeks ago, now has equaled his win total
from last season, when he struggled to a 5-14 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just keep feeding off each other,'' said Fassero of the
staff-wide success, ``and that's a big plus for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
