<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0844 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HEAT-KNICKS-BOS     05-20 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-KNICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS FORCE GAME 7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years, four elimination games.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetics be damned. The Knicks and the Heat don't care what
you, your Aunt Tillie, and Shaquille O'Neal think about the way
they play basketball. Laugh at their combined shooting percentages
(35 percent Friday night) all you want. They say it's sticky D and
heart and all that intangible stuff that makes their rivalry the
best current thing in American team sport.
</P>
<P>
   So we will be going to a Game 7, as if anyone expected
otherwise. The New York Knicks created Sunday's confrontation by
scoring the final 6 points of the game to give themselves a 72-70
victory over the Miami Heat at Madison Square Garden Friday night,
and so what if they only led for a total of 3 minutes 34 seconds?
They led when the final buzzer sounded, which is all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Majerle stuck out his knee after being beaten by Allan
Houston in a high pick-and-roll situation with 17.6 seconds to go,
and Houston drilled a pair of free throws that held up as the
winning points when Anthony Carter, taking an inside-out feed from
Alonzo Mourning, missed a 3-pointer at the buzzer. Mourning had to
pass. Jeff Van Gundy had sent everyone but the Harlem Boys Choir at
the Miami center once he caught the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   New York got a huge effort from Patrick Ewing, who had 15 points
and 18 rebounds, the last of which was a vicious follow-up dunk of
a Chris Childs miss that pulled his team within 2 at 70-68 with
1:57 to go. ``Patrick was terrific tonight,'' said Van Gundy. ``I'm
always happy for him when he's successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks can also thank Houston (21) and Latrell Sprewell,
whose 15 points and nine rebounds don't indicate his third-quarter
heroics. New York entered the second half trailing by 15 (45-30)
after playing a horrid first half. It was Sprewell's all-around
energy at both ends that dragged his team back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   It is the nature of this rivalry, which enters playoff Chapter
24 Sunday, that one team will go through long periods in which it
needs a basketball cleric to come in to administer some sort of
last rites. New York had such a stretch in the second period,
making zero field goals in the final 5:56. Miami reciprocated in
the second half, scoring 9 points in one stretch of 10:20.
</P>
<P>
   But the Heat were still in control, leading by 6 (66-60) with
4:28 left on a 3-pointer by Bruce Bowen and still leading by 4
(70-66) with 2:20 remaining on a second consecutive open jumper by
Carter, the happy beneficiary of New York's relentless inside
double-teaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the game, I thought, sort of in our hands,'' said Pat
Riley. ``We were up 6 and from there it went right downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley won't enjoy looking at the final two minutes. He'll wonder
how Ewing could outmaneuver Mourning (22 points, 10 rebounds) for
that big follow-up dunk, and he'll wonder what exactly was going
through seven-year veteran P.J. Brown's head when he rammed into
Childs in the backcourt with his team leading, 70-68. New York
already had the Mo, and Childs promptly tied the game. Things got
worse when Ewing knocked away an entry pass intended for Mourning,
setting up the fateful final possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolute madness,'' said Riley. ``Have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami was feeling pretty good about itself when a run of 11-0
put them up by a 43-25 score with 2:02 left in the half. The Knicks
were en route to a 27 percent (11-40) shooting half that also
featured a flagrant foul and a lane violation.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley, for one, wasn't cocky. ``I didn't feel comfortable
with a 15-point lead,'' he declared. ``We knew they'd make a rush,
and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   A rush is one thing, but a 25-point second half when you're
trying to close out a series is another, and thus Miami slinks back
home to play New York on its own floor in an elimination game for a
third straight year. They lost the last two, but this time it's
going to be played in a new building, so perhaps they assume the
karma will be different.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, New York and Miami are going as far as you can go. We'll
get back to you when we have some new news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
