<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON HELPS MARINERS RALLY FOR FOUTH CONSECUTIVE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Rickey Henderson era in Seattle started a day
early.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson arrived just before the game Friday night, but he
wasn't in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   He was there for the finishing kick in a dramatic 7-6 Seattle
victory over Tampa Bay, scoring the first of two eighth-inning runs
that carried the Mariners to their fourth consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, asked to pinch run after Jay Buhner drew a savvy walk
with the Mariners down a run, replaced Buhner as the crowd of
34,067 gave Henderson a hero's welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Even his teammates got a little of that good-time feeling going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey coming into the game like that was very dramatic,''
shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``It was very movie-like. I got
goose bumps when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was just for Henderson _ signed as a free agent after
the Mets released him on Tuesday _ trotting out to first base.
Imagine the feeling when Henderson took off on a 2-0 pitch to Stan
Javier. The Mariners were trying to pull off a hit-and-run, and
Javier simply slaughtered the pitch, lining it over center fielder
Gerald Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, 41 but still in amazing shape and one of the best
base runners in the game, had to pause near second base to make
sure the ball would fall. Once that was no longer in doubt,
Henderson kicked it in like few players can, scoring standing up
when most players would have slid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited coming in like that,'' Henderson said. ``With
the fans cheering like that, it gives you a special feeling. This
is a good way to start. Everything here feels upbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier, who earlier homered to break a 1-1 tie in the second
inning, capped the inning by scoring from third on a Mark McLemore
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Javier and McLemore both figure to see a dropoff in at-bats with
Henderson around, but both veterans turned in games that will keep
them in the Mariners' mix.
</P>
<P>
   Javier scored twice and drove in two runs. McLemore did a nice
impersonation of Henderson in the leadoff role, drawing two walks,
stealing three bases and driving in two runs with a single and the
game-winning fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   And DH Edgar Martinez was crucial to the victory, hammering out
three more hits and driving in two runs, his 10th and 11th RBIs of
the homestand. He's hit in 16 of his past 17 games and has raised
his average more than 100 points to .365.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgar gets in a groove like this a lot,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``And when he does, he stays in them for a long time, much
longer than most players.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mesa, who came into the game in the seventh inning, picked
up the victory and Kazuhiro Sasaki, back in the closer's role for
the first time since giving up game-losing homers in back-to-back
appearances, took over to pitch a 1-2-3 ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going to go with who I feel like in the closer's
role,'' Piniella said, making it clear that just by saving one game
Sasaki wasn't back as closer. ``I have confidence in Sasaki,
though, and he did a nice job tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson arrived just in time to suit up for the game. Although
he didn't start, he was a key focal point, even while sitting on
the bench. He comes to a Seattle team already in first place, and
Henderson made it clear he's ready to do what it takes to keep the
Mariners there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to come here and get a chance to play and help
this team,'' Henderson said. ``I thought in the back of my mind
that I'd like to play here, especially when Ken Griffey Jr. was
here, but it didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this team. It has a lot of talent. They've been playing
pretty good ball so far, and they have a nice lineup. The biggest
thing will be going out there and playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson pointed out that he's been in the postseason seven
times, and he hopes to be able to bring that experience to bear as
the Mariners go after their first playoff berth since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can bring experience to some of the younger guys, help them
out,'' Henderson said. ``When a club is motivated to win like this
one, you can help them get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson will get a chance to play every day and lead off,
manager Lou Piniella said. The two men met before the game, by
which time Piniella had decided against having Henderson rush into
action. But for the most part, Henderson will be the first name
Piniella writes down each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll need his rest, too, but he's going to play a lot,''
Piniella said. ``I want him in left and leading off, and that's
what he wants, too. And we'll let him show us what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is cool with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm motivated based on being happy,'' Henderson said. ``What
makes me happy is believing in the guys, believing in the manager
and having them believe in me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play the game to win, and if I can leave the game on a
winning note, that's what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Henderson is ready to give it up just yet. The deal he
struck with the Mariners includes a club option for the 2001 season
for $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   To earn that payday, Henderson will have to prove that he's
worth it and still able to play even at his advanced _ for baseball
_ age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have it,'' Henderson said. ``And I still love the
game.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
