members and have been suspects since the 1960s. Prosecutors plan to
use old and newly developed evidence.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo Deadline Averted
</P>
<P>
   The Senate defeated a measure to set a deadline for withdrawing
U.S. ground troops from Kosovo, averting a foreign policy setback
for the Clinton administration. The Senate stripped a provision
from a military spending bill that would have cut off funds for the
5,600 U.S. forces in Kosovo by July 1, 2001, unless Congress
approved an extension. The White House said the measure would
undermine the NATO operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Court Rules on Rape Cases
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the moment of its passage in 1994, the Violence
Against Women Act was on a collision course with the Supreme
Court's new interest in setting limits on Congress' ability to
bring the federal government into areas of state concern. The crash
finally occurred when the court voted, 5-4, that the act's
provision permitting victims of rape and other crimes ``motivated
by gender'' to sue their attackers in federal court was
unconstitutional. Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the law's chief Senate
sponsor, said the decision ``is really all about power: who has the
power, the court or Congress?''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   A Capitol Fixture Departs
</P>
<P>
   Presidents come and go, but Helen Thomas stayed at the White
House for 39 years. Thomas, who is 79 and covered John F. Kennedy
and every president thereafter for United Press International, quit
after the financially troubled news service was acquired by a group
with links to the Unification Church. ``I wish the new owners all
the best,'' Thomas said in leaving her employer of 57 years.
``Great stories, and happy landings.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   Peru Challenger Drops Out
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is running neck-in-neck with President Alberto K.
Fujimori in the polls, Alejandro Toledo dropped out of the runoff
in Peru's presidential race, saying he could not win on a playing
field fraudulently tilted against him. Fujimori apparently has a
clear shot at winning a third five-year term unless Toledo and the
international community put enough pressure on the government to
postpone the May 28 runoff election until mid-June. Fujimori said
he would not change the election date.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CLIFFORD KRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   The Fed Gets Serious
</P>
<P>
   Despite five quarter-point interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve over 11 months, the economy has kept roaring along.
So the Fed pulled out some heavier weaponry, raising rates by half
a percentage point to make clear that it will do whatever is needed
to head off inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank also hinted that further rate hikes are in the
pipeline, disappointing investors who had hoped for a sign that the
Fed was finished for the year. So far, though, there is not much
inflation for the Fed to extinguish.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Women and Stress
</P>
<P>
   When humans encounter stress, they will, by instinct, choose
``fight or flight'' _ or so goes the accepted wisdom. The trouble
is, that wisdom is based largely on the study of men. But guess
what? According to a study in the journal Psychological Review,
women are different. Instead of slugging or running when demons
appear, they ``tend and befriend'' _ they stick together and
nurture children. A good thing, too, the study suggests: It would
have been an evolutionary disaster if no one had protected the
young.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Hospital Giant Settles
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling fraud investigation of Columbia/HCA Healthcare
Corp. has lasted seven years, but prosecutors have finally won a
tentative settlement. The hospital giant agreed in principal to pay
$745 million in civil penalties to resolve allegations that it
cheated federal health programs. But the deal will not be finalized
unless the outstanding criminal investigations are resolved before
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KURT EICHENWALD
</P>
<P>
   Dominicans Vote for Change
</P>
<P>
   With the benefits of Latin America's fastest-growing economy
eluding them, thousands of Dominicans, tired of high prices and
blackouts, pulled the plug on the ruling party in presidential
elections. Although Hipolito Mejia, the candidate of the
left-center Revolutionary Dominican Party, just missed a majority,
he far outpaced his opponents. Facing an insurmountable margin,
Danilo Medina of the ruling Dominican Liberation Party declined to
pursue a runoff. Mejia has vowed to increase social spending and
help farmers hurt by imports and privatization.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID GONZALEZ
</P>
<P>
   New Rules on Diesel Fuel
</P>
<P>
   Trucks and buses are among the last uncontrolled sources of air
pollution, but their turn has come, the Environmental Protection
Agency said. The agency is seeking a 97 percent reduction in the
sulfur content of diesel fuel over the next decade in an effort to
reduce smog and remove harmful chemicals from the air. Oil refiners
have volunteered a 90 percent cut. Hearings on the proposed rules
will begin soon.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   This Flag Won't Fly
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the South Carolina Capitol will no longer see the
Confederate flag atop the dome as of July 1, after the state
legislature gave in to years of pressure and voted to remove it.
But they won't have to look far to see it _ a smaller version will
now fly in front of the Statehouse. That has angered some black
officials and the NAACP, which plans to step up its boycott of the
state, but business leaders say they believe the issue will quickly
fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
