<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TV-SEASON-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-20 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE UP AND KNOCK THE LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the most spontaneous _ and unexpected _ moment
at last week's annual ``up fronts,'' a four-day rite in which
network television executives nervously announce their new sitcoms
and dramas to advertisers in New York and bring in the casts of
current hit shows to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   As Scott Sassa, president of NBC West Coast, and Garth Ancier,
NBC's president of entertainment, introduced the stars of ``West
Wing,'' the audience at Lincoln Center stood for a prolonged
standing ovation, startling both executives and actors.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the flaws of the Aaron Sorkin dramatic series about a
fictional liberal president and his White House staff, the audience
was saying, in effect, that a grown-up and unpatronizing show was a
source of rare pride to them. The show is successful, too.
</P>
<P>
   But then there was the rest _ old and new _ that the public will
see this fall. And the refrain heard among media buyers, talent
agents and managers, and television executives at the elaborate
parties around the city was: Is this really the best that network
television can offer?
</P>
<P>
   The new shows include appealing comedy series with movie stars
like Bette Midler and Geena Davis. Others are simply replicas: The
NBC show ``Tucker,'' about a bright boy living with mother, seems
similar to the Fox hit ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' The CBS series
``The Fugitive'' mirrors the Harrison Ford film and the 1960s David
Janssen prototype. The NBC series ``DAG,'' about a secret
serviceman guarding a feisty first lady, recalls the 1994 film,
``Guarding Tess.'' And an Aaron Spelling NBC series, ``Titans,''
about an overrich, oversexed Beverly Hills family recalls, well,
most of Spelling's series.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously missing from most of the networks (except WB) were
new teen-age shows and clones of ``Friends'' (twentysomethings
living in New York), which proliferated in recent years. The reason
was simply that many of these shows have flopped or fared poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Even executives at the youth-centric WB Network seemed far less
assured this year than they were last year when they crowed that
they knew precisely what their audience wanted. For the first time
in its half-dozen years, the highly successful network stumbled,
partly because of some poorly received shows, partly because of the
loss of WGN, a Chicago station. Now WB is plainly seeking to push
the envelope with ``Grosse Pointe,'' which spoofs the kind of
teen-age shows that the network often offers; the actors are as
pretty as they are vain and vacuous. One of the show's producers,
Darren Star, helped create ``Beverly Hills 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York preview came at an odd, maybe surreal, moment in
the ever-fluid world of television. The moment _ worthy of Terry
Southern _ came when ABC's huge hit, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' was briefly eclipsed last Sunday by the opening
episode of the CBS miniseries, ``Jesus.'' Variety's front-page
headline proclaimed: `` `Jesus' Tops Regis.'' (On Wednesday the
miniseries was toppled by the final episode of ``Beverly Hills
90210.'')
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, not one but two behind-the-scenes dramas about
``The Brady Bunch'' have surfaced. In the NBC's drama ``Growing Up
Brady'' which is broadcast Sunday night at 9 p.m., viewers
immediately learn that Robert Reed and Florence Henderson, who
played the parents of the six Brady children, didn't like kissing
much because Reed, who died in 1992, ``likes men more than woman,''
says the actor playing Barry Williams, who played Greg, the oldest
son. It's that kind of show. Fox has a show in a similar vein.
</P>
<P>
   In their hunger to lure increasingly fickle audiences away from
cable and the Internet, network executives said selecting and
scheduling programs was a roll of the dice as well as a blend of
considerations. CBS, for example, picked up the medical drama,
``City of Angels,'' about a hospital in Los Angeles for another
season despite poor ratings. The show, one of the first dramatic
series with a predominately black cast and crew, has been a big
disappointment. By all indications, CBS picked up the series for
another season partly to avoid the ire of civil rights groups,
which pressured the networks last year to accelerate minority
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of what our position should be in terms of
minorities, in terms of diversity,'' said CBS president Leslie
Moonves. (But a decision by CBS not to add a series about a
Mexican-American family in East Los Angeles to its prime-time
lineup, which the network had been promoting, caused disappointment
among Hispanic groups).
</P>
<P>
   Moonves, echoing his competitors at NBC and Fox, was clearly
obsessed with the extraordinary success of ABC's ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire.'' The show dominates the television landscape. (ABC
added only two and a half hours of new series programs to its fall
schedule).
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' may prove vulnerable, said Moonves, who has
placed probably his top new show, the Bette Midler comedy, ``The
Bette Show,'' against the quiz show. ``I lay awake at night
thinking how to fight `Millionaire,''' he said. ``And I can't
figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Millionaire' slips,'' Moonves said, ``that will be my one
Christmas gift.'' His colleagues at NBC and Fox, looking uneasily
about toward the new season, are hoping for the same gift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0038 </DOCNO>
