<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-NASCAR-REVIEW-ART-N     05-20 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NASCAR-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW STOCK CARS BECAME ICONS OF AMERICANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(Repeating to add graphic note) 
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSANNA RODELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUGEMONT, N.C. _ Racing commentators ticked off the aspects
surrounding Adam Petty's death last week at the New Hampshire
International Speedway: a fourth-generation racer killed at age 19
in a practice run, just weeks after the death of his
great-grandfather, Lee, a NASCAR champion three times over.
</P>
<P>
   Few pointed out that the young driver died a long way from
Daytona, Fla., and in the heart of Yankee country. But NASCAR has
traveled far since days when the first racers came roaring down
from the Blue Ridge Mountains in their bootlegging cars, itching to
find out who was the fastest. Today racers average 150 mph a lap
and over 200 on the straights.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe spread the fame of Junior Johnson, one of the greatest
drivers of the 1950s and '60s, who was sentenced to two years in
prison after he was caught firing his daddy's still. Wolfe's
Esquire article, ``The Last American Hero,'' later appeared in his
book, ``The Kandy-Kolored Tangerine Flake Streamline Baby.'' He
described Southern culture, carefully explaining that ``good old
boys'' were not necessarily old or boys.
</P>
<P>
   The South no longer needs translation. And along with country
music and culinary quirks like grits and red-eye gravy, NASCAR is
now part of American culture. Of the 21 race tracks in the Winston
Cup Series, the top races, only nine are in the Southeast. Since
1988 NASCAR has come to tracks in Nevada, Indiana, New Hampshire,
Arizona and California. There are also races in New York and
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   While old-timers trained by outrunning revenuers, many of the
young ``shoes,'' including Jeff Gordon, NASCAR's current superstar,
learned their down-shifting and trail-braking at the Skip Barber
School, considered the Harvard of racing schools. Some even have
college degrees, and a few colleges like the University of North
Carolina at Charlotte offer courses in racing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, folks down South miss the bad old days when stock cars
raced on dirt and the drivers drank hard, banged one another's cars
and brawled after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a parallel with the NFL,'' says Humpy Wheeler, the
longtime czar of Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte, N.C. ``In the
old days, it was just a bunch of thugs playing in the back yard on
a Sunday afternoon. Now it's in every living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Entry into the nation's living rooms has its price, and Wheeler
is clearly ambivalent about it. Part of that price, he said, is
formality. ``I'm the only one left with a nickname,'' he said.
``Used to be, everyone had a nickname _ Fireball Roberts, Banjo
Matthews, Tiny Lund.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days a seat belt might mean a length of rope tied
around a driver's waist. Cars, too, came right off the dealer's
stock on the showroom floor. When Bill France Sr. and other
racing-car enthusiasts gathered in Daytona Beach in 1947 to
establish the National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing, they
believed that ordinary people would want to watch what their own
cars could do. At the first official NASCAR-sanctioned race at the
old Charlotte Speedway in 1949, at least 10,000 spectators showed
up.
</P>
<P>
   One of the participants was Lee Petty, a bakery truck driver
from Level Cross, N.C., who wrecked his borrowed Buick Roadmaster
and had to hitchhike home. But before his death this year at age
86, Petty went on to many victories, and watched his son, Richard,
his grandson Kyle and his great-grandson, Adam, become NASCAR
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona's first races were on the beach. In Georgia, Virginia
and the Carolinas, the tracks were cut into the red clay. The great
racing families of Atlanta started out running moonshine.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, change crept in. The dirt tracks were paved over.
NASCAR's first race on pavement at Darlington in 1950 had a
pear-shaped track because the owner wanted to preserve a minnow
pond.
</P>
<P>
   One thing about NASCAR has remained unchanged: It's still a
white man's sport. A few women compete at the lower levels. Charlie
Scott, a black man, won a Winston Cup race in 1963, but only a few
blacks race today; none at the top level. Costs and sponsors may be
factors: It costs $10 million to run a team.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the sport changed forever when tobacco ads were banned
from television. R.J. Reynolds began to support NASCAR as a way to
advertise its products. The group's top series was renamed for
Winston cigarettes. The teams became more professional as the
purses grew; at least $2 million today compared to $1,500 in 1949.
Audiences grew, too. Estimates put attendance at the Winston Cup
Series races last year at 6 million; more than 150 million
television viewers watched.
</P>
<P>
   The personalities themselves became businesses. Among the most
successful is Richard Petty, whose cowboy-hatted profile identifies
his trucks and a line of products ranging from a limited 1991
edition of Pontiac Grand Prix automobiles to hot sauce. There is
now even a NASCAR Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, NASCAR's brightest star, has brought in a lot of young
male fans, but many old-timers see him merely as a winning machine,
and hard to identify with. ``We still haven't had that driver who
could do for us what Ali did for boxing, what Namath did for
football, what Babe Ruth did for baseball,'' Wheeler said. ``We
need the guy who can transport us out of the sport and into the
mainstream, who will take us onto the cover of Time rather than the
cover of Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler misses the old days. ``We still need that rough, tough,
good old boy who can mix it up on the track,'' he said. ``We don't
want 20 guys walking in wearing Brooks Brothers suits and Gucci
shoes, drinking tea down in the pit lane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-NASCAR-REVIEW-ART-N     05-20 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NASCAR-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW STOCK CARS BECAME ICONS OF AMERICANA 
