<P>
   The personalities themselves became businesses. Among the most
successful is Richard Petty, whose cowboy-hatted profile identifies
his trucks and a line of products ranging from a limited 1991
edition of Pontiac Grand Prix automobiles to hot sauce. There is
now even a NASCAR Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, NASCAR's brightest star, has brought in a lot of young
male fans, but many old-timers see him merely as a winning machine,
and hard to identify with. ``We still haven't had that driver who
could do for us what Ali did for boxing, what Namath did for
football, what Babe Ruth did for baseball,'' Wheeler said. ``We
need the guy who can transport us out of the sport and into the
mainstream, who will take us onto the cover of Time rather than the
cover of Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler misses the old days. ``We still need that rough, tough,
good old boy who can mix it up on the track,'' he said. ``We don't
want 20 guys walking in wearing Brooks Brothers suits and Gucci
shoes, drinking tea down in the pit lane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-VATICAN-SECRETS-REVIE     05-20 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-SECRETS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN REVELATIONS: THE THIRD SECRET RAISES MORE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Vatican's belated disclosure of the third secret of
Fatima last week was a little like the FBI announcing that Elvis
is, in fact, dead.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation that the long-suppressed prophecy contained a
vision of something that has already come to pass, the 1981
assassination attempt on John Paul II, deflated decades of
conspiracy theories and doomsday predictions (nowadays broadcast on
dozens of Fatima Web sites). Most third-secret devotees were
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Fatima, revered by Roman Catholics as a place where the Virgin
Mary appeared to three Portuguese shepherd children in 1917, has
long held a broader fascination for people attracted to unsolved,
spooky mysteries. Fatima addicts maintain that the third secret was
so terrifying _ their conjectures ranging from schism to nuclear
annihilation _ that no pope dared reveal it.
</P>
<P>
   And, as is so often the case when the Vatican lifts a veil to
appease public opinion, it raises more questions. So many, in fact,
that the Fatima mystery lives on: The Vatican's effort to end
tabloid sensationalism and cultish obsession has already spawned
new conspiracy theories.
</P>
<P>
   And doubting Thomases. The Rev. Nicholas Gruner, director of the
Fatima Center in Fort Erie, Ontario, who has a quarterly magazine,
``Fatima Crusader'' and a Web site (www.fatima.org), has been
lobbying for full disclosure since 1978. Immediately after the
Vatican announcement last week, Gruner said in a press release:
``We pray that the original will be photographically reproduced for
wide distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``original'' is believed to be a handwritten description of
the third secret by Sister Lucia de Santos, 93, the only surviving
Fatima witness, who became a Carmelite nun. Sister de Santos
declined to include the third part of the prophecy in her 1941
memoirs recounting the apparitions of the Virgin that, she said,
began on May 13, 1917. (May 13 is also the date that Mehmet Ali
Agca shot the pope. John Paul II, who has visited Fatima three
times, has credited the Virgin of Fatima with saving his life.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Fatima historians, Sister de Santos fell so ill in
1943 that her local bishop instructed her to write down the third
secret. Too scared to read it himself, he sent it to Rome in 1957.
Five popes declined to make the secret public _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend at Fatima, on May 13, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the
Vatican secretary of state, told 600,000 believers gathered to see
the pope that the prophecy revealed to the shepherds was a vision
of a ``bishop clothed in white'' who ``falls to the ground, amid
the corpses of those who were martyred, apparently dead, under a
burst of gunfire.'' He interpreted it as a prophecy of the 1981
shooting and said the Vatican would soon publish the secret, with a
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday was the first time the pope has ever addressed
the third secret. ``I thought it opportune to make public the
contents of the so-called third part of the secret,'' he told
believers at a general audience in St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has not yet explained why its experts are certain
the vision referred to John Paul II and not, for example, to the
white-robed archbishop of San Salvador, Oscar Arnulfo Romero, who
was shot and killed by right-wing death squads on March 24, 1980,
while celebrating Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But that interpretation would clash with Fatima's anti-communist
mystique. The first of the so-called Fatima secrets supposedly
predicted the end of World War I and the coming of World War II.
The second secret, believers say, augured that Soviet communism
would spread, then collapse and Russia would convert to
Christianity. The latter vision made Fatima an ideological shrine
for anti-communists in the Cold War, and the shooting of an
anti-communist Polish pope neatly fit the pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Scoffing at Wednesday's announcement as a ``made to measure
revelation,'' Gian Enrico Rusconi, a political scientist at the
University of Turin, wrote in the Turin daily La Stampa of the
pope-centered revelation as ``frankly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some believers were disbelieving. ``It's disappointing,''
Julio Estela, 33, a Portuguese car salesman, said after the
cardinal spoke. ``I think there is more.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone. ``I believe that the third secret also spoke
of crises and divisions within the church since the Second Vatican
Council,'' Rene Laurentin, a French monk and prominent theologian
of the cult of Mary, told Italian reporters. The chief exorcist for
the Diocese of Rome and the president of the International
Association of Exorcists, the Rev. Gabriele Amorth, said the
announcement left him ``perplexed.''
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants gave the Vatican points for spin control.
Fabrizio Rondolino, an adviser to former Italian Prime Minister
Massimo d'Alema, wrote in La Stampa, ``The dependency on ever
greater doses of the supernatural, from Padre Pio to Fatima,
responds to a strategic need of the church: to recuperate, in this
way, the unconventional forms of contemporary spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only person who took the Vatican announcement at
face value besides the pope was his would-be assassin. Among the
many conflicting statements that Agca, a Turkish national, gave
prosecutors in 1985 was a claim that the shooting ``is connected to
the third secret of the Madonna of Fatima.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the disclosure, Agca has given interviews saying he acted
alone _ up to a point. ``But Agca feels he was part of a larger
design, something bigger than he,'' said his lawyer, Marina
Magistrelli, who added that after the Vatican revelation, ``now
perhaps more people will believe him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
