<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-1STLD     05-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (subs to include additional brief at end)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crunching Numbers on the Hustings
</P>
<P>
   They sounded at times as if they were running for
actuary-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years from now, the massive baby-boomer generation will
begin drawing benefits,'' declared Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore countered, ``The numbers just don't add
up, and under the Bush plan a serious reduction of our national
debt is simply impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue under discussion by the presumptive Republican and
Democratic nominees for president was a vital one, if not exactly
the sort that stops voters' hearts: how to protect the Social
Security system, which both candidates say is slowly going broke.
Speaking in Southern California, Bush announced a plan for
reforming the federal retirement-benefits system that would allow
workers to invest some of their payroll taxes in private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fundamental difference between my opponent and
me,'' Bush said. ``He trusts the government to manage our
retirement. I trust individual Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore argued that Bush's plan misplaces its trust by exposing
workers' retirement money to the mercy of the markets and making it
impossible for the government to pay down the national debt. ``Tens
of millions of investors who have not gone through the Fordham
Business School,'' Gore said, ``would be placed in a situation
where a lot of financial shenanigans could take place.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also revealed a protective streak with his
own investments. After Bush told reporters that Gore had a lot of
money in stocks, Gore replied that he had not invested in the
markets in 25 years for fear of an appearance of a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth over money matters came as a New York
Times/CBS News poll showed that most voters are thinking less about
candidates' detailed fiscal calculations than about how nice they
seem. Bush was favored over Gore in the new poll by 47 percent to
39 percent, and although more respondents liked Gore's stands on
the issues, they liked Bush even more as a person.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   Using a Mouse to Check for Mice
</P>
<P>
   Vermin. There it was in blue and white, highlighted for all the
cyberworld to see. Vermin at Le Bernardin. Vermin, ruthless and
undiscriminating, the great equalizer of the restaurant world.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough week for restaurants in the nation's toughest
town, as the New York City Department of Health began posting
inspection reports on the World Wide Web. From the humblest Dunkin
Donuts to the extra-chic Le Bernardin, their dirty linen, so to
speak, was on display.
</P>
<P>
   So intense was the interest in the misdeeds of the eating
establishments that the department's Web site was paralyzed within
hours of its opening on Wednesday morning. By the afternoon, the
site was getting 23,000 hits an hour, far more than it could
handle, and by Friday visitors were still being turned away because
of high traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet site (http://207.127.96.244/webfood/search.htm)
provides summaries of inspection reports for each of the city's
18,000 restaurants. Some restaurateurs who felt scorched by the
reports complained that the Health Department did not provide
enough information.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the staff at Le Bernardin, consistently rated one
of the finest restaurants in the city, bristled at the report of
``vermin or other live animal'' in their food storage, preparation
or service areas. What really happened, said Eric Ripert, the
restaurant's chef, was that an inspector found mice droppings in a
single bag of flour. ``We talked to our purveyor right away and
they changed all the flour,'' he said. ``I don't think we have a
mouse in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE FRITSCH
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani Abandons Campaign For U.S. Senate Seat
</P>
<P>
   What would a week in New York be without at least one jolting
development in the race for U.S. Senate? So it was that on Friday,
four days after Hillary Rodham Clinton was formally designated as
the Democratic candidate at her party's convention in Albany, New
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani quit the race at a
packed-to-the-rafters news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the only real surprise was how long Giuliani took to
make the decision, which came after three weeks in which it was
revealed that he was suffering from prostate cancer, that he had
struck up a close relationship with a woman who wasn't his wife and
that he was seeking a separation from his wife, Donna Hanover,
after 16 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he needed to devote all his energy to deciding on
a course of treatment and running the city. The Republican Party
quickly turned to the future: at week's end, the most likely
replacement for Giuliani was Rep. Rick A. Lazio, a Long Island
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ADAM NAGOURNEY
</P>
<P>
   Arrests in 1963 Bombing
</P>
<P>
   Justice delayed may not be justice served, but Alabama
prosecutors figure it is better than nothing. A grand jury indicted
Thomas E. Blanton Jr. and Bobby Frank Cherry for the murder of four
black girls in the 1963 bombing of 16th Street Baptist Church in
Birmingham. Only one man, Robert Chambliss, has been tried in the
case, one of the most heinous acts of the civil rights era. He was
convicted in 1977. Blanton and Cherry are both former Ku Klux Klan
members and have been suspects since the 1960s. Prosecutors plan to
use old and newly developed evidence.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
