<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0885 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-REVIEW     05-20 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED, BUT HOW BADLY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When French troops in Bosnia captured Momcilo
Krajisnik last month, making him the highest-ranking Bonsian Serb
in the custody of the war crimes tribunal in The Hague,
Netherlands, Western officials said his arrest was a warning to
those suspects still at large that they could not sleep so easily
any more.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials here and in The Hague sounded a lot less
smug.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Dragoljub Ojdanic, the Yugoslav defense minister who was
indicted for crimes committed during Serbia's campaign against
Kosovo's Albanians, had just spent five days in Russia, where he
was received as a dignitary despite the fact that international law
obliged Russia to arrest the man.
</P>
<P>
   Ojdanic's visit dismayed supporters of the tribunal, but there
was little they or the State Department could do beside issue
public condemnations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the visit underscored the fundamental frustration
facing the tribunal. Despite its recent successes in arresting and
trying war crimes suspects from the former Yugoslavia, the most
senior military and political figures under indictment remain
safely out of reach, starting with President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   While they may have curtailed some activities _ Milosevic is
unlikely to risk a trip abroad _ their status as the world's most
wanted men has not scared them completely underground.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after Krajisnik's arrest, a respected Bosnian
newsweekly published a detailed account of the comings and goings
of Radovan Karadzic, the political leader of Bosnia's Serbs and
also a wanted man. The same report said that Ratko Mladic, who
commanded the Bosnian Serb army, often traveled from Serbia to
visit his farm in Bosnia, where he keeps bees, despite the presence
of 20,000 NATO-led peacekeepers. A month before, he had appeared at
a soccer match in Belgrade _ with bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration over the failure to catch these men prompted the
State Department to print up thousands of ``Wanted'' posters, to be
distributed in Bosnia, that offered $5 million for information
about their whereabouts. The effort drew immediate derision _ and
not just because the first batch was printed in English (a
Serbo-Croatian version appeared later), or because it included a
toll-free 800 telephone number that would work only in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., wrote to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright saying he had ``the information you are looking for.'' He
noted the most recent sightings of Milosevic and Mladic and even
gave Milosevic's address: 15 Uzicka St. in Belgrade, the
president's official residence. ( Helms asked that the reward money
go to a charity in North Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, it's natural that Serbia would become a haven for
wanted Serbs. But Helms and some human-rights advocates accuse wary
NATO peacekeepers of letting parts of Bosnia become havens too, out
of fear that arrests would provoke retaliation from nationalists
who support the suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-REVIEW     05-20 0571
