<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE-MERCHANTS (Omugo, Uganda) _ Melarsoprol is melarsen
oxide dissolved in propylene glycol _ literally, arsenic in
antifreeze. It kills 5 percent of those treated with it. But it is
the only medicine available to treat advanced sleeping sickness,
one of the historic scourges of Africa. The only alternative ran
out in July after the manufacturer abandoned it as unprofitable
when it turned out to be useless against its intended target,
cancer. Sleeping sickness is perhaps the most vivid example of the
disconnection between the world's pharmaceutical giants and the
fatal or debilitating diseases of the Third World's poor. A special
report. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-CITIZENSHIP (Geneva) _ Swiss law gives foreigners who meet
the residency requirements and have no criminal record the right to
apply for Swiss nationality as long as they are integrated into
Swiss society. But foreigners must virtually become more Swiss than
the Swiss to stand a chance of holding a passport. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-FUJIMORI (Lima, Peru) _ Alberto Fujimori faces a mounting
political crisis that will surely challenge his considerable pluck
and power. Alejandro Toledo, his opponent in the May 28 runoff
presidential election, dropped out of the race on Thursday.
Fujimori was left with an open field for victory, but one in which
his legitimacy and credibility would be questioned both here and
abroad. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Only two hours after Taiwan's
new president made his inaugural address, authorities in Beijing
released a surprisingly temperate response, charging him with a
lack of sincerity but not repeating the dire threats and invective
of recent weeks. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ The Clinton administration has argued
that Congress should vote for normal trade relations with China
because it will strengthen reformist forces in China. The vast
majority of influential Chinese agree. For millions of Chinese, in
fact, the congressional vote _ which, if positive, would ensure
China's full participation in the World Trade Organization _ has
taken on a transcendent aura beyond the boundaries of trade or
politics. By Elisabeth Rosenthal with Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-BILL (Washington) _ If the China trade bill slips
through Congress this week, as some supporters now expect, Sander
M. Levin, a Democrat who has voted against all of President
Clinton's major trade initiatives, will take some credit for
helping provide the margin of victory. Levin won backing from House
leaders late last week to amend the bill granting China permanent
trade ties, to establish a human rights and trade policy monitoring
commission for China. Vote counters on both sides of the aisle said
the proposal, co-sponsored by Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., has helped
recruit perhaps two dozen undecided lawmakers into the pro-trade
camp. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-RUSSIA (Warsaw, Poland) _ In Poland, long a trophy of
East-West competition and now one of NATO's newest members, the
installation of Vladimir Putin as Russia's president has raised new
questions about Moscow's intentions. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   BLAIR-BABY (London) _ Cherie Blair, the wife of Prime Minister
Tony Blair, gave birth to a baby boy early Saturday, and hours
later, mother, father and son left the London hospital for a quiet
weekend in the privacy of 10 Downing St. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MBEKI-AIDS (Undated) _ When President Thabo Mbeki of
South Africa said last year that AZT was too dangerous to give to
HIV-infected pregnant women, AIDS researchers and activists were
taken aback. The drug is commonly used to prevent transmission of
the disease to newborns. That reaction turned to shock when Mbeki
appointed an AIDS advisory panel that included researchers who have
postulated that HIV does not cause the disease, a position long
rejected by the overwhelming majority of doctors and scientists.
Now Mbeki is embarking on his first state visit to the United
States since succeeding Nelson Mandela as president last year, and
activists and those who treat AIDS are wondering how to greet him.
By Daniel J. Wakin.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SEPARATISTS (Janthoe Baru, Indonesia) _ Separatists in
Aceh, a staunchly Muslim region on the northern tip of Sumatra,
have been fighting for independence since 1976 and pose a major
problem for President Abdurrahman Wahid as he tries to stabilize
his nation of 210 million people. Many people say that it is of far
greater urgency for Indonesia to stop Aceh from slipping away than
it was in the case of East Timor, which voted for independence last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-DEATH-PENALTY (Chicago) _ Four months after he rekindled the
death penalty debate by imposing a moratorium on executions in
Illinois, Gov. George Ryan says he doubts any inmates will be put
to death while he remains in office. The governor, a Republican,
has appointed a commission to study ways to fix problems with the
death penalty and says he will not go ahead with executions unless
the panel can give him ``a 100 percent guarantee'' against any
mistaken death-row convictions. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-MEXICANS (Detroit) _ When 18-year-old Jesus Lopez
arrived here 18 years ago, he was convinced that those Mexicans who
had come before him were crazy. ``In those days, over here there
was only burned-out houses,'' he recalled. But today, Detroit is
being hailed as the nation's new Mexican boomtown. A wave of new
arrivals started showing up here six years ago, most directly from
Mexico. They say they came to escape rising costs and growing
hostilities against immigrants in Arizona, California and Chicago,
and to reunite with older relatives who had been cashing in on
Detroit's labor shortage for more than a decade. By Nichole M.
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-TREATMENT (New Orleans) _ Responding to a call to improve
the quality of cancer care in the United States, a leading cancer
organization said that it was working with other groups to develop
a national system to monitor how well each cancer patient is
treated. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   WONDERLAND-MURDERS (Los Angeles) _ Federal prosecutors have
reached back to history here to revive a sensational murder case,
unveiling an indictment that alleges that a former nightclub mogul,
his bodyguard and a pornography actor killed four people in the
Hollywood Hills nearly two decades ago. The ``Wonderland murders,''
so-named after the site, 4763 Wonderland Ave., where the killings
took place on July 1, 1981, proved a potent mix of seamy celebrity,
drugs and violence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO (Midland, Texas) _ Part 1: A Boy From Midland. Many of
the roots of George W. Bush's political philosophy as a
presidential candidate seem to go back to his childhood in Midland,
a conservative, up-from-the-bootstraps town that has grown from
25,000 when he was a little boy to almost 100,000 today. A special
report. Articles in this series will examine the lives of the
presidential candidates as the campaign progresses. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-WEBSITES (Undated) _ In the 2000 election, independent
and home-grown Web pages created by individual voters with some
Web-design skills and a little spare time are multiplying
exponentially. Often rivaling the sophistication of the official
Web sites, these grass-roots Web sites are a new way for ordinary
voters to engage in the political process _ a high-tech version,
many say, of putting a sign in a voter's front yard or a bumper
sticker on a car. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   POLTICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ A Republican invades Democratic
territory; Loophole inspires legislative end run; Internet
addresses as a political tool; A message to Bush: Listen to your
mama; On the road again in North Dakota. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID (Washington) _ Hundreds of millions of dollars set
aside by the federal government to help provide health insurance to
poor people leaving welfare remains unused because states have not
claimed the money, a new accounting by the Department of Health and
Human Services shows. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   DC-MAYOR (Washington) _ If all continues to go well, the
nation's capital will be allowed out of the intensive care ward
fashioned by Congress sometime next year. The District of Columbia
will not only regain home-rule prerogatives lost in its profligate
past; it will also confirm the stewardship of Mayor Anthony A.
Williams, an unlikely politician as bland in his style as the paint
on the municipal walls. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's a real, real world. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A trade policy tragedy. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
