<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 21, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This final budget adds YUGO-WARCRIMES-REVIEW and eliminates the
previously budgeted HEIGHT-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   LOSALAMOS-CHAOS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Theorists at the Los Alamos
lab who study complex systems ranging from financial markets to
thunderstorms _ not everyone there designs bombs _ often refer to a
phenomenon called ``sensitive dependence on initial conditions.''
Chaos, for short. Tiny actions can have enormous, unforeseeable
outcomes. The idea has entered the culture of popular science as
``the butterfly effect'': A butterfly flapping its wings in Rio de
Janeiro causes a hurricane off the coast of Louisiana. A small fire
routinely lit to clear a few hundred acres of tinder erupts into a
firestorm that closes down a nuclear facility and sends a plume of
smoke billowing into Texas and Colorado. By George Johnson. (Moved
in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-JERUSALEM-REVIEW (Abu Dis, West Bank) _ It took
Yasser Arafat many years to arrive at the gate of Jerusalem. But
last week, when Israel conceded to him full control of Abu Dis and
two other villages, the PLO chairman moved one step nearer to his
dream. The villages are a morsel of greater Jerusalem but one with
a bird's eye view of the gold-leafed Dome of the Rock. By Deborah
Sontag. (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   LISTON-CONSPIRACY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Americans love a conspiracy
theory, whether it concerns the murder of a president or the defeat
of a boxer. And so it is that, Muhammad Ali, who easily dispatched
Sonny Liston in the ring, may never beat him in popular mythology
and public opinion. There, Liston may forever be held up by the
famous ``phantom punch'' that floored him in their heavyweight
championship fight in 1965. The myth of that unseen punch is making
a comeback just in time for the 35th anniversary of the bout. A new
book, ``The Devil and Sonny Liston,'' and an upcoming biographical
movie are giving new life to old theories that the Mob or the Black
Muslims or someone besides Ali sent Liston to the canvas. By Allen
Barra.
</P>
<P>
   ABU-JAMAL-REVIEW (Undated) _ For whatever symbolic figures may
be worth, Mumia Abu-Jamal, whose appeal to the federal courts for a
new trial could receive a response any day now, has become the most
recognizable death row inmate. And while the United States is the
industrialized world's leader in executions, doubts are now raised
by mainstream politicians about how this accelerating aspect of
criminal justice can ever be run fairly enough for accused
murderers who can not afford a competent defense. But is Mumia the
right poster boy for the anti-death-penalty movement? By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-SCOTUS-REVIEW (Washington) _ To many interest groups on
both the left and the right, the 2000 presidential campaign is not
so much about whether Al Gore or George W. Bush makes it to the
White House. It's about who Gore or Bush would put on the Supreme
Court, where vacancies are a good possibility during the next
presidential term. Three of the nine justices are age 70 or older.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR-REVIEW (Undated) _ When racing commentators discussed
Adam Petty's death at the New Hampshire International Speedway last
week, few pointed out that he died far from Daytona, and in the
heart of Yankee country. NASCAR, once identified with the
Southeast, has traveled a long way since the first racers came
roaring down from the mountains in their bootlegging cars. By
Susanna Rodell.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SEASON-REVIEW (New York) _ After last week's annual four-day
rite in which network executives nervously announce their new
programs to advertisers, the question on the minds of media buyers,
talent agents and managers and TV executives at the elaborate
parties around the city was: Is this really the best that network
television can offer? By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   WILLS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Excepts from some memorable and
bizarre wills.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   WARLORDS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The capture of Foday Sankoh, the
notorious Sierra Leone warlord, highlights a longtime question:
Just how much business can good guys afford to do with bad guys?
The presumption in democratic societies these days is that
strongmen who inflict terrible crimes, whether on their neighbors
or on their own people, should pay for their wrongdoing. But the
reality has not been so simple. As the 1990s spawned warlords from
Yugoslavia to Haiti, from Cambodia to Africa, the basic principle
was often sacrificed to the pragmatic interests of striking peace
deals, no matter how dubious or shaky. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-SECRETS-REVIEW (Rome) _ When the Vatican revealed that
the long-suppressed 1917 prophecy called the Third Secret of Fatima
was something that has already happened _ the 1981 assassination
attempt on Pope John Paul II _ many conspiracy theories and
doomsday scenarios were deflated. Fatima junkies had believed the
Third Secret was so terrifying that no pope dared reveal it. But
somehow the Fatima mystery lives on; the Vatican's effort to end to
tabloid sensationalism and cultish obsession has instead spawned a
new breed of conspiracy theories. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-WARCRIMES-REVIEW (Washington) _ Wanted, but how badly?
Despite the war crimes tribunal's successes in arresting and trying
suspects from the former Yugoslavia, the most senior military and
political figures under indictment remain safely out of reach. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
