<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PARKS-INTERVIEW-3Take     05-20 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-INTERVIEW-3Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF DENIES SYSTEMATIC CIVIL RIGHTS ABUSES IN LAPD
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Daily News Staff Writers Alexa Haussler and Rick Orlov
contributed to this story.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Breaking his silence on the threatened federal
lawsuit against the LAPD, Chief Bernard C. Parks defended the
department's overall performance and denies it is guilty of
systematic civil rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   In his first interview since the U.S. Justice Department
ultimatum was issued two weeks ago, Parks told the Los Angeles
Daily News that key deficiencies identified by the LAPD's Board of
Inquiry _ management oversight, training and tracking officer
misconduct _ already are being corrected and reforms are being
implemented in light of the Rampart Division scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying that no one could go into our files and find
a use of force, an officer-involved shooting or a personnel matter
with which they would disagree,'' Parks said. ``But when you look
at the totality ... we don't see the actions or activities
citywide, or in the concentration (of Rampart).
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, if it was a pattern and practice, then the
management would condone the activities or actions of employees, or
the training perpetuates those activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department under acting civil rights chief Bill Lann
Lee, a former Los Angeles attorney, has threatened to sue the city
alleging ``a pattern and practice'' of civil rights violations by
the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the government's case, based on a four-year
investigation, have not been revealed to city officials, who are
negotiating a possible consent decree that could lead to
appointment of a federal monitor and allow a federal judge to
review the department's performance.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview late last week, Parks insisted the LAPD's
problems can be, and are being, corrected by the department's
management.
</P>
<P>
   Even as crime is dropping, Parks said problem officers are being
disciplined or retrained, as evidenced by a steep decline in
reported use of force, officer-involved shootings and vehicle
pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is not being addressed citywide or
departmentwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said that while dirty-cop-turned-informant Rafael Perez
and his partners engaged in a practice of illegally arresting
people, the department's investigations don't support a wider
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen that occur citywide, or in any kind of
conscious or orchestrated event,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a variety of ways people (officers) have gotten in
trouble, but many of them are isolated, where officers made poor
decisions. But that's not something that's condoned by the
department, nor is it a conspiracy among officers to do something
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks also expressed concern about the impact of a consent
decree that would give a monitor and federal judge oversight of the
LAPD, undermining, he said, the ability of any chief to run the
department successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd think that in order to have some real benefit from the
chief of police, you've got to allow him to do his job,'' he added.
``If you say you need another layer of involvement, then there's no
incentive for chiefs to be honest and forthright in their
departments.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks' comments came as Los Angeles officials led by City
Attorney James Hahn have opened talks with Lee and other Justice
Department officials about reforming the LAPD in the face of
charges that there is a pattern of excessive force, false arrests
and unreasonable searches and seizures by officers.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic schools of thought on what violates the
relatively untested ``pattern or practice'' statute signed into law
under the 1994 Crime Bill, civil rights and government lawyers tend
to agree.
</P>
<P>
   One test is whether a department has engaged in a high number of
civil rights violations; the second is whether its management has
condoned or minimized egregious acts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mayor Richard Riordan's assurances the Justice
Department won't sue the city and that an agreement can be reached
that would maintain local control of the LAPD, there is no
indication federal attorneys are backing away from their consent
decree demand, with its oversight punch repugnant to Parks and
other LAPD managers.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and his Justice Department staff in a meeting last week gave
city leaders a six-inch stack of copies of consent decrees obtained
for police departments in Pittsburgh; Steubenville, Ohio; and the
New Jersey Department of Law and Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Imposition of an LAPD consent decree has a unified lobby in
local civil rights groups and lawyers - some with close ties to Lee
or members of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chief is wrong; it would be foolish to try to
litigate this case,'' said Michael Small, chief counsel for the
American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California and a former
Justice Department civil rights division attorney in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Justice Department, the ACLU has seized on the LAPD's
Board of Inquiry review of the Rampart corruption scandal as an
admission of widespread civil rights violations. Parks calls that a
misinterpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reads like a road map to bring a pattern and practice
lawsuit at least for a failure to oversee Rampart CRASH (Community
Resources Against Street Hoodlums),'' Small said of the LAPD
internal investigation released March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's chock-full of events on the street, and descriptions of a
management and supervision style that's the kernel of a pattern and
practice lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU has urged the Justice Department to include racial
profiling remedies in any consent decree, following a federal
lawsuit filed in February alleging the constitutional rights of
minority drivers routinely are violated by LAPD officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know about the racial profiling lawsuit and we've
suggested that racial profiling be placed on the table,'' said
Small, who as a Justice Department attorney participated in
monitoring the Pittsburgh racial profiling element of that city's
consent decree.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has declined to discuss the details of the case. City
officials said they're encouraged they will be advised of the
specifics in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said today's police force is far different from the one
the Christopher Commission found in 1991 to contain dozens of
problem officers who had gone unidentified by the department or
were tolerated despite repeated citizen complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation has been obscured, he said, by the Rampart
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling reform from a civil rights perspective
is an LAPD order issued last month requiring watch commanders to
review the probable cause for all people who are jailed, and to
check them for injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said Rampart was a vector that pointed out systemwide
indifference among officers to the correct processing of
incarcerated persons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were not paying attention when arrestees were put into
custody,'' Parks said. ``People were being taken off the street and
taken to jail without the review of a supervisor. Rampart alerted
us to it, but it's a systemwide issue. We corrected it
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks claims a series of other measures show the LAPD is
addressing its shortcomings and moving in the right direction.
Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --Discretion to reject citizen complaints has been removed from
area supervisors, who culled out so many complaints in the past
that citizen concerns were severely underreported. The number of
citizen complaints under department review jumped from 1,800 in
1997 to about 5,000 in each of the last two years, Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   --Citizens can no longer stop investigations by rescinding
complaints. An unusual number of rescinded complaints were recorded
at Rampart CRASH, where people said officers intimidated them to
recant.
</P>
<P>
   --Captains who sit on disciplinary boards of rights have been
instructed by Parks to impose suitably severe penalties on officers
found guilty of administrative allegations. In 1998 and 1999, a
total of 100 officers were fired. Over the previous seven years, 95
officers were fired, LAPD records show.
</P>
<P>
   --A complete review of discipline would show more officers are
punished for verbal or physical abuse of citizens, Parks contended.
A review of 1998 terminations showed six officers fired for on-duty
transgressions involving force, verbal abuse or lack of probable
cause. The other 48 officers were fired for a variety of on- and
off-duty infractions.
</P>
<P>
   --Officers are more likely to be assigned to a desk job for
serious violations that fall short of termination, and sometimes
forfeit the right to carry a weapon, Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   --The reconstitution of CRASH into anti-gang units that are
trained in gang abatement, but restrained from doing major
narcotics work, has been completed. Before Perez was convicted of
stealing $1 million worth of cocaine from a department evidence
locker, he said he and other cops gave drugs to informants, planted
evidence on suspects and sold drugs.
</P>
<P>
   --Limiting use of informants to detectives, and in rare
instances to other officers with advance permission, is now
standard policy.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said in his estimation the department has finally done
what its critics have demanded for decades: reviewed and then
talked about itself candidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we haven't broken the code of silence in our (Board of
Inquiry) report, then when does this code of silence get broken?''
</P>
<P>
   Small, the ACLU's chief counsel, said complaints of LAPD officer
mistreatment continue to pour into the office.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``hundreds'' of complaints alleging racial
profiling in stopping minority drivers, Small said there is
considerable anecdotal evidence of continued civil rights
violations on the streets of minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard hundreds of other people who have had terrifying
encounters with gang units over the last couple of years and
continuing to the present day - so much so as to suggest the
Justice Department is right on in saying there is a pattern and
practice of abuse across town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John W. Harris, who grew up in Watts, said that in the
absence of empirical evidence to substantiate an across-the-board
civil rights accusation, the perception of such a pattern persists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually manifests itself in people sharing stories. A
certain person is stopped and harassed for no apparent reason;
minority drivers get stopped more often than white,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Justice Department lawyers have been provided with
such anecdotal evidence in support of minority communities'
insistence that the infection of police abuse persists.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the stories we hear, it's not just some rogue cops at
Rampart; we're talking about lawless officers all over town,''
Small said.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said the department faces a long road to complete the
reform process and re-establish its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Central is a new computer tracking system, which would
efficiently give managers the kind of narrative on problem officers
necessary to make informed decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The existing system _ subject to harsh Justice Department
criticism _ is more an indicator of problems, but prone to failure
if managers don't follow up with time-consuming paper research. A
federal grant to improve the system was never used by the
department _ an issue that has been seized on by critics of the
LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said ultimately no single reform is the panacea, but
rather the integration of better systems with better-trained
managers is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has solidly backed him in the face of intense
criticism, and Parks said he will not back down in his beliefs
about reforming the LAPD, nor will he walk away from the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll continue on as chief as long as the city allows me to,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
