<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-ART-NYT     05-20 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS POLITICAL CRISIS MOUNTS, PERU'S LEADER RELISHES FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Taking a break from a boisterous campaign rally the
other day in the colonial city of Cajamarca, President Alberto
Fujimori pointed to a dark cloud gliding over his head and cried,
``Let there be rain for the farmers!''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, the sky poured open, and thousands cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' Fujimori laughed into his microphone.
``Everything is coordinated.''
</P>
<P>
   It has often seemed that way over the last 10 years, as Fujimori
effectively confronted an array of plagues _ from hyperinflation to
terrorism to an invasion of narcotics traffickers, from war with
Ecuador to massive flooding caused by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   But only a day after Fujimori played with the clouds over
Cajamarca, he faced a political crisis that will surely challenge
his considerable pluck and power. Alejandro Toledo, his opponent in
the May 28 runoff presidential election, dropped out of the race on
Thursday. Fujimori was left with an open field for victory and the
prospect of a third five-year term, but one in which his legitimacy
and credibility would be questioned both here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori now faces the possibility of unending protest marches,
criticism from Washington and other capitals, and even, perhaps,
economic sanctions from the U.S. Congress and the Organization of
American States that could impede his fight against drug
trafficking and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old president, who is the son of Japanese
immigrants, was able to face down international pressures after he
suspended the operations of his own Congress and Supreme Court in
1992 because he had overwhelming popular support. But now Peru is
badly split, with university students and labor unions preparing to
mount the biggest street protests in more than a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, in effect, has become a victim of his own success. Now
that he has virtually defeated the terrorists of the Maoist Shining
Path, a growing number of Peruvians are seeking an easing of his
authoritarianism. In the last three years, even as the terrorism
waned, Fujimori did not ease his hold on power. He tightened it.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori decided he could run for re-election even though the
constitution prohibits three consecutive terms. He had three judges
dismissed by Congress when they disagreed with his legal
interpretation that the constitutional term limit did not cover his
first term because it was completed before the constitution itself.
He then established control over several television networks
through legal maneuvers, and withdrew Peru from the jurisdiction of
a regional human rights court.
</P>
<P>
   His powers were amply on display in the first round of the
presidential race when all television networks, save for one cable
channel, virtually boycotted his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been manipulating so much that even if he won fairly,
people wouldn't believe it was a fair process,'' said Enrique
Zileri, editor of the political magazine Caretas. ``Whatever
happens, Fujimori becomes a much weaker president who will be
discredited internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernan Chaparro Melo, a pollster, said, ``With 57 percent of the
people continuing to believe the election process is unjust, we are
entering difficult times.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori has had his back to the wall before, and he has
always shown himself to be a leader of great resourcefulness and
impeccable timing.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few weeks, Fujimori has emerged from his early
campaign slumber and appeared eager for a fight. He told
enthusiastic campaign rallies that he would not accept a
postponement of the election even before Toledo demanded that the
vote be put off several weeks to give foreign election observers
time to test computer software installed to count the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has sharpened his message, arguing more forcefully that
he is the one candidate strong enough to lead this desperately poor
and often chaotic country. Taking on his greatest weaknesses, he
pledged an all-out attack on unemployment and confronted his
foreign critics with diatribes designed to inspire Peruvian
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need foreigners to tell us how to hold elections,''
Fujimori told a crowd in the city of Trujillo shortly after
Toledo's announcement that he was dropping out of the race if the
election was not postponed.
</P>
<P>
   After underestimating Toledo, an U.S.-educated business school
professor who rose meteorically in the weeks before the first round
vote, Fujimori finally began taking him on _ calling him a
rudderless, indecisive leader who only knows how to turn to
Washington, Buenos Aires and European capitals for political
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's magic was amply on display last week as he toured the
north of the country. He laughed, danced and gleefully tossed
cassettes of his campaign songs to passers-by who thrilled at
seeing their president.
</P>
<P>
   As a brass band played his campaign theme song, Fujimori went
into a fevered jig on the stump as a throng of more than 10,000
went wild. ``My advisers tell me I shouldn't dance,'' Fujimori
laughed, ``but I can't help myself!'' It was the kind of populist
touch that led him to landslide victories in 1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in his heavily accented English for effect, he told the
crowd, ``They ask: `What is happening in Peru?''' Then answering
the question firmly in Spanish, he said, ``We've had a government
the last 10 years that has been decisive and has never ducked the
tough issues.''
</P>
<P>
   To crowds that filled the central plaza of Cajamarca, a highland
city of magnificent baroque churches, luscious cheeses and lyrical
poets where the Incas made their first stand against the Spanish
invaders in the 16th century, Fujimori called on the crowd to cheer
loud enough so the Argentine government could hear.
</P>
<P>
   He snickered at Toledo for traveling to Buenos Aires to consult
with President Fernando de la Rua and former President Raul
Alfonsin.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his opponents, he said: ``If they were really
democrats and really trusted the people, they wouldn't complain all
the time in Washington and Buenos Aires. They show by going abroad
that they don't care about the votes of the Peruvian people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
