extraordinary pressure; they must weigh the lofty moral and
educational standards of their schools against students, sports
fans, wealthy alumni and donors demanding success on the playing
field. Seldom have the contending forces _ and the potential risks
to a university's reputation _ been more evident than at Indiana
University last week, when the legendary basketball coach, Bob
Knight, escaped dismissal even though the university president and
trustees concluded he had a long history of abusive behavior,
including choking a player and bullying a secretary. By James C.
McKinley Jr.
