<HEADLINE>
TWO DREAMS OF JERUSALEM CONVERGE IN A BLUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (repeats to add art notes) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABU DIS, West Bank _ It took Yasser Arafat many years to arrive
at the gate of Jerusalem. But last week, when Israel conceded to
him full control of Abu Dis and two other villages, the chairman of
the Palestine Liberation Organization moved one step nearer to a
dream that had sustained him through his exile in Tunisia. The
villages are a morsel of greater Jerusalem, but one with a bird's
eye view of the gold-leafed Dome of the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is well known to be an intense symbolic focal point
for both Israelis and Palestinians _ as well as for Jews,
Christians and Muslims worldwide. But when the dusty neighboring
town of Abu Dis was finally given over to Palestinian control, it
briefly reminded everyone that even physical Jerusalem is a loaded
concept: Its borders, fixed on a map, are blurred on the ground in
an emotionally complicated, politicized way.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Dis epitomizes a reality usually obscured in the simplistic
public debate about Jerusalem and its fate: Just as the village is
integrated with the Jerusalem area geographically, economically and
socially, East Jerusalem itself is entwined with the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   That became clear last week, but it was still left unsaid.
Jerusalem is rarely publicly discussed by Israeli or Palestinian
leaders in anything but black-and-white terms. It is the ``eternal,
undivided capital'' of Israel, on the one hand, and the future
capital of the Palestinian state on the other: seemingly
irreconcilable concepts that have led many intelligent politicians
to recommend that the issue be left unresolved in the current,
supposedly final, peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerusalem is very much on the table in the serious,
non-secret back-channel negotiations that are under way in
Stockholm. And experts agree that the private discussion will have
to be creative and realistic enough to take into account the
lessons of Abu Dis and acknowledge that the dynamic on the
Jerusalem issue shifted last week, even if quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when you are talking about sovereignty, the Palestinian
people will say we are in the sphere,'' said Zakaria al Qaq,
co-director of the Israel/Palestine Center for Research and
Information in Jerusalem. ``It is no longer pure abstraction. That
battle for Jerusalem that was being waged long distance will now be
fought up close.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Israel's decision was hardly celebrated. In fact, as the
Parliament was voting to transfer the territory to the
Palestinians, the West Bank was aflame in violent confrontation
with the Israelis. When the intense violence died down,
Palestinians made it clear that they were not elated, even if they
were relieved. Israel was supposed to withdraw from 28 villages in
the Jerusalem area by last year under the Oslo peace agreement,
they said. Just three was too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   And furthermore: Abu Dis looks like a village and, with raw
sewage flowing roadside, it smells like a village. No Palestinian
will ever mistake Abu Dis for Jerusalem itself. If the Israelis
intend it as an alternative capital for the Palestinians state,
which is what Barak seemed to be saying last week, Palestinians
find this an insult, a joke and a deal-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Abu Dis is closer to the heart of the contested city than
is the Israeli Parliament or the Israeli prime minister's
headquarters. After the physical transfer takes place, Arafat can
be photographed with his uniformed troops against the backdrop of
the famous minaret of the holy city's skyline. He can open an
office in the town's modern new governmental building and place his
desk chair in Jerusalem proper, since the building is reportedly a
few feet over the border.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Israeli right wing reacted last week with audible
emotion _ anger. They saw the concession of Abu Dis to mean that
the peace talks had come to the endpoint they had long feared: a
negotiation over the status of Jerusalem itself. In tours of Abu
Dis, they found out what Palestinians know: Abu Dis and the other
two villages may not be Jerusalem, but on the ground that
distinction vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   The municipal border actually transects the town, so the only
way to tell where Jerusalem leaves off and Abu Dis begins is by the
city sidewalks that abruptly end. Abu Dis residents work in
Jerusalem, shop in Jerusalem and pray in Jerusalem _ whether or not
they have proper papers to move back and forth. There are seven
checkpoints leading to Jerusalem from the West Bank, one official
noted, but there are 70 roads and paths by which to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current municipal boundaries are irrelevant,'' said
Menachem Klein, a senior fellow at the Jerusalem Institute for
Israel Studies. ``Abu Dis is part of Jerusalem functionally, just
as the 200,000 Palestinians in Jerusalem are part of the West Bank.
No Israeli or Palestinian leader can ignore this reality, whatever
they say publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
