<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIRAMAX-STUDIO-2TAKES     05-20 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRAMAX-STUDIO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE STATES AUDITION FOR PLUM ROLE: HOLLYWOOD EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., N.Y.)   By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are the bouquets and bonbons of the
economic-development world, and these days they are raining down on
Robert De Niro, the Academy Award-winning actor, and Miramax Films,
which are still looking for a place to build a sprawling film
studio.
</P>
<P>
   New York state is down on one knee, pledging a road and perhaps
even a sewer system. New Jersey is whispering sweet nothings about
sales tax exemptions and possibly a direct capital investment. And
Connecticut, though hush-hush about its exact courtship strategy,
is also dangling tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven months since a tentative film studio deal between
New York City, De Niro and Miramax Films collapsed, the three
states have wasted no time in wooing the taciturn film star and his
influential partner, Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax.
Officials say they are eager to pick up the ball they believe Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani dropped.
</P>
<P>
   It was no secret that the partners felt burned when the Giuliani
administration announced in October that it had chosen another set
of developers to build studios at the Brooklyn Navy Yard. Giuliani
had, after all, tried out his best Godfather imitation for De Niro
and then held a glittering news conference in Brooklyn about their
collective vision for a sound stage complex there.
</P>
<P>
   But the city's sudden shift in favor of other developers (after
administration members decided that that group would build the
studios faster and require less city money) apparently did not dim
the interest of De Niro in creating a film studio in the New York
region. Although a record number of films and television shows have
been shot in New York and New Jersey in recent years, members of
the movie industry and state officials have long complained about
the area's shortage of sound stages, which has forced filmmakers to
go to Los Angeles and Toronto for indoor photography.
</P>
<P>
   The leading studio site contenders appear to be properties in
the city of Yonkers, N.Y., in southern Westchester County, and in
the Hudson County, N.J., town of Harrison, two municipalities
desperate to redevelop their industrial waterfronts with the sort
of sexy centerpiece that the movie partners could provide. De Niro
and Weinstein had briefly considered sites in New York City, but
they have zeroed in on those two tracts, according to someone who
went on some of the tours.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Miramax, a subsidiary of the Walt Disney Co., nor De
Niro's company, TriBeCa Productions, would comment on their quest
for a parcel. But people who have met with the actor and Weinstein
and have seen architects' sketches for the two sites say their plan
goes beyond a large film studio to include housing and possibly
stores and restaurants. Such elements could make the proposal more
attractive to investors skittish about the possibility of studios
sitting empty between productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a dire need for studios in New York,'' said Charles A.
Gargano, chairman of the Empire State Development Corp., New York
state's economic development agency. ``The problem is these things
do not work by themselves. They do not generate enough money, so
they have to have some additional development with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some developers and film executives doubt whether Miramax and
TriBeCa Productions will ever get a shovel in the ground. They cite
a series of grand plans for film studios in recent years that
either evaporated or were drastically scaled back, mostly for lack
of financing.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned late last year, for instance, was an ambitious plan to
build a television and movie studio complex on top of a Manhattan
office building at Houston and West Streets. The $160 million
project, called Hudson River Studios, was to include five sound
stages. But the developers lost their financing after two soap
operas that had committed to using the space pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, after years of robust growth, the number of feature
films shot in New York City actually fell by 12 last year to 209.
The Mayor's Office of Film, Theater and Broadcasting is quick to
point out that film production was down slightly nationwide as
well. But the office still contends that there is not enough studio
space in New York to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. They cite a glut of studio space in Los Angeles
and fear an eventual glut in the New York region, too, especially
if the developer selected for the Brooklyn Navy Yard, New York
Studios, realizes its plan for 11 sound stages. The development
group, led by Douglas C. Steiner, is demolishing buildings at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   And Kaufman Astoria Studios in Queens is adding a seventh
studio, but its president, Hal G. Rosenbluth, said: ``We're pushing
the envelope to believe you can build dozens of stages and actually
fill them. We're never going to displace Hollywood. All the
creative decisions to green-light things are still in Los Angeles,
and the majority of the actors, directors and producers live in
L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials in New York and New Jersey are downright bubbly,
promoting the superiority of their respective sites as they
assemble incentive packages for De Niro and Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is more coy. Edward Dombroskas, executive director
of the state's film office, said the filmmakers ``are looking at a
couple of different sites, but I can't reveal where they are.''
Dombroskas was also hush-hush about incentives, but did say breaks
on sales and property taxes were available to companies locating in
so-called entertainment zones.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, the filmmakers are looking at a former steel
plant on the Passaic River in Harrison, according to local and
state officials. In 1998, an independent film production company in
Manhattan, the Shooting Gallery, settled on the same 41-acre site
for a grandiose studio plan with 15 sound stages and a $75 million
price tag. That plan was abandoned for a much smaller project in
Manhattan, on Leroy Street in the West Village.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison officials think a Miramax-De Niro studio would have a
better chance of succeeding given the principals' track records.
The mayor of Harrison, Raymond J. McDonough, said he met with
representatives of TriBeCa Productions and Miramax only three weeks
ago, and ``they asked me how they could obtain all the property in
the redevelopment area.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials are offering several lures, from financing
through the Hudson County Improvement Authority to annual payments
to the studio company over 10 years that would represent a portion
of the state income tax revenue generated by the new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Gualberto Medina, New Jersey's secretary of commerce, said the
state was also considering a direct investment of money in the
project and was working with the filmmakers on a ``joint request
for proposals'' from potential real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
   Local and state officials said the Harrison property would be
perfect for a studio complex: It has a cavernous column-free
building with 103,000 square feet and a 100-foot-high ceiling, and
it is across the street from a PATH train station. Gregory J.
Castano, the lawyer for the Harrison Redevelopment Agency, said,
``No other site offers a building like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yonkers site, a former wire factory, also has a building
with a 100-foot ceiling, sans columns, although it is smaller, at
30,000 square feet. The 13-acre parcel may be a bit cramped for a
mixed-used development, but it is a striking location, sitting
alongside the Hudson River, with the wooded cliffs of the Palisades
across the way and the Manhattan skyline to the south. It, too, is
convenient to public transportation, with a Metro-North Railroad
stop only a couple of hundred yards away.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring main building, which is clad in unfortunate
powder-blue panels, was recently used to film a scene from ``Sleepy
Hollow'' _ a nighttime shot of a cornfield that entailed hauling in
600 tons of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girth of the walls, the thickness of the floors, the
enormity of the space _ it's got such character,'' said Paul W.
Adler, the general manager of commercial services for Prudential
Rand Realty, which represents the property's owner, BICC PLC.
``Some of the offices look like something you could film a Bogart
movie in.''
</P>
<P>
   BICC, a transportation and development company in London, is
talking to Weinstein and De Niro about a joint venture, Adler said.
That would also enable the company to oversee a necessary
environmental cleanup of the site, estimated to cost $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano, the economic development chairman in New York state,
said the state reached out to the filmmakers after learning that
they were looking in New Jersey last fall. While New York would not
contribute ``seed money'' to the studio project, the state could
help with infrastructure improvements and savings on sales tax, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing here is to get them to build studios in New
York,'' Gargano said. ``That's a very important industry, and it's
good for New York state. New Jersey is ahead of us because they've
been dealing with them longer.''
</P>
<P>
   So are De Niro and Weinstein stringing along New Jersey and New
York, the same way that the Giuliani administration treated them?
State and local officials say their eyes are open. ``They've been
candid that they're looking at other areas,'' said Castano, the
lawyer for the Harrison Redevelopment Agency, ``and we've known
that from the beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
