<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-SPORTS-DISCIPLINE-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLLEGE SPORTS, DISCIPLINE IS OFTEN BENCHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: also see the 1,050-word
COLLEGE-SPORTS-DISCIPLINE-ABRIDGED) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the president of Florida State University, Talbot
D'Alemberte, dared to suggest last fall that a star wide receiver
serve a jail sentence before returning to play football, some of
the irate letters he received were telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dare you treat Athletic Director Hart and Coach Bowden as
mere subordinates,'' wrote an alumnus, Ron Lawrence. ``I will never
give another penny to the university as long as you are president
of the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   When outstanding athletes or popular coaches get in trouble,
college presidents like D'Alemberte face extraordinary pressure;
they must weigh the lofty moral and educational standards of their
schools against students, sports fans, wealthy alumni and donors
demanding success on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom have the contending forces _ and the potential risks to a
university's reputation _ been more evident than at Indiana
University last week, when the legendary basketball coach, Bob
Knight, escaped dismissal even though the president, Myles Brand,
and the university trustees concluded he had a long history of
abusive behavior, including choking a player and bullying a
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   To many people outside Indiana, the decision seemed odd, a
capitulation to a powerful coach with a persistent three-decade
record of inappropriate words and actions. But within the state,
where many members of the political power structure are alumni of
Indiana University, and Knight is a celebrity whose name is more
widely known than the governor's, the decision to give Knight one
more chance made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the state, more people view him as a case of the
positives outweighing the negatives,'' said Murray Sperber, an
English professor at Indiana who writes books on college sports and
has long been a critic of Knight. ``That explains the pressures on
Brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Many critics say Knight's case illustrates the great divide
between the ideals of universities and the reality of big-time
college sports: in many schools, athletics have become a potent
entertainment business, with coaches and athletes who become media
stars and help market schools, attracting donations and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``College sports becomes the bridge between the elite culture of
the university and the mass culture outside the university upon
which the university depends,'' said Dr. Allen L. Sack, the
director of the sports management program at the University of New
Haven. ``In the midst, holding up that bridge, are the college
presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, officials at the University of Minnesota and
the University of Tennessee have struggled with allegations of
academic fraud by athletes, while the University of Nebraska dealt
with accusations that star football players physically abused
women. The University of Vermont canceled part of the hockey season
earlier this year because of hazing, and Providence College
expelled three basketball players last week over an assault.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brand insists that he made the decision to give
Knight ``one last opportunity'' without regard to pressure from
alumni and Hoosier basketball fans, who staged a demonstration on
campus and flooded Brand's office with e-mail messages. Several
alumni organizations also threatened to stop giving to the
university, said Michael Pegram, a booster who organized the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may have been people who said, `I won't give money
anymore,''' Brand said in an interview. ``All those issues have to
be totally ignored in the decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brand said he and most of the nine-member board of
trustees had been leaning toward dismissing Knight until the
basketball coach posted an apology on the Internet. Then Brand met
at his home with Knight and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said he told Knight that the trustees were on the verge of
voting to dismiss him. But during a three-and-a-half-hour
conversation, he said, Knight persuaded him to recommend penalities
instead. For the first time, Knight accepted responsibility for his
past actions and promised to rein in his temper, Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said he believed that the university had been culpable as
well. For 29 years, he said, officials had either ignored Knight's
abusive behavior or let him off with light sanctions, setting
``implicit rules'' that Knight could behave as he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Brand recommended to the trustees that Knight
be given one last chance. The coach was fined $30,000, suspended
for three games and ordered to abide by a strict code of conduct or
face dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever sanction I gave him would not have been enough,''
Brand said. ``The meat of the issue were the directives about how
he's expected to behave in the future and if he doesn't, he doesn't
have a second chance anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy decision to make was to terminate Bob Knight,'' Brand
added. ``I knew there was a groundswell of interest outside the
state to terminate him.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even inside the state, opinion was divided. Trustees said they
had received hundreds of letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was down the middle,'' John Walda, the board president,
said ``It was either `This was a witch hunt begun by the media and
you should ignore it,' or `It's about time, you should get rid of
Coach Knight.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another trustee, Ray Richardson, a former state legislator, said
the decision was a no-win situation politically for the board. A
poll by The Indianapolis Star last month showed about 55 percent of
state residents thought Knight should remain as coach and about 39
percent said he should not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge segment of Hoosiers that feel that he's done
some nasty things, but they weren't necessarily ready to fire
him,'' Richardson said. ``I was trying to figure out what would
please the people in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he had been prepared to vote to dismiss Knight,
but changed his mind after Brand told the board of Knight's sincere
promise to change. ``Knight's never had an incentive to control
himself,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty members, however, said the trustees' decision had
irreparably damaged Indiana University's reputation. ``It sends the
message that athletics are more important than academics, that
marketing and revenue streams mean more than scholarships,'' said
Dave Pisoni, a psychology professor.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida State University, the pressure on D'Alamberte to keep
the football team's star receiver, Peter Warrick, on the field was
more overt. One donor threatened to withdraw a $1 million
contribution, university officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick had been charged with another football player and a
department store cashier in a $600 shoplifting scheme. Warrick's
lawyer, John Kenny, along with the football coach, Bobby Bowden,
and athletic director, Dave Hart Jr., had worked out a plea
agreement with the Tallahassee prosecutor, Willie Meggs. Warrick
would plead guilty to a misdemeanor, and he would serve 30 days in
jail after the football season.
</P>
<P>
   But D'Alamberte said it was university policy, set after two
previous cases involving players convicted of crimes, that Warrick
must pay his debt to society before returning to football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd had that policy, and I thought I made it clear to everyone
all along that was going to be my policy,'' D'Alemberte said in an
interview. ``A lot of people got outraged, in part because it
looked as if everything had been worked out and I was stepping
in.''
</P>
<P>
   His office immediately received more than 600 letters and e-mail
messages, denouncing him as well as supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two or three major donors who were sending me
messages that they were not going to give the gift they had
promised,'' he said. ``The best thing for a university president to
do is to stake out a ground that he feels comfortable with and stay
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried alumni and other Seminole football fans also bombarded
the prosecutor, himself an alumnus, with angry mail. They lobbied
sympathetic state legislators to use their influence. ``I had
hundreds of phone calls,'' said state Sen. Jim King of
Jacksonville, also a graduate of Florida State. ``I thought the
phone would never stop ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Warrick's lawyer brokered a new deal. Instead of
jail time, Warrick was allowed to do community service _ picking up
trash for 30 days _ after admitting his guilt. D'Alamberte
permitted Warrick to rejoin the football team before doing the
community service, reasoning that the punishment was much less
severe than jail time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line I have drawn looks at the result produced by the
criminal justice system,'' he said. ``The judgment here is `This
has been pretty minor.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles went on to win the national championship at the
Sugar Bowl, in large part because of Warrick's outstanding play.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, university officials respond in varying ways when
coaches and athletes face possible suspension or dismissal. The
facts vary, and so do the outside pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Providence College, a small Roman Catholic school in
Rhode Island with a well-respected Big East basketball program,
came down hard on members of the basketball team for their role in
an assault last month.
</P>
<P>
   Three players projected as starters next season were expelled.
``An assault on a student goes to the very heart of who we are,''
the college president, the Rev. Philip A. Smith, said. ``This is
not a basketball issue for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, elected officials have even urged universities to
take strong action. The University of Vermont canceled the
remainder of the hockey season last January after Gov. Howard Dean
intervened in the wake of a hazing scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A former member of the team had alleged in a lawsuit that he had
been degraded during hazing. Among other things, he said he had
been forced to wear women's panties and to parade naked at a party
while holding the genitals of other freshman players.
</P>
<P>
   University officials had investigated the allegations last fall,
but had had difficulty penetrating a wall of silence among the
hockey players, said the president, Dr. Judith Ramaley. The coach,
Mike Gilligan, had planned to suspend each player for one game on a
rotating basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was outraged at what had gone on,'' Dean said in an
interview last week. ``My concern was that the university didn't
appear to be taking any action.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean made a rare appearance before the board of trustees, where
he is an ex officio member, and made his feelings known. University
officials then asked the state attorney general to investigate the
allegations. Under oath, several hockey players admitted they had
not told the truth earlier and provided details. Ramaley then
canceled the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Although hockey is the most popular college sport in the state,
Ramaley said she had not been pressured by fans or alumni to go
easy on the players. Indeed most Vermont alumni seemed to support
canceling the season, she said. The problem had been getting to the
bottom of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned to our shock the students had lied,'' Ramaley said.
``We ended up making a statement about character.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Indiana's decision to keep Knight on may have also
been about character, critics say. Knight's flamboyant and volatile
style has kept him and his teams in the public eye for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a media star of heroic proportions,'' said Sack of New
Haven. ``You are messing with an American institution, who stands
for all that popular culture and mass culture holds in high
regard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
