<P>
   BKN-HAWKS-LOTTERY _ For the first time in eight years, the
Atlanta Hawks missed the playoffs and will have a lottery pick in
June 28 NBA draft. Their position will be determined today as the
selection portion of lottery will be held in New York. The Hawks'
last lottery pick was Adam Keefe in 1992, the 10th overall pick,
and that choice followed the 1991 drafting of UNLV's Stacey Augmon
with the ninth overall pick. As the Hawks prepare for the lottery,
we will attempt to look at what players might be available for them
to select and a chart of hits and misses for the team on draft day.
(Denberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   EYE-SURGERY _ It has been so great for Greg Maddux, Tiger Woods
and Laura Davies that it has become the vogue in all sports for
athletes to undergo Lasik eye surgery. In fact, many everyday
recreation athletes -- at least those of financial means -- are
having the procedure. You might be surprised at the number of
athletes -- from baseball to NASCAR -- who have had the surgery.
The reason is simple: As Eddie Murphy said in 'Trading Places,' ``I
can see.'' (Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EYESURGERY-SIDE _ The procedure is simple: A laser slices a thin
layer of skin from the cornea in a 20-minute time period. The
$5,000 cost, spare change for most pro athletes, remains a bit
prohibitive for the weekend warriors. And insurance won't pay.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SKIP-CARAY _ Skip Caray is entering his 25th year as TV and
radio broadcaster of the Atlanta Braves. Part of a blue-blooded
announcing lineage _ father Harry is in the baseball hall of fame,
son Chip is current announcer of the Cubs _ Skip is like neither of
them. Weaned on announcing baseball back in the bad old Braves
days, he's known to be more sarcastic than sentimental. He says
this year he's the ``new'' Skip _ he's quit drinking, lost weight,
and promises not to bite the heads off callers who phone his
pregame show and ask, for the umpteenth time, how to compute a
slugging percentage. We'll see. (Jubera, Cox News Service). 88.
WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
