<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CALIFORNIA0521-COX     05-20 2095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    California win for Bush is an uphill battleBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Of all the bold ambitions harbored by GOP
presidential candidate George W. Bush, none is so bold _ or such a
long shot _ as this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to win California,'' he said recently in the state
that could go a long way toward determining this year's White House
race.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of talk that has the California GOP _ fresh out of
in-state heroes _ convinced that the Texas governor can ignite a
Republican renaissance in a state that's become about as Democratic
as a big state can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an uphill fight. The game of government is a one-party
game in California right now,'' said Mark Sheppard, chairman of the
Young Republican Federation of California. ``In this election, the
California Republican Party, because of Governor Bush, has a unique
opportunity to redeem ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But in politics, one party's poster boy is the other party's
punch line. Among California Democrats, Bush is a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is funny,'' said Garry South, Democratic Gov. Gray Davis'
top political adviser, ``because he doesn't have the slightest
chance of carrying California.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisan rhetoric aside, the facts are clear. Vice President Al
Gore cannot win the presidency without winning California, which
has 54 of the 270 electoral votes needed for victory. Bush can get
to the White House without carrying California, but a win here
could seal it.
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats, on the cutting edge of a national effort
to cast Bush as out of the mainstream, are now working to prevent a
Bush win by portraying him as standard-issue right-winger.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about Bush as some kind of new Republican, they say.
Forget about Bush connecting with California Hispanics, who have
been alienated and energized by GOP support here for measures
ending affirmative action, bilingual education and benefits for
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   And, Democrats here say, forget about Bush carrying California,
one of only three states where Democrats have the Governor's
Mansion, both U.S. Senate seats, a majority of the U.S. House
delegation and majorities in both state legislative chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure in Texas he looks like a compassionate conservative
because Texas is so far to the right,'' said South. ``In that
landscape he really does seem like a sensible moderate. In
California, the guy looks like a right-wing wacko.''
</P>
<P>
   In his East Los Angeles office, Hector Barreto, co-chairman of
the Bush campaign here and the son of a wealthy former Kansas City
businessman, acknowledges that the Republicans are up against a
tough set of facts, including their failures in California and a
general feeling that the state has done well under Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``But tell them not to let the facts blind them,'' he said,
echoing the Bush believers' mantra.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, in stylish Westwood, Gerry Parsky, Bush's
California chairman, isn't letting the facts cloud the optimism he
feels from his 21st floor office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right, if you look at history,'' he says in the face of
the litany of why a Republican can't carry California. ``But I
think you're wrong if you look at this candidate and the progress
he has made so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Through monthly visits and a series of major policy speeches out
here, Bush is working on the moderate image and trying to connect
with Hispanics, who could make up as much as 15 percent of the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is a reasonable person,'' said Parsky, a venture
capitalist whose daily commute is a private plane flight from a San
Diego suburb. ``He is not an extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   But California Democrats already have a TV ad campaign in mind
to push the W.-stands-for-wacko message. Party strategist Bob
Mulholland sees a commercial featuring footage of Bush and Bob
Jones University President Bob Jones III during the now-famous
February speech at the conservative South Carolina college.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if Bush Jr. comes to California and says, `I'm a different
kind of Republican,' then we go up on the air on choice and guns.
It takes his knees out from under him. He is not a different kind
of Republican. We got him, babe,'' said Mulholland.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers seem to support the Democrats. An American Research
Group survey completed May 1-9 among 600 likely California voters
showed Bush trailing Gore 50 percent to 36 percent. And no
anti-abortion rights candidate has won a major race here since the
elder George Bush did it in 1988. All 10 U.S. Senate races since
the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision have been won by candidates,
including two Republicans, who favored abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Recent presidential elections out here have been GOP disasters.
In 1992, the elder Bush, who conceded the state, picked up only 33
percent of the vote. In 1996, GOP nominee Bob Dole, who also made
no real effort, got only 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And then it got really bad for Republicans. In 1998,
then-Attorney General Dan Lungren lost the gubernatorial race to
Democrat Davis by 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether two years ago was an aberration or the
beginning of a trend,'' said Lungren, who believes a combination of
1998 events _ including an anti-union initiative that riled and
roused labor _ contributed to his landslide defeat. ``No one can
make an accurate prediction now about what will happen in November.
But George Bush is doing those things he needs to do to put himself
in position to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Field Poll, which has been measuring California politics
since 1947, found that Davis beat Lungren ``in nearly every region
of the state and piled up majorities among Democrats, independents,
moderate and liberal voters, men and women and across all income,
age, educational, race and ethnic groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis carried the Hispanic vote by a 78-17 margin. A poll
conducted for the Southwest Voter Registration Education project
late last year showed Bush within one percentage point of Gore
among Hispanics in Florida, Texas, Illinois, California and New
York, states that account for about 80 percent of the Hispanic
population.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, Bush trailed by a whopping 27 percentage
points. California Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamente, a co-chairman of the
Gore campaign here, said that trend will persist through Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he wants to do for the nation what he has done for
Texas,'' said Bustamente, eager to call attention to ethnically
insensitive comments of two Bush appointees. ``My response is 'No
thanks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Health Commissioner William Reyn Archer, a Bush appointee,
recently apologized after saying that young, unmarried Hispanics
lacked the belief ``that getting pregnant is a bad thing.'' Another
Bush appointee, Charles Williams of Marshall, recently resigned as
chairman of the Texas Commission on Law Enforcement Standards and
Education after it was revealed he had testified in a 1998 lawsuit
that terms such as ``porch monkey'' were not racial slurs. He also
said that blacks didn't mind being called ``niggers'' 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dealing with California Democrats' efforts to
link Bush to his appointees' comments, the Texas governor's
things-to-do list includes undoing the political damage lingering
from ex-Republican Gov. Pete Wilson's support of the propositions
ending bilingual education, affirmative action and benefits for
illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Bush takes no position on bilingual education, saying instead
that he is interested in results and is willing to let local school
officials decide the best way to go.
</P>
<P>
   He opposed the 1994 California proposition that ended benefits,
including education, for illegal immigrants. The measure was later
ruled unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But some political scientists say the differences will be lost
on California Hispanics who won't look beyond the party label.
Michael Latner, a Field Poll project manager, saw nothing in the
March primary that indicates Bush is making progress among
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear as though Hispanics are distinguishing him
as a different type of Republican,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State University political scientist Larry Gerston
agrees, saying Bush will be ``very hard-pressed'' to avoid being
``lumped in with Wilson.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has acknowledged the hurdle, saying, ``It's going to be
tough just because I've got 'Republican' by my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Barreto believes Bush has to carry 40 percent of the Hispanic
vote to carry California. In the state's nonpartisan primary in
March, with all presidential contenders on a single ballot, Bush
pulled only 18 percent of the Hispanic vote, according to exit
polls. Gore took 55 percent. The GOP candidates combined for 36
percent, a statistic Parsky sees as cause for optimism. But
Bustamente believes Bush is California dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very cynical thing to think you can speak a little
Spanish and ride in a Cinco de Mayo parade and then represent the
interests of a community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That work has to begin now as Democrats try to marginalize Bush
on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He runs the risks the possibility of being Lungrenized,'' said
Latner. ``Lungren was not a far-right conservative by any means
when the election began. But Davis was successful at using issues
such as gun control and abortion and staying on that message and
hammering that into the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland and other California Democrats like to say their
state is the most ``anti-gun'' in the nation, and Bush's ties to
the National Rifle Association will prove politically fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, says Mulholland, is ``the most anti-choice, pro-NRA and
pro-voucher Republican presidential nominee ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsky believes Bush can overcome the effort to hand the
right-wing image on him, but it will take a three-pronged approach
complete with constant visits by the candidate, a strong TV ad
campaign and a grassroots effort.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky says he has a commitment from the Bush campaign to
compete ``at the highest level possible'' on all facets of the
campaign, and that the effort won't just be a sleight of hand to
force Gore into spending money in California.
</P>
<P>
   As state chairman, Parksy is in charge of the grassroots part of
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The potential problem, however, is that some of the best foot
soldiers in that effort are not second-guessing their support for
the propositions that alienated many Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them gathered for lunch last week in a flowery meeting
room in Orange, a solidly Republican part of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The ladies of the Orange Republican Women Federated are
unapologetic about their support for the measures ending bilingual
education, affirmative action and benefits for illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we went to another country and tried to be in their
country we would have to learn their language,'' Patricia Welch, a
club vice president. ``And the same thing with benefits. We
wouldn't get benefits. If I moved to Italy, for instance, I would
not get benefits from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Club member Charlotte Bell still believes affirmative action
made her daughter a victim of reverse discrimination when she was
denied admission to UCLA's nursing school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was qualified. A lot of the other people they were
accepting were not qualified,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's meeting began with longtime member Mary Widdows
leading the Pledge of Allegiance and bemoaning the fact that local
Hispanics and Vietnamese fly the flags of their homelands more
often than other local residents fly the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like them coming here and getting welfare within 24
hours,'' said Widdows, daughter of German immigrants. ``That's not
fair to us who are paying huge taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily the sentiment Bush wants permeating the
campaign. But San Jose State political scientist Gerston says all
of those issues could fade in importance if the state's now-golden
economy starts to show some tarnish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventional wisdom is this is a Gore state for a lot of
reasons, not the least of which has been the coincidence of the
phenomenal economic recovery of California with the successes of
the Clinton administration.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to run against prosperity, according to Gerston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we talk with our hearts and we vote with our
wallets. And no one does that more than California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
