<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SKIP-CARAY0521-COX     05-20 2895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIP-CARAY0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goodbye grouch, hello Mr. Mellow: Announcer promises to be good
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The two- two pitch...''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Caray is perched, Buddha-like, in a radio booth high above
home plate at Turner Field. He's warming up: 45 minutes before the
Braves' next-to-last exhibition game, Caray is pronouncing into a
dead microphone a phrase that, as Atlanta baseball's radio and TV
announcer the past 24 seasons, he has repeated . . . tens of
thousands of times? Hundreds of thousands? He leans again into the
dead mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two -two pitch...''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be here in the booth to know it's Caray. That
voice. One of the most distinctive styles in sports broadcasting,
it doesn't require that you even be a baseball fan to recognize it.
Caray's delivery _ a nasally, sweet-sax honk at the high end, with
the low notes kept nice and warm in the back of his throat _ has
crackled over the airwaves so many years it's now part of the
region's ambient summer soundtrack, like crickets and lawn mowers
and kids squealing under a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been there so long he's become an icon,'' says Allen
Ginsberg, director of special projects for BBDO South ad agency.
``When people hear his voice, they just identify it with baseball
games.''
</P>
<P>
   More memorable than the sound, however, is the tone. When not
ramped up to describe the Braves '95 World Series victory (``Yes!
Yes! Yes!''), or Sid Bream's slowpoke, pennant-clinching expedition
from second base to home plate in the '92 playoffs (``Braves win!
Braves win! Braves win!''), Caray puts the dead into deadpan _ a
dry, wry, wily inflection that courts crankiness, sarcasm and the
kind of summer's-night, old-friend knowingness that comes from
having seen most of what he's seeing many times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skip is like balsamic vinegar on a fine salad,'' says Jeff
Hullinger, WAGA sportscaster and the radio voice of Falcons
football. ``He has a little vinegar in him, and that's such an
important part of a good meal. So many places around the country
have these vanilla-voiced guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say things that drive me and John (Schuerholz, Braves
general manager) up the wall,'' adds Braves president Stan Kasten.
``He's always testing the boundaries. He lives for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's never malicious,'' he says. ``That's why he's
freakin' lasted so long.''
</P>
<P>
   It's 15 minutes before the game. Caray leans into that dead mike
one last time. Nobody else in the booth has paid any attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-two pitch...'' Caray says again, the same way he said
it the two other times: deliberate, detached, self-mocking. It's
Skip Caray doing Skip Caray.
</P>
<P>
   He then pushes away from the mike and heads toward the press box
food court. He has a wide man's rolling, canoe-rocking walk, and on
his way out says to no one in particular, ```The two- two
pitch...As long as I can say that, I'm all right.''
</P>
<P>
   `I GOT GRANDCHILDREN I'D LIKE TO SEE GROW UP'
</P>
<P>
   At 60, the middle rung on a broadcasting dynasty that started
with his father, Harry, and continues with his son Chip, Caray is
attempting these days to be something more than all right. He has
announced this year (during Braves games, on Neal Boortz's radio
show) that he intends to be a ``new, mellow Skip.''
</P>
<P>
   The makeover is prompted by two concerns that reached critical
mass last season. The first: Caray's grouchy, even Grinchy persona
on WSB radio's pregame show, where he flashed little patience for
callers wanting to know, for instance, how to compute a player's
slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The second: his health, on which decades of road-trip-style
drinking took a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at (WSB) thought I was being too hard on callers,''
Caray acknowledges. ``I don't think so, but I decided I'd be Mr.
Mellow. Ever since I quit drinking, I look at things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray says he hasn't had any alcohol since New Year's Day; he
drinks water during games and treats himself to a diet soda
afterward. He's lost 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had enough,'' he says, sipping water inside his soaring
house where he lives with Paula, his wife of 24 years, and
18-year-old Josh, the youngest of four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get older, it (alcohol) gets tougher to handle,''
Caray adds. ``I was told that cirrhosis of the liver was a
longshot. I got grandchildren I'd like to see grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   His new mellowness caught a lot of people by surprise. While WSB
radio group general manager Dave Meszaros said Caray was
cooperative and ``not defensive'' when they met following last
season to discuss his call-in show demeanor, other employers have
had a different experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the most difficult employee I've ever had in my life,''
says Bob Wussler, former executive vice president of Turner
Broadcasting who now runs a media consulting business in
Washington. ``He wanted to show up late and go home early. He never
wanted to read the promos. We had epic battles over contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to deal with him, including Ted (Turner),''
Wussler adds. ``But at the end of the day, he did whatever you
wanted him to do. It was just getting him to the point of agreeing
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray's handling of pregame callers came to a head last season
when sports talk-show hosts at rival 790 The Zone regularly blasted
what they viewed as Caray's abrupt, rude manner with fans phoning
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were very irritated by his treatment of callers,'' says
790 afternoon host ``Steak'' Shapiro, who admits fanning the flames
to gig the competition. ``It sounds like the last place he wants to
be is in front of a mike talking to listeners. When I started to
trumpet that, the response was huge. People said, `Finally,
somebody is calling this guy out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Others recall an off-the-air Caray who could be gregarious and
generous one minute (``I know him as a guy who'd give you the shirt
off his back _ just don't try to take it,'' says on-air sidekick
Joe Simpson), then bitingly short-tempered the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to get crazy about any little thing. He'd get
furious,'' says his brother Chris Caray, retired from a St. Louis
travel business. ``He was a piece of work.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's a new man _ it's really spooky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes with age,'' Chris adds. ``There's a part of all of us
that continues to grow, even in our 50s and 60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting inside his home on a late Thursday afternoon, Caray is .
. . mellow. He looks over at a visitor and asks, ``You want a
drink?''
</P>
<P>
   The visitor blinks back. A few minutes earlier, Caray had gone
on about how he doesn't miss the booze one bit.
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head. ``Just because I don't drink 'em doesn't
mean I can't still pour 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   He then goes to the kitchen and puts together a whiskey and
water. Just a splash. Pours it with a fine, schooled hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a really good drink.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAYOR OF RUSH STREET
</P>
<P>
   Caray learned to pour 'em from the best: his father, the late
Hall of Fame announcer Harry Caray. It was his father who taught
Caray to love baseball, pushed him into broadcasting, showed him
what a good time the profession could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my dad in his underwear many times, coming out of the
bathroom, stubble on his face after a hangover, going to work,''
Caray recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Harry was an institution in St. Louis through four decades, then
a national institution as the Cubs announcer on WGN in Chicago. He
cried ``Holy cow!'' after every homer, led Wrigley Field fans in
``Take Me Out to the Ballgame'' during the seventh-inning stretch,
was known as ``the mayor of Rush Street,'' the bar-lined avenue he
virtually called home. In his later years, his bombastic style and
thick, black-rimmed glasses became a campy imitation on ``Saturday
Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   He died two years ago, at age 83. His funeral was televised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked broads and booze and never tried to fool you,'' Caray
says. ``Dad was a fun guy, and I miss him every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray grew up, in St. Louis, the son of that institution. A
tricky spot: Sometimes good, sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   Caray's parents divorced when he was barely a teen, a
high-profile, highly affecting circumstance. The day after the
divorce, Caray saw it headlined in a St. Louis newspaper. Something
like: Caray's Wife Throws Him Out at Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day was the longest walk to school of my life,'' he
remembers.
</P>
<P>
   It also might be the moment that the no-excuses,
quit-your-whining template that underpins Caray's character _ from
his caustic humor to his frank impatience _ was born. His mother,
Dorothy, now 81 and living with Caray's sister near Atlanta,
remembers him never complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a girl in my class who came from divorced parents,
and we talked about how people use divorce as an excuse for what
they do,'' Caray recalls. ``We were like a support system for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   With a younger sister and brother, Caray lived mostly with his
mother, a shy woman with a dry humor. For Caray's siblings, their
father's visits were often off-the-wall stopovers of the
hard-drinking life of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were difficult times _ I couldn't really describe it,''
says his sister Patricia Caray, retired from Coca-Cola. ``It could
be tough, but the love was still there. Sometimes you had to remind
yourself of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Skip is not the kind of person who'd think about (the
divorce) one way or the other. He'd look at it as the hand he was
dealt and play it. He really loved his father _ to be his father's
son was all he could ever want.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry took his oldest son to spring training each year, and on
road trips with the Cardinals each summer. Skip loved it. He still
remembers the train rides, listening to coaches tell stories for
hours in hotel lobbies, mingling with players like they were
neighborhood dads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any heroes in baseball _ I knew the players on a
first-name basis,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Caray was a good high school athlete, but a knee injury turned
him into what he calls the first requirement of a sports announcer:
a frustrated athlete. He was in the booth by junior high school,
doing his own radio sports report on powerhouse KMOX. His
relationship with broadcasting was as natural as it was with
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never afraid of the mike,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His father wanted him to become a broadcaster and Caray, who
earned a journalism degree from the University of Missouri, never
considered anything else. Why would he? His father's life was a
rolling party, and he made more money than a lot of players.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE FATHER, LIKE SON
</P>
<P>
   After announcing minor-league baseball in Oklahoma and Georgia _
he was the voice of the old Atlanta Crackers in '64 and '65 _ Caray
arrived in Atlanta for good in 1969, to do Hawks basketball. He was
30, married and had two children. But the marriage broke up (``I
was too young''), the kids moved back to St. Louis with their
mother, and Caray followed in his father's hard-living footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got divorced just when birth control came into being, and
before AIDS became a problem _ every night was New Year's Eve,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Most nights were spent at the now-defunct Brave Falcon Lounge,
that attracted that era's men on the make _ sportsmen, lawyers,
salesmen _ and plenty of women wanting to make it with them. For a
while, Caray had his mail delivered there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Dewar's and water and let's see what happens,'' he
says. ``God, I loved that place. For the most part I was with good
friends. The laughs _ the laughs were so much better than the
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he adds, ``A lot of the happiness was superficial. A little
booze and a young lady and you sorta forget about missing your
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray eventually met his second wife there. Paula Prather owned
the hairstyling salon Caray went to next door, and she'd stop by
the Brave Falcon after work. She turned down a bunch of Caray's
advances; born in Georgia, she didn't know anything about baseball
or Harry Caray. ``I just sorta stumbled into it,'' she remembers.
</P>
<P>
   They married in 1976. Caray adopted Paula's young daughter, and
a few years later they had Josh. When he wasn't on the road, Caray
became a homebody.
</P>
<P>
   Says oldest son Chip, now a Cubs announcer, ``That's where
there's a difference with my grandfather (Harry): My dad had a
greater appreciation for the importance of family at a younger age.
While he loves his job, he doesn't live for his job, like my
grandfather did.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather loved meeting and talking with people all the
time _ that was his personality. My dad can't do that. Nobody's
like Harry Caray. And nobody can be.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ONLY A GAME
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine now, with the Braves' decade-long success,
the degree of utter lousiness Caray described for fans of those
early Hawks and Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bad with the Hawks that Kasten, then the team's
assistant general manager, challenged Caray nightly by finding an
obscure word for him to work into the broadcast: syzygy, homunculus
_ like that.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Bob Costas recalls in the middle of one Hawks blowout
Caray giving viewers permission to turn off their sets, as long as
they patronized the station's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the greatest thing I heard an announcer
say,'' Costas says. ``It breaks that wall, where the announcer is
telling the fan, `I'm thinking what you're thinking.' It was, like,
subversive.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray kept it up when he joined the Braves. ``Ted (Turner) told
me, `I don't know anything about this (stuff), say whatever you
want.'''
</P>
<P>
   He did: He'd page through a TV Guide during a game to see what
else was on; give scathing reviews of the sci-fi B-movies that then
filled TBS's schedule; instituted a ``punchline of the day,'' with
viewers sending in dirty jokes that couldn't be told on the air, to
which Caray would read only the punchline.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Skip's humor really came in. His imagination would
run amok,'' says broadcasting partner Pete Van Wieren, who joined
the Braves the same year as Caray. ``We were out of some races so
early that there were no boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Those lean years are what carved Caray's unhyped,
it's-just-a-game style that, because of TBS's cable reach, became
familiar around the country. ESPN anchor Rich Eisen remembers
imitating Caray while growing up in New York, and now regularly
imitates him during ``Sports Center.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People love the voice. They come up to me in airports and ask
me to do it,'' Eisen says. ``I'm a New Yorker, and I never thought
I'd be known for doing an imitation of a guy who does baseball in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Skip, you get a kind of good-natured world weariness,''
adds Costas. ``I'm sure he's too low-key for some people, in the
same way Harry could be too over the top. But those of us who have
an interest in broadcasting and baseball have an appreciation for
what he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry was broad enough that everybody got him. Only the
intelligentsia get this.''
</P>
<P>
   YOU EITHER LOVE HIM OR HATE HIM
</P>
<P>
   An hour before another game. Caray's hunched over a live mike
inside a cramped WSB radio hut in Turner Field's centerfield
pavilion _ ``Skip-in-a-box,'' some at WSB call the setup _ hosting
the pregame show. He's fielded a half-dozen calls so far and been
nice as pie.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone's enamored of the new, mellow Skip. For some, his
doesn't-suffer-fools-gladly approach was a cult find. Chipper Jones
compares him to ``not Rush Limbaugh, exactly . . . He's the Neal
Boortz of play-by-play.'' Boortz says he should have a forum on
``60 Minutes'': ``He'd make Andy Rooney look like a priest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate baseball but I never turn off the pre-game show,'' says
Marcia Killingsworth, Georgia native and public relations manager
at Georgia Public TV. ``The people who call are so passionate about
the Braves, and the tone Skip uses when he responds to some of
their minutia _ it's so dry, honestly, I almost drive off the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People either love him or . . . dislike him,'' adds Braves
pitcher John Smoltz. ``I've grown to really like him. The first
time I listened to the pregame show, I couldn't stop laughing.
People say he's a rude son-of-a-gun, but I know how many calls he
has to deal with and it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz grins. ``I'm thinking of getting somebody to call him up
and ask a really stupid question. Just to see how he responds.''
</P>
<P>
   Could that person be Rob in Stone Mountain?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where and how,'' begins a caller identified on a computer
screen inside the WSB hut only as Rob in Stone Mountain, ``should I
consolidate my student loans?''
</P>
<P>
   Caray's confused. He asks Rob to repeat the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' says Rob. ``Where and how should I consolidate my
student loans?''
</P>
<P>
   Caray is trying to decide if this is the kind of call he'd so
famously boot in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a job and then pay 'em off . . .'' Caray begins.
</P>
<P>
   Rob interrupts. ``Is Clark Howard around?''
</P>
<P>
   Rob's got the wrong show. Caray tells him to try back another
time and breaks for a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to make me mad,'' he says off the air. ``A
simple'' _ he uses an expletive phrase _ ``would have been an
appropriate answer. But I'm going to be this way all year. Until I
lose it. If I lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Caray smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Smiles!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
