</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIP-CARAY0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goodbye grouch, hello Mr. Mellow: Announcer promises to be good
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The two- two pitch...''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Caray is perched, Buddha-like, in a radio booth high above
home plate at Turner Field. He's warming up: 45 minutes before the
Braves' next-to-last exhibition game, Caray is pronouncing into a
dead microphone a phrase that, as Atlanta baseball's radio and TV
announcer the past 24 seasons, he has repeated . . . tens of
thousands of times? Hundreds of thousands? He leans again into the
dead mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two -two pitch...''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be here in the booth to know it's Caray. That
voice. One of the most distinctive styles in sports broadcasting,
it doesn't require that you even be a baseball fan to recognize it.
Caray's delivery _ a nasally, sweet-sax honk at the high end, with
the low notes kept nice and warm in the back of his throat _ has
crackled over the airwaves so many years it's now part of the
region's ambient summer soundtrack, like crickets and lawn mowers
and kids squealing under a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been there so long he's become an icon,'' says Allen
Ginsberg, director of special projects for BBDO South ad agency.
``When people hear his voice, they just identify it with baseball
games.''
</P>
<P>
   More memorable than the sound, however, is the tone. When not
ramped up to describe the Braves '95 World Series victory (``Yes!
Yes! Yes!''), or Sid Bream's slowpoke, pennant-clinching expedition
from second base to home plate in the '92 playoffs (``Braves win!
Braves win! Braves win!''), Caray puts the dead into deadpan _ a
dry, wry, wily inflection that courts crankiness, sarcasm and the
kind of summer's-night, old-friend knowingness that comes from
having seen most of what he's seeing many times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skip is like balsamic vinegar on a fine salad,'' says Jeff
Hullinger, WAGA sportscaster and the radio voice of Falcons
football. ``He has a little vinegar in him, and that's such an
important part of a good meal. So many places around the country
have these vanilla-voiced guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say things that drive me and John (Schuerholz, Braves
general manager) up the wall,'' adds Braves president Stan Kasten.
``He's always testing the boundaries. He lives for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's never malicious,'' he says. ``That's why he's
freakin' lasted so long.''
</P>
<P>
   It's 15 minutes before the game. Caray leans into that dead mike
one last time. Nobody else in the booth has paid any attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-two pitch...'' Caray says again, the same way he said
it the two other times: deliberate, detached, self-mocking. It's
Skip Caray doing Skip Caray.
</P>
<P>
   He then pushes away from the mike and heads toward the press box
food court. He has a wide man's rolling, canoe-rocking walk, and on
his way out says to no one in particular, ```The two- two
pitch...As long as I can say that, I'm all right.''
</P>
<P>
   `I GOT GRANDCHILDREN I'D LIKE TO SEE GROW UP'
</P>
<P>
   At 60, the middle rung on a broadcasting dynasty that started
with his father, Harry, and continues with his son Chip, Caray is
attempting these days to be something more than all right. He has
announced this year (during Braves games, on Neal Boortz's radio
show) that he intends to be a ``new, mellow Skip.''
</P>
<P>
   The makeover is prompted by two concerns that reached critical
mass last season. The first: Caray's grouchy, even Grinchy persona
on WSB radio's pregame show, where he flashed little patience for
callers wanting to know, for instance, how to compute a player's
slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The second: his health, on which decades of road-trip-style
drinking took a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at (WSB) thought I was being too hard on callers,''
Caray acknowledges. ``I don't think so, but I decided I'd be Mr.
Mellow. Ever since I quit drinking, I look at things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray says he hasn't had any alcohol since New Year's Day; he
drinks water during games and treats himself to a diet soda
afterward. He's lost 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had enough,'' he says, sipping water inside his soaring
house where he lives with Paula, his wife of 24 years, and
18-year-old Josh, the youngest of four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get older, it (alcohol) gets tougher to handle,''
Caray adds. ``I was told that cirrhosis of the liver was a
longshot. I got grandchildren I'd like to see grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   His new mellowness caught a lot of people by surprise. While WSB
radio group general manager Dave Meszaros said Caray was
cooperative and ``not defensive'' when they met following last
season to discuss his call-in show demeanor, other employers have
had a different experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the most difficult employee I've ever had in my life,''
says Bob Wussler, former executive vice president of Turner
Broadcasting who now runs a media consulting business in
Washington. ``He wanted to show up late and go home early. He never
wanted to read the promos. We had epic battles over contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to deal with him, including Ted (Turner),''
Wussler adds. ``But at the end of the day, he did whatever you
wanted him to do. It was just getting him to the point of agreeing
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray's handling of pregame callers came to a head last season
when sports talk-show hosts at rival 790 The Zone regularly blasted
what they viewed as Caray's abrupt, rude manner with fans phoning
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were very irritated by his treatment of callers,'' says
790 afternoon host ``Steak'' Shapiro, who admits fanning the flames
to gig the competition. ``It sounds like the last place he wants to
be is in front of a mike talking to listeners. When I started to
trumpet that, the response was huge. People said, `Finally,
somebody is calling this guy out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Others recall an off-the-air Caray who could be gregarious and
generous one minute (``I know him as a guy who'd give you the shirt
off his back _ just don't try to take it,'' says on-air sidekick
Joe Simpson), then bitingly short-tempered the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to get crazy about any little thing. He'd get
furious,'' says his brother Chris Caray, retired from a St. Louis
travel business. ``He was a piece of work.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's a new man _ it's really spooky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes with age,'' Chris adds. ``There's a part of all of us
that continues to grow, even in our 50s and 60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting inside his home on a late Thursday afternoon, Caray is .
. . mellow. He looks over at a visitor and asks, ``You want a
drink?''
</P>
<P>
   The visitor blinks back. A few minutes earlier, Caray had gone
on about how he doesn't miss the booze one bit.
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head. ``Just because I don't drink 'em doesn't
mean I can't still pour 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   He then goes to the kitchen and puts together a whiskey and
water. Just a splash. Pours it with a fine, schooled hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a really good drink.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAYOR OF RUSH STREET
</P>
<P>
   Caray learned to pour 'em from the best: his father, the late
Hall of Fame announcer Harry Caray. It was his father who taught
Caray to love baseball, pushed him into broadcasting, showed him
what a good time the profession could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my dad in his underwear many times, coming out of the
bathroom, stubble on his face after a hangover, going to work,''
Caray recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Harry was an institution in St. Louis through four decades, then
