</P>
<P>
   ``Those were difficult times _ I couldn't really describe it,''
says his sister Patricia Caray, retired from Coca-Cola. ``It could
be tough, but the love was still there. Sometimes you had to remind
yourself of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Skip is not the kind of person who'd think about (the
divorce) one way or the other. He'd look at it as the hand he was
dealt and play it. He really loved his father _ to be his father's
son was all he could ever want.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry took his oldest son to spring training each year, and on
road trips with the Cardinals each summer. Skip loved it. He still
remembers the train rides, listening to coaches tell stories for
hours in hotel lobbies, mingling with players like they were
neighborhood dads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any heroes in baseball _ I knew the players on a
first-name basis,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Caray was a good high school athlete, but a knee injury turned
him into what he calls the first requirement of a sports announcer:
a frustrated athlete. He was in the booth by junior high school,
doing his own radio sports report on powerhouse KMOX. His
