<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADUATON-ATTIRE0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going out in style
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For the first time in 12 years, you and your
parents finally see eye-to eye on your choice of outfits: the cap
and gown.
</P>
<P>
   But as with every other get-up you've tried to sneak past the
'rents, your under-gown attire will be a series of compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Since it can get rather hot under that gown, and graduation
ceremonies seem to go on forever, try wearing something
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only outfit that 'breathes' less than a graduation gown is
a space suit,'' said Marne Loveman, marketing and development
associate at Party411.com. ``Nothing is worse than a graduate who
squishes across the stage, so think light, airy fabrics like cotton
and linen.''
</P>
<P>
   Women should look for a nice dress or skirt that does not extend
below their gown, which, according to Jostens, should hit about
midway between their knees and ankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the school has specific rules (and many do), please
make sure that Miss Graduate is wearing something easy and elegant
_ a simple dress or a skirt and blouse would be perfect,'' Loveman
said. ``Whatever she chooses, what's underneath should be in a
light color if her graduation gown is white, or yellow. Not only is
it cooler, but nothing ruins the look of that hard-earned
graduation gown more than seeing the faint outline of the magenta
dress underneath _ which, of course, you won't even notice until
the pictures come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys also feel the tug of looking nice in cap and gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on school customs, Mr. Graduate may need to wear a
tie,'' Loveman said. ``If so, this is the time to borrow a rep
(ribbed silk) tie or foulard (soft, lightweight silk, rayon or
acetate fabric made in a twill weave) from Dad to wear with a
neatly pressed shirt in white, blue or another pale color. Either a
spread collar or button down, both are perfectly fine. Even if a
tie is not required, it looks so much better that you ought to
bribe him to do it. Don't insist on dress trousers; neatly pressed
casual khaki or olive drab is fine. However, draw the line at jeans
and shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Sedberry, college administration counselor at Waco High
School, said the administration always tries to remind graduating
seniors that this is an important event and they should try to act
dignified in their appearance and demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them to wear a dark color under your (red) gown,''
Sedberry said. ``We also suggest they wear short sleeves because
often it's hot and they have to stay in (their gowns) for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable part of the graduate's attire is their
shoes. Any type of dress shoe should be fine, but just remember if
you can't walk around in them everyday without tripping and
falling, then it might be best to wear a different, more
comfortable pair. The last impression you want to leave your
classmates with is of you falling face-first on the stage or into
the superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls should go with a moderately dressy shoe,'' Loveman said.
``Boys need to wear either a loafer or dress shoe. Graduation is
not the place for flip-flops . . . tennis shoes or bunny slippers,
regardless of the gender of the graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedberry added: ``Students need to wear shoes that are
appropriate _ not tennis shoes, but dress shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveman said parents should explain to their children that
graduation ceremonies are meant to be a formal, important event not
a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor is graduation the time for your kid to affix a message out
of masking tape letters to the top of their mortarboard or the back
of their gowns,'' Loveman said. ``Do your best to discourage it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedberry agreed: ``We do discourage that because this is a
serious time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
