<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SKUBE-WIT0521-COX     05-20 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-WIT0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wall of words comes tumbling down
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Periodically there come in one's life Rubicons that
must be crossed, and one of these for Dr. Vivian Bearing is the
matter of punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   The lead character in Margaret Edson's Pulitzer Prize-winning
play, ``Wit,'' is a pedant for whom commas and commitment are
paired. ``Nothing but a breath _ a comma _ separates life from life
everlasting,'' her old professor E.M. Ashford declaims in a scene
that defines the play's deceptive conflict. ``It is very simple
really. With the original punctuation restored, death is no longer
something to act out on a stage, with exclamation points. It's a
comma, a pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Bearing, like her mentor, is a scholar, a ranking authority, she
lets us know, on the poetry of John Donne. She is also a
50-year-old woman dying of ovarian cancer. Between the two _ the
contingency of life and the confines of one particular cubbyhole in
the English department _ are no distinctions. ``I know all about
life and death. I am, after all, a scholar of Donne's Holy Sonnets,
which explore mortality in greater depth than any other body of
work in the English language.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit,'' as audiences have learned for themselves and drama
critics have ably pointed out, is a play about mortality and about
professional vanity. But it is also a play about the failure of
language. Therein lies, of course, the irony _ a word Bearing uses
with a literary critic's proprietary relish. (``Irony,'' Bearing
tells the audience with blue-nosed formality, ``is a literary
device that will be deployed to great effect.'')
</P>
<P>
   Things are never (ironically) quite as they seem, and among them
is communication between people who have every reason for mutual
understanding and yet are imprisoned by their private tongues. Even
here, the word ``imprisoned'' is not quite right because they have
chosen _ for reasons of pride _ to close the cell door behind them.
Knowing only the lingua franca of their subspecialty, they talk
past one another in a profusion of polysyllables. The nub of the
matter _ that she is going to die _ is buried in language, the very
medium by which one person connects with another.
</P>
<P>
   ``In invasive epithelial carcinoma,'' the lead oncologist tells
her, ``the most effective treatment modality. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   As he's speaking, Bearing is adjudicating what he'd said moments
before:
</P>
<P>
   ``Insidious. Hmm. Curious word choice. Cancer. Cancel.''
</P>
<P>
   The words, accurate enough in their technical meaning, obscure
more than they reveal. In doing so, they impose a conversational
distance between doctor and patient that both _ for their separate
reasons _ use as emotional protection.
</P>
<P>
   It is only slightly different with her doctor's understudy, a
young man who, it turns out, took Bearing's course in 17th-century
poetry while an undergraduate. Jason Posner remembers her; she does
not remember him. Both are competitively intelligent, fearful of
making a mistake, fencing with every word. Now it is the student
who has the advantage. When the diagnosis is malignancy, literary
criticism is at even greater discount. But his patient's illness
only presents Posner with another intellectual puzzle to be solved,
not a life that has met its implacable enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Disease, as Susan Sontag wrote in ``Illness as Metaphor,'' is
the nightside of life, ``a more onerous citizenship. Everyone who
is born owns dual citizenship in the kingdom of the well and the
kingdom of the sick. Although we prefer to use only the good
passport, sooner or later each of us is obliged, at least for a
spell, to identify ourself as citizens of that other place.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wit,'' the duality is seen in the further dimension of
reason vs. feeling. In an opening scene that elicits laughter
because of its pomposity, Bearing _ speaking to the audience _
says, ``How are you feeling today? Great. That's just great.'' It
is not, she says, her usual way of speaking:
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend toward something a little more formal, a little less
inquisitive, such as, say, `Hello.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But people ask how she's feeling, and she must answer: ``Should
one reply, `I feel good,' using `feel' as a copulative to link the
subject, `I,' to its subjective complement, `good'; or `I feel
well,' modifying with an adverb the subject's state of being?''
</P>
<P>
   These, too, are intellectual puzzles, and she's reached the
point where she just says, ``I feel fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet feel is not what she habitually does, anymore than her
doctors do, and when the armor of intellect cracks she is exposed
and vulnerable. On her deathbed, her old mentor, a Dr. E.M.
Ashford, visits her. Words can no longer protect her, and she had
never allowed them to deepen her. She had used them to hide from
life. Her old teacher had seen it years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paper's not the point,'' Ashford is shown telling Bearing
when she was an undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vivian,'' teacher tells student, ``you're a bright young
woman. Use your intelligence. Don't go back to the library. Go out.
Enjoy yourself with your friends. Hmm?''
</P>
<P>
   She went outside, briefly. Students were on the lawn, ``talking
about nothing, laughing. The insuperable barrier between one thing
and another is . . . just a comma? Simple human truth,
uncompromising scholarly standards? They're connected? I just
couldn't . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And back to the library she went, to bury herself in texts, safe
from the world, safe from life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
