<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0972 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIO-ABRIDGED-ART     05-20 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIO-ABRIDGED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S VALUES GROWN IN CONSERVATIVE SOIL OF WEST TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: A full-length version, BUSH-BIO, has also been filed.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDLAND, Texas _ The fourth-grade classroom erupted in titters
as George W. Bush, one of the class clowns, faced his friends. He
had quietly used an ink pen to draw a beard and long sideburns on
his cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Frances Childress, marched George to the
principal's office at Sam Houston Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been making a disturbance in class,'' the principal, John
Bizilo, recalls Childress telling him.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was pretty obvious for anyone in the 1950s version
of the West Texas oil town of Midland: Bizilo told George to bend
over and then reached for his paddle, the thickness of a Ping-Pong
paddle but narrower and twice as long. Bizilo gave George three
``licks,'' and the boy's shrieks filled the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit him, he cried,'' Bizilo remembered. ``Oh, did he
cry! He yelled as if he'd been shot. But he learned his lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the roots of Bush's political philosophy as a
presidential candidate _ including his belief in tough love for
juvenile offenders _ seem to go back to his childhood. Midland, a
conservative, up-from-the-bootstraps town that has grown from
25,000 when he was a little boy to almost 100,000 today, mirrors
Bush's optimism, his faith in business and his doubts about an
activist government. While growing up, George W. Bush absorbed West
Texas values that many old friends say are central to understanding
who he is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his political philosophy comes completely from the
philosophy of the independent oil man,'' said Joe O'Neill, a fellow
rapscallion in childhood. ``His homage to his parents, his respect
for his elders, his respect for tradition, his belief in religion,
his opposition to abortion _ that's the philosophy he grew up with
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself made a similar point. ``I don't know what
percentage of me is Midland,'' he said, ``but I would say people,
if they want to understand me, need to understand Midland and the
attitude of Midland.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has often said that ``the biggest difference between me and
my father is that he went to Greenwich Country Day and I went to
San Jacinto Junior High.'' That may be an exaggeration of the
younger Bush's populist credentials, because he is also a product
of Andover, Yale and Harvard. But there is still something to it.
</P>
<P>
   The father suffered politically because of the perception that
he was a blue blood. The younger Bush also has been tainted by the
idea that he was born into privilege with a visa to effortless
wealth and prominence. Yet George W. Bush actually had a rather
ordinary childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Midland childhood is a striking contrast to that of another
boy growing up at the same time, Al Gore, who instead of being
paddled in Bizilo's office was attending the elite St. Albans
School in Washington and listening on an extension as his father
the senator spoke on the telephone to President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Midland was a world of clear rights and wrongs, long on
absolutes and devoid of ethical gray shades. It may be the source
of some of Bush's greatest political strengths, the
unpretentiousness and mellow bonhomie that warm up voters, and also
of his weaknesses, including an image of an intellectual
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   The oil made Midland a boomtown, attracting ambitious
businessmen like the elder Bush and many other out-of-staters.
These people made for a conservative town but not a redneck one;
Midland had a large proportion of geologists, engineers, lawyers
and accountants.
</P>
<P>
   Children bicycled everywhere and crime was almost nonexistent.
Yet what no one volunteers is that it was also rigidly segregated,
like most places in the South. Racial slurs were routine, and young
George picked up the words from neighbors. Once when he was about 7
years old he used one in front of his mother, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Proctor, who was playing with George at the time,
remembers watching as Bush dragged her son into the bathroom. She
washed his mouth out with soap as he spluttered indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family was probably the only one around that didn't use
racial slurs,'' Proctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the racism directed at blacks, there was a measured
respect for the Mexicans who came to work in the oil fields. As a
boomtown, Midland welcomed Mexican immigrants, who were regarded as
hard-working and thrifty. Some friends find an echo of that
attitude in Bush's efforts to push the Republican Party to reach
out to immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I formed the very strong impression,'' recalls Randall Roden,
a neighbor boy and friend, ``and I think George has the same one,
that these people came for economic opportunity and worked very
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, though born in 1946 in New Haven, Conn., while
his father was still a student at Yale, moved to West Texas when he
was not quite 2. The Bush family in the Northeast had money, but
the elder George left all that behind to make his own fortune in
West Texas. Equipped with connections but initially without seed
money, George and Barbara Bush and little George, their firstborn,
settled in a tiny apartment in the hard-driving oil town of Odessa.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They later moved to Midland and into a series of nicer houses as
the family prospered.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gov. Bush is often seen as a princeling, and Al Gore
as more of his own man. But in the 1950s and early 1960s, it was
the other way around. Back then, the name George Bush belonged only
to an obscure Texas businessman. In contrast, ``Albert Gore'' was
virtually a household name, belonging to a prominent senator (the
present candidate's father and namesake).
</P>
<P>
   Yet young George was not some country hick, and he also learned
to fit into the world of his Connecticut grandparents. The family
regularly spent part of the summer at the family retreat in
Kennebunkport, Maine, and in 1954 the father took George and his
best friend, Randall Roden, to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The boys and girls who once played dodgeball at Sam Houston
Elementary School offer recollections that are very similar:
Midland was an idyllic place in which to grow up, and George W.
Bush was a very typical child.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, his ambition was to be another Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``All George ever wanted to be was a Major League baseball
player,'' recalled a buddy, Terry Throckmorton. ``That's all he
ever talked about.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever accused Bush of being an intellectual, and the
indifference to books started early. Childhood friends recall Bush
reading only two sets of books for pleasure _ the Hardy boys and a
series of mystery books about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we sit around in those days reading books?'' asked Robert
A. McCleskey, a playmate, smiling broadly. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstwhile acquaintances, while deeply admiring of the Bushes'
goodness and decency, have trouble recalling early signs of
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no, I never did think about what he might do in life,''
said Austine Crosby, his third-grade teacher. ``He was just a good,
well-rounded young man, and he did his work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he did not distinguish himself as a student, former
classmates describe him as smart and blessed with an excellent
memory. He had a passion for baseball statistics, a first-rate
collection of baseball cards and a reputation as such a shrewd
trader.
</P>
<P>
   Midland may not have had the best schools, George's onetime
playmates say, but _ like Hot Springs, Ark., where Bill Clinton
grew up _ it offered a nurturing environment and self-confidence
for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a town of embedded values,'' Bush said of Midland, adding
that it had ``a heavy dose of individualism and fairly healthy
disrespect for government.''
</P>
<P>
   The city was also was steeped in optimism, and for many people
growing up here in the 1950s, the moral of childhood was that the
system worked, that anyone who struggled enough in that baking
desert had a good chance of finding oil and striking it rich.
</P>
<P>
   The antipathy for government seems a little odd, from afar,
because in those days the oil business depended heavily on quirks
in the tax code. Still, when the people of Midland sought a
theater, a hospital and a baseball diamond, they did not ask the
government but raised money themselves and turned out to do much of
the work.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one terrible interruption in his relaxed
childhood, occurring when George was 7. He was at school when he
saw his parents' green Oldsmobile drive up.
</P>
<P>
   His parents had come to tell him that his 3-year-old sister,
Robin, had died of leukemia. The loss staggered the family, and
some friends say that George's closeness to his mother dates partly
from his efforts to comfort her at that time.
</P>
<P>
   The death left him as a quasi-only child, for his next-oldest
sibling, Jeb, was six and a half years younger. Neil and Marvin
were 9 and 10 years younger, and Dorothy was 13 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's political debut appears to have come in the
seventh-grade. Classmates recall that he ran for class president
against Jack Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   Jack was a formidable candidate, and four years later at Boys
Nation he would be elected vice president, defeating a personable
candidate from Arkansas named Bill Clinton. Yet in running against
George, Jack was less fortunate, and classmates say that George was
elected by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for George because he was cuter,'' recalled Peggy
Porter Weiss, ``and in the seventh-grade that's what counted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
