<HEADER>
A0975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-KHMER-ROUGE-NYT &LR;      05-20 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KHMER-ROUGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRIALS FOR THE KHMER ROUGE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, May 20:
</P>
<P>
   Two decades after the Khmer Rouge killed more than a million
Cambodians, surviving leaders of the terror may finally be
prosecuted for their crimes. The United Nations recently reached an
agreement with the government of Cambodia that could establish a
credible judicial process for handling the cases. The court would
be in Cambodia and require the cooperation of the Cambodian leader,
Hun Sen, who had been seeking to cripple any prospect of
independent justice. He has now agreed _ orally at least _ to
substantial safeguards against his ability to manipulate the
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia's judicial system has neither the competence nor the
political independence to conduct fair trials on its own.
International participation is essential. At issue has been a
legitimate demand by the United Nations that the tribunal include a
foreign prosecutor with sufficient independent authority to issue
indictments. Under a compromise proposed by the United Nations,
co-prosecutors _ one foreign and one Cambodian _ would issue
indictments. Disputes between them would be resolved by a judicial
panel comprising three Cambodian judges and two foreign judges. A
``super majority'' of four judges would be required to quash an
indictment, meaning that the foreign judges could thwart any effort
by Hun Sen to override indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The new framework should make it possible to prosecute senior
Khmer Rouge officials with whom Hun Sen cut deals of immunity in
exchange for political loyalty. Some issues have yet to be ironed
out, including control over witness protection and extradition of
suspects who might flee Cambodia. There would still be room for Hun
Sen to try to manipulate the trials themselves. Cambodian judges
will have a say in the outcome of the trials as well as in
procedural rulings.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Hun Sen will carry out his end of
the bargain. But if he does, the trials would be conducted under
the careful scrutiny of international observers as well as the
Cambodian public. Breaches of due process will be duly noted and
widely condemned. Any miscarriage of justice will do harm both to
Cambodian survivors of the Khmer Rouge terror and to the
credibility of the United Nations. If it becomes clear that justice
is not being done, the United Nations must be prepared to suspend
its participation and walk away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
