<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-BLAIRBABY-052     05-20 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BLAIRBABY-0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    BRITAIN'S BLAIR, A DADDY AGAIN, IS MOVED BY THE EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON, Jr. 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ While he's unwilling to knock off a few weeks to be a
full-time daddy, British Prime Minister Tony Blair is expected to
bend his schedule to serve the needs of his new son.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's hard-driving attorney wife Cherie gave birth to Leo, the
couple's fourth child, early Saturday morning. It is the first
birth to a sitting prime minister in 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its being a novel advent because of the stature
of Leo's mom and dad, the birth and pregnancy also have been
watched closely because of his parents' ages: Blair is 47, and his
wife is 45.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cherie Blair's much chronicled pregnancy went without a
hitch, and the birth was natural and routine. It was the first
delivery that the prime minister attended in person.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to reporters in Downing Street Saturday afternoon, the
blue-jean clad prime minister was obviously moved by the
experience. ``It was the first time I've seen the whole thing
through, and it was quite a struggle, really,'' said Blair after a
night that had provided him little time for sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like any father who sees their baby born. It is a very
moving experience,'' he said. ``He's a gorgeous little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo was born four days ahead of schedule at 12.25 a.m. British
time (7:25 p.m. Eastern Time) and weighed 6 pounds 12 ounces. In a
bit of revenge for Cherie Blair, who has been displayed in her
heavily pregnant
</P>
<P>
   glory without mercy by British newspapers, the birth came too
late for the papers to indulge in their usual headline frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping past reporters staked out overnight at the hospital,
the Blairs returned to their Downing Street apartment immediately
after the delivery. The first glimpse of the new baby is not
expected until next week. For weeks, Britons have been debating
whether Blair would follow the leanings of his wife and Labor
Party, which support paternal leave, or the dictates of his
renowned workaholic personality.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who has said he expects to change his share of diapers,
has ruled out taking a full leave. Instead he said he will adopt a
vacation work schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously will try to do as much as possible to cut down in
that period what I'm doing,'' Blair said in a recent interview.
``But I still have to run the country; that still has to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days before heading to the hospital to give birth, Cherie
Blair _ who uses her maiden name Booth at work _ argued in court to
force her husband's government to expand Britain's new parental
leave law to cover
</P>
<P>
   parents of children born before the provision was enacted.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Cherie Blair _ a very successful lawyer _ caused a
buzz when she criticized the long hours demanded in today's
workplaces and encouraged employers to strike a balance between
work and family.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Finland's prime minister had availed himself of
his country's paternity leave laws to take time off from office.
``I, for one, am promoting a widespread adoption of this fine
example,'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   The British public apparently is fine with the idea of the prime
minister's leaving Parliament for parenthood. A Gallup poll in the
Daily Telegraph on May 15 found that 57 percent believe Blair
should take time off and ``let others take important decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that 60 percent of Britons believe that
someone ``who carries the heavy responsibilities that the Prime
Minister does should play an active part in caring for the new
baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Bookmakers had been taking bets on what the child might be
called, with Leo installed as 2-1 favorite. Yogi, Teddy and Rupert
were offered at 1,000-1. The baby was named after Blair's father.
</P>
<P>
   The Blairs' other children are sons Euan, 16 and Nicky, 15, and
daughter Kathryn, 12. The couple has worked with success to keep
them out of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Blair informed her husband of her condition in September,
on the eve of a major party conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a moment to forget,'' Blair recalled a few weeks
later. ``I think I said you're joking' and she said 'No, I'm
not.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked, you know, the usual questions and I did get round to
saying that's wonderful, darling. But that was after a few
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information: http://www.number-10.gov.uk,
http://www.bbc.co.uk,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ananova.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
