<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BLAIR-BABY-NYT &LR;      05-20 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-BABY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTER'S WIFE GIVES BIRTH TO BABY BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Cherie Blair, the wife of Prime Minister Tony Blair,
gave birth to a boy on Saturday, and hours later mother, father and
son left the London hospital for the privacy of 10 Downing St.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cherie and the baby are absolutely fine,'' Blair told
reporters outside the official residence. ``He's a gorgeous little
boy, and they are just resting now.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth child for the Blairs and the first baby born to a
serving prime minister in 152 years, Leo Blair arrived at 12:25
a.m. weighing 6 pounds 12 ounces. He was named for Blair's
76-year-old father, whom the prime minister called at his home in
Shrewsbury, Shropshire, with the news shortly after returning to
Downing Street at 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Blair, 45, had a natural childbirth, and Blair said he
was present in the delivery room. ``It was quite a long labor,'' he
said. ``It went on for quite a few hours, but it is quite a
struggle in the end for Cherie, and I think she is very relieved
it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking tired but relaxed in an open neck blue button-down shirt
and carrying a mug of coffee, Blair, 47, said: ``I feel like any
father who sees their baby born. It's very moving really, and if
any of you have been through it, you'll know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby, he said, had been ``really good through the night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is,'' he continued, ``you forget how tiny they are,
and also changing nappies in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added, ``It's quite an experience, but it's worse for
Cherie, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been tremendous interest in the arrival of a new
Blair, but the family delivered on its wish to keep the event as
private as possible. Except for the curbside news conference and
the flowers that kept arriving at the famous black front door with
the white 10 on it, the day was much like any other Saturday at the
Downing Street residence where the Blairs have made a point of
trying to produce as normal an upbringing as possible for their
family.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's other children, Euan, 16, Nicky, 14, and Kathryn,
12, have been kept out of the public spotlight, and judging by the
first day of his life, little Leo will also.
</P>
<P>
   A single bobby kept guard outside, and a construction team
worked noisily with spades, hammers and a pneumatic drill on a
leaking fire hydrant on the pavement opposite the brown brick
building housing the family apartment. Asked if he was worried he
might be waking the Blairs' newborn son, the drill operator, Chris
Southam, 28, said, ``I don't feel guilty because I have to work
seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the first bouquets to arrive were ones from the queen and
Prince Philip and from the Conservative party leader, William
Hague, 39, who was obliged by repeated questions to say that yes,
he and his wife, Ffion, did intend to start a family as soon as
they could.
</P>
<P>
   With so few images to play, television news spent the day
interviewing astrologers, baby magazine editors, parental rights
advocates and bookmakers, who had made Leo a 2-to-1 shot as the
best bet for the name.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had gone to the Chelsea and Westminster Hospital at noon
Friday. The prime minister followed in the evening, with an aide
carrying an overnight bag that was all the evidence the Saturday
morning newspapers needed to make the imminence of the new arrival
their page one headlines.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Saturday's Independent captured the mood. ``The
rumors started at lunchtime,'' it read. ``A 45-year-old woman had
gone into labor, and Fleet Street prepared to give birth.''
</P>
<P>
   The original announcement that Blair was pregnant came on Nov.
18 after word leaked to one of London's tabloid newspapers. Cherie
Blair had surprised her husband with the news in late September as
he worked in his office preparing the speech he was to deliver days
later to the annual Labor Party conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a moment to forget, but I do a little because I was
so shocked,'' Blair said in an interview published last Sunday in
The New York Times Magazine. ``Delighted, of course, but really
shocked. I think I said, `You must be joking,' and she said, `No,
I'm not.' I asked, you know, all the usual questions. And I think I
did get around to saying, `That's wonderful, darling.' But that was
after a few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Blair, a prominent employment rights lawyer, continued
working almost up to the birth, her last court appearance last week
appropriately dealing with the issue of parents juggling career and
family. On Tuesday she argued a case for the Trade Unions Congress
that challenged the way Blair's government has introduced parental
leave benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, modeled on a European Union directive, gives
parents the right to take 13 weeks off during the first five years
of their child's life, but the Blair government has restricted the
benefit to parents of children born after Dec. 15, 1999. Cherie
Blair, who practices under her unmarried name, Cherie Booth, told
the justices that the limit unlawfully excluded 2.7 million people
who were already parents of children under 5.
</P>
<P>
   The whole matter of parental leave became an issue for the
Blairs when she noted in a speech to a legal group in London the
experience of the Finnish prime minister, Paavo Lipponen, 59, who
took a week away from the office to spend with his newborn daughter
in March. Cherie Blair pointedly encouraged the ``widespread
adoption'' of Lipponen's ``fine example.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention turned to Blair, who let his decision on how he would
react be known in the Times Magazine interview. ``I know what
people want me to say,'' he said, ``but the truth is if I went away
and stopped taking calls or having any conversations, it just
wouldn't be real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take more time off. I'll try to cut down on official
things. You've got to have some common sense about it _ you want to
spend more time with your baby, but you don't give up the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
