<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-790&AMP;ADD-     05-20 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA REACTS MILDLY TO TAIWAN'S CHANGE OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Only two hours after Taiwan's new president
gave his inaugural address, authorities in Beijing released a
surprisingly temperate response, charging him with a lack of
sincerity but not repeating the dire threats and invective of
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In his first speech as president on Saturday, Chen Shui-bian
promised that unless the mainland attacked Taiwan, he would not
declare independence, change the country's official name of
``Republic of China,'' or take other overt steps to establish
Taiwan's formal independence.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Chen had called for just such acts in years past, it
was a measure of how far he has traveled to gain support among
Taiwan's nervous majority and to avoid provoking Beijing into a
military attack.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen, whose Democratic Progressive Party still includes many
champions of independence, did not say Taiwan was a part of ``one
China,'' as Beijing has repeatedly demanded.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, Taiwan officials were studying China's
response even as inaugural parties continued, and did not issue a
statement. But independent experts were intrigued by the lack of
expected belligerence and a tantalizing reference to conditions for
possible negotiations over economic and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's response was more moderate and gentle than we
expected,'' said Yang Kai-huang, an expert on cross-strait
relations at Soochow University. ``I think that China prefers to
talk rather than go to war.''
</P>
<P>
   In a famous story in Chinese history, Yang said, you give your
enemy a soft response as a test. If he does not pay you back with
good will, then you have every justification to come back with
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe China is using this strategy,'' Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   The actual exchange is couched in the fine semantical
distinctions over phrases like ``one China'' and ``two states''
that have taken on huge weight in the debate over Taiwan's future,
but may appear to outsiders to be little more than wordplay.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing considers Taiwan to be a vital part of Chinese territory
that was separated during the civil war that ended in 1949, when
Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists fled to Taiwan. Chen, in his newly
moderate stance that still leaves Beijing enraged, says Taiwan does
not need to declare independence, because in practice it is already
a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, ratcheting up the pressure, Beijing has said
that indefinite delay in progress toward reunifying Taiwan with the
motherland could be cause for war. It has lambasted Chen, who was
elected in March, for failing to adopt ``one China'' as a starting
point in future relations.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, China says it can grant Taiwan exceptional
autonomy, greater than Hong Kong's, if it will only accept the
notion of unity.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Chen, in a speech that was mainly devoted to
domestic concerns and Taiwan's progress toward democracy, did not
discuss reunification, but rather the need to build ``conditions
for cooperation through good will.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, in an ambiguous statement that, given his
background, seemed to be half an olive branch, ``We believe that
the leaders on both sides possess enough wisdom and creativity to
jointly deal with the question of a future `one China.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing, in an unusually quick response, predictably called Chen
``insincere'' on the central issue of unity. The statement, issued
by the Communist Party Central Committee and the government's
Taiwan Affairs Office, said, ``The new leader adopted an evasive
and ambiguous attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the new leader of the Taiwan authorities expressed that
he would not go in for `Taiwan independence,' he should have
attached no condition to it,'' said the statement, carried by the
New China News Agency. ``Still less should he have refuted the
reality that there is but one China and that Taiwan is part of
China by saying that one China is something in the `future.'''
</P>
<P>
   But compared with recent threats, the statement seemed mild.
Even more intriguing was the discussion of specific conditions
under which negotiations between the mainland and Taiwan might
begin. Chen, during his campaign for the presidency, said he was
ready to talk about relaxing restrictions on direct transportation,
commerce and communications across the Taiwan Strait _ something
that Beijing has long sought.
</P>
<P>
   The statement Saturday said that the suspended negotiations
between a Chinese semigovernmental group, the Association for
Relations Across the Strait, and a Taiwanese counterpart could
begin again if the two sides ``will express in their own way orally
that both sides across the strait stick to the `one China'
principle,'' as China says the two sides did in 1992.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Beijing and Taipei differ in their explanation of what exactly
was agreed to on the meaning of ``one China'' then, but in 1992
they were able to set the issue down long enough to hold meetings
and consider more practical issues.
</P>
<P>
   A second condition for new talks laid down by Beijing was that
``the Taiwan authorities make a clear-cut commitment that they will
not advocate the `two-states theory.'''
</P>
<P>
   This refers to the statement last year by outgoing President Lee
Teng-hui that Taiwan and China enjoyed a ``special state-to-state''
relationship, rather that one of a locality to the center. The
words caused a crisis and led China to end all negotiations with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's security officials have already said they do not intend
to use the offending phrase, but add that it merely described
reality. So depending on how much China wants to talk, this
condition could be declared met or not.
</P>
<P>
   It remains doubtful that Chen can agree, right now, even to an
oral statement that there is only ``one China,'' many experts
believe. Before he can make any bold moves on policy toward the
mainland, Chen needs to build more of a consensus in his party and
the society, said Bau Tzong-ho, a political scientist at National
Taiwan University.
</P>
<P>
   So the more tempered statement from Beijing on Saturday may not
be a breakthrough, these experts said. But it may force Taiwan to
weigh anew how far it can bend its own ideal in order to keep China
talking rather than shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen's words on cross-strait issues Saturday were
designed to avoid provocation, the entire speech carried a subtext
that could not please leaders in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of his talk was not devoted to the confrontation
with the mainland but rather the state of Taiwan's hard-won
democracy, the need to root out corruption, economic and
environmental goals, and devotion to human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The speech ended with Chen shouting: ``Long live freedom and
democracy! Long live the people of Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, noted Andrew Yang, who heads a defense research
institute here, ``The speech carried heavy symbolism that Taiwan is
an independent country already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
