<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CHINA-TRADE-BILL-485&AMP;     05-20 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-BILL-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CRITICS OF TRADE BILL ARE SWAYING VOTE IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Neb., Colo.)   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the China trade bill slips through Congress this
week, as some supporters now expect, Rep. Sander M. Levin, D-Mich.,
who has voted against all of President Clinton's major trade
initiatives, will _ ironically _ take some credit for helping
provide the margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Levin won backing from House leaders late last week to amend the
bill granting China permanent trade ties to establish a human
rights and trade policy monitoring commission for China. Vote
counters on both sides of the aisle said the proposal, co-sponsored
by Rep. Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., has helped recruit perhaps two dozen
undecided lawmakers into the pro-trade camp.
</P>
<P>
   China has called the proposed commission an interference in its
internal affairs. The Republican leadership had been cool to the
idea. Clinton administration officials had kept their distance.
Labor unions and some human rights groups have called it weak.
</P>
<P>
   But Levin's proposal has proven crucial to Democrats, and a few
Republicans, who have found it politically impossible to vote for
trade deals in recent years because labor unions and consumer
groups oppose them so strongly. If critics call it a fig leaf,
supporters are hailing it as an innovative tool to keep political
pressure on China even while granting it long-sought guaranteed
trade access to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited to see what he would come up with before I decided,''
said Diana L. DeGette, D-Colo., who announced her support for the
Clinton administration's top remaining legislative priority after
Levin detailed the commission's structure on Friday. ``My
constituents care a great deal about human rights and want to see
something done on this front.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was modeled on the Helsinki Commission, which inspected
human rights conditions behind the Iron Curtain during the Cold
War. Levin envisions that Congress and the White House will appoint
high-level commissioners, including members of Congress and
distinguished outsiders, who could monitor conditions in China and
report to both branches.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the commission would issue a report recommending
legislative or administrative steps that might help raise pressure
on China to improve its human rights conditions, though it would
not have the power to enforce its recommendations. The commission
could study ways of turning up the heat on Beijing that are not
inconsistent with the World Trade Organization, including some
kinds of sanctions and U.S. policy toward loans from international
aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A second part of the Levin-Bereuter proposal enacts into law
provisions that would help the United States fight sudden surges of
imports from China. Both provisions won backing from the Republican
leadership last week, which agreed to include them as part of the
bill that would grant China permanent trade status. A vote in the
House is expected to take place Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Levin represents a heavily unionized district of Michigan. With
unions increasingly wary of foreign trade deals that open markets
and threaten industrial jobs, Levin hasn't met many trade
agreements he likes. He voted against the North American Free Trade
Agreement in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He said he decided late last year to find an alternative to a
straight vote on China's trade status. He said he wanted to
``reshape globalization'' so that trade deals would promote human
values, not just the free shipments of goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that trade and globalization can be forces for
good, and we can't stop them,'' Levin said. ``But we have to shape
them. In China's case, you can't just vote yes and trust that
social and economic changes will come along together.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions and consumer groups have criticized the proposal as
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a well-meaning effort,'' said Thea Lee, a senior official
at the AFL-CIO and an outspoken opponent of the China trade bill.
``But it's redundant with what's already done and may even be
counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some human rights groups are less dismissive, though many say
that the Levin commission could be much stronger if it had the
power to force a Congressional vote on its recommendations each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be stronger and we think that there's a chance it
will be stronger before this is finished,'' said Mike Jendrzejczyk
of Human Rights Watch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jendrzejczyk said the Helsinki Commission had real influence on
Soviet bloc nations, but that China, unlike the former Soviet Union
and Eastern Europe, had not signed a treaty permitting review and
inspection of human rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
