<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SWISS-CITIZENSHIP-520     05-20 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-CITIZENSHIP-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS POLICY ON CITIZENSHIP STIRS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ When Alija Huskic and his wife, Suzana, left Bosnia in
1991, just before war erupted there, they chose Switzerland for
refuge because of its reputation for good works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know anyone there, but we knew that Geneva was the
symbol of the humanitarian tradition,'' Huskic said. After moving
to the city that is the base for the International Red Cross,
Huskic, now 41, who had trained as a mechanical engineer, began
work as a caretaker for two estates. His wife found a job as a
nursery school teacher. Their daughter, Nina, went to school. They
mastered French, and slipped easily into Swiss society.
</P>
<P>
   In three more years, they will be eligible to apply for Swiss
passports.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed until March, when 48 naturalization applications
in a blue-collar suburb of the Swiss city of Lucerne were defeated
in a popular vote. All those turned down were Turks or people from
the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection has stirred debate across Switzerland, beginning
in Emmen _ the Lucerne suburb _ which in April halted review of its
250 pending naturalization requests amid charges that its vote on
the issue amounted to racist selection.
</P>
<P>
   The government announced that it would study simplifying the
process of becoming a citizen, and revived proposals to allow the
children of foreigners born in Switzerland to get passports more
easily.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Europe warned that the country's system left
``room for discriminatory practice,'' a finding that made the Swiss
bristle, particularly after the international criticism of their
actions in World War II, which included turning away Jewish
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss law gives foreigners who meet the residency requirements
and have no criminal record the right to apply for Swiss
nationality as long as they are integrated into Swiss society. What
the Emmen vote made clear is that foreigners must virtually become
more Swiss than the Swiss to stand a chance of holding a passport.
</P>
<P>
   As part of what some media have dubbed the ``fondue test,''
local officials usually stop by the applicant's house to check on
the way the family lives, the level of cleanliness and neatness,
and, some say, even what they eat. ``Whether our house is clean or
not does not indicate whether we are fit to be citizens,'' said
Huskic, who nonetheless notes that the future of his 17-year-old
daughter Nina lies in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Diltz, a member of the Emmen legislative body, sees no
problem with asking that foreigners be assimilated. ``If they want
to be Swiss, it's not enough if they just try to speak the
language. They must do more,'' she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, suspicion of foreigners has been
aggravated by the record number of people from the Balkans who have
flooded into Switzerland. Federal policy bars such asylum seekers,
who are viewed as transients, from working.
</P>
<P>
   Resentment has been fueled by perceptions that many foreigners
engage in crime, particularly drug trafficking. Overall, one in
five are non-Swiss in the country of 7.2 million, which has one of
Europe's highest percentages of foreigners.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This explosive mix has been percolating for several years, as in
other European countries, including neighboring Austria, and it led
last fall to soaring support for the nationalist Swiss People's
Party, which campaigned on the slogan ``Stop Asylum Abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Emmen vote, several villages elsewhere in Switzerland
have rejected applicants for citizenship, most of them also from
the Balkans. These decisions _ part of the enshrined Swiss idea
that the people decide _ have rarely been contested in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But in March, a court struck down the refusal by the town of
Pratteln in northwestern Switzerland to give citizenship to five
Turks, while accepting Italians and Spaniards, on grounds that it
violated the constitution's ban on discrimination. The town is
considering an appeal to Switzerland's top tribunal, which would
set the stage for a landmark ruling defining once and for all what
is required to be a Swiss citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss human rights groups, meanwhile, have banded together to
push for laws giving asylum seekers full social and economic
rights, and to get the employment ban on them repealed.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, officials even offered citizenship to the 48 people
rejected by Emmen, an impractical offer since they live in a
different city and speak German rather than French.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we require everyone to be assimilated, we are creating a
country where everyone has the same ideas about our problems,''
said Jean-Marc Froidevaux, one of the Geneva politicians who made
the offer. ``This is not going to help Switzerland get ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
