<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POLAND-RUSSIA-720&AMP;ADD     05-20 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-RUSSIA-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA AND POLAND SEEK TO HEAL RIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ In Poland, long a trophy of East-West
competition and now one of NATO's newest members, the installation
of Vladimir Putin as Russia's president has raised new questions
about Moscow's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has signaled a desire to improve relations between the
former Warsaw Pact allies, making telephone calls to the Polish
president and showing new openness about the killing of Polish
officers during World War II by the Soviets at Katyn, Polish
Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek said.
</P>
<P>
   The overtures mark a welcome symbolic change from recent public
feuds over Russian spying in Poland and Polish popular support for
the Chechens, which caused Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to
cancel a visit here in February.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the signals from Putin, senior Polish officials say a
serious exchange of official visits is unlikely before autumn, and
other influential officials, like Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek's
chief foreign policy adviser, Jerzy Marek Nowakowski, see more
difficult times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   They say that Putin is likely to increase diplomatic and
economic pressure on Ukraine to draw closer to Moscow, putting
Poland, which favors a sovereign Ukraine's orientation toward the
West, in a more awkward position.
</P>
<P>
   They say they also expect Putin, who is trying to show a
stronger Russian face abroad and extend Russian influence, to try
to block any further expansion of NATO membership, especially to
any Baltic nation, something Warsaw also supports. Poland is
especially eager to have its neighbors Lithuania and Slovakia in
NATO, Geremek said.
</P>
<P>
   But some Polish analysts say that a new government is likely to
take a softer line toward Moscow in any case, meaning that Putin
has little incentive to put real substance behind his effort at
better ties.
</P>
<P>
   Marek Matraszek, Warsaw director of CEC Government Relations, a
political consulting firm, noted that the leftist party's leaders,
including President Aleksander Kwasniewski, have spoken about a
reconciliation with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Matraszek said that a new government would be less likely to
push a new round of NATO expansion that would include any Baltic
states _ still a red line for Moscow, which in Soviet times ruled
the three Baltic nations for 50 years, and still feels proprietary
about the many ethnic Russians living there.
</P>
<P>
   Geremek emphasized that the first year of Poland's membership in
NATO had proved ``a force for stability in Europe,'' answering
those who thought NATO expansion would destroy the West's relations
with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is trying to press the idea that NATO expansion is
creating problems, not solving them,'' Geremek said. ``But it's not
true. NATO expansion has stabilized the region. And our support for
postcommunist integration should not destroy the policy of good
neighborly relations.'' Given trade, markets and energy interests,
he said, both countries ``have the basis for a more normal
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   It was left to a senior aide to point out that NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia over Kosovo _ which started less than a month after the
Poles, Czechs and Hungarians joined NATO last spring _ did more to
upset Moscow than NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow-Warsaw disputes earlier this year had more to do with
Russian domestic politics than any Polish policy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As Putin maneuvered for the presidency, Moscow found it useful
to ``play the Polish card'' in response to NATO and prospective
European Union enlargement, officials said, touching the ever-ready
anti-Russian nerve here.
</P>
<P>
   Poland was the one new NATO member that wanted to celebrate its
first anniversary of membership and remains fundamentally
pro-American and pro-NATO. In the Czech Republic and Hungary, by
contrast, the war in Kosovo _ coming so soon after their entry into
the alliance _ underscored deep doubts about NATO among significant
minorities of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Grzegorz Kostrzewa-Zorbas, a former government official and a
scholar of international relations at the Polish Academy of
Sciences, sees Russian policy toward Poland driven almost entirely
by the domestic Russian debate over the loss of national pride and
status. Kosovo was a pretext, not a central factor, he says. ``The
Russians regard us as Slavic traitors and puppets of the West,'' he
said. ``That still resonates.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The relationship, given the swings of history, has been
traumatic for both sides. Poland occupied the Kremlin in the 17th
century and defeated the Red Army in 1920, while doing much to
destroy Moscow's sway over Eastern Europe. Poles, who like to think
of their country as the European cultural center that brought forth
Chopin and a strong Catholic Church, remember the occupation by
Russia and then the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Poland expelled nine Russian diplomats accused of
spying, many of them caught on videotape, officials say, picking up
or leaving material at hidden drops. The Russians responded by
expelling nine Polish diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Then in February a demonstration in Poznan against Russian
actions in Chechnya turned ugly when protesters broke into the
Russian Consulate and tore up the Russian flag. The police watched,
but did nothing. The Polish government apologized and dismissed
some policemen, but Ivanov canceled his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Polish officials say that Putin now seems to understand that
public disputes with Poland can be counterproductive, especially
given that Poland remains Moscow's seventh-largest trading partner.
At least 100,000 Russians, Belarussians and Ukrainians live and
work here. At the same time, officials say, some senior
representatives of Russian organized crime have traveled to Poland
on diplomatic passports.
</P>
<P>
   Nowakowski, a Russian expert, says that timing is important.
Putin became president after Poland entered NATO, so he can start
afresh to create ``a more realistic partnership.'' Putin is also
considering attending a ceremony in July when Poland opens a
military cemetery for the dead of Katyn, officials say, which would
be a gesture highly prized here.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Nowakowski said, Russia is trying to play
Polish politics now, paying more attention to President Kwasniewski
and the former communists than to the government, and trying to win
support for a second natural-gas pipeline through Poland to Western
Europe that would bypass Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   For Nowakowski, ``the future of the states between Russia and
Poland'' _ Ukraine, Belarus and the Baltic nations _ ``is the most
important question for Russian-Polish relations.'' And he sees
potential trouble ahead, especially over Ukraine, where Russia
could use economic levers and even military pressure to keep Kiev
in line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
