<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SEPARATISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMED GANGS SABOTAGING UNEASY PEACE IN INDONESIA  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JANTHOE BARU, Indonesia _ If an era of peace is dawning in
restive Aceh Province, no one seems to have told the villagers of
Janthoe Baru.
</P>
<P>
   Since armed men descended from the nearby mountains on the night
of May 7 and looted and razed 21 houses, around 1,500 terrified
people have been sleeping every night at the village mosque.
</P>
<P>
   The destitute villagers, as well as officials in the nearby
provincial capital, Banda Aceh, are either unsure about the
identity of the armed men, who are blamed for a series of killings,
looting and arson, or are afraid or unwilling to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid has conceded that rogue soldiers
from the Indonesian Defense Forces might be involved in the
attacks. But local police and military officials in Aceh say an
unidentified ``third force'' of hired thugs, bandits, or even
disgruntled independence fighters from the Free Aceh Movement is to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   Separatists in Aceh, a staunchly Muslim region on the northern
tip of Sumatra, have been fighting for independence since 1976 and
pose a major problem for Wahid as he tries to stabilize his nation
of 210 million people. Many people say that it is of far greater
urgency for Indonesia to stop Aceh from slipping away than it was
in the case of East Timor, which voted for independence last year.
</P>
<P>
   With Aceh, they say, the nation's sovereignty, stability and
economic future are at stake. Aceh accounts for 13 percent of
Indonesia's oil production and the shipping lanes through the
Strait of Malacca between Aceh and Malaysia, are among the busiest
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Army generals in Jakarta, Indonesia's capital, have made it
clear that they will not allow Aceh to gain independence, a move
that experts have warned could set off a violent ``Balkans-style''
breakup of Indonesia and threaten regional security in Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen the breakup of Europe,'' said Abdullah Ali, a
leading political analyst and university professor in Banda Aceh.
``Who knows? We should keep our fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   People across this province of 4 million are leaving nothing to
chance. Mosques in Banda Aceh and other provincial centers have
been packed daily with worshipers praying for the success of an
agreement between the Indonesian government and the separatist
guerrillas that was signed on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, signed in Geneva, is seen as a first step to
ending fighting that has killed as many as 5,000 people since 1989.
The pact calls for a ``humanitarian pause'' in hostilities
beginning in June and the establishment of two independent
commissions to monitor the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But major issues have yet to be worked out, including autonomy
for the province, disarming the rebels, and removing non-Acehenese
military units. For their part, the rebels have refused to drop
their 24-year-old demand for independence.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman here, Col. Safri Deangmapuji, said
provocateurs had stepped up attacks to undermine trust between the
Indonesian military and rebels. He blamed them for a grenade attack
on a police traffic post last Sunday, two days after the peace
agreement was signed. The authorities also suspect that the
unidentified armed group lobbed a grenade at a police truck the
next day, wounding three people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard for the police,'' Deangmapuji said. ``We're
trying to respect this agreement, but on the other hand you have
this group running around trying to disrupt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims and witnesses said the attackers wore civilian clothes
and sandals during some raids and military uniforms during others.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid initially said the provocateurs were rebels dressed in
military uniforms, but at a recent news conference he said he had
been told that ``some are rogue elements belonging to'' the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The military has logging and other business interests in Aceh,
and does not want the province to break away as East Timor did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the central government tries to negotiate with the Free
Aceh Movement, the military does not seem to agree that the
government should sign an agreement,'' said Saifuddin Bantasyam,
executive director of the Care Human Rights Forum in Banda Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if there's something happening in Aceh, then the military
can say there is no reason to sit down with the Free Aceh
Movement,'' he said, adding that his organization had no evidence
to implicate either the military or the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bantasyam conceded that very few people had blamed
rebels for attacks on civilians, while the military has an
extensive record of human rights abuses against the Acehenese,
including killings, kidnappings and torture.
</P>
</TEXT>
