<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The low-pressure system that has brought repeated rains to the
Middle Atlantic states over the past few days will remain nearly
stationary Sunday, bringing yet another bout of showers and
thunderstorms. In the Carolinas, some strong thunderstorms will
develop with large hail and damaging winds a possibility. Farther
to the north, continued onshore breezes will yield another cloudy,
damp and cool day along the Northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will develop in the lower Mississippi Valley on Sunday,
as a pocket of cool air above 5,000 feet passes over warm, moist
air. Some of the showers will produce very heavy rainfall in brief
periods of time. Meanwhile, showers will also develop in the
western Great Lakes as warm air is forced to rise up and over
cooler air.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing onshore winds in the Pacific Northwest will produce
showers, clouds and patches of fog. The deserts of the Southwest
will remain very hot.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MOIST MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   A deluge struck Grand Rapids and Lansing, Mich., on Thursday as
nearly 3 1/3 inches of rain fell on both cities. This is now the
second wettest May on record in Grand Rapids with more than 7
inches of rain so far. The extraordinary wetness resulted from a
line of intense thunderstorms moving across the same area. Like a
log in a stream aligned with the current, these rainmakers followed
a course over the same region for several hours, producing record
rainfall.
</P>
</TEXT>
