<SLUG> BC-DC-MAYOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MAYOR GETS THINGS DONE QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If all continues to go well, the nation's capital
will be allowed out of the intensive care ward fashioned by
Congress sometime next year. The District of Columbia will not only
regain home-rule prerogatives lost in its profligate past; it will
also confirm the stewardship of Mayor Anthony Williams, an unlikely
politician as bland in his style as the paint on the municipal
walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sea change from four years ago,'' the mayor said,
his zest characteristically masked as he pursued a budget fight
with the district council and tackled a school crisis. He hailed
these problems as a healthy sign of the revival of local
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are debating not whether we're going to spend the city
into the ground or not,'' Williams said. ``The new question is how
much we're going to invest in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   This city-state by the Potomac, the perennial ward that Congress
seems delighted to scold and micromanage, is clearly moving to a
higher ground of civic morale. Constituents' confidence about the
city's direction has more than doubled in the less than two years
of the Williams administration, with seven in 10 residents feeling
positive about the city's course, according to polls of the
district's often demoralized public.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, some of the watchdogs of Capitol Hill are
snapping less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Williams is making real progress in turning around
Washington,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who heads
the District of Columbia subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Williams arrived here in 1995 as a grim technocrat and emergency
budget cutter when Congress created a board of financial overseers
to halt the capital's spiral of deficits and mismanagement and
hired him as chief financial officer. From that narrow opportunity,
he molted into a competitive politician and became the people's
choice in a difficult time.
</P>
<P>
   In his 16 months as mayor, Williams, 48, has labored to replace
the city's wastrel image of the flamboyant Marion Barry era with
his own devotion to quiet executive techniques. In a way, the best
measure of Williams' initial success may be the fact that he is
sometimes criticized for lacking the populist flash of Barry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He suffers from terminal caution,'' complained Mark Plotkin, a
relentless civic goad and the political commentator for the local
public radio station WAMU. Plotkin made the mayor sound like Calvin
Coolidge, complimenting him for installing ``rectitude and calm''
but faulting him for failing to fully tap the energy of his
electoral mandate and ``take us to another plane'' by fighting with
passion for needs like full self-rule and voting rights for the
city's congressional delegate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've had flair before,'' the district council
chairwoman, Linda W. Cropp, said of the Barry era. She expressed no
regret for the businesslike Williams style, even as she confronts
him in the budget fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's given the district a sense of hope that things can
happen,'' Cropp said. ``He has many wonderful ideas, although when
it comes to implementing them he's still on a learning curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Major problems like the tattered school system and persistent
youth violence are far from solved. But the mayor and the council
seem resolved to innovate: They are presenting the voters a
referendum next month to give the mayor a role in school management
through the power to appoint some members of the school board. They
are also on the way to delivering four balanced budgets in a row,
the required formula for regaining home-rule powers after years of
chimerical bookkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   In this endeavor, Williams has assiduously avoided what in the
Barry era came to be known as ``the race card'' _ harvesting the
vote of the divided district's black working-class majority by
playing off the affluent white minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never personally use race as an excuse for anything,''
said Williams, a Yale graduate. He emphasized his obligation to
unify and not to deal with the criticism, by now a cliche, that he
might not be ``black enough'' for a city that is 60 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's not appropriate for others,'' he said of
racial complaints. ``But I've been given a lot of opportunities and
advantages where I'm sure I can personally say race plays a role.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor stressed that Washington ``is still very fractured and
divided.'' But he insisted that unheralded programs of mutual good
will crisscross the Anacostia River, the city's main racial
dividing line. He maintained that a recent increase in auto
registrations indicated the viability of his goal of gaining
100,000 residents in this decade, including returning suburbanites
attracted by the district's walkable neighborhoods and burnished
housing stock.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Anacostia in one of the low-income southeast wards
that are part of the black political power base, the new mayor,
despite his ruling-class aura, occasioned no great complaint at
Brace's Unisex salon on Minnesota Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Barry was a great people person,'' Alice Taylor said.
``This new mayor is working at a different angle. But he's doing
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Clara Sherrod agreed. ``Barry was a street politician
who knew our problems,'' she said. ``But I'd say the streets are
really looking better with Williams. He's having grass planted
around here and cleaning up things.''
</P>
<P>
   Over in Georgetown, part of the district's white power base in
the northwest quarter, there is palpable pleasure at the way the
Williams bow tie is replacing the Barry dashiki as a D.C.
signature. ``He's made the city a lot more presentable,'' said Pat
Scanlon, a volunteer at the Christ Child Opportunity Shop, a
consignment store on Wisconsin Avenue that finances local
charities.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a white customer who would not give his name grumbled:
``He still thinks this is a black city and packs the payroll with
his own. What about us?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it is a black city,'' Scanlon responded. ``So what's
wrong with hiring your people who are qualified so they work and
pay taxes and have nice houses?''
</P>
<P>
   In the Barry years, the payroll for the district, which must
provide a mix of state and city services, was criticized as a
strategic patronage trough when it ballooned to 50,000 employees
for a city of 550,000. It has been cut since the fiscal crisis was
declared five years ago; this year it reached a congressionally
authorized level of 32,719, a reduction of 1,450 from last year,
although Williams wants it lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running this city is like Roebling trying to build the
Brooklyn Bridge and digging and digging for the bedrock,'' he said
in frustration. He said he kept uncovering the ``muck'' of old
corruption as he tried to reform such scandal-ridden agencies as
the mental retardation treatment program, whose lethal failures
were laid bare by The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer is what I call agency bypass surgery,'' he said of a
radical plan to create an entire new treatment agency alongside the
existing failed system to supersede it.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of these past failures has prompted Eleanor Holmes
Norton, the district's congressional delegate, to caution that any
criticism of Williams ``should be tempered by the disaster
disguised as a city'' that he inherited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making this city work,'' Norton said. ``He's what we
needed _ a mayor who came to office who had done something other
than run for office.''
</P>
<P>
   While he is portrayed as an un-politician who is making the city
forget the slick Barry era, Williams actually apprenticed seriously
in practical politics as an elected member of the New Haven, Conn.,
board of aldermen when he was studying at Yale for his
undergraduate degree in economics. Twenty years later, he is not
above artfully stroking his Capitol Hill watchdogs; he even
attended a fund-raiser for an influential conservative Republican,
Rep. Ernest Istook of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to look out for my people, you know,'' the mayor
explained, unapologetic about becoming the complete practitioner in
the nation's ultimate political city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
