<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRUG-MONEY-I-KAN &LR;      05-20 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MONEY-I-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ACROSS COUNTRY EVADE LAWS TO KEEP CONFISCATED PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN DILLON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Hughes said.)
</P>
<P>
   As a result, private citizens are now more vulnerable to
forfeiture because circumvented state laws often provide more
protections than federal forfeiture laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, some state laws protect people from having property
forfeited by police unless they're charged with a felony. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But under federal law, authorities don't even need a criminal
charge to forfeit property. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, experts estimate that the great majority of forfeitures
occur without a criminal charge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most state laws require that forfeitures be ordered by a judge.
Federal law enforcement has the power to order forfeitures without
a judge _ and does in most cases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And it's costly to contest a federal forfeiture. Defense
attorneys estimate it costs at least $10,000, so many won't even
accept a case unless the value of the seizure is large. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {( Begin optional trim )}
</P>
<P>
   Although many people whose property is seized are no doubt
guilty of a crime, that doesn't mean all are. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Carroll, a disabled, 64-year-old Maryland woman, could
lose her house because police found a third of an ounce of cocaine
and other drugs that some of her children left there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under Maryland law, a house usually can't be forfeited without a
criminal conviction. Police tapped the federal government to
forfeit the three-acre property, which has been in Carroll's family
for a century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I got sick, so sick in my stomach and started crying,''
Carroll said. ``I'm just praying.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, who has osteoarthritis and receives $500 a month from
Social Security disability, has never been convicted of a crime,
her attorney said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The state can't take her house, so they run to the feds,''
said the attorney, Stephen F. Allen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carroll continues to live in the home while Allen fights the
forfeiture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Salem, Assistant U.S. Attorney, described the forfeiture
as a ``hybrid adoption'' because federal agents were aware of the
police investigation but were not involved in the searches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Salem also said the forfeiture would be justified because
Carroll didn't take enough steps to protect her property, even
though she says she evicted her children and changed a lock before
proceedings began. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She claims she changed a lock on a door though I'm unclear
which door it is,'' Salem said. ``She claims she took steps that
even if I would credit them as true, the government believes them
to be insufficient to justify innocent ownership. There was no
effect. That didn't keep the children out of the house.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {( Begin optional trim )}
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that many state laws have tougher forfeiture
standards than federal law, legislators say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to make sure that people who are subject to
forfeitures have some basic rights,'' said Georgia Rep. Jim Martin,
a Democrat and chairman of the Judiciary Committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And some of those protections are erased when police give the
money to federal law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   {( End optional trim )}
</P>
<P>
   Not all police departments send forfeitures to federal agencies,
but many that do candidly acknowledge it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody uses the federal system,'' said Lt. Harry Kearley of
the Alabama Bureau of Investigations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, police explain, they believe money they seize is
linked to drugs, but they can't prove it under state standards, and
they don't want to give the money back to a suspected drug dealer.
Federal law lets them take the money out of the owner's hands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {( Begin optional trim )}
</P>
<P>
   For example, police in Azusa, Calif., used easier federal
requirements to take at least one forfeiture worth more than
$450,000 to them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, an officer stopped a driver for improper use of his
turn signal and searched the vehicle when the driver said it didn't
belong to him. The officer found $611,500 in a hidden compartment.
A dog signaled the presence of drug residue on the cash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To forfeit the money under state law, police usually need a
felony conviction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But police found no drugs and sent the driver on his way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, the department gave the money to a federal agent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is there are situations under which California law
will not permit forfeiture, and federal law will,'' said Andy
Cuellar, a deputy district attorney in Alameda County, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little California can do about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Alaska case shows just how strong federal powers are. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks police had seized $44,850 in cash from Perry Johnson
after finding cocaine in his home. But charges were dismissed
because of an illegal search. Police knew they couldn't keep the
money under state law, so they gave it to the DEA for adoption. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court ruled in 1993 that police had no right
under state law to give the money to the DEA. Under federal law,
though, police could keep the money, so the city wrote a cashier's
check to Johnson for $58,654, which included interest, according to
court records. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the DEA seized that money, too, saying it could be traced to
drug transactions. The federal government returned 40 percent to 60
percent to Fairbanks police, a police official said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {( End optional trim )}
</P>
<P>
   Forfeitures can mean a lot of money for police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department says that from October 1996 through March
1999 it accepted $208,454,000 in seizures from state and local
police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that figure is still being audited because the Justice
Department has not published an annual forfeiture report since
1996, although the law requires the report to be produced each
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the $208 million figure is almost certainly low. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over one period, the Justice Department reported that Missouri
police gave federal agencies only half as much as the state auditor
found in just a sampling of cases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the nationwide total, forfeitures can quickly add up
for individual departments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, the St. Louis Metropolitan Police Department
received back more than $2.5 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 alone, the Georgia Bureau of Investigation took back
$1.7 million. &QL; 
(Both those figures include proceeds from joint investigations.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And in a single case in Indiana, a state trooper stopped a truck
for speeding on Interstate 70. Troopers found $811,470 and turned
it over to the DEA, which this year returned almost $500,000 to the
state police and $121,000 to a sheriff's department that helped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {( Begin optional trim )}
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, enough is at stake that police work with federal
agencies no matter what their state law may be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, police in some states that award forfeiture money
to special funds purposefully divert the money so it can end up in
their coffers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin law mandates that forfeiture money goes to public
schools, but only $16,906 went into Wisconsin's education fund
during the year ending in June 1999, according to the state
treasury department. During just six months of the same period,
local law enforcement gave the federal government $1.5 million in
seizures. &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
