<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-MURDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHARGES IN 19-YEAR-OLD HOLLYWOOD DRUG KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Federal prosecutors have reached back to history
to revive a sensational murder case, unveiling an indictment that
alleges that a former nightclub owner, his bodyguard and a
pornography actor arranged the killings of four people in the
Hollywood Hills nearly two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The case sounds like something out of ``L.A. Confidential,'' but
it is really more ``Boogie Nights.'' The ``Wonderland murders,''
named after the site, 4763 Wonderland Ave., where the killings took
place on July 1, 1981, proved a potent mix of seamy celebrity,
drugs and violence. The killings occurred in an era of notorious
Los Angeles criminals, including the Skid Row Slasher, the Hillside
Strangler and the Night Stalker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was dope, porn, sex and drugs and organized crime, and
John Holmes and all of these types of things that made it kind of a
draw back then,'' said Tom Lange, a retired Los Angeles police
detective who investigated the case, and who was later assigned to
the charges against O.J. Simpson. ``Perhaps things are now provable
that weren't provable years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The wide-ranging racketeering indictment unsealed on Friday
accuses Eddie Nash, a former owner of Hollywood nightclubs like the
Starwood and the Kit Kat Club whose real name is Adel Gharib
Nasrallah, of running a cocaine and heroin distribution syndicate
since the 1970s, as well as laundering money, tampering with a
juror, and witnesses and tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities say that the case grew out of a separate
investigation into an Armenian crime syndicate and that it led to
renewed accusations that Nash, with his bodyguard, Gregory DeWitt
Diles, and a pornographic film star, John Curtis Holmes, carried
out the Wonderland murders.
</P>
<P>
   Nash's lawyer, Fred Rucker, did not return telephone calls. But
when Nash, appearing on a television news program two weeks ago,
was asked if he had ordered the killings, he said: ``No, I did not.
All I can say is what I've said for the last 20 years. I really did
not kill anyone or have anything to do'' with Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes died in 1988 of an illness related to AIDS, and Diles
died in 1995. Nash, 71, was arrested at noon on Friday at his
condominium in Tarzana, a suburb northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The three were tried on slaying charges and ultimately acquitted
in state court trials, the last of which was in 1991. The
prosecutors say the killings were committed in retaliation for a
break-in and drug robbery at Nash's home two nights earlier, in
which he was made to kneel and beg for his life, and Diles was
grazed by a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the suspected robbers, Ronald Launius and William
Deverell, lived at the Wonderland residence and were killed there
with two women, Barbara Richardson and the owner of the home, Joy
Miller. The victims were beaten to death with lengths of pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes was accused of playing a role in both crimes and being
the link between the two camps. Lange said Holmes was a drug client
and associate of Nash, and left a sliding door unlocked for the
robbers at Nash's residence.
</P>
<P>
   Nash was believed to have figured out Holmes' role and forced
him to reveal the robbers' identities and help in the killings.
Holmes, who was staying at the Wonderland residence, was accused of
opening the door to let the killers in, and participating in the
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in Nash's first trial, in 1990, deadlocked 11-1 in favor
of conviction; and the federal authorities now say that the
hold-out juror, a woman who at the time was 18 years old, was paid
a bribe on May 15, 1990, by an associate of Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Lange and another investigator, Nils Grevilius, have written a
book about the case, ``Four on the Floor,'' but it has not been
published.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
