u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-LOTTERY0521     05-20 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-LOTTERY0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery pick helping Hawks focus on future
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About halftime of today's Eastern Conference game, a
man will start flipping the placards to tell the Hawks whether they
get their best draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   First to third probably would change the course of the
franchise. Five would be nice, and the Hawks can't slip lower than
eight.
</P>
<P>
   The team picked better than ninth only once _ and then messed
that one up with Jon Koncak in 1985. The Hawks can at least assuage
the agony of being 28-54, their worst season since they pulled out
of Milwaukee in the early '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about it is we're only looking at the top of
the draft, and it allows us to focus a lot better,'' general
manager Pete Babcock said before heading off to the studios of NBA
Entertainment in Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing has 1,000 Ping-Pong balls, 250 of them marked for
the Los Angeles Clippers, who had the worst record in the league.
Next is Chicago with 200, then Orlando, from Golden State, 157;
Vancouver, 120; Atlanta, 89; Chicago, via Washington and Golden
State, 64; New Jersey, 44; Houston, 18; Orlando, from Denver, and
Boston, 9 each; Dallas, 6; and Orlando, 5.
</P>
<P>
   The draw is for the top three picks. Then, teams pick in order
of number of games lost.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks can't be fourth. If they draw one of the first three
positions or hold fifth, Babcock says: ``We will be pretty sure
we'll be getting someone who has a real chance to become an impact
player in this league. If it's a real young guy, it will take a
little longer, but we'll know the potential to become a big-time
player (is there), and you have to feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Babcock isn't going to narrow his list with the draft 39 days
away. But the consensus is that Kenyon Martin, the Cincinnati
senior power forward, is the top pick, if his fractured leg is
healing without complication. Martin is an athletic player who has
developed a perimeter game.
</P>
<P>
   After Martin, Iowa State forward Marcus Fizer, LSU forward
Stromile Swift, Texas center Chris Mihm, Cincinnati swingman
DerMarr Johnson and East St. Louis prep star Darius Miles are the
top of the lottery. Remove Mihm as a candidate for the Hawks, who
don't need a center, and their options are pretty well-defined.
</P>
<P>
   Fizer isn't Martin, but he can score from the wing or take it
inside. Swift, Johnson and Miles are 6-9, all long and lanky and
all young, but they all have marvelous futures. While Johnson and
Miles will play out on the floor, Swift is a shot-blocker and an
explosive leaper who has medium range on his jumper. With his two
years of college, he should develop a little faster. Johnson is
intriguing for his ability to shoot the 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   If the Hawks slip as low as seventh or eighth, they could be
looking at UNLV's 6-5 Courtney Alexander. The best shooting guard
in the draft, Alexander often is compared _ for better and worse _
to Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Florida sophomore Michael Miller, 6-8, and Michigan State's
Morris Peterson, 6-6, would be possibilities, Miller for his
potential, Peterson for the maturity and all-around game that
helped lead Michigan State to the championship that the Gators lost
in the NCAA final. DePaul sophomore Quentin Richardson has a
lottery chance, but he is behind Miller and Peterson and is not a
good ball-handler.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
