<SLUG> BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
 
SPORTS COLUMN: WHERE DERBY WINNERS GO NEXT By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Compared with the international glamour of the
Kentucky Derby, the Preakness comes off as a family reunion, held
every year on the third Saturday in May.
</P>
<P>
   For all its quaintness, the Preakness usually has one thing the
Kentucky Derby never will have, by definition:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Derby doesn't have a Derby winner,'' said Joe Orseno, the
trainer of Red Bullet, who not only did not win the Derby but did
not even compete in it.
</P>
<P>
   This is good reasoning on Orseno's part. The Preakness is where
Derby winners generally go when facing the prospect of what to do
with the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Just such a challenge was confronting Fusaichi Pegasus on
Saturday. The Kentucky Derby winner would try to win the Preakness,
the second leg of the Triple Crown, against a small field of seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to win a second one to win a third one,'' Orseno
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The race would go a long way to prove whether Fusaichi Pegasus
was the super horse that racing needs so badly. The Derby has much
of the glitter, but the Preakness has the gritty feel of a survival
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned about bringing a horse back in two
weeks,'' said Neil Drysdale, the taciturn Englishman who trains
Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   The year's racing calendar did not begin on the morning of May
6. These eight horses have been brought along this season,
essentially getting through a demolition derby of flying hooves and
looming bodies, complicated by their own tiny and fragile bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been my theory that the Preakness is so tough
because it's the third tough race in a row, not two,'' said D.
Wayne Lukas, who has tried it every which way.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus lost his first race, then has won five
straight, including the Wood Memorial in New York on April 15. The
Preakness has its own eccentric condition of dropping back from the
Derby's distance of a mile and a quarter to a mile and
three-sixteenths _ with slightly less room to erase mistakes, to
allow true ability to assert itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to win when you're way ahead, but what if something
is off your shoulder?'' asked Bob Baffert, the trainer of Captain
Steve, with a dollop of wishful thinking. ``There's always
something you didn't expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has been down this road before. Having won both the
Derby and Preakness in 1997 with Silver Charm and in 1998 with Real
Quiet _ only to lose in the Belmont _ Baffert has felt the swell of
expectation as he arrived in Baltimore with a Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't watch a lot of sports, but I get interested during the
playoffs,'' Baffert said. ``To me, the Derby is like the start of
the playoffs. You suddenly get interested in it. After the Derby,
you start asking, `Who's this Fusaichi Pegasus? Who's this Captain
Steve?'''
</P>
<P>
   That is where they all were early Saturday, in rather soggy
Baltimore, whose mood of earnest diligence may have been enhanced
by Drysdale. The native of Surrey, England, has tossed a bit of
figurative cold water on the party here by choosing to conduct
business in seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   While the seven other Preakness horses were quartered in Barn
40, only a few steps from the endless supply of coffee and
doughnuts at the hospitality tent, Drysdale opted for the drab
security of a grassless cement compound at Barn 7, behind metal
gates.
</P>
<P>
   Blandly, Drysdale insisted he knew nothing of the security
measures that had guards locking the gates early and often.
</P>
<P>
   Being so close to the nation's capital, the home office of
duplicity, the mystery of the extra security could easily be
labeled Gategate.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the odd raised eyebrow _ hard to document on the
printed page _ there was little criticism of Drysdale's antisocial
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to do what's right for the horse,'' Baffert said.
``He's got obligations to that horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert glanced around at the assembled riffraff with cameras
and notepads and said: ``We're very trusting here. I'm glad he's
not here. You'd have 100 people watching him. You look around and
you say, `Where did all these kooks come from?'''
</P>
<P>
   The kooks did not take it personally. Oh, no. Besides, anybody
who follows racing knows how precarious life can be for these
thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Lukas had Charismatic, a handsome heir of Secretariat,
barreling through the Derby and the Preakness, one of only 26
horses to win both, and coming to the Belmont to try to be the 12th
Triple Crown winner. But Charismatic broke down in the stretch, and
only an acrobatic dismounting by the gallant jockey Chris Antley
stabilized the colt and saved him for a life in the pastures. It
can happen fast.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers appreciate what they are demanding of their horses,
and sometimes they step back from the call of the Derby. Orseno
kept Red Bullet out of the Derby after a fruitless chase of
Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot to ask of the horse,'' Orseno said. ``We had a
terrible ride in the Wood, which was why I held him out of the
Derby. I gave him a full week off, and he needed that week. We'd
like to have him for the rest of the year. I would have loved to
win the Derby _ but not at the horse's expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Orseno added: ``I'm surprised there have been as many
Derby-Preakness winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 26 in the first 124 runnings of the Preakness. And on
Saturday, Fusaichi Pegasus tried to be the 27th. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
