<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL: RILEY NOT AFRAID OF CHALLENGES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You want to give him a dignified ending, offer him a
cigarette and tell him how courageously he and his men fought. Pat
Riley stares at you in disdain.
</P>
<P>
   He knows what this is about and wants no sympathy. Before it is
over, he will envision triumph and tragedy. He will even use those
words. As long as two weeks ago, when the struggle began, he knew
this day would dawn: Game 7 against the Knicks, he and his
swordsmen against the empire.
</P>
<P>
   The Gladiator, dressed in Armani armor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great, great group of guys, hard-working, good
men,'' he said of his Miami Heat. ``Are they good enough to win?
That's going to be the ultimate tragedy, if they're not. Because
they'll know they're not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolute madness,'' Riley called Game 6, minutes after Madison
Square Garden stopped shaking. The Heat having squandered a
15-point lead in the second half, he referred to the rivalry as
``one big death grip that both teams have on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments before, he had taken that long, hard walk from the
court, through the tunnel, down a corridor and into the locker room
of his crestfallen team.
</P>
<P>
   His head slightly bowed after a 72-70 loss that tied the series
at three games apiece, the cameras caught something revealing: a
wry smile. He did not have a hollow, end-of-the-world look about
him. Nor did he have a deathly pallor that suggested he had had it
with this maddening game and this opponent he can't quite slay to
free himself from emotional torment.
</P>
<P>
   He is not devastated as much as he is reveling in the moment,
basking in...the pain. Riley, the masochistic loser, loving every
minute of a grueling loss.
</P>
<P>
   It was this way in New York, when Reggie Miller of the Pacers
shot the Knicks down in Game 1 of their 1995 epic, Riley's last
series on the Knicks sideline. It was this way in Game 5 last year
and in 1998, that sinking feeling that his best shot was not good
enough, that he had to start all over again and use the pain as
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Because if it hurts this bad to lose, it must feel even more
euphoric to win. Who else would use ``preordained'' and ``destiny''
for basketball? Who else would appear more haggard and battered
after a tough victory in Game 5 than an absolutely surreal collapse
in Game 6?
</P>
<P>
   Riley, with the battle of Carthage on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He will walk into his own building on Sunday, in front of 20,000
people who in their hearts cannot fathom the Heat beating the
Knicks in a deciding game on their home floor. For two seasons
running, Riley has endured his former employers putting him on
vacation early.
</P>
<P>
   All around him, Knick fans will engulf the American Airlines
Arena, the enemy invading his home. It will be loud and intense. He
knows they're coming, just as he knows this series could again come
down to one bounce, one shot, one second of desire that either
validates his stature as the greatest coach in team sports or
punctures the myth for the third straight year.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the reality is probably somewhere in between. He has
turned men who should be playing pickup basketball at a community
center into solid, NBA veterans, capable of incredible things with
the game on the line. He has done so much with so little since he
left Magic and Kareem and the Showtime Lakers, that to assail his
coaching ability for not winning a title since then is almost
ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   But he also stays with the same group of veterans too long,
stubbornly believing their hearts can compensate for any amount of
talent thrown at them. A part of you actually admires that about
him, the idea that he believes he can beat you with people who
simply try harder and work more, regardless of the weapons at their
disposal.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, you also wonder if anybody but him and Jeff Van
Gundy could go through this without losing their senses.
Battle-hardened by their shared history, oblivious to the madness
around them, they keep hoping beyond hope that their soldiers do
what they ask of them.
</P>
<P>
   Riley rented a theater in Boca Raton, Fla., while the Heat were
preparing for the Knicks. Together, they watched the World War II
submarine movie ``U-571.'' Riley made parallels about the movie and
his team, but there is a better one playing now.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Gladiator,'' the character played by Russell Crowe
gallantly commands the Roman Empire army until the new Caesar tries
to have him assassinated. He winds up in a faraway land and
essentially needs to kill other men for the crowd's pleasure to win
his own freedom. He fights his way back to Rome, to the original
Coliseum, and faces off against his mortal enemies, who just happen
to be his former employers. We won't ruin the end for you.
</P>
<P>
   It's on NBC at 3:30 p.m. on Sunday. Russell Crowe's wardrobe has
been upgraded. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
