<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS LOOKING FOR A STAR IN DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The odds, and their sorry luck, would tell you that
the New Jersey Nets cannot expect the Ping-Pong balls to flow their
way in Sunday's National Basketball Association draft lottery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in a season in which there are no clear-cut choices in the
draft, the Nets may find that wherever they roam through the
lottery, they may find a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the player who would probably be regarded as one of
the best is Kenyon Martin,'' general manager John Nash said of the
Cincinnati power forward. ``After that, it is a toss-up. We could
draft seventh and get a player who could be the rookie of the
year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nets could draft seventh, the spot they now hold because
they had the seventh-worst record in the league, or they could get
a lucky bounce from the Ping-Pong balls and draw one of the top
three positions. Or, if one or more of the teams behind the Nets in
the seeding moves up, the Nets could drop to eight, nine or 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ping-Pong balls numbered 1 through 14 are placed in a drum
and then drawn in four-ball combinations with 1,001 possible
combinations. Before the draft, 1,000 combinations are assigned to
the 13 spots in the lottery with the NBA's worst team, the Los
Angeles Clippers getting 250 chances, the Chicago Bulls getting 200
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets have 44 combinations. Perhaps the team that could have
the biggest day is the Orlando Magic, which has five picks with the
last spot in the lottery and two more because of trades. The Magic
inherited the third-highest slot from the Golden State Warriors,
with 157 chances, as well as the 10th slot from the Denver Nuggets,
with nine chances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will select 22nd in the first round and do not have a
second-round pick, having surrendered it to Utah. The Nets will
select No. 36 overall in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Martin are center Chris Mihm of Texas, a first-team
all-American, and 6-foot-8-inch forward Marcus Fizer of Iowa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other prospects are forward Stromile Swift of Louisiana State,
who excelled last season as a sophomore after playing only one
semester as a freshman; sophomores Mike Miller of Florida and Joel
Pryzbilla of Minnesota; Darius Miles, who spurned St. John's for a
chance at the NBA; the nation's leading scorer, shooting guard
Courtney Alexander of Fresno State; and Iakovos Tsakalidis, a
center from Greece. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-R-NY-REPUBS-SENATE-AR     05-20 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-REPUBS-SENATE-ART-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE OPENS RACE WITH ATTACK ON HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island came roaring into the
race for senator from New York on Saturday, attacking Hillary
Rodham Clinton as a ``far-left, extremist'' candidate who has ``no
real rationale for serving here other than as a steppingstone to
some other position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think her ambition is the issue,'' Lazio declared in an
interview, as he formally announced his candidacy in a race that
has been upended by the decision of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to step
aside for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's remarks came as Republican leaders in New York and
Washington lined up behind the candidacy of the Suffolk County
Republican, who had himself suspended his campaign last year in
deference to party leaders who wanted Giuliani as their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio announced a two-day trip around the state, an aggressive
come-out-of-the-box approach intended to discourage any other
Republicans who might be thinking about challenging him, as well as
to push the Conservative Party into falling behind his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The tenor of Lazio's comments _ he repeatedly criticized
Clinton's credentials and ideology _ suggested that the campaign,
with the change in candidate, was going to be harsh and fast-paced.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers have already begun to attack Lazio as extreme
and conservative, noting that he had supported many of the
initiatives of the former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, as they
tried to discredit his candidacy before he had a chance to find his
groundings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's press secretary, Howard Wolfson, responded to Lazio's
comments Saturday morning by saying: ``It sounds like the same old
negative attack politics. He hasn't even formally announced, and
already he's on the attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he considered himself ``a centrist, a mainstream
Republican.'' ``We're conservative, right-of-center on budget and
tax issues, national security issues,'' he said. ``And I think
we're realistic on social issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He described his Democratic opponent as ``far left,'' adding:
``She's part of the discredited philosophy that helped lead New
York to ruin during the Cuomo years. I think we've turned the
corner and we don't want to go back to those failed days.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Lazio jumped at almost every opportunity to
criticize Clinton. He responded vigorously when asked if he would
make an issue out of the fact that Clinton did not live in New York
before this year, a subject that Giuliani frequently raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the real thing,'' he said. ``I don't have to try to be
someone else. I was born here. I went to school here. I fished in
these waters. I clammed in its bays. I graduated from our schools.
My children were born in New York state. I've lived here my whole
life. There will be no question of my commitment to this state.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said, Clinton was hurt both by the fact that she
had never lived in the state where she wants to serve, and because
of the cloistered life she lived as a first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know New York if you have bodyguards around you all
the time,'' he said. ``You've got to know what it's like to ride
the subways, to drive your own car, to buy your own gas, to buy
groceries here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people can see through who Hillary Clinton is, and
they will have a chance to know Rick Lazio as the real deal,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazio's announcement on Long Island came as his campaign sprang
almost overnight into full life. Workers at his headquarters in
Suffolk County answered the phone ``Lazio 2000,'' early Saturday,
and Lazio's Web site urged voters to contribute money, addressing
what his aides acknowledged on Saturday was one of the more vexing
problems he faced in his contest against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Newly hired staff members flew up from Washington, with a
notable representation from the presidential campaign of Lamar
Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee. That is because
Lazio's media adviser, Michael Murphy, performed the same role for
Alexander in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The new Lazio campaign staff struggled through a chaotic
morning, as they grappled with such questions as which town Lazio's
headquarters was located in (Bay Shore) and the area code (631),
from an onslaught of news media that abandoned Giuliani at City
Hall for Lazio's headquarters on Long Island with startling speed.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's advisers and state Republican leaders, concerned that
Giuliani's prolonged exit had dealt Clinton a strong early
advantage, moved to tap down even the most remote prospect that
Lazio would face any competition for the party's nomination.
``There is no question Lazio will be the candidate,'' said Sen.
Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Across New York state, Republican leaders fell in line with Gov.
George Pataki and the state Republican chairman, William D. Powers,
and proclaimed not only their support for Lazio but also their
belief that he would prove to be a formidable opponent to Clinton,
despite the obvious obstacles he faces now. (Some Republicans went
so far as to privately suggest that he was a better candidate than
Giuliani would have been.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The race at the end of the day is going to be about who best
can serve New York, and based on his record in Congress, it's
clearly going to be him,'' said Zenia Mucha, the chief political
aide to Pataki. She said that Lazio ``understands what it means to
be a New Yorker. She's in the process of learning. His basic
philosophy is a smaller role of government for the people. Her
basic philosophy is that government has all the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King of Long Island, bowing to this reality, withdrew
from seeking the Republican nomination. He said Saturday morning
that he did not want to cause any division within the Republican
party, and mentioned Pataki's enthusiastic endorsement of Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's circles on Saturday, the debate was not over
whether the candidate should attack Lazio, but when. Unlike
Giuliani, Lazio is barely known to most New Yorkers, so the
immediate struggle is a race to see which side succeeds in defining
Lazio first _ both in remarks on the campaign trail and in
television advertisements _ over the next few weeks. All of this
suggests that this campaign will, in fact, be harsher and more
pointed than the Clinton-Giuliani race ever had a chance to become.
</P>
<P>
   There was definite worry in Republican circles that Lazio would
have been a stronger candidate had he had an earlier start, which
would have allowed him more time to raise money, get the experience
he needs to run a race, and become better known to New Yorkers.
Republicans, though, emphasized repeatedly that Lazio would be a
strong candidate, because he appeared to have a hunger for the job
that Giuliani never evinced, and also because Lazio was more in
tune with Republican positions on issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
