<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-20 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLYING AROUND THE MOMENTUM: KNICKS' COMEBACK HAS HEAT REELING 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since April 9, some odd force seemed to be working to accomplish
payback for the Miami Heat. After being eliminated from the
playoffs the last two seasons by the Knicks, including last year's
heart-wrenching first-round loss on Allan Houston's short jumper
with 0.8 seconds left in the final game, the Heat seemed destined
for retribution.
</P>
<P>
   There was Tim Hardaway's wild and desperate 3-point heave that
beat the buzzer and gave Miami a 95-94 overtime victory over the
Knicks, in that April 9 game, in the teams' final regular-season
meeting. There was Anthony Carter's game-winning runner that the
Knicks thought flew over the top of the backboard; it bounced high
off the rim and sank into the net to end Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   There was Dan Majerle's resurrection from the offensively dead
in Miami's Game 5 victory, when he somehow managed to outplay
Houston and squeeze 16 points out of his battle-worn, 34-year-old
body.
</P>
<P>
   And, Friday night, there was the seemingly insurmountable
18-point second-quarter lead the Heat built over the Knicks in
what, until the final seconds, looked like a sure series-clinching,
demon-exorcising victory at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as the teams prepare for a decisive Game 7 Sunday at
American Airlines Arena in Miami, the force seems to have switched
sides and handed the momentum to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the Knicks' comeback from a 45-30 halftime
deficit in Game 6? How else to explain the fact that they never
took a second-half lead until Houston scored the game's final
points, on free throws, with 17.6 seconds left, in the Knicks'
72-70 victory?
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the Knicks, a small team with poor
rebounding figures all season, outrebounding the rugged Heat on
Friday after being destroyed on the backboards in each of the first
five games?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolute madness,'' Miami coach Pat Riley said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, man, just amazing,'' Heat center Alonzo Mourning
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat is surely kicking itself for allowing the Knicks to
rally and win and, even though Game 7 is on Miami's home court, its
psyche has to be battered, just as the Knicks' mind-set must be
cocksure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of life in us,'' said Knicks center Patrick
Ewing, who played tremendously in recording 15 points and 18
rebounds in Game 6. ``We feel good. To come this far and lose on
Sunday, that's not what it's all about. We could be on vacation
right now, but there is still life in us.''
</P>
<P>
   While the victory seemed to add another marvelous chapter to the
Knicks' postseason domination of the Heat, a coach, Jeff Van Gundy,
warned against putting the comeback in the history books next to
Larry Johnson's 4-point play last year and Willis Reed's limping
entrance on the Garden court in 1970 just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great, great comeback,'' Van Gundy said. ``But we
need to win the series. The only thing that makes it really
memorable is if it leads to a series win.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the Knicks have the edge in Game 7 in that they are
coming off a remarkable come-from-behind victory, but they also
have history on their side. They have defeated the Heat the past
two seasons by winning decisive games on Miami's home floor. In
fact, the Knicks have won five of their last nine playoff games in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   There are obstacles, however. The Knicks, who lost the teams'
only Game 7 meeting in 1997, will have to break a streak that dates
to 1998. Over the clubs' last 11 playoff contests, neither team has
won back-to-back games. But if they can overcome an 18-point
deficit while facing elimination, can't the Knicks overcome
anything the Heat has on its side?
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks believe so, and it was that type of positive thinking
that led them to rally after the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them that we picked the most inopportune time to
play the worst half we played all year,'' Van Gundy said, recalling
his halftime speech. ``I told them that they were going to be part
of the best comeback in their playoff lives, and that if they
didn't believe that to stay in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired, perhaps, by Van Gundy's words, the Knicks charged on
the Garden floor with renewed vigor, outscoring the Heat by 13-3
over the first four minutes of the third quarter to quickly put
themselves back in contention. Then, big fourth-quarter
performances by Houston (7 points), Ewing (4 points, two rebounds)
and Chris Childs (4 points, two assists) enabled the Knicks to pull
it off.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who scored 14 of his team-high 21 points in the second
half, said the Knicks will carry the same positive thinking into
Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room, there's no time to have negative thoughts in
your head,'' he said. ``There's no time to look down or look behind
you, and I mean, that's what this team is made of. It's made up of
a lot of character. The bottom line is we have it in us. And I
think it will give us momentum going into Sunday, because we know
what we have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
