   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS-CADDELL _ Profile of Houston attorney Mike Caddell,
now commanding national attention as he takes dead aim at the
government's actions in the Branch Davidian tragedy at Mount
Carmel. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald). 60.
</P>
<P>
   DYING-HEARTLAND _ LEBANON, Kansas _ As the clock strikes 3, the
old ladies of this depressed farm town shuffle past the boarded-up
red brick storefronts on Main Street and into LaDow's general store
for a daily dose of coffee and gossip. Every afternoon, Monday
through Friday, a dozen of them gather around two kitchen tables by
the window to discuss the world's problems, and their own. Their
small town is withering away. And these genteel women, many of them
farm widows, are a living testament to this unhappy trend. Across
Smith County, Kansas, and indeed throughout rural America, a
generational time bomb is ticking. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITHDYING-DATA _ Chart material _ and photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wednesday in (a) national category.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-GOP _ As GOP activists hold their last statewide meeting
before 2002 in Savannah, a question arises: Who will the
Republicans put forth for governor when Democrat Roy Barnes runs
for re-election? Some of the possible Republican candidates - Linda
Schrenko, John Oxendine - will be working the delegates this
weekend in Savannah. We'll ask who's running _ and whether anyone
stands a chance of unseating Barnes. (Judd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES-BLINDTRUST _ Another look at Barnes' blind trust and his
efforts to avoid filing a complete financial disclosure. Barnes'
lawyer has stepped up the lobbying of Attorney General Thurbert
Baker, strongly criticizing an analysis of the financial disclosure
law by Teddy Lee of the state Ethics Commission. Baker is expected
to issue an opinion on the issue by late this week. Many observers
expect Baker to rule that Barnes has to file a full disclosure; the
law does not take into account blind trusts. Former Gov. Joe Frank
Harris had a blind trust until the current disclosure law took
effect. He then dissolved the trust and complied with the law.
(Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LEGIS-CONFLICTS _ Georgia's part-time legislators, like those in
most other states, face a constant potential for conflicts of
interest. Most lawmakers hold jobs outside the legislature nearly 1
in 5 sit on committees that regulate their own business interest.
The findings are part of a national study by the Washington-based
Center for Public Integrity which found that many lawmakers have a
financial interests in the laws they impose. (Whitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS _ BEIJING _ An American human rights organization
gives a briefing on its talks with China's Ministry of Justice
concerning political prisoners. Although China suspended human
rights talks with the United States a year ago, it quietly agreed a
few months ago to resume dialogue with this non-profit, run by a
businessman who favors normalizing trade relations with China.
(Chao, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE _ BEIJING _ As the U.S. Congress prepares for a vote
on giving communist China ``permanent nation trade status,'' we
profile a textile factory which will be affected by opening up more
trade and accession to the World Trade Organization. (Chao, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., May 18, in (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-ELECTIONS _ PORT AU PRINCE, Haiti _ An advance on the
Haiti elections scheduled for Sun., May 21. More TK. (Williams, Cox
News Service). MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX _ MEXICO CITY _ As the second presidential debate
nears, opposition candidate Vicente Fox comes in riding a wave of
momentum with polls showing in him either in a dead heat or ahead
of ruling party candidate Francisco Labastida. But does Fox, who's
pulling from both liberal and conservative camps for support,
really carry the day against the entrenched Institutional
Revolutionary Party's vaunted political machine? We ask him,
directly. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday, May 19.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUN-SUICIDE _ WASHINGTON _ Largely absent from the political
debate on guns is the fact that more than half of gun deaths among
young people are suicides. Gun control groups say that the suicide
rate would fall if guns weren't available. The NRA says that
premise is ridiculous because people in that state of mind would
find some other way to kill themselves. We ask counselors and other
experts what they think. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With GUNS-DATA _ Comparing U.S. youth suicide rates with those
of other countries; gun suicide stats for the nation and Cox
states.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ORGANIZE _ WASHINGTON _ As the Million Mom March and
World Bank demonstrations show, the Internet has become a powerful
tool for organizing virtual communities around a particular
political idea. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
