   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-WIT _ Periodically there come in one's life Rubicons that
must be crossed, and one of these for Dr. Vivian Bearing is the
matter of punctuation. The lead character in Margaret Edson's
Pulitzer Prize-winning play ``Wit'' is a pedant for whom commas and
commitment are paired. ``Nothing but a breath _ a comma _ separates
life from life everlasting,'' she says in a scene that defines the
play's deceptive conflict. ``It is very simple really. With the
original punctuation restored, death is no longer something to act
out on a stage, with exclamation points. It's a comma, a pause.''
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. MOVED
</P>
