<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TERROR-GAME-0521-COX     05-20 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-GAME-0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    MOCK BIOLOGICAL WARFARE ATTACK BEGINS IN DENVER
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. _ ``Virtual patients'' began reporting to
Denver-area hospitals Saturday as a multi-agency mock biological
warfare drill got underway to test the ability of public health and
law enforcement agencies to respond to a real world attack.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise, announced in advance, is to last 10 days and
involve not only local hospitals, mayors and police but top federal
officials, including Attorney General Janet Reno and other members
of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Ordered by Congress, the bio-terrorism ``attack'' in Denver
coincided with a mock chemical warfare attack in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, the Federal Emergency Management Agency, the Centers
for Disease Control (CDC) and other agencies sent participants to
both the exercise here and the chemical weapons walk-through in
Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Although the drill _ being called ``TOPOFF,'' for Top Officials
_ was known in advance, participants were not aware of its scope
and were not told the details. As of Saturday afternoon, for
example, public health officials still had not determined what
``disease'' had caused patients to appear in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the surprise factor, organizers of the drill hoped it
would identify weak points in the government's ability to respond
to an attack, said spokesmen for agencies involved in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the exercise is to assess the nation's crisis and
consequence management capacity under extraordinarily stressful
conditions,'' said Gina Talamona, a Justice Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   A Denver FBI official told reporters covering the $3.5 million
simulated bio-terrorism attack here that because of ``simulated
intelligence,'' the bureau already had information of terrorist
activity in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the FBI said, it had identified and taped off a
``crime scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides several dozen reporters who came to cover the exercise,
officials were having to accommodate inquiries from ``virtual''
news media and a Federal Emergency Management Agency press officer
had to first determine whether a reporter's questions Saturday were
authentic or were part of the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you real world media, or are you from VNN?'' the press
officer asked. VNN, he said, stood for ``Virtual News Network.''
</P>
<P>
   In Portsmouth, exercise organizers used a concoction made of
garlic and Gatorade to spread a foul-smelling, ``chemical warfare''
cloud over the start of a make-believe charity foot race.
</P>
<P>
   CDC spokeswoman Barbara Reynolds said that because public health
agencies in various parts of the country vary greatly in their
ability to respond to a biological terrorism attack, the outcome of
the Denver exercise _ ``good or bad'' _ will not reflect the
overall level of preparedness of the U.S. public health system.
</P>
<P>
   State and local public health officials have complained that
many areas are poorly equipped and trained for dealing with a germ
warfare attack, even though they will be the first line of defense,
along with hospitals and local physicians.
</P>
<P>
   CDC has a five-year program aimed at getting the nation's public
health system in shape to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The drill has not been without its critics. Some said it was
unrealistic to stage simultaneous chemical and biological terrorism
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Following the August, 1998, bombing of U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania, U.S. officials including President Clinton have said
terrorist organizations such as that headed by as Saudi exile Osama
bin Laden were trying to acquire biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States sent cruise missiles to attack a plant in
Sudan, where Clinton said bin Laden was trying to develop germ
warfare weapons.
</P>
<P>
   . In congressional testimony in March, CIA Director George Tenet
said terrorist organizations pose major threats to U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Nesmith's email address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
