<HEADER>
A1048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER0521-COX     05-20 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Genial Rocker works crowd
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Instead of the St. Bernard-called-to-dinner dash with
which he usually bolts for the pitcher's mound, he slipped through
a pair of blue curtains and waved almost shyly.
</P>
<P>
   There were no 98-mph fastballs unleashed, no nervous facial
twitches. Just countless autographs obligingly signed and one very
broad grin for a little boy who asked about his silver Corvette
parked outside.
</P>
<P>
   Even the insults were different for John Rocker Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's tall and handsome,'' podiatrist Gabe Borchardt
sighed, midway through the controversial Braves reliever's hourlong
appearance at the B.P. Sports Collectible show. ``Why can't he be
short and ugly like the rest of us?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rocker has been a special case ever since he insulted
foreigners, gays and New Yorkers in an interview with Sports
Illustrated last December. Since a season-starting two-week
suspension ended, he's collected 10 saves and a lot of fan support
at Turner Field, but he's also had at least one minor run-in with
media in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   So who could blame hundreds for showing up for his first public
appearance this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of get a kick out of him,'' admitted Bill Wolfe, 50, a
noise pollution consultant who got autographs for himself, his
father and father-in-law. ``He's half my age and I wouldn't want to
be held accountable for everything I said half a life ago. Plus,
he's a hell of a ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   While largely non-minority in nature, the crowd was a diverse
blend of Braves fans, baseball lovers who'd come to get Rafael
Furcal's or Tony Perez's autographs and figured ``Oh, what the
heck,'' and curiosity seekers. Some who were there to see other
players had no interest in seeing Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people like to be in the middle of
controversy,'' said Erin Hynek, 28, who clearly had other
motivations Saturday. Hynek and friend Jennifer Kinard arrived 2
1/2 hours early (``We're autograph amateurs,'' Kinard laughed),
carrying their hard-to-find Rocker game jerseys to be autographed
at $35-a-pop, and an obvious thing for the big guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the girls who scream `We love you' from the top of the
bullpen,'' Kinard told Rocker later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate that,'' Rocker grinned. ``Will you be there
tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   He even handled the tougher stuff, which _ while hardly rising
(or sinking) to the level of Shea Stadium insults _ including
agreeing to autograph the infamous Sports Illustrated issue and
politely refusing to inscribe ``Kiss my butt'' on a mini-Braves
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he might have a good sense of humor and say `yes',''
the requester, Russell Nicometi, 23, said afterward. ``But at least
he smiled at me.''
</P>
<P>
   And at least he didn't bite the head off a reporter who ventured
one question _ how long can you sign and still pitch effectively?
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hours, 18 minutes,'' Rocker joked with a small smile.
``Three hours, 19 minutes and it totally affects my pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Give that guy another save.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
