<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-ASSESS-AR     05-20 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-ASSESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GIULIANI'S LEGACY HANGS IN THE BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Rudolph Giuliani quit the mayoralty tomorrow, he
would leave behind a city that is safer and more prosperous than it
was when he took over City Hall in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A solid legacy, but a narrow one, especially since New York
City's prosperity is linked closely to the thriving national
economy and crime is down all over the Giuliani-less country. And
the mayor's image is marred by a reputation for insensitivity,
especially racial insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   So it makes perfect sense that Giuliani wants to devote the next
year and a half to being ``a better mayor,'' as he said on Friday
when he withdrew from the Senate race _ to build on his successes
and knock down the barriers he concedes he may have erected between
his administration and many minority New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   If revising his legacy is indeed the objective of the newly
introspective-sounding mayor, the issues are out there waiting for
him. He faces the skepticism of people who have heard similar
commitments from him before, only to see them go nowhere. He may
also find that he gets less attention than he used to. Nothing
collapses as quickly as the prominence of a politician about to
lose his platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares what he says?'' asked H. Carl McCall, the state
comptroller and likely candidate for governor. ``He's a lame duck.
He's on his way out. People are going to focus on the Senate race
and who is going to be the next mayor. If he'd done this two or
three years ago, fine, but he has already put his mark on
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller recalled the mayor's pledge to reach out to
minorities when he was running for re-election in 1997. He did not
do so for a year, until Amadou Diallo, an unarmed African
immigrant, was killed by police officers. Then he met with McCall
and others. ``Then I never heard from him again,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani still has 19 months in office. His health allowing,
he can do a lot even if hampered by skepticism and the dimming of
the spotlight. There is everything from the symbolic _ removing all
those barricades around City Hall before the next mayor does _ to
matters as complex as expanding health insurance coverage, a new
Giuliani goal.
</P>
<P>
   Some issues have been pending a long time. One of the most
problematic for this mayor has been improving relations between the
Police Department and minority groups in the city, especially in
the aftermath of the shooting deaths of Diallo and Patrick M.
Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote to him last week, said this is the time to drop his
opposition to the independent police board,'' said Peter F.
Vallone, the Council speaker. ``That would be great not only for
the future of the city, but would have a strong impact on the city
right now.'' Creating an oversight board might also be a way of
responding to a recent report by the U.S. Civil Rights Commission,
which accuses the police of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   But the police commissioner, Howard Safir, rebuffed Vallone last
week, and the speaker has yet to hear from the mayor, who is still
fighting his idea in court.
</P>
<P>
   Many other matters are before the mayor now, especially one that
always tops the list of issues people care about in public opinion
polls: education.
</P>
<P>
   The city's contract with the United Federation of Teachers is in
negotiation, as are all municipal union contracts. The mayor has
focused on a merit pay plan for teachers _ rewarding individual
teachers with bonuses tied to higher student test scores. That is
anathema to the teachers' union, which considers merit pay divisive
and subjective. Nobody familiar with the powerful teachers' union
gives the idea a realistic chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can say, `I'd like individual merit pay, but I know it's a
nonstarter, so let's come together on a group plan,''' suggested
Mark Green, the public advocate, referring to merit pay for the
faculties of entire schools rather than for individual teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor could also call for reduced class sizes and find the
financial resources to make that possible _ dropping his proposal
to cut the income tax surcharge and dedicating the income to
schools, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   He has often said he wants to eliminate the Board of Education;
so does Vallone. Both want the school system to be under direct
city control. The two could lobby for change in Albany, on schools
and on another central issue _ getting the state Legislature to
raise New York City's debt limit so the city can borrow more. If it
cannot, projects like construction of schools are in trouble. ``Now
that he no longer has to worry what they think of him in Syracuse
and Buffalo, he could do more; he's never been up there with me,''
Vallone said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said on Friday that he had become more sensitive to the
importance of extending health insurance to more people. That is
not exclusively a city issue. But the mayor could channel more city
money to the municipal hospitals, the health refuge of many poor
uninsured New Yorkers. The hospitals have lost a great deal of city
financing in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   He could mobilize city agencies to encourage more people to
enroll in a newly expanded state program for low-income New Yorkers
_ Child Health Plus and Family Health Plus. Health care experts
estimate that a half-million city residents are eligible but
unenrolled.
</P>
<P>
   As he reconsiders his mayoralty, Giuliani might look again at
his policy requiring single homeless adults to work in exchange for
shelter. That was shot down by a Supreme Court judge but the
decision is now on appeal by the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   The city is also still planning to deny shelter to parents who
do not comply with city requirements _ participating in workfare,
for instance; their children would go into foster care if shelter
were denied. That plan is on hold, pending court action, but is
still official city policy.
</P>
<P>
   These approaches have led to broad criticism, and to
Leno-Letterman caricatures of a heartless mayor. Giuliani strongly
defended his homeless policies as recently as three nights ago,
during a nationally televised town hall meeting. He told his
questioner, Andrea Mitchell, that encouraging dependency was cruel,
while encouraging independence was humane _ long his approach to
welfare and homeless issues.
</P>
<P>
   Other elected officials say they doubt that the mayor's plan to
govern differently means that he is prepared to change his
ideology, but just his public temperament. That alone can make a
difference. Green, the public advocate, who has been the target of
Giuliani's disdain, noted, with amazement in his voice, that when
he called the mayor after Giuliani dropped his Senate candidacy,
the mayor took his call. ``We said more than `hello' for the first
time in three years,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   But can a change not in content but tone _ in itself a difficult
thing to pull off for so entrenched a personality _ accomplish the
mayor's goal of ``reaching everyone in this city''?
</P>
<P>
   After six and a half years of seeing one kind of mayor, some who
work with Giuliani are openly dubious. ``If he is sincere and truly
wants to reach out, I think the black community has always been
open to wanting to work with the mayor,'' said C. Virginia Fields,
the Manhattan borough president. But there are many skeptics, she
added, because the mayor has made similar promises before, and
failed to convincingly follow up. He can still keep his own
commitment to change, she said. ``But not easily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
