<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     05-20 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: HERE, THERE, EVERYWHERE A RODRIGUEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The list of American League batting leaders is like Old
MacDonald's Farm _ here a Rodriguez, there a Rodriguez, everywhere
a Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   It is the A-Rod and I-Rod show, and it promises to run all
season, maybe even into the postseason voting for most valuable
player. Last year the league MVP race produced a close finish
between Ivan Rodriguez, the winner, and Pedro Martinez. This year
the race could be just as close but three-way, among Ivan
Rodriguez, Martinez and Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both tops,'' Gene Michael, the Yankees' vice president
for major league scouting, said of the Rodriguezes. ``They have to
be the best two players, certainly among the top four or five
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, the Texas manager, called the Rodriguezes ``two
special people.'' He has managed Ivan for six years and has known
Alex for seven years. He marvels not only at how they play
baseball, but also at the kind of people they are. Michael marvels
at the kind of offense they produce while playing positions where
players are not supposed to hit the way they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing defensive positions,'' said Michael, once a
shortstop who hit the way shortstops are supposed to, batting .229
with 15 career home runs. ``You're supposed to have defensive
players at those positions. These guys are doing remarkable
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop, of course, has undergone a transformation. First, Cal
Ripken showed that a shortstop could be an offensive player, too,
and now Rodriguez is joined by Nomar Garciaparra and Derek Jeter in
generating the kind of production once reserved for outfielders and
first basemen.
</P>
<P>
   As the Texas Rangers' catcher, I-Rod last season batted .332,
the highest average for an AL catcher since Bill Dickey's .362 in
1936, and he hit 35 home runs, a league record for catchers. A-Rod,
the Seattle star, last year hit 42 home runs for the second
successive season, tying his own AL record for shortstops and
becoming the only shortstop besides Ernie Banks to hit 40 or more
home runs more than once.
</P>
<P>
   But their 1999 performances were apparently only a prelude to
what I-Rod and A-Rod would produce this season.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, Ivan led the league in slugging
percentage (.772), Alex was second (.725); Ivan led in total bases
(125), Alex was fourth (103); Ivan was tied for the home run lead
(16), Alex was third (13); Alex led in runs scored (45), Ivan was
tied for second (37); Alex led in road batting average (.420), Ivan
was second (.400); Ivan was second in batting average (.377), Alex
was third (.366); Alex was third in runs batted in (43), Ivan was
fifth (41).
</P>
<P>
   Ivan also led the league in extra-base hits (30) and was second
in hits (61) and multiple-hit games (19); Alex was first in on-base
percentage (.483) and tied for second in walks (34).
</P>
<P>
   Ivan, who began playing in the major leagues at the age of 19,
had progressed steadily as a hitter but leaped to a different level
last season after acceding to the Rangers' request and not playing
winter ball in Puerto Rico. The Rangers had asked him not to play
the previous winter, but he played nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Puerto Rico, he was playing winter ball even
though we had asked him not to,'' Oates said. ``He asked me to come
watch him. I said I can't do that; that would be condoning what
you're doing. I said to him, `Why are you playing?' He looked me in
the eye and said, `Oatesy, I just love to play baseball.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has such a love for the game,'' Oates added, ``he plays it
like kids play Little League.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also plays it however the manager wants him to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just adapts to whatever role I ask him to do,'' Oates said.
``I hit him sixth, shared some feelings with him about it, told him
he may not get good pitches to hit, but he did what we needed
there. I moved him up to second, said I need you to score 100 runs
and steal bases. He did that. This spring I said you're going to
hit third. That means you can't be running; you have to give Raffy
a chance to swing the bat. But you still have to score 100, hit a
few home runs and drive in 100. Sure enough, the guy goes out, hits
the ball in the seats, drives in runs and he's still scoring
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he believed Rodriguez could bat anywhere in the
lineup and play anywhere in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about moving him to second base in three or four
years,'' the manager said. ``I think he plans to talk to Joe Torre
about how it was moving to third. He may go to Bucky Dent's
baseball school and work out in the infield. You probably don't
want him catching his whole life, but he's so valuable back there
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' Rodriguez has become even more valuable in Seattle
with the departure of Ken Griffey Jr. The early returns indicate he
is handling his responsibility well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dynamite,'' Michael said. ``When he came out of high
school, he was already fully developed. He's very strong and keeps
getting stronger. He's a better hitter than he was. He struggled
for a year or two, then it was gangbusters.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates, who met Alex Rodriguez when he was a senior in high
school, saw him recently when the Mariners played in Texas this
month. ``I told him I appreciate watching him play,'' the manager
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that three-game series, Alex rapped seven hits, including two
home runs, in 13 at-bats and drove in five runs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No-Hit Kids to Closers
</P>
<P>
   Jose Jimenez might not realize it, but he is following the path
of Dave Righetti's pitching career. Righetti pitched a no-hitter
for the Yankees in 1983 at the age of 24, then became a relief
pitcher and the team's closer the next season. Righetti is the
Yankees' career leader in saves with 224. Jimenez pitched a
no-hitter for the St. Louis Cardinals last season at the age of 25,
and this season he has become the closer for the Colorado Rockies.
He has five saves.
</P>
<P>
   Consistency on the Mound
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won all eight of Al Leiter's starts this season,
the best such perfect record in the majors through Friday's games.
James Baldwin, who had won his first seven starts, was scheduled to
start Saturday for the Chicago White Sox. The Arizona Diamondbacks
have won all seven of Brian Anderson's starts and have a 22-3
record in games started by Anderson, Randy Johnson and Todd
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   Bell vs. Belle
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning development last season, Jay Bell produced greater
power numbers than Albert Belle, hitting one more home run, 38 to
37, and generating a higher slugging percentage, .557 to .541.
Showing that the outcome was no fluke, the Arizona second baseman
again leads the Baltimore right fielder. Going into Saturday's
games, Bell had hit seven home runs and had a .520 slugging
percentage, while Belle was at five homers and .467.
</P>
<P>
   Flexible and Flying
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton seems as if he singlehandedly plans to replace the
offense the Rockies relinquished when they traded Vinny Castilla
and Dante Bichette. James Baldwin seems as if he singlehandedly
plans to pitch the White Sox into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, Baldwin had a 6-0 record and Helton
was the best hitter in the National League. Helton led the league
with a .418 batting average; had the best average with runners in
scoring position (.472); had the second-most total bases (111); was
second in slugging percentage (.828), runs scored (39) and on-base
percentage (.503); was third in runs batted in (41); and was tied
for fourth in home runs (13).
</P>
<P>
   The strong performances of Helton and Baldwin stem from a
similar source, the discovery of a flaw in their off-season
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I changed my off-season workout so I wouldn't be tight and
inflexible,'' Helton said. ``I felt that was holding me back. My
upper body was inflexible and keeping me from hitting as well as I
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the first baseman had been a poor hitter. Last season
he batted .320, slugged 35 home runs and drove in 113 runs. But
Helton hired a personal trainer and changed his winter routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to more of an Olympic lifting program, gaining strength
and flexibility all in one,'' he said. ``It's hard to do. There's a
lot of technique to it, which I still really can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Helton began the season with greater flexibility, and his
performance serves as an eloquent spokesman for the program he
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin could join Helton in a joint commercial. He, too, worked
with a trainer and changed his workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting too big for a pitcher,'' the 28-year-old
right-hander said. ``I love to work out with weights. That's
nothing that you want because I was losing a lot of flexibility. I
thought being a bigger pitcher made a better pitcher, but I found
out that it's not necessarily true.''
</P>
<P>
   As last season progressed, Baldwin, unable to work out as much,
found that his body was becoming more flexible. ``They told me I
was too big during the first part of the season,'' he said. ``I
worked out like a maniac during the off-season, then went to spring
training and worked out like a maniac. The next thing you know,
yes, I'm strong, yes, I look good, but as far as my performance on
the field, it wasn't that good. This makes a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Baldwin did not gain his sixth victory until Aug.
13; by then he also had 11 losses. He has won 11, 12 or 13 games in
each of his previous four seasons. Less than two months into this
season, he's halfway toward surpassing those totals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
