<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK: LEWIS CASE A TRIAL FOR NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If over the next month or so, Court TV finds that its ratings
suddenly spike, reaching the sort of numbers once enjoyed by
``Seinfeld,'' the network can thank players, coaches and executives
in the National Football League. They will be watching for news
about one of their own, Baltimore Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis, who
has been accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a three-time Pro Bowl player, and two co-defendants,
Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeney, are accused of stabbing Jacinth
Baker and Richard Lollar on Jan. 31 during a brawl after a
post-Super Bowl party.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial begins, most likely this week, people across the
NFL _ from commissioner Paul Tagliabue, to those in the Ravens
organization, to players on vacation or working out preparing for
July training camps _ will be monitoring what happens. They will be
reading newspapers, listening to coverage on the radio and watching
Court TV. Tuning in to the cable channel is apparently the
preferred choice among NFL types to get the latest information on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis trial is probably one of the most discussed topics in
the NFL right now.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to make light of a serious situation. Two people
were killed, and Lewis, if found guilty, could spend the rest of
his life in prison. If that did happen, the NFL would receive the
kind of tarnish that could stain its image for years. And there is
still a murder case pending with another NFL player, the former
Carolina wide receiver Rae Carruth, who is accused of masterminding
a plot to kill his former girlfriend, who was pregnant at the time.
She died in December after being shot in November. The baby
survived.
</P>
<P>
   But right now the league is focused on the Lewis trial because
it is at the forefront. And with so much at stake _ a man's
freedom, closure for the families of the victims and the image of a
billion-dollar sports league _ it is no wonder that many people in
the NFL seem to be following the case so closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what he is accused of is true, then I don't feel sorry for
him at all,'' one National Football Conference general manager
said. ``But on the other hand, this is my league, a league I care
about very much, so for his sake and the league's sake, you just
hope he was not involved. Either way, this is something I am going
to spend every free minute of my time following.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always talked about,'' one American Football Conference
head coach said. ``When we have staff meetings, one of the
questions someone always asks is, `Anything going on with the Lewis
case?' When I talk to other coaches, Lewis' name always comes up.
My players are also always talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of miles away from the Atlanta courthouse where the
legal proceedings are taking place, the Lewis trial is a frequent
topic among officials at the NFL Players Association headquarters
in Washington. When general managers speak to each other,
complaining about the lack of salary-cap room or bragging about
their draft picks, a comment or two about Lewis always slips into
the conversation. When players get together for off-season
workouts, Lewis is brought up often.
</P>
<P>
   No group within the NFL _ except for perhaps the Ravens _ is
watching the case more closely than the league office in New York.
It is safe to say that as the trial begins, they are at Defcon 1.
NFL security officials are staying in constant contact with the
Atlanta police and other authorities. When the flood of negative
publicity again begins as the trial heats up, league officials will
constantly remind the news media and fans that the vast majority of
its players are good citizens, which is indeed the case.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Baltimore team officials, while believing in Lewis,
are beginning to think that even if he were cleared of the murder
charges, but found guilty of one of the lesser counts, such as
obstruction of justice, the league may still suspend him for at
least several games.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens officials believe that the NFL will want to make an
example of Lewis: If you do not choose your friends more carefully,
you can end up being tried for murder. And even if you are found
not guilty, you will still have to deal with the NFL
</P>
<P>
   Part of Lewis' defense will most likely be that he was simply in
the wrong place at the wrong time and that he had nothing to do
with the stabbings. As his case unfolds, no matter what happens,
there will be lots of people watching, many of them a part of the
game Lewis plays.
</P>
<P>
   Young Is Taking His Time
</P>
<P>
   The agent for Steve Young said the San Francisco quarterback
would most likely take ``every last second'' before deciding
whether to play again.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Steinberg said his 38-year-old client had been medically
cleared to play despite sustaining a series of concussions during
his 15-year career. The latest occurred last season when Young was
hit in the head by a blitzing defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg disagreed with some members of the news media who have
portrayed Young as a person in denial about the possible health
risks of playing again. Steinberg has had seminars for his clients
regarding the risks of concussions, and Young has attended all of
those meetings. Steinberg also said Young had passed every test
administered to him.
</P>
<P>
   It's Never Too Early
</P>
<P>
   Some head coaches believe that championships are won months
before the season begins, and the teams that put the most work into
passing and training camps reap the rewards during the season. If
that is the case, the Tennessee Titans and the Baltimore Ravens are
on their way to good seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, Steve McNair is throwing the ball crisply and, for
the first time in years, is playing on healthy feet. McNair has
worked well in passing camps in the new offense, which while still
run-oriented, allows him more freedom. ``We're going to spread
people out a little more than we have been and we're going to give
the quarterback more options,'' coach Jeff Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, the Ravens were happy with their passing camp,
because players, even the rookies, have almost completely digested
the imaginative offense of coach Brian Billick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, rookies have a little more of a base,'' Billick said.
``We're not having a lot of mistakes _ a few. They won't be quite
as lost the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the League
</P>
<P>
   One of the good guys in football, the personnel man Bobby Grier,
who was fired by New England, was hired as a scout in Houston last
week. . . . Giants linebacker Corey Widmer remains a possible
salary-cap casualty on or after June 1. . . . Indianapolis coaches
say quarterback Peyton Manning has spent this off-season working as
hard as ever. That is a scary thought, because Manning has little
to work on. Manning is setting an example for the rest of the team,
and making a statement that, despite its success last season, the
franchise still has a long way to go before reaching the Super
Bowl. . . . Green Bay tight end Mark Chmura, after being charged
with felony third-degree sexual assault of the family's babysitter,
will most likely be released by the Packers next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
