<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED BULLET MAKES IT CLEAR: NO CROWN FOR FUSAICHI PEGASUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Two weeks after he won the Kentucky Derby for his
fifth straight score, Fusaichi Pegasus suffered a great upset
Saturday when he was outrun by 3} lengths in the homestretch of the
Preakness by Red Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   The colt who carries the name of the flying horse of Greek
mythology was the overwhelming 1-5 favorite, apparently poised to
give one more legendary performance on a heavy track at Pimlico
Race Course. But one he got hooked up with Red Bullet in the
homestretch, he could not compete. And at the finish, Red Bullet
won by daylight, while Pegasus held second place by the length of
his head ove Impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the 22nd consecutive year, since Affirmed in 1978,
racing was denied its ultimate prize: the Triple Crown. For the
first time in recent memory, no colt seemed more capable of
achieving it than Fusaichi Pegasus. But for the first time in
decades, a horse who did not race anywhere at 2 came back to win
one of racing's classics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled to the outside,'' said Jerry Bailey, who rode Red
Bullet, ``and hoped it would force Pegasus to go wide around me.
And it happened exactly that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux, the jockey on Fusaichi Pegasus, made no excuses
for his beaten favorite, but said: ``The track was a little
ggreasy. He did some slipping around. He got squeezed coming out of
the gate. But in the final run for home, he was outrun.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a day that dawned with clouds, rain and cold and
threatened to disrupt racing form, particularly the commanding form
exhibited by Fusaichi Pegasus in his first six races.
</P>
<P>
   The large bay colt with the royal breeding and royal price tag _
the son of Prospector cost $4 million as a yearling _ came into the
Preakness as the heavy favorite, two weeks after he dominated the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The rain, though, prompted D. Wayne Lukas to observe, only
partly in jest, ``Everyone now has a perfect excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fusaichi Pegasus went to the post with the same jockey, Kent
Desormeaux, who won the Derby, the Pimlico Special and the
Black-Eyed Susan Stakes within those two weeks. And he raced with
the same credentials: one loss, by a neck, in his debut last
December, then five straight impressive scores this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus even won the Wood Memorial in New York last
month in his final prep race for the Triple Crown classics, and won
it on a heavy track that officially was described as ``wet-fast''
but that looked and felt muddy. He flew past Red Bullet that day
and won by four lengths, giving fans in the East a large clue to
the legend that he had created in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track at the Wood was off,'' said Neil Drysdale, his
trainer. ``He's trained on an off-track, and he's bred to handle an
off-track.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly ran the Preakness on an off-track, although his
rivals questioned in advance how he would handle it. Bob Baffert,
remembering that his Captain Steve had won the Kentucky Futurity
last year on a sloppy track at Keeneland in Kentucky, said Saturday
morning:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of how much they like mud, or don't. Most horses
don't like mud kicking into their faces. My horse won in the
slop.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert reflected on the dangers of challenging Fusaichi
Pegasus, and added, ``But we need all the help we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the eight horses in the Preakness also ran in the
Kentucky Derby: Fusaichi Pegasus (first), Impeachment (third),
Captain Steve (eighth), High Yield (15th) and Hal's Hope (16th).
They might have derived some slight comfort from the recent history
of the Preakness. No horse had won the Preakness after skipping the
Kentucky Derby since Deputed Testamony in 1983, and 71 had tried.
And no Derby winner who went on to become the Preakness favorite
had actually come through in the Preakness since Spectacular Bid in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd did not include the owner of the favorite, Fusao
Sekiguchi, the venture capitalist from Tokyo who paid the $4
million to buy the yearling two years ago. He attended the Derby
but remained at home for the Preakness, citing the length of the
trip from Japan, but he reaffirmed his faith in Fusaichi Pegasus
and said again that he would have paid even more money to buy the
colt.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at Pimlico Saturday apparently was not deterred by the
weather or the memory of bizarre happenings at the Preakness in the
past. Two years ago, a fire in an electrical generator outside the
track caused Pimlico to lose power on a hot afternoon, including
air-conditioning units and the tote boards. Last year, a spectator
leaped onto the track, stood in the middle of the horses thundering
through the homestretch and threw a punch at Artax.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the crowd may have been drawn, in part, by the unusual
pattern of the last three years of the Preakness when three horses
won the Derby and the Preakness but then, on the brink of sweeping
the Triple Crown, failed to win the Belmont Stakes in the final
strides. In 1997 Silver Charm was foiled; in 1998, Real Quiet
missed his moment of history, and in 1999 Charismatic finished
third after fracturing a leg in the homestretch of the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   So, even greater suspense was shouldered by Fusaichi Pegasus,
especially with the added threat from Red Bullet, who had not raced
in the five weeks since Pegasus outran him in the Wood. He carried
the colors of a strong stable, owned by Frank Stronach, the
Canadian business executive and owner of the Magna worldwide
enterprises, and he had the services of the country's premier
jockey, Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to see him sit off the speed and make one big
run,'' said his trainer, Joe Orseno. ``But that will all be in
Jerry's hands when they leave the gate. He knows what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the decision to pass the Derby, the trainer added: ``
Stronach said, `My heart says Derby, but I want what's best for the
horse.' And we agreed that the right thing to do was wait the five
weeks for the Preakness, and take our best shot to beat Fusaichi
Pegasus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
