<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-20 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN INVADES DEMOCRATIC TERRITORY; LOOPHOLE INSPIRES
LEGISLATIVE END RUN; INTERNET ADDRESSES AS POLITICAL TOOL; A
MESSAGE TO BUSH; ON THE ROAD IN NORTH DAKOTA 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, a conservative freshman Republican from
Pennsylvania, barely won election in 1994, and he has been on the
Democratic hit list ever since. Polls indicate that his Democratic
opponent, Rep. Ron Klink, a moderate, is within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   But Santorum appears to have more going for him now than he did
when the Democrats first took aim at him. He has toned down his
hard-edged conservatism somewhat and come out in support of a
number of popular government aid projects.
</P>
<P>
   His challenger was battered in a hard-fought, divisive
Democratic primary, whereas Santorum had no primary opposition. And
he has raised over $6 million for his campaign, while Klink had to
mortgage his home just to get through the primary.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Santorum is not only working his Republican base
hard but, anticipating a contest that could be decided by a few
points either way, has also begun to go after the Democrats' base.
Last week, Santorum held a rally in the heavily black heart of
North Philadelphia, serving notice that while about 95 percent of
the city's blacks usually vote Democratic, he did not intend to
surrender a single black vote.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by 18 black church, community and business leaders,
he declared: ``We are going to actively campaign in the
African-American community. We're going to fight for every vote.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the business leaders, Cody Anderson, praised the senator
for showing up in North Philadelphia and said he was ``worthy of
support'' because he had looked after the community's interests.
``I had accepted a definition from other people of the senator,''
Anderson went on. ``But everywhere I go recently, I've run into
people who have told me of the projects he's supported _ computer
labs, contracts, grants.''
</P>
<P>
   Klink's office called Santorum's visit ``puzzling'' in light of
his ``lifetime rating of 25 percent from the NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOPHOLE INSPIRES LEGISLATIVE END RUN
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gov. Jim Geringer of Wyoming vetoed a bill that
proposed a constitutional amendment to curtail veto power by
governors. This year the Legislature tried again.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second go-round, legislators sent the bill directly
to the secretary of state for action after passage, saying they had
found a loophole in state law that permitted constitutional
amendment measures to bypass the governor's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Geringer says he is going to court to get a ruling on the
legality of the end run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lesson in civics,'' he said last week. ``I have an
obligation as governor to be sure that process is followed. It was
not.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET ADDRESSES AS A POLITICAL TOOL
</P>
<P>
   In the world of the Internet, it is known as cybersquatting _
the practice of putting down $75 to lay claim to an especially
appealing or recognizable Internet address before another person or
organization can, and then offering to sell that address to the
latecomer for a nice profit.
</P>
<P>
   So campaign aides to Rep. Bob Wise, a moderate-to-liberal West
Virginia Democrat who is running this year for governor
(www.BobWise2000.com and www.BobWise2000.org), were not especially
surprised the other day when an e-mail message came stating that
one Scott Loughery of Baltimore had laid claim to the addresses
www.Wise2000.com and www.Wise2000.org.
</P>
<P>
   Wise's aides replied that Loughery, who they say identified
himself as ``a Wise supporter,'' might want to consider
``donating'' the addresses to the Wise campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Loughery, as the Wise aides tell it, countered with an offer to
sell both addresses for $1,500 and added: ``Should you take a pass,
I will likely be approaching some well-heeled members of the
business community who may wish to use it to hamper such a
pro-labor governor taking office. They could conceivably set up an
opposition site that effectively shuts down your fund raising.
Sorry for the shakedown. I got cynical about politics when Clinton
took over. I'm a proud member of the Green Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise's aides clicked on the Wise2000 sites. Up came the site of
Wise's Republican opponent, Gov. Cecil Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   They accused the governor of resorting to ``trickery'' and
``chicanery.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood denied any involvement. Yes, his aides reported,
Loughery had approached the governor about buying the Wise2000
sites for $1,500 to ``damage'' Wise in a race considered a toss-up.
But, they said, the governor ignored the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Loughery says he has no comment, ``none at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Wise2000 sites? At the beginning of the weekend,
clicking onto the sites brought up the Ralph Nader campaign site.
Nader, the consumer advocate, is seeking the Green Party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A MESSAGE TO BUSH: LISTEN TO YOUR MAMA
</P>
<P>
   In December, Barbara Bush, the former first lady and the mother
of Gov. George W. Bush, declared in an interview with ABC News that
the Republican Party should not take a stand on abortion in its
national platform. ``I believe in states' rights,'' she said, ``and
I don't think it should be in the national platform. There's
nothing a president can do about it anyway, in all honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words are about to come back to haunt her son, who has said
he will fight to keep the Republican Party's anti-abortion plank at
this summer's national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans for Choice, an organization that has threatened
noisy, divisive demonstrations at the convention if the plank is
not removed or modified, is preparing to run 30-second radio
advertisements that call on Bush to ``listen to your mama'' rather
than to the hard-right conservatives who tend to dominate the
party's platform deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heed her, not Pat Robertson and Ralph Reed,'' says the
advertisements' narrator, Adrian Cronauer of ``Good Morning,
Vietnam'' fame. ``Listen to your mama. That's a family value we can
all agree on.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD AGAIN IN NORTH DAKOTA
</P>
<P>
   Another update on Duane Sand, the retired Navy man who
campaigned across the frozen breadth of North Dakota in January _
on foot _ to call attention to his novice run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he make it and end up with the Republican
nomination (to even his own surprise), but he is off on another
marathon, of sorts, as he chases after the entrenched Democratic
incumbent, Kent Conrad.
</P>
<P>
   What now?
</P>
<P>
   Sand plans to hit every city and town in the state that has a
post office _ all 300 or so of them.
</P>
<P>
   No mention of the crossroads that have post offices. Not yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
