<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 05/20/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BOYTON BEACH, Fla. -- May 20, 2000 --
MINISTERS-WIVES-COX-2 -- Andrea Gardner, wife of Rev. Ron Gardner,
gives a short lesson on Jesus Christ to children in their new
parish, the Boynton Beach Baptist Church in Boyton Beach, Fla. The
church currently meets at Crystal Lakes Elementary School, and
while Ron gives his service and sermon to adults, Andrea takes the
children to a separate room where she conducts ``Children's
Church.'' (Jennifer Podis/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- May 20, 2000 --
MINISTERS-WIVES-COX-1 -- Times have changed, and the role of the
reverend's wife has evolved. Forget the image of the matronly
minister's wife with her white shoes, white gloves and preordained
hostessing duties, many pastor's wives are speaking their minds and
loving life. Esther Ilnisky, the wife of Pastor Bill Ilnisky, found
her own place in life and founded her own ministry, The Esther
Network International and Children's Global Prayer Movement.
Ilnisky takes in the beauty of the sunrise at Phipps Park on Palm
Beach just prior to the start of her husband's Easter Sunrise
service Sunday morning. (Bruce R. Bennett/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ZACATECAS, Mexico -- May 20, 2000 -- MEXICO-FOX-COX-2 --
Vicente Fox, the Mexico's National Action Party's presidential
candidate, greets supporters at a rally in the city of Zacatecas,
Mexico. With six weeks to go before the most competitive
presidential election this country has ever seen, Fox is a
phenomenon who could unleash a revolution in Mexico if he wins on
July 2. Judging from most opinion polls, the rancher, and former
Coca-Cola executive and governor is the first opposition candidate
who has a chance at finally defeating Mexico's Revolutionary
Institutional Party, which has controlled Mexico's presidency since
1929. (Sergio Dorantes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LEON CITY, Mexico -- May 20, 2000 -- MEXICO-FOX-COX-1 --
Mexican presidential candidate Vicente Fox, who belongs to Mexico's
National Action Party, the PAN, which governs six states and is
generally considered the most socially and fiscally conservative of
Mexico's political parties, talking with his campaign manager while
hoseback riding at his San Cristobal ranch in Leon City, Mexico.
With six weeks to go before the most competitive presidential
election this country has ever seen, Fox is a phenomenon who could
unleash a revolution in Mexico if he wins on July 2. (Sergio
Dorantes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BEIJING -- May 20, 2000 -- CHINA-TRADE-COX-2 -- As the
U.S. Congress prepares to vote on permanently normalizing trade
relations with China, which President Bill Clinton says is
necessary to allow the U.S. to benefit from a far-reaching trade
accord securing China's entry into the WTO, all that laborers in
China see is a rapidly-changing economy that is leaving them
behind. Liu Jiuwang, in front of the Beijing Textile Machine
Factory where he has been working for 20 years. Liu says the
WTOwill be good for Chinese consumers, but workers like him are
unlikely to reap the full benefits of an open economy. (Julie
Chao/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BEIJING -- May 20, 2000 -- CHINA-TRADE-COX-1 -- The way
Chinese factory workers see it, lay-offs loom inevitably in their
future, regardless of any vote by the U.S. Congress or whether
China joins any world trade bodies. The state-run factories they
work at are dinosaurs left-over from the era of the planned economy
and will most likely not make it in the era of global economic
competition. A worker at the Beijing Textile Machine Factory, where
equipment is outdated and layoffs are looming. (Julie Chao/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WEST ISLIP, N.Y. -- May 20, 2000 -- NY-SENATE-REPUBS --
Congressman Rick Lazio, his wife Patricia, and daughters Kelsey,
and Molly walk off after announcng that he will run for Senator at
West Islip High School in Long Island, N.Y. on Saturday, one day
after New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani announced that he was
pulling out of the Senate race. (Vincent Laforet/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MIAMI -- May 20, 2000 -- BKN-RILEY -- Pat Riley, coach
of the Miami Heat, will walk into his team's arena on Sunday, in
front of 20,000 people who in their hearts cannot fathom the Heat
beating the Knicks in a deciding game on their home floor. For two
seasons running, Riley has endured his former employers putting him
on vacation early. Riley, the Gladiator, dressed in Armani armor
during Game 5 of the second-round Eastern Conference playoffs
against the Knicks in Miami (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 20, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-ASSESS -- If
revising his legacy is indeed the objective of the newly
introspective-sounding mayor of New York City, the issues are out
there waiting for Rudoplh Giuliani. His health allowing, he can do
a lot even if hampered by skepticism and the dimming of the
spotlight. Giuliani's withdrawal from the Senate race on Friday was
recorded by news cameras from all over the country, and by a City
Council member's video camera. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 20, 2000 -- NY-CARDINAL-FIRSTMASS-3 --
Archbishop-designate Edward Egan, known for his strict support of
conservative church teachings, assumed the spiritual leadership of
2.4 million followers in the New York Archdiocese, and ordained
five new priests Saturday in the first Mass he's celebrated at St.
Patrick's Cathedral since being named to the nation's most
prominent Catholic pulpit. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 20, 2000 -- NY-CARDINAL-FIRSTMASS-2 --
Archbishop-designate Edward Egan, far right, ordains five new
priests Saturday in the first Mass he's celebrated at St. Patrick's
Cathedral since being named to lead the New York Archdiocese. Egan,
who has been bishop of Bridgeport, Conn., for 12 years, has said
working with parish priests will be among his top priorities in New
York. He won praise in Connecticut for bringing local men into the
priesthood, and told worshippers at St. Patrick's that he was
thrilled to perform Saturday's ordinations. (Ruth Fremson/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 20, 2000 -- NY-CARDINAL-FIRSTMASS-1 --
Archbishop-designate Edward Egan, known for his strict support of
conservative church teachings, assumed the spiritual leadership of
2.4 million followers in the New York Archdiocese, and ordained
five new priests Saturday in the first Mass he's celebrated at St.
Patrick's Cathedral since being named to the nation's most
prominent Catholic pulpit. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- May 20, 2000 -- DC-MAYOR -- Washington,
D.C, the city-state by the Potomac, the perennial ward that
Congress seems delighted to scold and micromanage, is clearly
moving to a higher ground of civic morale. In his 16 months of
incumbency, Anthony A. Williams, the 48-year-old mayor of The
District of Columbia, has labored to replace the city's wastrel
image of the flamboyant Marion Barry era with his own
jot-and-tittle devotion to quiet executive techniques. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MIDLAND, Texas -- May 20, 2000 -- BUSH-BIO-4 -- George W.
Bush, though born in 1946 in New Haven, Conn., while his father was
still an overachieving student at Yale, moved to West Texas when he
was not quite 2 and grew up in the nurturing environment of
Midland, Texas. The Little League baseball catcher in Midland,
Texas in 1954. (George Bush Presidential Library/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 20, 2000 -- BUSH-BIO-3 -- George W. Bush,
though born in 1946 in New Haven, Conn., while his father was still
an overachieving student at Yale, moved to West Texas when he was
not quite 2 and grew up in the nurturing environment of Midland,
Texas. George W. and George Bush at an oil rig opening, 1954. (Bush
Family Album/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- May 20, 2000 -- BUSH-BIO-2 -- As the son of a
president and scion of a wealthy family, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, is often perceived as a child of privilege, but neighbors
from his home of Midland, Texas, insist that in the 1950s that was
not the case. The Bush family in 1958, clockwise from top: George
Bush, holding Neil. George W., the oldest child; Jeb; and marvin,
held by his mother Barbara Bush. (George Bush Presidential
Library/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- May 20, 2000 -- BUSH-BIO-1 -- While growing
up, George W. Bush absorbed West Texas values that many old friends
say are central to understanding who he is today. The Bush family,
about 1950, from left, Barbara, George W., George and his parents,
Dorothy Walker and Prescott S. Bush. (George Bush Presidential
Library/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ABU DIS, West Bank -- May 20, 2000 --
PALESTINIANS-JERUSALEM -- Jerusalem is well known to be an intense
symbolic focal point for both Israelis and Palestinians, as well as
for Jews, Christians and Muslims worldwide. Abu Dis, a dusty
neighboring town, given over to Palestinian control, is closer to
the heart of the contested city than is the Israeli Parliament or
the Israeli prime minister's headquarters. From Abu Dis, the Dome
of the Rock in the heart of the Old City is visible. (Rina
castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
