<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GEORGIA-GOP0521-COX     05-20 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-GOP0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor's giant shadow has GOP leaders gloomy
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ To Linda Schrenko, it's almost as if she has no
choice but to run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   And for that, she blames the Democratic incumbent, Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has fixed things so that if I want to remain state school
superintendent, I have to run for governor because he's doing
everything to control education,'' the Republican education chief
said. ``Everything that's not under his direct control, he creates
a bureaucracy that is under his direct control.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schrenko said she has no intention of entering the
governor's race in 2002. Instead, she said, she will seek a third
term as superintendent _ and hope that some other Republican takes
on, and defeats, Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko's dilemma was on abundant display this weekend in
Savannah as Georgia Republicans held their state convention.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP activists who gathered here desperately want to unseat
Barnes in two years _ to take an office that only one Republican
has ever occupied by election. (Republican Rufus Brown Bullock was
elected and served from 1868 to 1871, when he resigned. Republican
Benjamin F. Conley took over for Bullock for two months and 12 days
before a Democratic successor took office.)
</P>
<P>
   But no one is yet ready to commit to a race that, many
Republicans acknowledge, is all but unwinnable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people who are interested in running,'' said
Chuck Clay, chairman of the Georgia Republican Party. But ``no good
politician wants to commit political suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it seems a campaign against Barnes would be a mission
destined to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the governor is extremely popular with Georgians. His
campaign organization, which never disbanded after the 1998
election, reported raising $2.2 million last year. The campaign
recently took the unusual step of running television ads in which
Barnes touted his education reform plan _ a full 2 1/2 years before
the 2002 election.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all that, history is firmly on Barnes' side. In the
quarter-century that Georgia governors have been allowed to serve
consecutive terms, no incumbent has lost a bid for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Georgia governorship has essentially become an eight-year
term,'' said Charles Bullock, a political scientist at the
University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans' best hope for getting a qualified candidate
would be if something blows up in Barnes' face,'' Bullock said.
``There are a lot of things that could happen. But so far he has
led a charmed life.''
</P>
<P>
   That point, he said, is not lost on potential Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republicans may field a credible challenger to Barnes,
Bullock said, ``it may not be someone from the first tier.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clay said a number of prominent Republicans are
considering the campaign. They include some of Georgia's eight
Republican congressmen, Schrenko, Insurance Commissioner John
Oxendine and former Attorney General Mike Bowers, who lost in the
1998 Republican gubernatorial primary.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the potential candidates spoke during the convention,
and some _ like Schrenko _ flirted with the idea of running. But
none gave a firm indication of leaning toward challenging Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Republicans have only one announced candidate for
statewide office in 2002: state Sen. Bill Stephens (R-Canton), who
says he will run for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting statewide candidates would be easier, Clay said, if
the party wins the White House this year and gains seats in the
General Assembly. Conversely, he said, Republican defeats this
November _ especially at the legislative level _ could be
disastrous for recruiting gubernatorial candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to get shellacked,'' Clay said, ``you're not going
to find folks coming out of the woodwork.''
</P>
<P>
   The Savannah convention was devoted to electing delegates to
this year's GOP national convention. But talk about the party's
prospects in 2002 never slipped far beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention hall's podium, bravado reigned.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine, for instance, predicted a ``surprise'' for Barnes in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a Republican president and a Republican
vice president fly down here on Air Force One to campaign against
him to put a freely elected Republican in the office of governor in
the state of Georgia,'' Oxendine declared.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor, though, delegates were less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``People vote Democrat because their parents voted Democrat and
their grandparents voted Democrat,'' said Frank Hardeman, a
delegate from Savannah. ``It's a hard trend to break.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
