<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT KIND OF ODDS TO CLIPPERS HAVE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the Heat, 21-20, at halftime and while you crack open the
emergency Tums, NBC adjourns to the NBA Draft lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Limping in to draw straws at David Stern's faith-healing tent
will be the league's ranking have-nots. Thanks to math provided by
the NBA, the Clippers' Elgin Baylor has dibs on today's catbird
seat. The expected prize: wounded Cincinnati Bearcats power forward
Kenyon Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, whose team scored lottery victories in 1988 and 1998
(the years after David Robinson and Tim Duncan were available, he
points out) again plans to abstain from good-luck charms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People offer to give me all kinds of stuff,'' Baylor said.
``If I thought a good-luck charm would work, I'd send it there by
itself and they could put it in the chair instead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck's fine, but it's also a good idea to promote the
conspiracy-free zone. Just in case the watchdogs of talk radio are
right and any hanky-panky is scheduled to go down, a tiny stuffed
green bear will the ride the head of each of the representatives on
stage at Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   According to league sources, the NBA informed each participating
team that a back-stage witness to the Ping-Pong ball droppings
would not be necessary this year.
</P>
<P>
   OK.
</P>
<P>
   So, what kind of odds do the Clippers have?
</P>
<P>
   As the worst team for NBA 2000, they have a 25-percent chance to
land the top pick. This is measured by having 250 of a possible
1001 Ping- Pong-ball combinations. The Chicago Bulls, whose crummy
play folded down the stretch, have 200 of the 1,000 issued to the
13 lotto participants.
</P>
<P>
   But - due to rotten karma and expansion embargoes - the last
time the league's worst team claimed the top pick was 1990 (New
Jersey, Derrick Coleman).
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of karma, the team entering the lottery ranked No. 3
for Ping-Pong-ball stockpiling has scored the first pick the last
three years. If the streak continues, Orlando (via Golden State,
the last gasp from the Chris Webber-Penny Hardaway trade) is home
free. &QL; 
Points of view
</P>
<P>
   Phase 1 in the Clips' 2000 pre-draft screening process was a
two-day festival starring four relatively big-time point guards. As
you may recall, the Clippers are to point guards as Montana is to
zydeco music.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most notorious name in this quartet belongs to Erick
Barkley, whose only fraternal tie with the Chuckster is his quick
history of controversy. Barkley, now abandoning St. John's after a
tumultuous sophomore season, is the heralded playmaker blessed by
white-glove treatment from the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been portrayed a certain way in the media,'' he said at
the end of a businesslike skirmish at USC's Lyon Center, ``but
people don't know that I'm a really humble dude.''
</P>
<P>
   The humble dude was temporarily suspended from play last season
following a suspicious swap of sport utility vehicles and for
allegedly allowing the loot needed to square his prep school
tuition to be coughed up by an AAU coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to finally not have to wake up every day and see my
face in the newspapers,'' said Barkley of his momentary escape from
NCAA scrutiny and the New York City microscope. ``All of that
stress is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new stress is no slouch.
</P>
<P>
   While under Clipper surveillance Barkley spent parts of Thursday
and Friday in hand-to-hand combat with relentlessly clever Scoonie
Penn (Ohio State), speedy Speedy Claxton (Hofstra) and gung-ho Matt
Santangelo (Gonzaga).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very nervous the first day,'' said Barkley, who some
scouts project as the first point guard to disappear from the draft
board June 28. ``Today, I feel more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, Erick, but it might be time to suspend the relaxation and
work a bit more on that jumper. The only member of this foursome
who didn't complete four years of collegiate eligibility (which may
not be an issue here), the erratic Barkley appears to be a reach as
a top 10 pick.
</P>
<P>
   The real fun was had spying on Penn vs. Claxton, the equivalent
of slap-boxing between freelance cats. Penn also was the best
shooter on display, while Claxton is, unequivocally, the quickest
point guard in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, who goes about 5-foot-9 if he switches to the thermal
socks, began the cool-down period of the two-day trial by flipping
the ball against the backboard, leaving the floor for a while, then
slamming the ball through the rim with both hands. Santangelo, who
checks in at 6-1 when bubble gum is stuck to the bottom of each
shoe, upped the ante with a two-handed reverse that included a
Harold Miner-style, waist-level pump. Sweet, but he's still a
second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   All the 5-10 Claxton had was a rock-the-cradle, jackhammer dunk
that blew away the others. The Speedy tour's next stop is Toronto,
where he'll match skills with Khalid El-Amin, the robust front man
from UConn.
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively scheduled for Tuesday's Clipper lab tests are small
forwards Jason Kapono, UCLA's freshman from Artesia High, and Chris
Carrawell, who just finished a terrific senior season at Duke. &QL; 
Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Joe Jones, the official uncle of and unofficial spokesman for
6-9 LSU sophomore Stromile Swift, has been telling NBA personnel
heavyweights his nephew will stay in school if he's not going to be
a top-three pick. Well, it's been impossible to locate anyone who
thinks the vertically splendid Swift will go later than four.
Nobody can guarantee it won't be No. 4, but don't believe any
one-spot snub (a salary difference of about $300,000 a year for
three years) would really put Swift back in college. ... Miami
point guard Anthony Carter, the hero of the Heat's Game 3 victory
at New York, may not be a lock to stay put next season. The Heat
will have to pony up its coveted $2.25 million exception to retain
the ex-Saddleback College and CBA hotshot, who - a source says -
could receive a more lucrative offer from (drum roll) the Indiana
Pacers. ... If 7-0 Texas center Chris Mihm (a top-four favorite)
flees the draft and hustles back to Austin for his senior season,
he may be only the fourth big man selected in the 2001 draft. The
possible top three: Dominguez High's Tyson Chandler, Eddy Curry of
Thornwood High in Chicago's south suburbs and Yao Ming from China.
An unofficial Team Ming source said the 7-5, 19-year-old - at press
time is as close to a lock for the 2001 draft as his country's red
tape will allow. ...
</P>
<P>
   Darius Miles, who's jumping from East St. Louis (Ill.) HS and
may land in the top seven of the draft, has done what we'd heard he
wouldn't do. He's put his future in the busy hands of agent David
Falk. ... According to league sources, DeShawn Stevenson from
Fresno's Washington Union HS is taking the predictable hop from the
adidas camp to agent Arn Tellem. ... Joel Przybilla, the 7-1
sophomore refugee from the University of Minnesota, was witnessed
having a near-monster workout for the New Jersey Nets. His next
stop is Chicago, where crafty GM Jerry Krause is telling people
he's wild about Mihm. ... The worst thing about Arvydas Sabonis
disappearing from Saturday's Game 1 is that his head is too big to
be cropped for a milk carton photo. ... A freakish blast of air
from the team jet demonstrated that Coach Jeff Van Gundy's Honda
Civic has better ``ups'' than his starting power forward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
