r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-L     05-20 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT AT WRIGLEY MIGHT BECOME NORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disciplinary actions coming to the Los Angeles Dodgers from
Tuesday's rumble at Wrigley Field should come this week, but the
implications and fallout from it will last much longer.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than an isolated issue in which players went into
the stands, more than fines and suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Because of everything that happened, every ballpark in the
league is forced to evaluate its security, how the staff reacts to
such incidents and what course of action needs to be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the belief this is a one-time happenstance at
Wrigley, so little needs be done is ignorant thinking. Not when
yahoos like Andrew Tellers, the guy who mooned John Rocker at
Dodger Stadium earlier this month, is flying to Atlanta to meet
Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more idiotic? That's a sure way to have fans
stay off the field. Let them meet the person they went after.
</P>
<P>
   So while Frank Robinson, vice president of on-field operations,
watches videotape and conducts interviews before his expected
severe punishments, Kevin Hallinan, baseball's director of
security, is figuring out the best way to reduce the risk of
altercations between fans and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a park like Wrigley is representative of many of the
new ballparks, where there is a greater proximity of fans to
players,'' said Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of
baseball operations. ``We need to take steps that are preventative
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even though Wrigley Field security reacted slowly, the
issue should have the same effect as an oil change: preventative
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Blame Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter for going into the stands to
catch the guy who allegedly whacked him in the back of the head and
took his cap with one out in the bottom of the ninth inning. Blame
any Dodger who followed into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine. Robinson and judges from the sure-to-come civil
lawsuits will be the ones who ultimately decide how much the
involved players and coaches should be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   They also should find a way to keep the dopey fan from allegedly
hitting a player, or stealing a hat.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the Cubs organization for not having security in place to
prevent such an incident. Not until the next day did Cubs director
of stadium operations Mark McGuire say it was necessary to have a
security guard at the backs of the bullpen players to watch the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities already recognized this isn't 1950. Instead, there
are people in the stands who do nothing but drink all night and, if
the opportunity exists, watch a pitch here and there.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, fans running onto the field during games earn
harsher penalties, such as being charged with a misdemeanor, being
fined up to $2,500 and receiving a one-year jail sentence.
Previously, a citation was the only punishment.
</P>
<P>
   This also isn't the first time anything happened at Wrigley
Field. Giants manager Dusty Baker remembers former Dodgers teammate
Reggie Smith being involved in incidents at Wrigley Field and
Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer is not always right,'' Baker said. ``And the more
intimate the ballparks, the more of a chance of something
happening. Reggie's mom was really ill, and somebody in the stands
at Wrigley was talking about his mama. Somebody says something
personal to you, and you kind of react.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were playing at Candlestick, someone yelled to Reggie,
`I feel like hitting you with this beer can.' Reggie told him, `If
you do, I'll come up and kick your butt.' The guy threw the can,
and Reggie was like Bruce Lee - one move and he was in the stands.
The guy had his hands on a rail, and wouldn't let go. The security
people clubbed him and broke his hand. He sued the Dodgers, and I
think he got $150,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident is ugly enough to spread blame aplenty
around. That's the issue Robinson must deal with.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger issue is how to stop it from occurring again.
That responsibility falls upon everyone involved in baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
