<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LABOR AND THE CHINA VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, May 21:
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, the president of the AFL-CIO, is doing his country
and the labor movement a disservice by fighting so hard against
permanently establishing normal trade relations with China. Of all
the groups lobbying on this issue, none has made a greater historic
blunder than organized labor. By bludgeoning Richard Gephardt and
the Democrats into sticking with labor on the issue, which the
House is set to vote on this week, Sweeney is squandering much of
the good will he has built up in recent years and damaging the
interests of American workers. House Democrats should back the
bill, which deserves bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has had trouble finding a sure footing in his
approach on China. He began in 1993 by making tough demands on
human rights and now too often looks the other way on these issues.
But the administration has reached a formula that is basically
sound. Human rights are served, not hindered, by opening China to
more foreign goods, particularly in telecommunications and
technology, which are bound to bring more information from abroad
to the Chinese people. China's membership in the World Trade
Organization will allow more scrutiny of its treatment of workers,
its record of piracy and even its treatment of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 19th century, the Democratic Party has stood for
workers' interests, and it interpreted their interests as being
served by free trade. It used to be that big American corporations
favored high tariff barriers to protect themselves against cheaper
foreign goods, but Democrats saw that workers are served not by
insulating their employers from competition, but by food, clothing
and other necessities sold here at low prices.
</P>
<P>
   The bill before Congress does not open the United States to more
Chinese products. Rather, it opens China to more American goods and
investment, and imposes a mechanism that can be used to challenge
unfair Chinese practices. Labor fears that more investment abroad
will lead to less investment at home, and fewer jobs. But if
American technology and manufacturing companies are not allowed to
compete in China with other foreign investors, they will be less
able to serve as healthy employers in the United States. Some
American workers will doubtless be hurt by foreign competition. But
the solution is to help these workers, not to try to block the
forces of economic globalization that are benefiting the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's reasons for taking on this issue may have more to do
with his own political interests than those of workers at large. He
won his election with the support of the Teamsters union and is now
listening to the Teamsters on this issue. Other unions within the
labor coalition are less enthusiastic about the AFL-CIO's
wrongheaded stance. Many Democrats in Congress are angry that
organized labor has also opposed lowering trade barriers for Africa
and the Caribbean, where some of the most miserably paid workers in
the world would benefit. Organized labor claims it is now standing
up for Chinese workers by opposing the trade bill. But workers in
the developing world know that trade is one of their only avenues
of hope.
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill could be Clinton's last tough legislative battle
as president. His commendable willingness to stand up to labor and
most members of his own party on trade belies his reputation as
subservient to his party's core constituencies. On the other side
of the aisle, Gov. George W. Bush has shown leadership in
repudiating the isolationists in his own party. Organized labor's
decision to turn this into a make-or-break test of loyalty for its
supporters has been shortsighted and destructive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-KAPLER-RANGERS-LA     05-20 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KAPLER-RANGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER'S LEARNING CURVE EXTENDS FROM DETROIT TO TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Be patient.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Gabe Kapler has told himself for years, even before
he was a 57th-round draft pick. The refrain is just as common from
his manager these days.
</P>
<P>
   After a standout career in which he was named minor-league
baseball's player of the year, Kapler is batting just .200 early in
his third season.
</P>
<P>
   Being a key component in a nine-player trade that sent him from
Detroit to Texas for former American League MVP Juan Gonzalez
during the offseason hasn't made the situation any easier, but he
and his coaches continue to express confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the first three years in the big leagues, I think
is still a learning experience,'' Kapler said. ``Right now, I'm
just trying to learn everything I possibly can from the veteran
players on the team. I think I can add some things - play hard all
the time, play how I know - but I'm still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are willing to let 24-year-old Kapler take his time.
He is currently on the disabled list with torn quadriceps - he is
scheduled to return this week - but the comparisons to Gonzalez
persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not Juan Gonzalez and we didn't expect him to do what
Juan did right away,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``He's
not the only player we traded for and that trade was made for the
long term. (Kapler) is still young and he's adjusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gonzalez, Kapler is a muscular outfielder known for hitting
home runs. Kapler doesn't strike out much, but has a tendency to
pull the ball. The biggest adjustment he is trying to make, though,
is adapting to the life of a major-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing like I dreamed it would be,'' Kapler said. ``I
like it, but it's much more of a job than I thought it would be.
It's hard to describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, how to handle the ups and downs of this game, that's
a challenge everybody goes through. The fact that this is a
business, it's a means of putting food on the table, it's not so
much the game we all grew up playing. It's a lot different now.
It's something I have to learn to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   A realization of what he needs to learn, and the confidence he
will be able to do so, has fueled Kapler's persistence since he was
an amateur. He admits he was ``not that great'' during his career
at Taft High of Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   At Moorpark College in 1995, he earned all-conference honors and
led the Raiders in almost every offensive category. But being
picked so late in the draft that year was an indication he was not
considered a legitimate prospect.
</P>
<P>
   He was among the offensive leaders at every level in the minors.
After setting Southern League records and earning MVP honors in
1998, Kapler was called up to the Tigers in September. No other
Tiger drafted as late as the 57th round has played in the majors
since the MLB draft began in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   A strong showing in spring training earned him a spot on
Detroit's 1999 opening-day roster. Kapler batted just .245, but hit
18 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   He welcomed the trade to Texas as a fresh start, saying he never
felt comfortable in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   He started the season by reaching base in eight of his first
nine plate appearances and getting six hits within the first two
games, including two home runs on opening day. But he has had
multiple hits in only one game since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time to adjust,'' Kapler said. ``Like I said, I'm
taking it as a learning experience. This game is very humbling.
That's part of what I'm learning right now, how to deal with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt in my mind I'll overcome those things. I have
no doubt in my mind I'll have a very good career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
