</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS BEAT YANKEES, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND, Ohio _ His other personality disappeared by the time
the Yankees lost in the bottom of the ninth inning, leaving the
gregarious side of David Cone to wander the clubhouse and apologize
for nasty words uttered when he was pitching against the Indians
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, he snapped at Charlie Wonsowicz, the Yankees' batting
practice pitcher and video coordinator. ``Don't worry about it,
man,'' Wonsowicz said, reassuring Cone. ``Hey, I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates will forever forgive Cone's game-day temper as a sign
of how much he cares. His teammates desperately want him to win,
having watched the way he evolves, adjusts, compensates for the zip
his fastball is losing gradually.
</P>
<P>
   Cone threw well Saturday, relying more on his curveball, but the
Yankees could not pad an early two-run lead and Cone could not hold
that advantage, betrayed by his defense in the end. The Indians
broke a ninth-inning tie when reliever Jeff Nelson walked four
batters and forced home a run with two outs in the ninth as the
Indians won, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 24-15, one game behind Boston in the American
League East, and they are 4-1 against the Indians here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time we beat those guys,'' said Omar Vizquel, the
Indians' shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The season was 26 days old when Cone won a decision for the
first time this season, and 22 more days have passed without
another victory. At this stage in his career, it is as if Cone is
given a completely different set of physical tools every season,
and every season he must figure out how to implement them in the
best way possible.
</P>
<P>
   His slider was his best pitch for years, and he finds his slider
now is not consistently sharp. His fastball has diminished just
slightly, and opponents who have faced him say he does not have the
same arm extension as he did a couple of years ago. Rather, he is
throwing with his right arm closer to his body, bent at the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   So Cone makes changes. A different place on the pitching rubber.
Far fewer sliders. Many more curveballs, at 70 to 73 miles an hour,
mixed with fastballs of 86 to 88 mph. Because there is a great
difference in the speeds of his breaking ball and fastball, he has
kept hitters off-balance. He also had a good split-fingered
fastball Saturday, using it with effectiveness against the likes of
Jim Thome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have good velocity,'' Indians Manager Charlie Manuel
said. ``But he's a pro. He's not afraid to throw what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone shut out the Indians for the first six innings, holding
Cleveland hitless on six at-bats with runners in scoring position.
``I had a much better mix today through six innings,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitted against the Indians' Chuck Finley, Cone had a 2-0 lead
into the seventh, but it could have been much larger. Bernie
Williams seemed to break belated off first base in the first inning
and had to stop at third base on Jorge Posada's two-out double. The
Indians right fielder Manny Ramirez, often a defensive liability,
made three terrific catches Saturday and saved at least four runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Ramirez hustled back toward the right-field
fence on a drive by Alfonso Soriano and reached up, appearing to
turn his head and lose sight of the ball. But he caught the ball
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Cone carried the 2-0 edge into the bottom of the seventh and
hung a curveball that Richie Sexson whacked into the left-field
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Enrique Wilson hit a liner to left, a position Lance Johnson was
manning for the first time since Sept. 10, 1990 _ and the ball
glanced off Johnson's glove. Johnson said later he lost the ball in
the lights. Cone was relieved after Einar Diaz's sacrifice bunt,
and he watched anxiously from the bench as Mike Stanton pitched to
Kenny Lofton with a one-run lead. Lofton slapped a short fly to
left-center, where Johnson _ who has a poor throwing arm _ made the
catch on the run and threw home, too late to get Wilson. Tie game.
Cone got up and left the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no complaints,'' Cone said. ``I'm not going to complain
about run support or tough luck. I had a lead and let it get
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson entered in the eighth, the score still tied, and escaped
a jam when Travis Fryman lined into a double play with the
potential lead run at third. But with two outs and a runner at
first in the ninth, Nelson walked Lofton, then Vizquel, loading the
bases. The crowd roared as Nelson struggled to find the proper arm
slot in his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee reliever got ahead of Roberto Alomar one ball and two
strikes, then threw a ball high, and another.
</P>
<P>
   Full count. Nelson fired a fastball so high that Alomar had to
fall back to get out of the way, and the game was over. ``It was
just one of those days,'' Nelson said. ``I don't ever try go out
there and walks guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson can find some solace in the fact that his record is 6-1.
Cone is 1-3 for the season, stuck on 181 career victories, trying,
searching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
