<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0521-COX     05-20 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore stores more in the bank than Bush
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although likely Republican presidential candidate Gov. George W.
Bush raised three times more money than Democrat Al Gore last
month, the vice president made up the difference with taxpayer
funds and continued to have more money in the bank than his
Republican opponent, campaign finance reports released Saturday
show. Bush reported raising $3.8 million last month, bringing his
record-setting total to more than $84 million, while Gore took in
$1.1 million and received $2.5 million in federal funds. Through
April 30, Gore had $5.7 million in the bank, plus an expected $4.5
million in federal funds, for a total of $10.2 million. Bush had $6
million cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gore is accepting federal funds, he is limited to
spending $40.5 million on his campaign. The campaign reported that
$27.1 million of its spending through April 30 fell under the cap,
leaving Gore $13.4 million to spend through the Democratic National
Convention in August. Bush, who is not taking federal money, can
spend as much as he can raise.
</P>
<P>
   GORE AD CAMPAIGN KICKING INTO HIGHER GEAR
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by sagging poll ratings of Democrats who say Gore is not
connecting with voters, Gore's campaign staff is planning a $10
million television ad campaign with the Democratic National
Committee. The ads, which would highlight party issues and Gore's
biography, are expected to air this summer. ``He needs to ratchet
the campaign up a little,'' said Jim Ruvolo, a top Democratic
activist in Toledo, Ohio. ``He's not connecting on a personal
level. He's got to get in situations where people see him as a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Gore competitive with Bush in Missouri and other
closely watched swing states like Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey
and New Mexico. Bush is ahead in 17 states that account for more
than two-thirds of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the White
House, public polls show. Gore leads in eight states with fewer
than half the needed voters.
</P>
<P>
   HOW MANY HOURS IN A DAY?
</P>
<P>
   Some television network executives are snickering at recent
statements by CNN executives that the Cable News Network plans to
broadcast 264 hours a day of the upcoming Republican National
Convention. Yes, that is 264 hours a day. However, CNN executives
say the programming totals include coverage from all of the cable
network's growing array of 24-hour news outlets _ such as CNN
International, CNN En Espanol and CNNfn _ all of which will carry
simultaneous coverage of the four-day convention, which starts July
31 in Philadelphia. ``Over here, there are still only 24 hours in
the day,'' said a publicity agent for a competing outlet. ``Even if
the number of hours are fewer, our reporting and analysis are every
bit as strong as they've ever been,'' said Marc Burstein, executive
producer of special events for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gail Evans, a CNN executive vice president: ``How could it
be overkill when we're talking about the fate of this country and
who we're electing?''
</P>
<P>
   GET READY TO BE ASKED AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming months, the public will be inundated with
political polls, some of which might make the presidential campaign
even harder to understand, said veteran pollster Andrew Kohut,
director of the Pew Research Center for People and the Press. Kohut
blames a shorter news cycle and the public's fascination with
political scandals for perpetuating the trend. ``Polls are being
ordered up more quickly, being done more quickly and they're being
reported more quickly,'' Kohut said this weekend in Portland, Ore.,
during the annual meeting of the American Association for Public
Opinion Research. ``These polls conducted at breakneck speed on the
heels of big events where public opinion is distorted by the
emotion of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH GETS A SURPRISE KISS
</P>
<P>
   Lots of candidates kiss babies, but Texas Gov. George W. Bush
had the tables turned on him Friday by a 77-year-old man who laid a
surprise peck on Bush's cheek as they shook hands. Howard Koen of
Paducah, Ky., said he did it just for fun. Asked later if any other
men had kissed him during his campaign, Bush replied: ``None as
cute as that.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
