u s BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS     05-20 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT DIAMONDBACKS, 8-7 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Hampton waited three and a half hours to take
the mound Saturday, and he did not stick around until the game
ended. But the Mets left-hander made his appearance count.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton worked six shutout innings before leaving with tightness
in his upper back, as the Mets held on to beat the Arizona
Diamondbacks, 8-7, before an announced crowd of 37,121. The actual
crowd was much smaller, as most fans chose not to wait out a rain
delay at the start of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of Hampton's injury was not immediately known, but
he did not show any effects of it during the game. In fact, Hampton
(5-4) was performing as the Mets expected when they traded for him
last December, displaying not only strong pitching but also
superior athleticism for the third start in a row.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed four hits and one walk in his six innings, striking
out four. Hampton has won his last three outings, and lowered his
earned run average by more than two runs to 4.21 by giving up just
one earned run in his last 231/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks rallied from an 8-2 deficit in the ninth,
scoring five runs off Rich Rodriguez and John Franco. But Armando
Benitez struck out Erubiel Durazo with runners on first and second
to end the game for his 11th save.
</P>
<P>
   For the second game in a row, Hampton also had a single. In his
previous start, his bunt hit sparked a five-run rally that led to a
5-1 victory over Florida. Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter was
aware of Hampton's offense, saying before the series that he had
never spent as much time reviewing a pitcher's hitting ability. But
the analysis accomplished nothing.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and one out in the fourth, Hampton lined a
single to left off Omar Daal, scoring two runs to give the Mets a
3-0 lead. He is now batting .261 after hitting .311 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a better hitting pitcher in the league than
Hampton?'' Showalter said. ``I don't think so. He's a slasher. He's
up there and he gets it done. He helps himself so much because he's
so athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   One batter later, when Joe McEwing's grounder scooted under the
glove of second baseman Jay Bell for the second of four Arizona
errors, Hampton raced from first to third. Derek Bell, who went 2
for 4, knocked in Hampton with a single _ chasing Daal from the
game _ and Edgardo Alfonzo brought home McEwing with a sacrifice
fly to give the Mets a five-run inning and a 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's single extended his hitting streak to 10 games. Acquired
from Houston in the same trade that brought Hampton to the Mets,
Bell entered the game tied for the National League lead in hits,
with 59. Showalter reviewed Bell in his scouting meeting before the
series, but came up with no answers: Bell does not have any
tendencies, he said, and no matter where you pitch him, he is
capable of hurting you.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Bell, who bats second, came up near the end
of a rally, not at the start of one. The Mets have gotten very
little production from the bottom of their order this season,
partly because shortstop Rey Ordonez's average had not been above
.200 since the first game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton, who bats one place above Ordonez, in the seventh
spot, came into the game hitless in his last 22 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth, Benny Agbayani, Payton and Ordonez all
singled to load the bases for Hampton. Ordonez, who had reached on
an infield single and scored in the third, saw his average creep
above .200 with the hit. His average is now .198 after he finished
the day 2 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks never mounted much of a challenge against
Hampton. Their best chance came in the top of the fourth, when a
single and Hampton's only walk put runners on first and second. A
ground ball advanced the runners, but Hampton fanned Bernard Gilkey
on a changeup to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   He worked a 1-2-3 fifth and stranded two runners in the sixth by
striking out Kelly Stinnett to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook, Pat Mahomes and Rodriguez each worked an inning
after Hampton left the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
