<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED: CUBS ARMS IN BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs signed Eric Plunk and Tim Worrell to
minor-league contracts with the hope that after a few weeks, they
would be able to pitch in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't find anyone to pitch in the bullpen,'' Cubs general
manager Ed Lynch said. ``If I have to keep shuffling guys in and
out, that's what I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   So far nothing has worked. The Cubs entered their weekend series
with Cincinnati having blown more saves (nine) than they converted
(seven). Their 7.45 ERA was the worst since STATS, Inc., began
keeping track of such numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Aguilera, once a trustworthy closer, lost the job to Todd
Van Poppel after allowing 10 runs in his last 5 innings. He's
allowed four homers and walked 12 in 16 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything to improve the bullpen,'' Lynch said.
``Whether it's trades or signing guys that are struggling or
anything, We're trying to make it better. It's the main concern. We
had a four-run lead in the ninth inning last week and gave up
six.''
</P>
<P>
   Control is the main problem. The bullpen, which is 6-11, has
walked 101 in 129 innings, and manager Don Baylor said it's
affecting his decisions. Rather than go to his bullpen to protect a
one-run lead late Tuesday against the Dodgers, he left in Kevin
Tapani. Todd Hundley hit a three-run homer in the eighth to give
the Dodgers the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't close the deal,'' Baylor said. ``If we could
close the deal, we'd be in the middle of the pack somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cubs are 16-27, and their .372 winning percentage
is second-worst in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Jones not Chipper: On the surface, Atlanta third baseman Chipper
Jones appears to be off to a nice start, but he's not thinking that
way. He's hitting .299 with 10 homers and 29 RBI, but the reigning
MVP thinks he should have much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hanging on right now,'' Jones said. ``My consistency,
average-wise and power-wise, has been terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the root of Jones' displeasure is his performance with
runners in scoring position. He's hitting .207 in that situation
after batting .308 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting myself out a lot, swinging at bad pitches,'' Jones
said. ``Sometimes, I feel so good that I feel I can hit any pitch
that they throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Red hot: It wasn't too long ago Cincinnati was having all sorts
of problems in nearly every aspect and St. Louis was threatening to
blow open the NL Central. Now, the Reds and Cardinals are tied atop
the division after the Reds won eight of nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing like we have something to play for,'' shortstop
Barry Larkin said. ``I like the fight and the fact that everybody's
helping and playing hard. Different people are getting the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Mets lefty Al Leiter is 5-0 with a 3.24 ERA, much
different than the way he celebrated a four-year, $32 million
contract last season when he was 0-4 with a 6.12 ERA through eight
starts. ... Former Met and Dodger Bobby Bonilla is having a huge
laugh at the expense of the Mets, and manager Bobby Valentine in
particular. Bonilla is still being paid by the Mets, but he's
playing regularly for the Braves, who lead the NL East by five
games. ``I had to get out of New York because I wasn't playing.
This is like a gift. I'm ecstatic now. Hey, I'm doing the
Macarena,'' Bonilla said. ... Phillies lefty Randy Wolf, an El
Camino Real High graduate, struck out Mark McGwire three times
Wednesday then admitted afterward that he has had a poster of
McGwire on his bedroom wall since he was 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
