<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT TRAILBLAZERS, 109-94 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shouts of ``MVP! MVP!'' cascaded around Shaquille
O'Neal Saturday afternoon, only the fans were not cheering a
spectacular dunk or a blocked shot by the Lakers' center.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal stood at the free-throw line with Game 1 of the National
Basketball Association's Western Conference finals still undecided,
certainly a situation that normally fills the Staples Center with
tension.
</P>
<P>
   Not Saturday, not during the final five minutes of the Lakers'
109-94 victory. O'Neal survived a brutal contest of Hack-a-Shaq and
made 8 of 12 free throws down the stretch to finish off the
Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, O'Neal made seven consecutive free throws,
thwarting the Trail Blazers' effort to rally from a 26-point
first-half deficit.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal led the Lakers with 41 points and 11 rebounds. Glen Rice
added 15 points and Kobe Bryant had 13. O'Neal made 13 of 27 free
throws to counter Portland's strategy of intentionally fouling him
to put him on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player,'' Coach Mike Dunleavy of the Trail
Blazers said. ``I like Shaq a lot. He just can't make all his free
throws. From my point of view, if we had scored a few more times in
that stretch, we'd have been right back in the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers had closed to 97-88 with 4 minutes 50 seconds
to play. Scottie Pippen scored 19 points and Bonzi Wells had 17,
all in the second half, to lead Portland, which lost Rasheed
Wallace midway through the third quarter when he was ejected after
a second technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going pretty good until they started to
hack Shaq,'' Coach Phil Jackson of the Lakers said. ``That got the
crowd into it and got him focused to hit seven in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Lakers' weapons fired with expert precision en route
to a 63-42 first-half lead. O'Neal scored 12 points and Bryant had
12, but Robert Horry led the decisive rally, a 26-4 run that
covered almost eight minutes of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Horry came off the bench and scored all 12 of his points in that
span. He and Rice capped the run with consecutive 3-point baskets,
then stood chest-to-chest during a Portland timeout, ignoring the
towel-waving and back-slapping along the Lakers' bench. Four and a
half minutes remained in the second quarter, but already the Lakers
led by 52-30.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpshooting Horry and Rice calmly bumped fists, quietly
acknowledging their work with a firm nod. Meanwhile, the Trail
Blazers cast puzzled looks at one another.
</P>
<P>
   Portland did not shoot poorly (52.8 percent) or rebound badly
(12 rebounds to the Lakers' 17) in the first half. But the Trail
Blazers failed to extend their defense far enough to bother the
Lakers' 3-point shooters, who drilled 8 of 12 attempts. Portland
made only 4 of 10 from behind the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers went to the free-throw line 24 times, compared
to the Lakers' 43 times. Dunleavy had complained all week about a
variety of officiating subjects, including his team's shortage of
free-throw attempts against the Lakers this season.
</P>
<P>
   His frustration continued Saturday as the Lakers were called for
only eight fouls _ none were committed during the act of shooting _
while they made 7 of 9 free throws in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell down in some defensive areas, but they hit shots, and
we couldn't get to the line,'' Dunleavy said. ``That was a big
factor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
