<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-REUNION0521-COX     05-20 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNION0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Terminal cancer patient reunites with her sons
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The pain of terminal liver cancer turned to
10 minutes of wailing when Marie Mercius saw her four sons together
for the first time in seven years Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, thank God, thank God, thank God . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   Mercius yelled those words in Creole so many times that a
hospital employee opened the door to check what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The employee saw the boys and left politely. By now, most of the
nurses and patients and even the patients' families at Bethesda
Memorial Hospital in Boynton Beach knew something of Mercius'
terrible and wonderful and yet terrible story.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have told her she's dying. The Immigration and
Naturalization Service bent its rules and the community chipped in
so three of her sons could fly in from Haiti Friday night and apply
to become permanent residents. Her fourth son came to West Palm
Beach to live with her four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, thank God . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   Mercius was standing when she saw them, but collapsed face-first
onto the bed at the sight of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Her two 6-foot boys _ Jacques Sully, 19, and Yvelor Sully, 15 _
lifted her. They were quiet, but sobbing as hard as she was.
Pierre, 11 and developmentally disabled, clung to Jacques, unable
to comprehend the gravity of the journey he had just made. He
yelled, ``Mama,'' as he had been doing all morning and licked his
brother's ear. Rock, the 13-year-old who's been living with his
mother, sat silently in the corner of the hospital room.
</P>
<P>
   Mercius spent the week willing herself to live, yet worrying
that when she soon dies the teenage sons _ who lost their father
seven years ago _ won't have parents anymore. The sons weren't told
of their mother's condition directly. Yet they knew she was sick
and they accepted their first plane ride and the beginning of their
American life with a kind of nervous wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   If she hadn't been near death, INS officials would not have
bumped her up on their list of applicants to grant her residency
Monday. And the agency would not have offered Mercius' sons parole
status _ a step that lets them stay in this country legally while
they apply for permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   Mercius, 46 and aware of all of those bitterly ironic factors as
she clutched her sons Saturday, begged God to let her live.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was the apex of an anxious 30 hours that saw her
three sons emigrate from the hemisphere's poorest country to its
richest.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques, Yvelor and Pierre awoke at 5 a.m. Friday in a Haitian
town called Arcahaie, where they had been living with their
grandparents since their mother left. Marie Mercius said she was
forced to leave because, as a cook to the children of former
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide, her life was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   In Arcahaie, Jacques and Yvelor had lots of friends and played
lots of basketball. They watched television and rooted for Los
Angeles Lakers basketball star Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre, the youngest, received special attention from his
brothers, his aunt, his uncle and, especially, his grandmother.
When he's not being watched and held, he often falls down or hits
himself. His right wrist has deep scars because he couldn't resist
touching fire one time. He can't talk in complete sentences, but
he's able to let others know when he's thirsty, said Kledanor
Mercius, the boys' uncle.
</P>
<P>
   When they were ready to leave the house for the last time
Friday, Uncle Kledanor loaded his rusted white Isuzu pickup with a
floral suitcase and a wicker love seat. Kledanor usually uses the
truck to haul Coca-Cola and beer 35 minutes from Port-au-Prince,
earning the equivalent of about one U.S. dollar for each case he
resells. Thirty to fifty cases a week affords him a decent living
by Haitian standards.
</P>
<P>
   Including their grandfather, their aunt and Kledanor's
girlfriend, there were seven of them in the truck. By 7 a.m., they
reached the INS office in Port-au-Prince, hoping their immigration
papers had arrived in time for them leave on the afternoon flight
to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials in Nebraska had sent their paperwork by overnight
mail on Monday. But because service to Haiti is slow, the
definition of ``overnight'' can be stretched.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the documents had arrived, removing one
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the children met the woman who championed their
cause _ a Haitian-American activist. Daniella Henry, executive
director of the Haitian-American Community Center, learned the
depth of Marie Mercius' illness two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Henry spent much of the past two weeks calling in favors from
INS agents who have appeared on her local Creole radio show. Not
only did INS officials expedite the families' applications to a
dramatic extent, they also agreed to waive more than $600 in fees
due when the children apply for permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   Henry persuaded Air Haiti to donate plane tickets for the
children. She raised money in the community so the boys' aunts in
West Palm Beach could buy them new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   When Henry arrived at the INS office in Haiti, she handed them
bags of new clothes and helped them finish filling out forms. The
family spent the rest of the morning at a clinic, collecting their
medical documents.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques and Yvelor were remarkably subdued, almost dejected.
Although their uncle said he kept their mother's terminal condition
a secret from them, they have had hints. At one point, Yvelor
started looking at a Palm Beach Post story and photo from last week
that showed his very ill mother in her hospital room. Though he
cannot read English, he saw the picture, and his uncle immediately
grabbed it from him.
</P>
<P>
   The boys changed from their American-style baggy pants and
name-brand T-shirts into slacks, button-down shirts and ties. They
were about to see Port-au-Prince for the last time from the back of
a flat-bed truck.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques hummed under his breath and Yvelor gazed, occasionally
wiping his eyes of dust and _ perhaps _ tears. They were riding
behind a Haitian taptap bus that was so crowded, seven people were
hanging out the back.
</P>
<P>
   Between the vast potholes, people and cars fought for space,
carefully dodging older cars that had been run-down and abandoned
in the median. The smells of exhaust, trash and smoke competed for
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Port-au-Prince resembles a huge outdoor flea market. One person
sells chickens next to another who sells mangos or mattresses. On
another block, they're selling motor oil and tires. Down from
there, it's leather bags and furniture. The buildings behind the
make-shift stores are either crumbling or under construction,
except for the glistening new yellow Shell gas stations or the
black and red Texacos.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the city stands the mountains, reminding a visitor that
this is, at heart, a homeland worthy of the kind of nostalgia
Jacques and Yvelor must have been experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane took off, Yvelor continued to stare out the window,
down at the Island of Hispaniola and the Caribbean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saying goodbye to Haiti, I guess,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, he and his brothers would be clear of customs and
in Henry's silver Toyota 4-Runner, headed from Miami to Palm Beach
County. They wondered why Interstate 95 was so smooth and free of
traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   Henry called their mother with her cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have been in the hospital with you. That's where I
need to be,'' Jacques said to his mother, according to Henry's
translation.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation lifted their mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is good,'' Jacques said in English.
</P>
<P>
   The three sons spent Friday night with two aunts, who will
likely look out for them if their mother dies, as doctors say she
will.
</P>
<P>
   They were asking to see their mother, but it was nearly 10 p.m.
The next morning, there would be time for a visit with Dr. Serge
Thys, a local Haitian psychiatrist who specializes in children and
adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   Thys counseled them for free and handed Henry money so they
could buy their mother a plant, a get-well balloon and a vase with
two pink roses.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, meanwhile, was reading the Bible, Psalm 46. ``God
is our refuge and strength, a very present help in
</P>
<P>
   trouble . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The boys spent the afternoon with their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, she'll undergo a biopsy so doctors can determine how to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that she will eventually die of this disease _
timetable uncertain,'' said Dr. Eyal Meiri, one of her oncologists.
``The great thing here is that her family was able to see her.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
