<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD TO FACE GEORGIA IN FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Georgia's 'Dawgs will find out whether or not
they are barking up the wrong Trees in today's NCAA women's tennis
championship match.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford and Georgia advanced to the final with relatively easy
semifinal victories Saturday at Pepperdine. The Cardinal, which has
been ranked No.1 in the nation all season, beat Pacific-10 rival
Cal 5-0, and the No.2 Bulldogs beat SEC rival Florida 5-2. Stanford
and Georgia meet at 1 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud of the team, because we came out with a lot
of intensity,'' said Stanford's second singles player, Laura
Granville, who earned a 6-1, 6-3 victory over Amy Jensen. ``We know
we are the top seed and everybody is gunning for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's top-ranked singles player, Stanford's Marissa Irvin
(a Harvard-Westlake High graduate) struggled with her serve in the
first set but then blistered Anita Kurimay for a 6-7 (7-3), 6-1,
6-1 victory. Irvin double-faulted three times in the first-set
tiebreaker and had her serve broken to begin the second set, but
broke right back and took control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marissa has grown up a lot in the past couple years, and she
has a lot of poise and confidence,'' Stanford coach Frank Brennan
said.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 Lauren Kalvaria and No. 6 Keiko Tokuda earned two-set
victories, and No. 5 Jennifer Heiser won in three, but Brennan was
most impressed with Granville, who has lost just nine games in her
three matches this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably one of the best college tennis matches I've
seen,'' Brennan said. ``Granville probably hits the best passing
shots in college tennis, and Jensen is great with the serve and
volley. Granville, she's an assassin.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia had a little more difficult time than Stanford, as the
Bulldogs had to play doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia quickly fell behind when Whitney Laiho, ranked No. 8 in
the country, upset No. 5 Aarthi Venkatesan 6-0, 7-5. Georgia's
Esther Knox, Marissa Catlin, Lori Grey and Kelly Baskin each earned
singles victories.
</P>
<P>
   Florida forced the doubles play with a 7-5, 3-6, 6-2 victory by
Anne Nguyen over Julie Scaringe at No. 6 singles. Nguyen had
dropped the first two games of the third set.
</P>
<P>
   ``That win was important to us for two reasons,'' Florida coach
Andy Brandi said. ``First, because it kept us in the match
obviously, but also because I thought it would give us some
momentum going into the doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no such luck for the Gators. Georgia's top doubles
team of Catlin and Grey, ranked second in the nation, used four
service breaks to win 8-3. Georgia also led in the other two
doubles matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the doubles have been strong all year, so we were
pretty confident,'' Georgia coach Jeff Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   The draw for the singles tournament, which begins Monday, was
announced, with Irvin receiving the top seed, as expected. Texas'
Janet Walker was seeded second, followed by Adria Engel of Wake
Forest and Zuzana Lesenarova of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Sara Walker and Annica Cooper, USC's Veronika Safarova
and Jewel Peterson, and Ipek Senoglu of Pepperdine will compete in
the 64-player tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
