<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUICK CLASSIC NEXT MONTH LURES A TOP FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new date for this year's Buick Classic has helped the
tournament attract a solid field.
</P>
<P>
   This year's tournament will be held from June 8-11 at
Westchester Country Club in Harrison, N.Y., the week before the
United States Open at Pebble Beach. Although some players choose to
take a week off before a major, many players use the Buick Classic
as a tune-up. Five of the top 15 players in the current world
ranking have already committed to play the Buick Classic _ Davis
Love III, Ernie Els, Phil Mickelson, Tom Lehman and Sergio Garcia.
And Jim Furyk, ranked No. 12 in the world, said Tuesday that he
intends to play as well.
</P>
<P>
   A few international players will also stop in New York to play
the Buick on their way to Pebble Beach. Paul Lawrie, the reigning
British Open champion, is in the field, along with Jean Van de
Velde.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it is unlikely Tiger Woods will play, even though
Buick is one of his sponsors. The world's No. 1 player has a policy
of taking the week off before a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Tiger does something totally different from what he has
done in the past, we're not expecting him,'' said Peter Mele, the
Buick Classic tournament director. ``But we've been speaking with
many other players and we're hoping they'll commit soon.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of top players who played last year have yet to commit
themselves: David Duval, Vijay Singh, Fred Couples, Lee Janzen and
Justin Leonard. But all of them could still opt to play because the
commitment deadline is not until the Friday before the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Buick Classic, which was won by Duffy Waldorf, was
played the week after the United States Open and some players
elected to rest. But Furyk said that Westchester is an excellent
place to prepare for the year's second major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Westchester is one of the best layouts we see and it's one of
my favorite places to play,'' Furyk said. ``The biggest decision
about whether to play this year was having to travel across the
country for the Open the next week. But I think I'm going to go
ahead and play Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Westchester, you know the rough is going to be high and you
have to keep the ball in the fairway. That's similar to the Open.
It's not as demanding as the Open, where par is a good score, but
it's a challenging tournament that prepares you for what we'll see
the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   LOPEZ HAS GALLBLADDER SURGERY
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez underwent successful surgery last Tuesday to remove
her gallbladder. She is expected to be released from a Georgia
hospital later this week, and because the surgery requires a short
recovery period, Lopez is not expected to miss significant time
from this year's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A 43-year-old Ladies Professional Golf Association Hall of Fame
player, Lopez has 48 career victories, but she has not won since
1997. She is 78th on this year's money list, with $31,769 in five
starts. Last Sunday, she tied for 32nd at the Electrolux USA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The next women's major is the McDonald's LPGA Championship, June
22-25 in Wilmington, Del., and Lopez hopes to be at full strength
by then.
</P>
<P>
   PARNEVIK TO FACE WOODS AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   After holding off a late charge by Tiger Woods to win the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic last Sunday, Jesper Parnevik will compete
against Woods again beginning Thursday in Germany at the Deutsche
Bank _ SAP Open. Woods is the defending champion, headlining a
field that includes Colin Montgomerie, Lee Westwood, Michael
Campbell and Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik is playing the bulk of his schedule this year on the
PGA Tour. However, he will play four events on the European Tour,
hoping to finish in the top 12 on the European money list through
mid-August. That would earn him a spot in the NEC Invitational
(Aug. 24-27), a World Golf Championships event that has a $1
million first-place prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I rejoined the European Tour this year, because
that was my last resort to get into the NEC,'' Parnevik said. ``You
have to get into the World Golf Championships events, or else you
get too far behind on the U.S. money list.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik is third on the PGA Tour money list with more than
$2.13 million, trailing only Woods ($3.59 million) and Hal Sutton
($2.34 million). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
