<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      05-20 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS ADVANCE, BUT CELEBRATION CAN WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the Knicks and the Miami Heat prepared for Game 7
Saturday, the Indiana Pacers eagerly awaited the winner.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive year, the Pacers have reached the
Eastern Conference finals. They have confidence, they have
experience, and they will have home-court advantage against either
of their potential opponents. But the Pacers have a lot to prove to
themselves, and to whichever team they face.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have never reached the National Basketball
Association finals, and last year's conclusion was particularly
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Leading by two games to one in the Eastern conference finals
against the Knicks last year, the Pacers fell apart as the Knicks
won three consecutive games to reach the finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was a galling loss for the Pacers, who had allowed a
shorthanded Knicks team to take over the series without Patrick
Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the atmosphere in the Pacers' locker room Friday
night was subdued as the players left quietly like businessmen
leaving a board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers advanced Friday at Philadelphia by ousting the 76ers,
106-90, to win their playoff series, 4-2. But the 76ers quickly
became past history for the Pacers, because if the Pacers do not go
any further, they will consider this season a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to celebrate?'' said Reggie Miller, the Pacers'
shooting guard and a longtime Knicks nemesis, who led the Pacers
with 25 points. ``We've been here what, four, five times before? We
still have work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Miller to speak his mind. Asked Friday night which
team he would rather face next, he said: ``Personally, I'd rather
play the Knicks, because we could exorcise some demons there. But
we could also start a great new rivalry with the Heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Heat won Friday, an Indiana-Miami series would have
started Sunday. Now, the Pacers must wait until Tuesday to play,
and their players seemed unsure whether that would be to their
advantage or disadvantage. The Pacers will get a few days to rest,
but they could also lose their competitive rhythm. Coach Larry Bird
said he could usually sense how the Pacers will respond before a
game starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to play well tonight, because we had two
good days of practice going into the game,'' Bird said after
Friday's victory. ``I keep telling these guys that when we practice
well, it carries right over into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But it remained to be seen if the Pacers can finally make it to
the finals. The franchise is at a crossroad. Bird has said he will
not coach beyond this year. Miller is 34 years old. Rik Smits, the
starting center, is 33 and has a history of foot problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers believe their time is now. And if their core group
does not get it done this time, expect key changes in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are already a different team than last season.
Antonio Davis, a longtime forward, was traded to the Toronto
Raptors before the season, and Austin Croshere has assumed much of
Davis' playing time. But while Croshere is a better shooter than
Davis, the Pacers could miss Davis' rebounding and defense in the
next series, which is sure to be rugged, no matter which team they
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, not having Antonio is the major difference for us,
but a lot of guys have stepped up and played well without him this
year,'' said Jalen Rose, the Pacers' second-leading scorer, who had
21 points Friday. ``Antonio's not here, so we can't focus on that.
Hopefully, we can be a better team and go farther than we have.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Rose has stepped forward this season to become a
second reliable scoring option, the Pacers will be led by Miller,
who never gets tired of playoff pressure and who loves to drive
opposing fans crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought Friday when 76ers fans directed a
derogatory chant toward him, Miller smiled and said, ``I thought
they were saying, `Reggie rocks.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into a hostile environment, with 20,000 people who
have been all day drinking, making signs, cursing your name forward
and backward, and they're coming to taunt you? To me, that's the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The playoffs are when I'm at my best, when I can focus on one
opponent, rest my body between games, watch plenty of film on my
opponent, and come out ready,'' Miller said. ``I love being a part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Pacers want something more. ``I've done this before,''
Rose said of his reaction to reaching the conference finals. ``But
I want to win a championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
