<HEADLINE>
SLOW PACE OF MEDICAL INSURANCE PAYMENTS ANGERS DOCTORS, HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anger among doctors and hospitals toward slow-paying insurance
companies is boiling over across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The anger has politicized doctors' groups, inspired medical
associations to press for tougher laws, spurred regulators to levy
fines and, in Missouri, sparked talk of a class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers, who have lobbied hard against more regulations, find
themselves on the defensive. Spokesmen say health insurers are
unfairly accused by medical activists. They insist the industry is
paying claims faster as it embraces computers.
</P>
<P>
   For their part consumers are asked _ perhaps unjustly _ to take
sides in the fracas, as they seek to vent their own frustration
with a complex system that can seem out of control. It can take
months and even years for bills to get paid. And the consumer
suffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the doctor is angry at your insurer for making slow
payments ... the doctor may be less willing to see you and also may
ultimately drop your company,'' said Judy Waxman, deputy executive
director of Families USA, a consumer health-care advocacy group.
``And then you can't see that doctor at all.''
</P>
<P>
   State after state is confronting the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say a lot of regulators are interested in
upgrading their laws on prompt pay,'' said Kansas Insurance
Commissioner Kathleen Sebelius. ``Regulatory activity has
increased.''  &LR; brkhed:Legislative fight
</P>
<P>
   Most of the action lately has focused on tougher legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Gov. Bill Graves is expected to sign a ``prompt-pay law''
this week. Insurers would have to pay patient claims in 30 days or
face a 1 percent per month fine.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri a last-minute filibuster by two Republican
lawmakers, Sen. Larry Rohrbach of California and Sen. Walt Mueller
of St. Louis, effectively killed efforts to toughen prompt-pay
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Holloway, director of the Missouri Medical Society, said
slow payment began drawing more attention last year when existing
laws proved ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are seeing now is that a lot of anger just boiled
over,'' said Holloway. Doctors are discussing a class-action
lawsuit against the insurance industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical groups have been more successful in other states. More
than 30 states now have prompt-pay laws.
</P>
<P>
   Similar bills were introduced this year in Illinois, Hawaii,
Florida, North Carolina, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan,
Minnesota, Mississippi, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York,
Oklahoma, Rhode Island, Tennessee, Utah and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas the prompt-pay bill was sponsored by Sen. Karin
Brownlee, an Olathe Republican, and championed by Sebelius. It was
one of the few health insurance issues to get past a strong
insurance lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have figured out that they have to get involved, or
their practice of medicine won't be what it used to be,'' Brownlee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Slaughter, executive director of the Kansas Medical
Society, said the new law gave Kansas its first ``clear law on
timeliness of payment of health insurance claims.''
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri more than 260 physicians, most of them Republicans,
called state GOP officials and begged them to refrain from opposing
or filibustering the prompt-pay bill.
</P>
<P>
   The effort failed. While most state insurance plans agreed to a
compromise bill, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Missouri, the
largest health insurer in the state, fought the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opposed the legislation because we thought it was
unnecessary,'' said Catherine Edwards, executive director of the
Missouri Association of Health Plans. She said the existing state
law addressed the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Missouri bill passed, it would have allowed physicians
to sue insurers for late payments and assess a $50-a-day fine to
cover administrative costs incurred by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Randy McConnell, a spokesman for the Missouri Insurance
Department, said that Missouri laws now ``are not set up to provide
short-term relief for providers.''  &LR; brkhed:Administrative chaos
</P>
<P>
   The present reality is abominable, said Steve Buie, a Kansas
City physician. He said the failure to strengthen Missouri's
prompt-pay bill ``underscores the chaos in the existing system.''
</P>
<P>
   Impatient doctors are, however, finding increasing support from
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Missouri Insurance Commissioner Keith Wenzel fined
Group Health Plan of St. Louis $100,000 for paying claims late. The
insurer had been warned three years earlier to pay more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the problems have expanded, we're just now seeing the
first wave of enforcement across the country,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the toughest enforcement of this new wave has taken
place in Georgia and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Georgia Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine ordered
insurers to start submitting detailed reports, complete with dates
when claims were received and paid.
</P>
<P>
   He levied fines against such HMOs as Aetna U.S. Healthcare of
Georgia, United Healthcare of Georgia, Humana Employers Health Care
of Georgia and HMO Georgia, the health maintenance organization for
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found they weren't paying on time even when they said they
had received a clean claim.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this past March hospitals and doctors in the state
recorded one of their best months for collections. ``The only way
to get their (insurers) attention is to hit them in the
pocketbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Insurance Commissioner Steven Larsen recently entered
into consent agreements with four of that state's major health
plans amounting to more than $1.26 million.
</P>
<P>
   Three health plans _ Aetna U.S. Healthcare, FreeState and
UnitedHealthcare of the Mid-Atlantic _ were fined for failing to
properly oversee third-party service providers that paid medical
providers late. Kaiser Foundation health Plan was fined for use of
unapproved rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really surprised to find there was very little
oversight over these subcontractors,'' Larsen said. ``My sense was,
it was not so much part of an effort to purposely delay payment and
gain advantage of the flow of money. It was more a case of benign
neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   More actions are expected. More than 48 state and county medical
associations in the nation have surveyed members about insurance
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Carson, a spokesman for the Alabama Medical Association,
said his state survey showed the time it took to pay claims ranged
widely from 14 days to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association reported that health plans in
some markets were more than 120 days late in paying clean claims.
</P>
<P>
   The association said some payments were a year late and some
practices were owed more than $1 million by a single insurance
company.  &LR; brkhed:Insurers respond
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry spokesmen rebut these findings.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Stewart, a spokeswoman for the American Association of
Health Plans, said providers shared the blame. ``One of the things
we have found...is that a lot of the time we're not getting all of
the information we need to process the claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Coorsh, a spokesman for the Health Insurance Association
of America, said the AMA's information was simply wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming numbers of claims are processed within 14
days,'' he said. That would equal the average processing time for a
Medicare claim, the industry standard.
</P>
<P>
   Coorsh says consumers are being misguided by doctors, who are
using the prompt-pay issue as ammunition to fight insurers in their
larger battle over managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Some hospital officials are joining the fray, questioning
whether insurers are living up to their obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance companies are giving us more and more excuses for
either paying more slowly or paying us not at all,'' said Dennis
McClatchey, a spokesman for Health Midwest, the area's largest
hospital and health system.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it takes insurers an average of 75 days to pay
health claims owed to Health Midwest, but that the hospital system
is expected to pay its vendors and employees within 30 days.
``Obviously, there's a problem there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
