<SLUG> BC-WATER-BREAKS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRENCHLESS METHOD OF LAYING CABLE INCREASES, SO DO ACCIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON and ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The water-main break that temporarily cut off service to
thousands of Overland Park, Kan., and Leawood, Kan., residents last
week was the latest accident attributed to trenchless technology,
an increasingly popular method of laying underground lines.
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly was not the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer an Independence man was seriously burned while
working in a manhole in downtown Kansas City. Electrical equipment
ignited gas that had migrated from a line pierced months earlier by
a contractor laying underground cable.
</P>
<P>
   Similar accidents have killed at least two Missouri residents in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And such accidents are on the rise around the country, at least
partly as a result of the competition among telecommunications
companies to set up fiberoptic networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a tremendous horse race going on _ who can get fiber
to the house first?'' said Rich Maxwell, an industry expert who
works for a Lenexa contracting company that uses trenchless
technology. ``They are racing to put it in as fast as they can. You
have very rapid deployment, and you have 10 times the underground
construction you had even three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the race to be first to offer new communications services,
trenchless technology _ also known as directional drilling _ is
often used for the delicate work of stitching together the
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the amount of work being done, the industry is safe,
said Aubrey Holt, manager of marketing for Honeywell
International's sensor and guidance products unit in Austin, Texas.
But accidents occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately when they do happen, many people are affected,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trenchless technology is being cited in a growing number of
accidents, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   John Fry was working in a Kansas City manhole last summer when
he turned on his drill and was blasted by a flash of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went off like a bomb in the hole,'' said Fry, 26, of
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   The cause: gas from a line pierced months earlier by a
contractor's drill.
</P>
<P>
   Fry spent nine days in the University of Kansas Medical Center's
burn unit and almost three months out of work, but he survived.
</P>
<P>
   In February a gas worker was killed by an explosion that
occurred when a contractor laying telephone cable hit a gas line
near St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1996 a southeast Missouri woman died when a house
exploded. Laclede Gas Co. did not realize that it had installed its
gas line right through a clay-tile sewer line three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Directional drilling equipment bores a hole through the ground
for hundreds of feet, and then the line or the pipe is pulled back
through the hole. The method allows contractors to lay pipe without
digging a trench. Streets remain undisturbed, saving time and
money.
</P>
<P>
   Hazards, however, await as operators navigate through a maze of
underground pipelines, electrical cables, fiber optics, sewers and
water lines that crisscross one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real congestion may be underground, not at street level,''
said Leonard Krumm, director of field services for the city of
Minneapolis. ``There lies the danger of directional boring. You can
steer, but you can't see. You don't know what's ahead of you.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, there is no central location that shows
where all the utilities are situated. Each utility keeps track of
its own network.
</P>
<P>
   Damage to underground utilities is common.
</P>
<P>
   A need for more oversight of the public right of way is a hot
topic among cities and counties, thanks to passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The act opened the markets to competing phone companies,
spurring the rush to put fiberoptic networks into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Before the act, most cities had to deal with six utilities _
gas, electric, telephone, cable, sewer and water, said Krumm of
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of just one phone company, there are multiple
companies asking _ in some instances demanding _ to lay cable in
the public right of way.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, for example, 14 telecommunications companies
have placed cables in the public right of way. In Overland Park
eight companies have done so.
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis, which was among the first cities to feel the
effects of the telecommunications boom, has 22, and three more have
asked to enter the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes for a very congested underground,'' said Krumm,
considered a leading expert on right of way management.
</P>
<P>
   It also creates a need for city ordinances to address the
growing use of public right of way, said John MacMullen,
professional development manager for the American Public Works
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Managing the right of way does not mean driving the companies
away, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a municipality and city, this is something you want to have
happen,'' said Robert Albee, director of telecommunications
engineering at Vanasse Hangen Brustlin, in Watertown, Mass., and
former chief engineer for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to have them come in and do it in a managed way
and a responsible way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, for example, had so many companies asking for access to
the right of way to lay fiberoptic cable, the city forced them to
work together and place their cables at the same time in the same
trench.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because Boston's streets already are full of existing
utilities, the new telecommunications companies were forced to use
trenchless technology and bore holes up to 35 feet below the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   While some in government and the utility industry view more
regulation as the antidote, the trenchless technology industry is
working on its own cures.
</P>
<P>
   As an industry expert and manager of new project development at
A&AMP;L Underground in Lenexa, Maxwell works nationally to set training
standards for operators. The industry has a good track record,
given the amount of digging going on, he said, but operators need
to be better-trained.
</P>
<P>
   His company has developed a curriculum to train its employees
and sponsored a training program at Missouri Western State College
in St. Joseph in 1998 and earlier this year. Maxwell also supports
requiring operator certification to ensure proper training.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Society for Trenchless Technology is working
on a training curriculum for operators.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit educational group is also developing a ``best
practices'' manual to make digs safer, said John Hemphill,
assistant to the chairman of the society.
</P>
<P>
   And equipment manufacturers are responding to accidents.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago equipment manuals had little warning against
hitting power lines, said Ron Rosencrans, editor of the trade
publication Underground Focus. More recently, equipment
manufacturer Ditch Witch produced a CD-ROM that took operators
through a crowd of utility lines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some concerned about digging accidents want better government
oversight of companies that use the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government last year issued a report detailing the
best practices in the industry that prevent accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Missouri lawmakers were urged this year to strengthen
regulations, but neither legislature did. Kansas lawmakers did set
up a task force to study underground digging and make
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gas Energy wants cities to adopt ordinances to require
contractors to call gas companies before they dig using trenchless
technology, said Rob Hack, vice president of pricing and regulatory
affairs for Missouri Gas Energy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, none has.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies have a stake in better oversight,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telecommunications people are very interested in cities
doing a good job of managing public right of way also, because (the
companies) are the ones who are putting cable in ground,'' said
MacMullen. ``The better job the cities do, the better they are at
protecting what is there. It keeps their cable from being cut in
the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
