<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CORMIER-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCHING ORDERS CONFUSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will the real Rheal please stand up?
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said he raised his left arm as a
signal to the bullpen to summon lefty reliever Rheal Cormier
moments after Tim Wakefield was struck in the calf by a shot off
the bat of Detroit's Jose Macias.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, the man who had been throwing, righthander John
Wasdin, decided to go the extra mile _ or in this case the extra
300 or so feet, from the pen to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen coach John Cumberland had sent Wasdin out on his
seventh-inning rescue mission, but Williams motioned him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cumberland) said, `They're calling for you,' '' said Wasdin,
one of six Boston pitchers who helped lower the staff ERA Saturday
but didn't quite slam the door on the Tigers. ``So I said, `I'm
going.' All of a sudden I'm running in there, and oops . . . wrong
guy. I just ran out there before (Williams) actually made the call
which pitcher he wanted to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier retired Gregg Jefferies to end the inning, then Wasdin
faced two batters to start the eighth in the 2-1 Red Sox loss.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin said that while he's never been in a similar situation,
it wasn't the first time he's seen the wrong man enter and then
exit stage right.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I didn't get all the way to the mound like Flash (Tom
Gordon) did last year,'' Wasdin said, referring to a Gordon
appearance last season in which he was yanked off the mound before
throwing a pitch because he hadn't been activated. ``Well, at least
I got an extra sprint in today.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Brian Rose finished a five-batter stint in relief of
Tim Young _ who had replaced Wasdin _ the only pitchers left in the
Boston bullpen were Derek Lowe and Rich Garces, each of whom helped
shut down the Tigers Friday night, and Lowe was throwing in case
the offense put him in a save situation.
</P>
<P>
   By the time this one was over, Williams and Detroit manager Phil
Garner had used 11 pitchers, something that seemed improbable the
way starters Pete Schourek and Dave Mlicki battled to a 1-1 draw
through five innings.
</P>
<P>
   But after Schourek had reached 97 pitches on the cold afternoon,
it was time for Wakefield. The lights went on at Fenway just before
he took the mound to start the sixth, and then Juan Gonzalez lit up
Wakefield with a shot over the Green Monster that proved to be the
winning run.
</P>
<P>
   But Wakefield settled down, only to get plunked on the left calf
by Macias's infield hit. He took one warmup toss and said he could
have stayed in the game, but Williams decided to play it safe.
</P>
<P>
   That set in motion Williams's debut as a Boston traffic cop,
stopping Wasdin in his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised my left hand because with an injury you can bring in
any guy you want,'' said Williams. ``And because in a lot of cases,
nobody's warming up. I told the umpire, `Cormier,' so I guess it
tells me that Wasdin just wants to pitch. Nothing wrong with that.
He was just one hitter ahead of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier took about 20 warmup pitches after passing Wasdin on the
now two-lane highway to the pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously someone made a mistake,'' Cormier said with a
chuckle. ``So I just grabbed my glove and went out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, meanwhile, said even though he could have continued,
his calf ``cramped up on me pretty good. It's unfortunate. I got a
knuckler up to Gonzalez. I was hoping it was going foul, but it
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is feeling good, nevertheless, about his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitchers did their jobs,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Including one man, Wasdin, who couldn't wait to get to his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
