u s BC-BBA-TIGERS-STREAK-BOS     05-20 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TIGERS-STREAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS CHANGED STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the type of game that the Detroit Tigers have to win _
low-scoring, with good defense, and strong pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, who brought a three-game losing streak to Fenway
Park Saturday, don't exactly rip the ball, especially on the road.
As a team they have a .253 average.
</P>
<P>
   But they had just enough offense to muster a 2-1 victory over
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get hits when we've got guys on base, that's our
biggest problem,'' said Tigers manager Phil Garner, whose team had
nine hits. ``We've had a hard time getting anything to fall in for
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go, and you can't get ahead of
yourself, thinking you can pick up 15 games in one game. You can't
do that. It's tonight's game, tomorrow's game, or you get bogged
down.''
</P>
<P>
   A home run by Juan Gonzalez to lead off the sixth inning against
Red Sox reliever Tim Wakefield was the difference. It came on a
knuckleball, of course _ one that was high and right over the
middle of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think Wakefield would challenge Juan with a
fastball,'' said Garner, trying not to chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who had three homers in the Tigers' previous series,
in Cleveland, hit a blast right down the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit a knuckleball, the ball jumps,'' he said, with a
trace of a smile. ``I'm feeling more comfortable swinging the bat
lately. It's just that we need more guys on base. I'm trying the
best that I can to win games. We're trying very hard. Getting
runners on base is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Tigers' pitching was quite good, as well. Dave Mlicki
got his second win against five losses, going 5 1/3 innings and
allowing three hits. Four relievers followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mlicki did a good job, although he got a little nervous after
the fifth inning,'' Garner said. ``Our other pitchers did a fine
job. Mlicki's offspeed pitch is what helped him, getting ahead of
hitters and coming back when he had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki didn't exactly care for his changeup, usually one of his
strongest pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have real good stuff,'' he said, ``but I got by. I
threw to spots and changed speeds. I threw inside, but not to the
righties, however. I wanted to take the left-field wall out of it.
I'm used to pitching in small parks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
