<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-INDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHRE TRYING TO KEEP OPEN MIND ABOUT IRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Tony George sat in his posh suite in the new
Pagoda Tower at Indianapolis Motor Speedway Friday afternoon and
spoke about his stewardship of the Indy Racing League. He described
the all-oval, open-wheel series he founded in 1994 as a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the work that went unfinished at New Hampshire
International Speedway? Two years ago, track owner Bob Bahre opted
not to renew his three-year contract with the IRL after dwindling
attendance and infinitesimal television ratings led to estimated
losses of $700,000 per race.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike NASCAR, which found a perfect home at Loudon, N.H., for
two of its ever-popular Winston Cup races, the IRL didn't seem to
be a fit with NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to say and address all the things that
could've been done better from our standpoint and from the track's
standpoint,'' George said. ``It's so voluminous that I don't want
to get into it, specifically. But I think the fact that we were a
young series and it was very fluid for the first couple of years,
we didn't have a lot of knowledge of running a series, how to
structure ourselves, how to staff ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we probably depended too much on the promoters to sell
our product in their market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to provide better support and resources to the
promoters, to develop a better working relationship with the
promoters and probably a lack of those things caused New Hampshire
and others not to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   With the title sponsorship of Northern Light, an Internet
company based in Cambridge, Mass., George is hoping to expand the
IRL series to 12-13 races by reaching out to new markets, including
Chicagoland Speedway and Kansas Speedway. The new venues would help
offset the losses of dates in Atlanta, Charlotte, Dover, and Loudon
_ tracks with multiple NASCAR dates that no longer stage IRL races.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's just not us,'' Bahre said from his home in Maine. ``I
think we did as well with it as anyone else. Now, we lost money,
but I think those others lost a little more than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   When NHIS staged its inaugural IRL event in 1996, said Bahre, it
drew an estimated crowd of 40,000. By the end of the track's
three-year deal, attendance paled in comparision to that of the
NASCAR races, dropping to almost 12,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they both hurt each other,'' Bahre said, referring to
the split between the IRL and Championship Auto Racing Teams, which
also held races at NHIS, with varying degrees of success. ``When
they split, they harmed open-wheel racing. I like open-wheel
racing, but right now my No. 1 priority is stock car racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the IRL would ever return to Loudon, George said, ``I
don't think that, as sour a note as we parted company on, the door
was ever shut on a return at some point in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bahre, ``There's no hard feelings with us and the IRL. I
like Tony and think he's a gentleman and I respect the guy for what
he's done with his series.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the series proved to be viable enough, would he be
amenable to holding another IRL event?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, certainly _ if it's going to make money,'' Bahre said.
``We have a lot of fans who really love open-wheel racing, but we
just don't have enough to fill the stands. You can't continue to
lose money on this. It's no fault of Tony's, but it just didn't
make what we had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andretti speaks out
</P>
<P>
   Mario Andretti, a vocal opponent of the IRL, returned to the
Speedway last week as one of the four ``Legends of Indy'' honorees
along with Emerson Fittipaldi, Rick Mears, and Andy Granatelli.
Given his opposition to the IRL, Andretti was asked if it was
difficult for him to return to the Brickyard, where he won the Indy
500 in 1969. ``No, not at all,'' he said. ``I will always support
the Speedway. I don't want to see this race diminished in stature
at all. I mean, there's no interest whatsoever in that. My dispute
is with the IRL. I will not support the IRL because I think that's
what has disrupted open-wheel racing in America for us. I mean, we
are pulling in different directions and that doesn't make sense. We
should all be pulling in the same direction, so that's where my
problem is. But I will always support the Speedway.'' Like CART
owner Chip Ganassi, who is at Indy with his FedEx CART Championship
drivers Jimmy Vasser and Juan Montoya, Andretti tried to put
together a deal that would bring his son, Michael, 38, back to the
Speedway for the first time since 1995, but it fell through. ``I'd
love to be able to see Michael here, of course I do,'' Andretti
said. ``I mean, this is one of the things that to me are very
disappointing, that guys like him . . . Let's face it, he's not
getting any younger, but he does have the talent and the ability to
win this race, but he needs to be here and have the chance to try.
To be missing here since 1995 is a total travesty, not only for him
but for all the other talents that are in CART that would bring a
lot of excitement here . . . That's the travesty of it all, that
it's not happening. These poor guys are caught out because of
politics, things that they have no control over and, for whatever
reason, they're not here.'' Asked if he thought a reconciliation
between IRL and CART was possible, Andretti said, ``I don't know.
If I could sacrifice myself and be hung upside down somewhere and
be beaten to put this thing together, I would even do that. That's
how I feel about it. I don't know what else to do. Maybe we could
get a general consensus, get people writing in, and expressing
their wishes, and maybe that could change things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petty remains idle
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup driver Kyle Petty, still grieving over the death of
his 19-year-old son, Adam, will sit out the Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's
Speedway in Charlotte, N.C. Adam died May 12 during a practice run
for a Busch Series race at NHIS. Bahre said he had yet to speak
with Kyle or Richard Petty to express his condolences, but planned
to do so once things settled down. ``You don't want it to happen
anywhere _ and I don't want this to be taken the wrong way _ but
why did it have to happen here?'' said Bahre, who has been close
friends with Richard Petty since 1965. ``He was such a nice kid,
the nicest kid in the world. I met him a year ago at the Holiday
Inn in Concord where he was staying. I introduced myself and he
said, `Nice to meet you, Mr. Bahre,' and I was like, `Let's get one
thing straight, you can drop this `Mister' business. Just call me
Bob.' He just smiled that big Petty smile of his. He was such a
nice kid. It knocked everyone for a loop here and it makes you feel
bad for Richard, Kyle, and their wives and family.'' . . . Roberto
Guerrero was named driver of the No. 41 A.J Foyt/Kenny Brack
Motorsports entries. Because of his vast Speedway experience,
Guerrero was not required to undergo a refresher test, according to
Brian Barnhart, IRL director of racing operations . . . After
suffering serious spinal and neck injuries in a crash at Walt
Disney World Speedway in January 1997, Davy Jones will return to
IRL competition behind the wheel of the No. 40 Team Coulson Racing
car. Jones, however, was required to undergo a 10-lap refresher
course at 210 miles per hour before making a qualifying attempt . .
. Anthony Edwards, star of the hit NBC drama ``ER,'' will be the
celebrity pace car driver for the 84th Indianapolis 500 next
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
