<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-OILERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILER SPILLOVER WILL HAVE TRICKLE DOWN EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather than wait until June 28, when he would have been free to
shop for another job, the distinguished boss of the Edmonton Oilers
parted company with the franchise late Friday night, and is now
officially an executive designated for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Sather, 56, who broke into the NHL as a spare forward with
the Bruins at the start of the Bobby Orr era, soon will surface
either as the new boss of the New York Rangers or in the same
capacity _ and possibly part-owner _ with the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Adding further disruption to the Oilers, both head coach Kevin
Lowe and his top assistant, ex-Bruin Craig MacTavish, have escape
clauses in their contracts allowing them to bolt with Sather. Lowe,
if he elects to stay, possibly would be elevated to GM, with
MacTavish bumped up to head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Sather, a multimillionaire who was under contract with the
Oilers for two more years at $1.9 million per, has no real need to
work, other than to keep his competitive juices and cash flowing.
It became clear last week that he and Oiler ownership, only too
happy to move his salary off the books, no longer would be able to
coexist. Sather wanted the player payroll closer to the league
average. The owners were content to keep it, much like Boston, a
budget operation.
</P>
<P>
   But what does a vote of nonspending really say in Edmonton?
Isn't it tantamount to waving the white flag over northern Alberta?
Are they going to find someone else who will make more of that team
with less? The short, and only, answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is a sharp, capable guy, but every new GM needs a few years
of on-the-job training just to get comfortable in what can be, and
often is, a cutthroat game. Witness here in Boston, where Harry
Sinden has been bringing along Mike O'Connell for nearly six years.
</P>
<P>
   While payroll dwindled and, in turn, championships became a
forgotten fantasy in Edmonton, Sather became the club's second-most
valuable asset. Just as here in Boston, the fans' loyalty and
constant willingness to pay the ever-increasing freight is the
club's No. 1 asset.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Sather gone, the No. 1 asset is guaranteed to drop,
perhaps plummet. His departure, like those of Wayne Gretzky and
Mark Messier, Andy Moog and Grant Fuhr, Paul Coffey and Adam
Graves, is yet another raw reminder to the fan base that the days
ahead can best be described as numbered rather than better. Don't
be surprised if the Oilers are sold soon, perhaps in a matter of
months.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't it have been in the Oiler board's best interest to
sell while Sather was still part of the package? He would have had
the call there, too, able to walk away if he didn't like the party
that was buying his once-dominant franchise. Remember, it was
Sather who wrote the escape into the deals for Lowe and MacTavish.
He had to have the same deal himself. His walkaway right ostensibly
granted him the privilege to name where the club could be sold.
That, folks, is power. It also might be part of the reason
ownership was willing to cut him free, no strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   All of this presents a near-diabolical case of musical chairs in
the NHL, with Paul Allen as DJ.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours south of Edmonton, the Calgary Flames also are
readied for sale, although ownership last week presented a positive
spin to being some 4,000 season tickets short of staying. Imagine,
the Flames need to sell 40 percent more season tickets _ a total of
14,000, by June 30, less than six weeks away _ and they're charged
over the prospects. Huh? Their enthusiasm is admirable. But somehow
the numbers don't add up to the optimism. They'll put up the ``for
sale'' sign if the numbers aren't met by the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with the league's aid via intervention, the first
stage of the Coyotes sale was postponed last week. More investors
are needed. Current club owner Richard Burke said he'll wait for
his money. What's he going to say? Maybe there is no money. Gretzky
hasn't been able to decide whether he's a buyer, in part because he
didn't know whether Sather, his ex-boss from Oiler days, would be
in a position to join him in the desert deal. Sather now can go
wherever he wants, and the betting around Edmonton is that he would
prefer Phoenix to Manhattan because the former is closer to Palm
Springs, his home away from home when he's not stashed away in his
luxurious digs in Banff.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Allen, who for years has wanted to buy an established
NHL franchise and move it to Portland, Ore., waits to see what
becomes of these financial machinations.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Oiler owners simply opt to sell the whole show to
Allen? If Sather's gone, their asking price is lower today than it
was yesterday, but it's higher now than it will be with two or
three more years of losing attached to the bill of sale.
</P>
<P>
   If Sather ends up in New York, would the Coyotes and Flames both
offer themselves to Allen? The league would shed no tears over
seeing a small-market club like Calgary bolt for the States. For
that matter, losing Edmonton would be a matter of little angst in
Manhattan. But to see the Coyote franchise dissolve now, with fan
interest established and growing, would be the worst thing to
happen under the watch of commissioner Gary Bettman.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. Sather's decision will serve as the first domino
tipped in the serpentine connections between Edmonton, Calgary,
Phoenix, and Manhattan. He will move quickly now because his pal
Gretzky needs answers. Just as Burke needs answers. Just as the
Rangers need answers. And most important, just as the league needs
answers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A `trip' down memory lane
</P>
<P>
   Noel Picard, the St. Louis defenseman who provided the pitchfork
flip that sent Orr flying when the Bruins' legendary defenseman
scored the Cup-winning goal in 1970, lives these days in his native
Montreal. At 61, he still plays hockey on Monday nights and works,
he says, as a secret agent. ``I can't say too much about this,''
said Picard, when asked to provide details about his day job. When
Orr cashed in Derek Sanderson's return pass, Picard saw no harm in
sending the Boston icon into orbit. The season was finished. ``I've
talked to Bobby a couple of times since,'' said Picard. ``He's
always a gentleman _ a gentleman all the way. In my book, he's the
greatest hockey player who's ever been seen or heard. We played as
hard as we could and got beat by a great, great team.'' Picard's
daughter, Annie, attended the New England Conservatory of Music and
now teaches in Chicago. His son, Danny, has been in the US Air
Force for 12 years and is stationed near St. Louis . . . The annual
entry draft, held this year in Calgary, is just a month away. The
Bruins still don't know their spot in the first round _ it will be
finalized in a lottery held between Games 1 and 2 of the Cup finals
_ but don't be surprised if 18-year-old Boston University goalie
Rick DiPietro ends up at the top of the Boston wish list. The
Central Scouting Bureau hasn't updated its rankings since the May 1
opt-in date, but CSB director Frank Bonello says DiPietro will be
the No. 1-rated North American netminder. ``That's a no-brainer,
really,'' said Bonello. ``Everyone would have the kid No. 1. We've
seen some very good goaltenders come out in recent years,
especially in the Quebec League, but I don't know of anyone who has
had as much energy for the position as this kid. The way he handles
the puck is amazing. He'll fire it right past the defenseman, up to
his own forward at the other blue line.'' By Bonello's count, some
300 ``underage'' players joined DiPietro in opting into this year's
draft. Even though the May 1 cutoff date has come and gone, there
could be additions. ``For one thing,'' Bonello explained, ``if a
player is in the Memorial Cup, he has until seven days after his
last game to file his papers. Or in Europe, say a Russian player
signs his papers and the letter gets here three weeks later _ as
long as the postmark is April 29, he's in the draft. It happens.''
. . . Buffalo superstar-in-waiting Maxim Afinogenov returned from
the World Championships in Russia just before last weekend and
hooked up with Rochester, the Sabres' top farm club, for the AHL
finals . . . Save of the postseason: Flyer rookie netminder Brian
Boucher, on his back, flipping out his glove hand to block Patrik
Elias's shorthanded attempt in Game 3. ``Top five (saves) I've
seen,'' said teammate Rick Tocchet . . . Rumors around Long Island
have it that Mike Milbury's job as GM may not be safe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Superficial wounds
</P>
<P>
   Gee, here's a sensitive lead for you: ``It does not help matters
that Craig Ramsay looks like a cadaver.'' It was penned last week
by Toronto Star columnist Rosie DiManno. Amazing how, as an
industry _ in fact, as a culture _ we are so preoccupied by how
people look, rather than assessing their words and deeds. Ramsay's
Flyers sure looked lively, with a 2-1 lead over the Devils headed
into the weekend . . . New York Post hockey columnist Larry Brooks
figures Herb Brooks (no relation), who was behind the Yanks bench
for the Lake Placid miracle in '80, would be the perfect coach for
Team USA at the Salt Lake City Olympics in 2002. Makes a lot of
sense. And how about Mike Eruzione alongside as an assistant? ``It
would be an honor for me, and I'd do it in a heartbeat,'' said
Eruzione. ``But I don't believe I'd be considered. They'd want
someone who's behind an NHL bench day in, day out. Herb, though,
would be a brilliant choice. Clearly the guy can coach _ and he
showed that with Pittsburgh this year, just as he did with Team USA
in '80 and with the French team at the last Olympics.'' . . .
Chicago GM Mike Smith received permission from the Maple Leafs to
discuss the vacant Hawks head coaching job with Leafs assistant
Alpo Suhonen _ a hiring that could be made official Sunday. The
Leafs could have prevented that discussion from taking place until
July 1, when Suhonen's deal expires, but to his credit, Leafs GM
Pat Quinn granted permission . . . Unsettling news in Montreal,
where Canadiens legend Jean Beliveau, 68, learned during a routine
checkup that he has a malignant tumor on his neck. That was
followed a couple of days later by word that Rocket Richard again
was ailing. Perhaps no one in North American sport ever has
performed with Beliveau's grace and dignity, both on and off the
ice. Some six years ago, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien
asked Beliveau to be Canada's Governor General, but he turned down
the offer because a move to Ottawa would have taken him away from
his widowed daughter, Helene, and her two young daughters. In '89,
Helene's husband killed himself, and the Canadiens' great felt the
call to home was greater than the call to country. ``What I told
Mr. Chretien,'' Beliveau said at the time, ``was that to take my
wife and move to Ottawa would be deserting my family.'' Richard was
diagnosed with a rare form of stomach cancer more than two years
ago, and though he at first responded well to treatment, it
apparently is spreading. Of late, he also has been weakened by
drugs needed to combat a mild form of Parkinson's disease . . . The
Leafs are looking for a new head coach for their St. John's
(Newfoundland) farm club, and it could be Lou Crawford, whose only
cup of coffee (26 games) in the NHL came with the Bruins at the
start of the '90s. He is the brother of Marc Crawford, now behind
the Vancouver bench.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faceoff time for Yashin
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Yashin and the Senators sit down with arbitrator Larry
Holden in Toronto this week, with Yashin hoping to be declared a
Group 2 free agent. The Senators contend that he must still work
for them one more season, for the $3.6 million he thumbed his nose
at this past season. Holden must render his decision within 30
days, which could make for one heck of a lightning strike during
the amateur draft (June 23-24) . . . In South Philly, close to the
First Union Center, a sporting goods shop has cut the price of Eric
Lindros sweaters in half, to $59.99. And they're still not selling
. . . Wrentham's Garth Snow, who earned $1.4 million as a
sometimes-starter in Vancouver last season, likely will become an
unrestricted free agent July 1. He's expected back with the Canucks
only if he takes a deep discount in base pay . . . Roger Neilson,
back aiding the Flyers while recovering from cancer, has written
1,000 responses to those who sent him cards and letters during his
ordeal. Among those who have written: convicts serving time, and
even an atom squad from Lethbridge, Alberta. ``When you see the
letters from 10-year-old kids,'' Neilson told Toronto Sun columnist
Mike Ulmer, ``it's enough to make you bawl.'' Meanwhile, Neilson is
feeling better daily, his treatment and recovery guided by
well-known specialist Isadore Brodsky. Neilson: ``He said, `We
might as well tell you, you're in complete remission.' '' . . .
Former UMass defenseman Brad Norton, brother of San Jose blue liner
Jeff Norton, saw some time at forward late this season in the
Oilers' minor league system. He's got the size (6 feet 4 inches,
225 pounds) to be a power forward. The question is, does he have
the hands and speed? . . . Boston-based agent Neil Abbott said
Friday that he will be negotiating new deals for Bruins Group 2
free agents Sergei Samsonov and Kyle McLaren. Samsonov was
represented by Jay Grossman in the deal he signed as a rookie three
years ago. McLaren, who now has played five NHL seasons, had been
represented by Doug Messier . . . Ex-BU forward John Cullen won't
be back as an assistant in Tampa Bay this fall. He's opted to join
his uncle in the car business in Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
