<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TIGERS-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTDOWN DAY FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final score indicated the game had a true playoff feel, even
with Red Sox manager Jimy Williams and Detroit skipper Phil Garner
combining to use 11 pitchers, which suggested more of a football
score.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Boston on the short end of a 2-1 decision at Fenway
Park Saturday, and afterward all the managerial moves were
questioned, debated, and analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox missed chances, yes, but it was a baserunning blunder by
Brian Daubach in the fourth inning of a 1-1 game that grew more
important as the tight contest wore on. When it ended, and that one
run separated the teams, Daubach was distraught, and Trot Nixon,
the other player in the drama, grew a bit testy when questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the worst game I played in the big leagues,''
said Daubach. ``Obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had tied the score in the fourth and had the bases
loaded with one out when Carl Everett lifted a drive toward The
Wall, to the left of the scoreboard. Once the ball was hit, it
seemed certain that Nixon, on third, would score the go-ahead run
easily even if the ball were caught by Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   Williams thought ``the ball was caught in the wind,'' suggesting
that Daubach, on second, also might have thought the ball would fly
over Higginson's head. Williams also said he thought Daubach also
might have slipped between second and third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just a regular sacrifice fly,'' said
Higginson, also not expecting what was about to happen, ``and I was
just ready to throw the ball back into the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach said he thought the ball would be off The Wall, ``and I
was shuffling off the base,'' added the Red Sox first baseman, who
also was gunned down Friday night trying to go from first to third
on a single by Mike Stanley to left-center with two outs. And when
Higginson reached high against The Wall to catch Everett's drive,
Daubach thought he ``might have trapped the ball, and I kind of
hesitated for a second, and I was looking at the umpire to make the
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach was some 25-30 feet from second base when Higginson
caught the ball. And while it seemed Daubach slipped when he
attempted to return to second, ``I didn't stumble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson looked back to the infield and ``(Daubach) was
three-quarters of the way toward third. And when I looked over and
I saw him I thought I had a chance to get him if my throw was
accurate. It was bad baserunning more than a great play by me and
I'm sure he'll admit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon saw nothing of what was happening behind him. Higginson's
throw doubled Daubach off second an instant before Nixon's foot
touched the plate, and umpire John Hirschbeck immediately waved off
the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what had happened,'' said Nixon. ``It was just a
situation where (Daubach) was trying to be a little bit aggressive,
and it was unfortunate, but that didn't cause us to lose the game.
We had our opportunities to score runs. More of the blame should be
put on ourselves for not getting hits when we needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether Nixon trotted, ran, or dashed to the plate also
became an issue when that final ``2-1'' was posted on the
scoreboard. Daubach said there was no way for the usually
hard-charging Nixon to reach the plate in time if the throw from
left field was quick enough to register an out at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Trot was running hard,'' said Daubach. ``It's not his
fault. It's all my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I ran,'' said Nixon. ``I didn't lope home. I ran. It's
something to learn from, and I'm sure (Daubach) will learn a
lesson, but we're not going to hold it against him . . . I know I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Daubach conceded what players learn early in
their careers, that ``there was no reason for me to be that far off
second in that situation. And it cost us the game; we had just come
from behind and we had momentum and I took it away.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tim Wakefield replaced a struggling Pete Schourek (``I was
lucky, they hit a couple of long foul balls off me'') in the sixth,
the first batter he faced was Juan Gonzalez. Gonzalez promptly
launched a knuckler toward the ionosphere, the ball dropping onto
the roof of a building beyond Lansdowne Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit a knuckler flush,'' said Gonzalez, ``it jumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield (1-3) was another who took the loss personally, but
despite that knuckler to Gonzalez and Daubach's blunder, the Boston
batters all could accept blame. Five times the Sox had runners on
third and could not drive them in and the Sox were 1 for 8 with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   And it ended with the Sox' eighth one-run loss of their 14
defeats this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
