<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WOMENTENNIS-KIKIC     05-20 2338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WOMENTENNIS-KIKIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIKIC SERVES HER FAMILY WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN _ The setting is peaceful, almost serene. A warm,
late spring afternoon, with a light wind, bright sunshine and a
blue sky. On one section of the Torrence M. Hunt tennis complex at
Williams College, the men are practicing for their NCAA Division 3
tournament; on the other, the women are doing the same thing. On
the other side of a chain link fence, a lively intramural soccer
game is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this sits Selma Kikic, laughing and joking with
teammates. The 20-year-old sophomore seems at home, comfortable not
only with where she is, but with who she is.
</P>
<P>
   Her tennis career _ as part of the No. 1 doubles team and No. 3
singles _ is flourishing. She is among the favorites for the
national doubles title and won her singles and doubles match in
Williams's loss to Trinity (Texas) in the team competition on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Kikic about this sense of well-being, and she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them my `American moments,' '' she said. ``I feel
happy. I feel safe. I feel content. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing it is when you consider how Kikic got to where she is.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, there were no American moments in Selma Kikic's
life, nor in those of her family.
</P>
<P>
   Selma Kikic is Bosnian. She is also a Muslim, and in 1992, when
civil war tore apart the country formerly known as Yugoslavia, the
only moments Kikic and her family knew were filled with terror,
uncertainty, and upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swept away
</P>
<P>
   Little seemed unusual on May 3, 1992, in Doboj, a town of 35,000
in central Bosnia. At 12, Selma Kikic and her 10-year-old sister,
Sanida, were oblivious to the trouble brewing around them.
</P>
<P>
   The Kikics were simply living their lives. Selma's father,
Mensur, was an environmental engineer, and her mother, Almira, was
a pediatrician known for her willingness to help anyone, any time.
</P>
<P>
   While the parents were aware of the ethnic conflict in their
country, they felt secure in Doboj. Mensur had lived there his
entire life. Almira had grown up a few miles away in the hamlet of
Maglaj. The tension was growing, to be sure, but that was in
Sarajevo, a three-hour drive south _ a world away, in the mind of
Mensur.
</P>
<P>
   Almira, however, was worried. She heard things, saw some of the
wounded, and talked to colleagues. Her parents had told her what
war could do to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked about the refugees in World War II,'' she said.
``I never understood it when my mother said how families were torn
apart and brother and sister had to sometimes separate.''
</P>
<P>
   Almira felt the danger that was approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful,'' she said from her apartment in Dallas,
``because I was in the position to see things that were really
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of May 3, 1992, everyone in Doboj saw what was
happening as Serbian troops and tanks rolled into the city. At
first, it seemed ceremonial _ troops firing guns into the air and
people going about their business.
</P>
<P>
   But a far more serious message was being sent to Bosnia's
Muslims, who make up 44 percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
   Mensur was fired from his job; Almira was allowed to keep hers,
but people she had regarded as friends now avoided her in public;
bombs were going off in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Selma noticed that schoolmates started talking politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would come up and say, `How did your parents vote in the
election?' '' said Selma. `` `They voted for the Muslim candidate,
didn't they?' I said I had no idea. But all of a sudden my
so-called friends wouldn't talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When a woman whose child Almira had helped save a few years
earlier ignored her at a bus stop, Almira said something. The women
motioned her into a building, out of public view. ``I can't be seen
talking to you,'' said the woman. ``Your family is on the `death
list' and anyone seen talking to you will also be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   With bombs now going off without warning, and the children
hiding in the basement more than they played outside, Almira came
up with a plan. She feigned an illness and said she had to have
tests in Belgrade. While she was away, Mensur would take the girls
to Almira's parents' house in Maglaj, 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Mensur used forged travel papers to leave Doboj, and the girls
were told to pack whatever they could stuff in their backpacks,
nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, the Kikics left Doboj _ leaving behind their
apartment and money in the bank. Mensur took nothing but the
clothes he had on and some money in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``What money we had, we stuffed into socks,'' said Selma. ``I
didn't understand what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The odyssey lasted more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it was an adventure,'' said Selma. ``We were at my
grandparents, then we went somewhere else. But in September, my
mother told us we weren't going home. I just cried and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kikics finally wound up on Korcula, an island in the
Adriatic. Almira worked as a doctor, Mensur as a fisherman. For
recreation, Selma played tennis with Mensur, who had built the
first tennis court in Doboj. Selma's reputation as a junior player
started to spread and she was invited to try out for the 1996
Bosnian Olympic team, which required training in the town of Umag,
a 12-hour boat ride from Korcula.
</P>
<P>
   Almira knew Selma's opportunity there would be only temporary.
She wanted more of a future for her girls. The United States was
compiling a list of Bosnian refugees who might emigrate, and Almira
wanted her family to be included.
</P>
<P>
   The Kikics were among 11 families selected. It was Aug. 10,
1993. The family had been living as refugees in their own country
for 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   That was going to change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arrival in the States
</P>
<P>
   Dallas in August is unbearably hot. Thunderstorms are common,
but all they do is make you wet and hot. People cope either by
going on vacation to a cooler place or by going from
air-conditioned house, to air-conditioned car, to air-conditioned
office, to air-conditioned mall.
</P>
<P>
   But, Dallas is where the Immigration and Naturalization Service
decided to settle the Kikics that summer. Their trek had included a
ferry ride, a bus trip to Vienna, an eight-hour flight to New York,
then another four-hour flight to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Selma, the only member of the contingent with a
grasp of English, served as interpreter. The distance was tiring
enough, but the stress and uncertainty stayed with them until their
arrival around midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying, my sister was crying, and my parents were trying
to make some sense of where they were,'' said Selma.
</P>
<P>
   Their greeter, a Vietnamese refugee whose grasp of English was
limited, had been given instructions to deliver the Kikics to their
new home in Oak Cliff, one of Dallas's poorer neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The furnishings in their two-bedroom apartment consisted of two
mattresses and a refrigerator, which was empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents talked the whole night, wondering how they could
get back home,'' said Selma.
</P>
<P>
   The priority for Mensur and Almira was the well-being of their
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did, we did for them,'' Almira said. ``My personal
life didn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Education was essential, and the first stop for Selma and Sanida
was the TJ Rusk Intermediate School, a cauldron of discontent with
a student body consisting of some of the nation's poorest children,
many of them immigrants from Mexico and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited,'' said Selma. ``I wanted to make friends. I
wanted to go to school and learn things.''
</P>
<P>
   But her classmates had different ideas. Selma spoke little
English and no Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was different from the start,'' she said. ``It was so
obvious. I was one of four white kids. Nobody would listen. They
were always having fights with teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma would hear laughter and comments in a language she didn't
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would say things to me in Spanish; I would say things
back in Bosnian,'' said Selma.
</P>
<P>
   Almira, though a pediatrician, found work only as a nurse.
Mensur worked at various odd jobs _ at a factory, a grocery store,
a pizza restaurant, and a hotel. He found much-needed solace by
taking Selma and Sanida to play tennis on whatever public courts he
could find.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, tennis proved a salvation for the entire family.
Selma became known within the area's tennis community. Her story
spread, and when Dr. Amanullah Kahn, the oncologist Almira worked
for, heard of her prowess, he made some calls to the Hockaday
School, a prestigious preparatory school for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Another mentor, Craig Bell, who ran the junior program at the
University Club in Dallas, offered Selma a scholarship, which
opened more doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Kahn called and mentioned Selma,'' said Liza Lee, the
headmistress at Hockaday. ``It was an intriguing story. We don't
give athletic scholarships but are open to a wide variety of
backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockaday, in trendy North Dallas, was a world apart from Oak
Cliff and TJ Rusk, with 100 acres of woods, open fields, and
creeks. And with an endowment that tops $33 million, it is better
funded than many colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Both Selma, about to enter her high school freshman year, and
Sanida, heading to seventh grade, were given consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both did fabulously on our entrance exam,'' said Lee.
``Even language was not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockaday officials were willing to accept Selma but not Sanida
in midyear, but Almira did not want to separate her daughters, even
for a few months; so Selma and Sanida waited out the school year,
and in September 1994, both enrolled at Hockaday.
</P>
<P>
   After Selma's first day of classes, she returned home in tears _
to a much nicer apartment in North Dallas, where the family had
relocated _ but this time they were tears of joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is nice to me,'' Selma told her mother. ``They like
me. We have conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Both girls flourished, blossomed. By the time Selma was a
senior, college was a given. Almira and Mensur wanted her to stay
close to home, so Selma looked at Baylor, in Waco, 90 miles south,
and Louisiana State, a half-day car ride to the east in Baton
Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   But Becky Mallory, the Hockaday women's tennis coach, was a
graduate of Williams College and a former doubles partner of Julie
Greenwood, now the women's coach at Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I adored her from the get-go,'' said Mallory. ``I wanted her
for Williams from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma made a visit to Williamstown in April of her senior year,
and her decision wasn't difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took her about a minute to fit in,'' said Greenwood. ``I
picked her up at the airport, introduced her, and she fit in right
away. She came to our practice that afternoon, and I looked over
and she was wearing a pair of Williams shorts. That night she went
out dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking back
</P>
<P>
   Selma Kikic was finishing up her meal in the dining hall at
Williams. The chatter around her was about tennis, exams, and life
at school.
</P>
<P>
   She reflected on the past eight years with a sense of amazement,
and also regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents shielded me from so much,'' she said. ``I was so
confused. People were in denial over there. I think my father was
one of them. If my mother didn't shake him up, I don't know what
would have happened. My mother is one of the strongest women I have
ever been around. I admire her utterly and completely. I don't know
how she saw those things. But she came up with a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Almira's plan was to save her family. She has accepted her life
in America, but Mensur, who recently went back to Bosnia for a
five-week visit, wants to return.
</P>
<P>
   So do Selma and Sanida. But as visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a part of me,'' Selma said. ``Everything my country
stood for was gone right before my eyes. I will only go back to
visit, not to live. My friends have left. The country has changed
so much. I would love to go back and see my old home and see where
my (deceased) grandparents lived. I would like to walk into their
house the way I used to and tell them how much I love them. How
much I miss them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her Americanization, Selma insisted her core has not
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a Bosnian. I still have my Bosnian values,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real optimist. I fail to see evil in people. What
happened doesn't make sense. Why would people do things like that?
A lot of people over there lost a sense of who they were. I was
fortunate enough to have strong parents who wanted the best for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma's foundation was rebuilt at Hockaday and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming there (Hockaday) was so good for my self-esteem,'' she
said. ``I had a lot of mentors. I learned a lot of things. I felt
like I had rebuilt a trust in people. I lost it in Bosnia. I didn't
know if people were good anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister, who is finishing up her senior year at Hockaday and
probably will attend Bowdoin (she is on the waiting list at
Williams), feels the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measure of your life is what you can do for your parents
when they need you,'' said Sanida. ``They gave up so much for us.
They have done so much. I would love to see them happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Those true moments of happiness probably won't come for Almira
and Mensur in the United States. The talk is of returning to
Bosnia, but Almira said she still has some work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will choose to stay here,'' she said. ``I want to see my
daughters get married, have children, see them happy. People always
talk about the American dream. I never talked about that. I had a
wonderful life in my country. But the war changed that. Now I want
to see my daughters have a wonderful life.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma, who talks to her mother on the phone almost every night,
knows what Almira has done for her, for her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I have in life,'' said Selma, ``is because of what
my family has done for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
