<DOCNO> NYT20000520.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     05-20 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYLAND JUNIOR A DIAMOND CUTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYLAND _ There's a Citgo sign and a giant Coke bottle atop the
big green wall in left _ just like at the famous ballyard in
Boston. There's a parking problem on Opening Day, and to make it
even more Fenwayesque, there's a Big Dig nearby as the Carapezza
family adds a three-car garage to the end of their driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls, welcome to Pupque Park, a
Wiffle Ball replica of Fenway that Sunday will be the site of
dedication ceremonies featuring Bill Lee, Rich Gedman, national
anthem singer Scott Wahle, and author W.P. Kinsella, the man who
wrote, ``If you build it, he will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Carapezza built it, along with his brother Luke and pal
Ryan McCarthy. And people will come from all over. They will most
definitely come. For reasons they can't even fathom. Longing for
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella has gone the distance from Vancouver, British Columbia,
to Wayland, Mass., Lee just got back from Cuba and will arrive from
Vermont. Hundreds of friends, neighbors, and fans are expected for
Pupque's Opening Day event. There'll be a band, food, a blessing by
Rev. Corbett Walsh, a speech by Kinsella, batting practice for all
the kids, a silent auction with proceeds going to the Jimmy Fund,
and an outdoor, big-screen viewing of ``Field of Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad event considering that it was conceived and organized
by a 17-year-old Wayland High School junior with the vision, nerve,
and smarts of a Fortune 500 CEO. Kirk Carapezza is not yet old
enough to vote, but he's already built a ballpark, organized a
magamega-event with considerable star power, and galvanized his
school and community for a function conceived in the spirit of
charity and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't the Red Sox put a new park together this quickly?
</P>
<P>
   The ballyard is named after Kirk's french poodle, (pronounced
``Pup-key''), who died nine years ago. Kirk and Luke's first Wiffle
Ball field was in the family's backyard at 18 York Road and was
built with a lot of ski poles and trash bags. When backhoes arrived
for a new septic system, the park moved to the front lawn. Luke did
the initial layout, and with each passing month, new pieces were
added and the park got better.
</P>
<P>
   After reading ``Shoeless Joe'' and seeing ``Field of Dreams,''
Kirk wrote to Kinsella and invited the author to dedicate the field
in Wayland. It was not unlike farmer Ray Kinsella hunting down J.D.
Salinger. In the spirit of his own work, Kinsella wrote back and
explained that it was an expensive and time-consuming trip. He
suggested Kirk try to find a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me that a kid with this much enterprise deserves to
be rewarded, but I didn't think he'd come through,'' says the
author. ``He's a remarkable 17-year-old. When I was 17, I was
scared of adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Through McCarthy, a Boston College freshman, Kirk found a
sponsor in ChildrenFirst Inc. a Boston-based national child-care
company. ChildrenFirst is footing the bill for the author, and Kirk
has taken care of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful part of this is that it goes back to a kid
reading a book,'' says Rosemary Jordano, CEO and founder of
ChildrenFirst. ``It just takes a moment and in that moment a
child's life can be transformed. Kirk was moved to build this park
that is now bringing people together. It's a wonderful story of
taking your hopes and dreams and making them a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The park is a nifty Fenway facsimile with an 8-foot Green
Monster, Pesky's pole in right, and a gravel mound courtesy of the
Wayland Parks and Recreation Department. It's 70 feet down the line
in left, 75 feet to center, and 80 to right. There's a flagpole,
bleachers, and a small bench. Two trees serve as light towers and a
perimeter of pines shields the park from York Road neighbors.
According to Kirk, Pupque's longest homer was a 140-foot shot, but
he says, ``That was during the taped-bat era, which has been
outlawed.'' Today, only official yellow Wiffle Ball bats are used.
</P>
<P>
   The Wayland High School student government contributed a sound
system, chairs, stage, and funding. Local businessman Robert Weiler
is another benefactor. A neighbor donated wood for the monster and
some of the sponsor money will be used to rent a 100-square-foot
screen for ``Field of Dreams.'' Green Olive Catering will feed the
hungry masses.
</P>
<P>
   As the event grew, Kirk decided it needed a worthy cause. Kirk
loves the Red Sox; McCarthy and Carapezza are the original
center-field, red-shirt K-Men (they have a Web site and appear in a
commercial) and Kirk plans to work at Fenway this summer as a tour
guide. The Jimmy Fund is the official charity of the Red Sox and
Kirk has a letter from the Jimmy Fund stating that ``assistance . .
. to help make this event a success is highly appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the perfect charity,'' says Kirk. ``The field is for kids
and it's a great idea to help kids fight cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My business is children,'' says ChildrenFirst CEO Jordano. ``I
see thousands of kids. Most of them have a sense that the world's
about them. These boys, with every single thing they do, it's about
somebody else. They understand what it means to build community and
unite the people around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Carapezza is a dentist, and his wife, Nancy, is
president of the Massachusetts chapter of the League of Women
Voters. Kirk is the youngest of their four children, and they've
done nothing to discourage his dream. None of the neighbors have
complained about the Fenway replica in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that a kid this age has a sense of social
responsibility,'' says Leonard. ``He loves baseball with such a
passion and he found this outlet. He's brought a whole community
together. He has involved everybody in this passion of baseball and
it's a wonderful thing to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening Day ceremonies start at 3 p.m. on 18 York Road, just off
Route 126 near the Lincoln-Wayland border.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk built it. They will come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
