<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PLAYERCR     05-20 2717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PLAYERCRIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING UP THEIR ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, Peter Warrick, perhaps the most talented player
to be taken in this year's college draft, couldn't make it to the
Bengals' voluntary passing camp last week because he had some trash
to pick up in Florida _ but at least he was wearing the Bengals'
orange colors while he worked. He was working along a Florida
highway in a prison jumpsuit as part of a 30-day sentence for
theft.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Pro Bowl tight end Mark Chmura refused to go to
the White House with his Packer teammates after the Super Bowl
because he felt President Clinton was a lowlife and a liar in the
aftermath of his sexual liaison with a young White House intern.
Last week, Chmura was charged with sexually assaulting a
17-year-old babysitter after getting her drunk.
</P>
<P>
   This week in Atlanta, Pro Bowl linebacker Ray Lewis will stand
trial on two murder charges stemming from a late-night party on
Super Bowl Sunday in which he and two unsavory friends allegedly
got in a fight that ended with two men stabbed to death and Lewis
allegedly telling his limo driver to forget he saw anything.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in North Carolina, ex-Panthers wide receiver Rae
Carruth awaits trial on the drive-by murder-for-hire slaying of his
pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the NFL, which soon may be known as the National
Felony League if something isn't done.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Patriots vice president for player programs Don
Lowery was in San Diego last week, along with other league and club
officials, to discuss the growing problem of violence and
antisocial behavior among players. Although the NFL keeps saying
publicly that such incidents occur at a rate below the national
average, for the first time in league history two active players
are standing trial on murder charges, a situation that is nothing
short of outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of reasons for these problems, and one is the
heightened scrutiny the players are under,'' said Lowery. ``But we
can't deny that the star status of these athletes gives them a
delusional picture of what they can and cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question of the heightened violence involved in
some of these incidents. Just in the seven years I've been with the
Patriots, I've seen a change. Not in the number of incidents, but
the things they do are more flagrant, more egregious than before.
These guys live in a violent world, and too often they respond to
problems that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ideas discussed in San Diego was an effort to increase
background checks and assessments of players before they come into
the league to flag potential problem cases and offer them
counseling and other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an effort to lessen the potential of
susceptibility to violent acts with professional help,'' Lowery
said. ``We know we won't make progress on this without the support
of the players' union, and thus far we seem to have that. There are
privacy issues at stake, but we need some kind of programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To (Bill) Belichick's credit, he's already had me meet at
least a dozen times with the rookies and developmental players to
discuss security issues, issues of violence and anger and alcohol,
and what's expected of their behavior. That's about as much as you
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most proactive teams has been the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers. Head coach Tony Dungy is on a committee studying how to
cope with player behavior problems better, and his team has
developed a test it calls the Bucs Filter. It is a series of
questions, background checks, and individual interviews. A
character grade from A to F is given to the player. Although Dungy
has given players who fail to meet his standards a second chance
from time to time, he has basically brought a zero tolerance
approach to behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual owners meetings in March, Dungy talked at length
about how teams and the league might be able to improve the
situation, but in the end he did what coaches seldom do these days.
He put the onus on the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players make the decisions in their lives,'' Dungy said.
``It comes down to individual accountability. There are things that
can be done to help them from an educational standpoint, but in the
end they are responsible for the decisions they make and the
actions they take.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said with the arrival of Belichick, his own access to the
players has increased, and he already sees the benefit in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that came out of the meeting in San Diego was the
need for player-programs guys to spend more time with the
players,'' Lowery said. ``That's how you learn if they have
problems or issues. We can't control what they do 24 hours a day,
but there is a correlation between organizations with strict codes
of conduct and the behavior of their players off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that (even though) some of these players
are celebrities and earn millions, they are still kids who are
often alone in places far from home with no family near them. They
can tend to hang out with people who don't have their best interest
at heart. The typical hanger-on is the only type person who has the
same amount of free time as the players do on their hands, and if
you're not careful, that free time can lead to mayhem.''
</P>
<P>
   Before next season, a committee of owners, players, and league
officials will report back to commissioner Paul Tagliabue with
recommendations, although they are expected to be relatively minor.
What may not be minor is the upshot of the Lewis trial.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis is cleared of the double murder charge but found guilty
of acting in a peripheral role or obstructing justice, and he gets
no prison time, Tagliabue would have a rare opportunity. He could
slap Lewis with a stiff penalty _ banning him for the season or a
good portion of it and forfeiting his pay. If Lewis is convicted
and Tagliabue does anything less, it will be a signal from on high
that the games remain more important than reality.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The flip side
</P>
<P>
   For all the bad things you hear about player behavior, there's
more than a little good going on as well. Far more. Over the
weekend, Drew Bledsoe and Chris Slade appeared at a charity event
on Cape Cod for Best Buddies, an organization devoted to aiding
people with special needs. Last week in Miami, Dolphins head coach
Dave Wannstedt and 41 of his players participated in the team's
fourth Habitat for Humanity home-building effort. They contributed
not only money but also their time and effort to help build seven
new homes for families who could not afford them otherwise . . .
Bill Parcells reportedly is ready to enter cyberspace. Parcells is
negotiating with an Internet company to put his voice and video
online for those of you who missed it the last few years . . . Ever
since draft day, people have asked why on earth the Oakland Raiders
would select troubled Florida State kicker Sebastian Janikowski on
the first round. Only three other placekickers have ever been taken
on the first round, and none of them lasted more than five seasons
with the teams that drafted them. Such a move had not been made in
21 years, so why did the Raiders take the chance? In large part
because a year ago, Oakland's kickers converted only 63.9 percent
of their field goals and missed seven from inside 45 yards. Michael
Husted or Joe Nedney missed kicks in seven of the team's eight
losses, all of which were decided by 7 points or fewer. Things were
even worse the two previous years: Greg Davis was 29th in field
goal percentage in 1998, and Cole Ford was the league's worst at
59.1 percent in 1997. Janikowski, while admittedly kicking off a
tee, didn't miss a kick under 45 yards last season and overall
connected at a 77 percent rate. Then again, 23 Division 1-A kickers
and 20 NFL kickers were more accurate than that. Janikowski also
could be deported to Poland if he is convicted of trying to bribe a
police officer Jan. 23 after his roommate was arrested for
trespassing. But that is not considered a problem in the Raiders'
organization, where trouble is not seen as all that troubling . . .
Expect the Ravens to hire a possible replacement for Lewis after
June 1, when several solid veteran linebackers _ such as the
Packers' George Koonce _ are expected to be released. The Ravens'
fear is not that Lewis will be convicted on the murder charge but
that the league will punish him severely if he's convicted on a
lesser charge . . . Tennessee Titans president Jeff Diamond said he
is working diligently on a contract extension for head coach Jeff
Fisher. Fisher has said he wants a new deal by the end of the
team's final minicamp (June 15), or he will coach out the last year
of his $900,000-per-season deal and go on the open market knowing
the expansion Houston franchise will be eager to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dogged about sled
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the Super Bowl leads to a lot of things, including
the sudden acceptance of a long-held idea no one wanted to hear
about before. Titans defensive line coach Jim Washburn has for four
years been trying to peddle a blocking sled in which the coach
riding it can move any of three blocking pads forward, forcing the
lineman to react. Washburn couldn't get anyone to put it into
production until the Titans went to the Super Bowl in January. Now
he has it in production for $1,495 a pop through World Sporting
Goods of Loxley, Ala., with orders coming in from high schools and
colleges . . . Randy Mueller was shocked at many things he found in
New Orleans when he arrived from Seattle to take over as general
manager. Not the least of them was that the team had no pro player
scouting reports on file. No wonder they did so well in free agency
. . . Here's one of the things that makes Detroit Lions wide
receiver Herman Moore special. Coming off an injury-plagued season
in which he caught only 16 passes, the many-time Pro Bowl receiver
heard head coach Bobby Ross say he was now competing with Johnnie
Morton and Germane Crowell for a starting job despite the fact that
Moore has averaged 103.8 catches the last four years while Crowell
had only 81 and Morton 80 in their most productive seasons. Asked
what he thought about that, Moore replied simply, ``I don't think.
He has taken all the thinking out of it. There's no speculation or
second-guessing.'' He then met with Ross and was told the other
receivers deserved a chance to start. To that, Moore simply
responded, ``Just what is it I've done to be undeserving to be the
one to start?'' Other than get hurt, nothing, so when September
rolls around, expect to see a familiar face coming out of the
huddle on the first play of the new season. His name will be Herman
Moore . . . In a surprise move, the Cardinals brought back one of
the most controversial front office figures in the club's history,
rehiring George Boone as West Coast scout. Boone worked 23 years in
the personnel department, and among his first-round picks as player
personnel director were busts such as quarterback Steve
Pisarkiewicz, kicker Steve Little, wide receiver Clyde Duncan,
quarterback Kelly Stouffer, and running back Tony Jeffery . . .
Troubled Chargers quarterback Ryan Leaf said this week that after
spending two weeks rehabilitating his injured shoulder, he has
regained a good deal of mobility but remains unsure whether the
shoulder will hold up to the rigors of regular NFL use. He will
work with doctors at least three more weeks before he tries to
throw a football. Two weeks ago, Leaf was not optimistic about his
future because his shoulder wasn't responding to rehab.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Changing his stripes
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Buffalo Bills defensive back Steve Freeman is trying to make
a comeback in the NFL _ as an official. Freeman has worked 10 years
as an official, the last five in the Southeastern Conference. He
began working NFL Europe games last week . . . Although he remains
unhappy about being named the Jaguars' franchise player, defensive
end Tony Brackens ended his ``holdout'' and agreed to attend the
team's offseason workout program while agent Michael George tries
to negotiate a long-term deal. Brackens has been given a one-year
tender offer worth $4.2 million, the average of the top five
defensive linemen's salaries last year. He is demanding a long-term
contract worth twice that in annual salary, plus a $13 million
signing bonus . . . How's this for a tight fix? Jacksonville
offensive lineman Ben Coleman doesn't want to accept the minimum
contract offer given him, but the guy owns five ice cream stores in
Jacksonville and its suburbs that make more than the $440,000 he's
being offered to take a beating playing football. Among his
franchises is one at Alltel Stadium, home of the Jaguars . . . The
exodus from the Pittsburgh front office continued when chief
contract negotiator Dan Ferens quit after 19 years in the
organization to take a job with International Management Group.
Ferens has negotiated all the team's major contracts for the past
six years. All the major officials in the Steelers' player
personnel department have departed in the last two years, many
because of conflicts with head coach Bill Cowher . . . Two years
ago, Priest Holmes rushed for more than 1,000 yards for the Ravens.
Last year he came back from a serious injury to rush for 412 yards
in his last four games. This year, the Ravens drafted a running
back, Jamal Lewis, in the first round. Yet unlike so many players
today, Holmes has chosen to work and fight rather than moan and
complain. He attended the recent passing camp despite not being
under contract, signing an injury waiver while trying to decide
whether he will accept the team's $500,000 tender offer. Holmes
accepts that he will be a short-yardage and goal line runner behind
Lewis, saying, ``I may not get all the carries I may want, but when
I get my carries, I will shine.'' With that attitude, he probably
will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Receiver drops ball
</P>
<P>
   How's this for bad judgment? Bears wide receiver Bobby Engram
turned down a four-year, $10 million contract extension late last
season when he was on his way to both free agency and leading the
Bears with 88 receptions. But he got little interest during the
offseason and ended up re-signing with Chicago. What did he get? A
three-year, $5.85 million contract. Had he thought it out, Engram
would have seen that the draft was rich with receiving talent. He
also lugged those 88 catches only 947 yards, an average gain of
10.8 yards. In other words, he wasn't a game-breaker. Or a
bank-breaker, as he now understands . . . Sometimes it's best to
keep your mouth shut, as former Rams coach Dick Vermeil learned
last week. Speaking at a mailing industry convention in Atlantic
City, Vermeil told a story of how three of his players were busted
with prostitutes on nights before games and were threatened with
their wives being informed if they repeated the offense. Not
surprisingly, the story made headlines in St. Louis, and now
Vermeil is claiming he misquoted himself. ``It didn't happen with
this team,'' he told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch. In other words,
Vermeil claims the incidents occurred on the lousy Rams teams he
coached before this one . . . Vermeil turned down a chance to
return to his old college analyst job with ABC, and instead will be
named chairman of a $200 million venture capital fund run by
Safeguard Scientific Corp in Devon, Pa. The fund will help
minorities and women in high-tech industries. He will be working
with his son and former Eagle Reggie Wilkes . . . If you think your
budget is tight, try being the Panthers. They have been struggling
to get under the $62 million cap, but when it increases next season
by an estimated $5 million, they will really be suffering because
three of their players _ Sean Gilbert, Eric Davis, and Doug Evans _
will account for $21.442 million worth of cap space. Gilbert, who
hasn't been a bust but hasn't been worth the money he was paid to
come there, will carry a cap number of $9.75 million, one of the
largest in football. That's an increase of $6 million for him
alone. Carolina has twice restructured his deal and surely will try
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
