<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-REDBULLET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED BULLET BOLTS PAST PEGASUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ As it turns out, Fusaichi Pegasus is a bigger myth
than his namesake. The horse who was supposed to be the second
coming of Secretariat was nothing more than a runner-up Saturday as
Red Bullet blasted the field in the 125th running of the Preakness
at Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet beat Fusaichi Pegasus badly, drawing away to tally by
3 3/4 lengths before 98,304 spectators. Fusaichi Pegasus held on
for the place, edging Impeachment by a head, but he struggled over
a wet track, officially labeled ``good,'' and did not resemble the
horse who dominated the Kentucky Derby May 6. His legend lasted two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My horse showed what he's made of, he really exploded,'' said
Red Bullet's jockey, Jerry Bailey. ``He was the better horse today.
We've seen other horses come off the Derby and look unbeatable,
then lose the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fusaichi Pegasus is a good horse, but to win two or three
Triple Crown races is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3-10, Fusaichi Pegasus, who was ridden by Kent Desormeaux,
equalled Riva Ridge (1972) for the dubious distinction of being the
lowest-priced Preakness loser. Red Bullet was the second choice at
6-1 ($14.40 to win), but the way he covered the course, perhaps the
odds should have been reversed. The time of 1:56 for the mile and
three-16ths was pedestrian, but that could be attributed to the off
track.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet went along in seventh place early, ahead of only late
closer Impeachment, then rallied turning for home. Fusaichi Pegasus
had been running in front of Red Bullet but simply could not match
strides when the real running began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't handle the track,'' said Neil Drysdale, who trains
Fusaichi Pegasus. ``That's the way I saw it, that's the way Kent
saw it. It was a greasy kind of track, and he just couldn't go with
it. He was squeezed a bit (by Hal's Hope at the start), but I don't
think that hurt his chances at all. I'm disappointed for the horse.
I like to see him do well, giving everything he can. Remember, I've
been doing this all my life. This is not the first odds-on horse of
mine who has lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The track was a little greasy today,'' said Desormeaux. ``It
might have made a difference. Jerry and I pushed the button at the
same time, but Red Bullet had a bigger button. He just ran wild.
Today was their day.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet, a son of Unbridled, who won the 1990 Kentucky Derby
but lost the Preakness to Summer Squall, is owned by Frank Stronach
and trained by Joe Orseno. Last Saturday, Stronach, who owns seven
racetracks, including Bay Meadows, which he bought last week, and
Orseno combined to win the $750,000 Preakness Special with Golden
Missile, who was ridden by Desormeaux. It was the second Preakness
victory for Bailey (Hansel in 1991) and the first for Stronach and
Orseno, with Orseno winning on his first try.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus had beaten Red Bullet by better than 4 lengths
in the Wood Memorial April 15, but Red Bullet had been held out of
the Derby, thus avoiding the rigors of a 19-horse battle. He became
the first to win the Preakness without running in the Derby since
Deputed Testamony in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believed all week,'' said Orseno. ``I heard all that
about running for second place, but I never believed it. Fusaichi
Pegasus is a good horse, but I have a good horse, too. I just
wanted him to get a good trip and get the chance to show it. Jerry
did a great job on him, and the horse came through. This is truly a
gifted horse. It was up to me to make sure he was fit enough to get
to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in having the 3-year-old champion, not a
one-race wonder. We all had to run over the same track. I wanted it
to be a nice day and a fast track because I knew my horse was going
to run a big race and I didn't want everybody else to have
excuses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
