</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-HEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT'S HOTTES HAND IS COACH'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm still sticking with my
prediction of Knicks in six.
</P>
<P>
   When the Miami-New York series started, I looked at the players,
the schedule, the history and figured the Knicks just had too much.
They still might do it in Miami. But if they don't, it will be yet
another notch in the many-holed belt of Miami coach Pat Riley. We
can just hear Britney Spears: ``Oops, he's done it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Doc Rivers won NBA Coach of the Year and Phil Jackson was the
runner-up. But year in and year out, no one is better than Miami's
el jefe, who may have submitted one of his greatest coaching
efforts in taking this broken-down, offensively-challenged team so
far. I mean, they look positively primitive. They were within a
suspect foul call and a Houstonesque bounce of eliminating the
Knicks Friday night. They may have lost the game, but they made it
close playing the only way they know how to play: with dental
efficiency. They are not fun to watch (except for coaches). They
are not entertaining. But they are surviving.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Riles,'' said former Warriors and Trail Blazers coach
P.J. Carlesimo. ``I just think he's a brilliant, brilliant coach.
He's won with different teams. He has won with different styles. I
suppose he does get credit every now and then (as in Coach of the
Year awards with three different teams) but at times I think people
tend to take what he does for granted. They don't realize what a
great coach he is.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost painful to watch Miami, and yet the Heat are still
around. No one can shoot; was that Jamal Mashburn out there Friday
or some impersonator? Their point guard can't walk. His backup is a
rookie, albeit one who sometimes doesn't play like one. Their
shooting guard is an over-the-hill bomber who has transformed
himself into a defensive demon under Riley. Who ever thought, after
watching Dan Majerle all those years, that he'd be valued for his
defense?
</P>
<P>
   Riley's resume, is, of course, significant. He's never coached a
team that didn't make the playoffs, a claim few can make. Critics
point to his overbearing coaching and cite the Heat's early playoff
exits as proof. Never mind that last year, Miami could have done
what New York did had Allan Houston's shot not bounced in.
</P>
<P>
   Or, had the referees given Miami, instead of the Knicks,
possession after a tough-to-call out-of-bounds play just before
Houston's shot . . . Or that the year before, if Alonzo Mourning
had kept his temper . . . Or if Michael Jordan had stayed retired .
. .
</P>
<P>
   If Riley's teams were, indeed, beaten up, how could they
continue to play the dominating defense they play? That takes
effort. They don't lose their poise. They don't lose their focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with him in Miami,'' said Celtics GM Chris Wallace,
``he was able to install a tremendous focus in everybody, from the
scouts, to the coaches, to the players. He's able to keep the whole
organization focused. You can say that that's easy now, because
it's the playoffs. But he does it the whole season no matter who
you play, and the result in that is all those division
championships and the home-court advantage. That's what you play
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he's gotten imperious over the years, to the point where
you wonder whether he even knows who Britney Spears is, or if he's
ever seen ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' or, for that matter,
``Malcolm in the Middle.'' (His kids might like it.) But he's shown
that, in his chosen craft, he is still the master. He doesn't have
enough now for another ring, but he is extracting every last ounce
of basketball from his team.
</P>
<P>
   It may not make for great watching. But it does make for great
coaching. He's got one more chance to put away the Knicks. If it
doesn't happen, it won't be so much that Riley, the coach, didn't
get it done. He hasn't had enough since the series started, but he
has squeezed his players almost dry. He can only hope they have
something left for Sunday's winner-take-all showdown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jazz not dead yet
</P>
<P>
   There will be no farewells here for the Utah Jazz. Not yet. As
long as they still have Karl Malone and John Stockton, both of whom
are under contract for next season, they will be a factor. They won
their division this year when no one thought they would. We've
spent the last few years planning the Jazz's funeral, yet everyone
is still very much alive and breathing. Having said that, it's
going to be hard to stay on top in the cutthroat Western Conference
. . . Speaking of the Jazz, Bryon Russell had connected on 23 of 26
free throws in Utah's first eight playoff games before going 8 of
15 in the last two. Of course, he boinged two big ones at the end
of Game 5 with Utah trailing by a point. Both were short. And what
gives with Greg Ostertag? Is he that bad? He never even got into
the last two games of the Portland series. If he didn't have such a
ridiculous contract, he'd be prime for Rick Pitino to pluck. Then
again . . . Seattle GM Wally Walker and Vin Baker met last week,
and you can be sure a lot of things were on the table. Baker has
had back-to-back nightmare seasons in Seattle and is likely
unmovable because of his huge deal. He needs to lose some serious
weight and get back into his Milwaukee playing shape. And there's
no reason why he can't, especially with this summer's Olympic
schedule . . . Just wondering, but after watching Suns-Lakers, it
seems to me that Luc Longley is the Western Conference equivalent
of Pervis Ellison. Unless, of course, he's the Western Conference
equivalent of Chris Dudley. I keep waiting for Garry Trudeau to
find a spot for fellow Yalie Dudley in ``Doonesbury.'' . . .
Interesting comment from Tim Hardaway on Pitino. Hardaway was asked
by the Washington Post's Michael Wilbon for his thoughts on college
coaches making it in the NBA. Hardaway said, ``You can holler and
yell and get up into a college player's face and challenge him. NBA
players take offense at that. You have to change your demeanor and
some college guys can't. The methods you have to use to get pros
ready are different. We all know Pitino can coach, but his demeanor
hasn't changed at all from what I see. When I'm on the court, I
hear him say things I would take offense at.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Challenge ahead
</P>
<P>
   Jordan may be disinclined to break the bank to hire Mike Jarvis,
but the deal seems destined to get done because both sides want it
to happen. It's like agreeing on the price of your house when it's
up for sale. Jarvis's big challenge, of course, is not extracting
the necessary number of Benjamins from the Wizards, but trying to
do something with their personnel once he gets the dough. ``That is
a very, very challenging situation,'' said Carlesimo. ``I think the
timing is good for Mike. But it's not an easy situation.'' Jarvis
will have to work with the oft-challenging Rod Strickland, who has
alternately infuriated and bewildered coaches from coast to coast.
You can count Carlesimo as one of them; the two had what can
diplomatically be described as a coexistence in Portland. ``Rod and
I had our moments,'' Carlesimo said. ``I'm certain I'm not his
favorite coach. But we won games and we got into the playoffs. Rod
is an incredibly gifted player and I think Mike knows how to get
the most out of people. In fact, I'd be surprised if Mike and Rod
did not get along.'' . . . Knicks assistant Brendan Malone on the
job taken by his former boss, Chuck Daly, as an adviser and
consultant to the new regime in Vancouver: ``He will be the voice
of reason and experience in that organization. He gives some
respectability to that franchise.'' . . . Some 55 individuals
declared early for the NBA draft, including lottery locks such as
Chris Mihm, Stromile Swift, and Marcus Fizer. Those three could go
in the top five, as could high schooler Darius Miles, who decided
the NBA was more up his alley than the Big East. The top foreigner
is likely to be 7-foot-2-inch center Iakovos Tsakalidis of AEK
Athens. Celtics GM Wallace made goo-goo eyes at Tsakalidis in a
recent swing through Europe, but he's also very interested in
Zeljko Rebraca, another big (and better) center in Europe whose
rights are owned by the Raptors. The only other high school player
to enter is DeShawn Stevenson, a 6-5 guard from California. The
biggest loser: UCLA. Three Bruins declared early, although center
Dan Gadzuric was not one of them. They were JaRon Rush, Jerome
Moiso, and Jason Kapono. Some other schools had two entrants, among
them Cincinnati and DePaul. Early entrants can withdraw their names
up to a week before the draft. Last year, 39 players declared early
and 12 withdrew. Players also can retain their eligibility by not
signing with an agent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swap talk in Orlando
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the Orlando Magic trade two of their three
picks in the lottery before the draft. The last thing they want on
their salary cap is three rookie salaries, which would come to
roughly $4.7 million. The Magic have much bigger decisions to make
on the players they already have. And a quick look at their
payroll, along with the burdensome NBA rules, tells you that both
Ron Mercer and Chauncey Billups should start looking around. Both
players are locks to be renounced unless Orlando strikes out on
every possible free agent _ an unlikely scenario given the money
they have to spend. Here's the rub. The Magic already are committed
to spending nearly $13.4 million next season, or about $22 million
under what is presumed to be the salary cap for the 2000-01 season.
Throw in the No. 3 pick in the draft at $2.36 million and you're at
$15.7 million. That's still about $20 million under the $35.5
million cap. But here's where the trouble lies. The Magic, like all
teams, will be assessed cap figures for all their free agents, even
though they may have no intention of keeping them. And, in the
cases of Mercer and Billups, those figures point to renouncement.
Billups will go on the Orlando cap for about $9 million and Mercer
will go on for $6.9 million. Bye-bye. The Magic will have enough
trouble convincing players like John Amaechi and Chucky Atkins to
settle for the veteran minimum (around $500,000 for both lads) and
then seeing whether they can re-sign Bo Outlaw for less than his
cap figure of $4 million and Ben Wallace for less than his cap
figure of $1.8 million. If they can do that, then they'll have the
players already under contract (Darrell Armstrong, Mike Doleac,
Derek Strong, Pat Garrity, Matt Harpring, Corey Maggette) along
with Amaechi, Atkins, Wallace, Outlaw and, perhaps, Monty Williams.
Assuming they get the guys signed reasonably (Outlaw for, say, $3
million and Wallace for, say, $1.5 million) then that would leave
them with . . . less than $14 million. And that would mean
convincing their own free agents to take (relatively) short money
now while also jettisoning Mercer and Billups and the other two
draft picks. Now, $14 million would be enough to get one big guy
and a second not-so-big guy. They could also use some of that, if
they desired, to re-sign Mercer. (You can renounce a free agent and
re-sign him with the money you have left under the cap.) But the
bottom line is there seems to be no way they can get $18 million
under unless they do all of the above and can also deal some of
their kids and get nothing in return. If he can do that, Magic GM
John Gabriel should retire the Executive of the Year trophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
