<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FANS, IT'S SEVENTH HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Game 7s. Remember them?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell's career was defined by them. He played in 10 of
these babies, and his team won them all, usually because Russell
was the best player on the floor. Throw in a victory in a
best-of-five fifth game and the greatest winner of all time was
11-0 in NBA elimination games.
</P>
<P>
   Game 7s are why you spend extra hours in the gym working on your
shot. Game 7s are why you spend the lonely hours in the weight
room. Game 7s are why you pore over that videotape, as Count Basie
would say, ``One more time,'' and then one more time after that.
Game 7s are what make an athlete's or coach's life a whole lot more
exciting than yours or mine.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Game 7s affect more people than the competitors. If
you happen to be a Knick or Heat fan, you wish they were playing
now, not at 3:30. In all of American professional sport, there is
no greater fan rush than the anticipation of a Game 7. Football
doesn't have it. Football is always a one-shot deal. There is no
such thing as a football series, and this is football's loss.
Baseball, hockey, and basketball provide us with the thrill and
analysis of a series. These confrontations are little novels. There
are many story lines. Football, at best, is a short story. Sorry,
pigskin fanciers, but this happens to be the undeniable, and
unalterable, truth.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the New York Knicks and the Miami Heat, Sunday
afternoon's seventh game, while predictable, is almost unbearable,
particularly for Miami. There is a great deal of deja vu attached
to this game, given that the teams will be meeting in an
elimination game for the fourth consecutive season. Miami won a
Game 7 in 1997. New York won a Game 5 two years ago, and again last
year. (Recall Allan Houston's buzzer-beating kiss off the glass.)
And now they will meet in an elimination game once again. New York
made this happen by erasing an 18-point deficit to win by the
classic New York-Miami score of 72-70 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches Pat Riley and Jeff Van Gundy have done the requisite
tape viewing, but even they concede it's strictly pro forma, and
not meant to be productive. After four years and 23 playoff games
(not to mention the regular-season contests), what new lessons
could possibly be learned? The Heat know what Patrick Ewing likes
to do. The Knicks likewise know Alonzo Mourning's every athletic
idiosyncracy. ``It's not about changes,'' confirms Riley, whose
reputation might take at least a little hit if his team loses a
third straight deciding game to the Knicks on Miami's own floor.
``It's about both teams after six games bringing their best
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Unschooled observers might assume that the Heat will be somehow
demoralized after squandering the big lead in the big game. Uh-uh.
It doesn't work that way. They're coming home, and it's not even
the same building in which they lost those deciding games in '98
and '99. It's a new building, and it has no bad Heat history. They
will look at Friday night's game in a technical manner and get
themselves ready to play in their new house, and no one knows this
better than Van Gundy, a certified pragmatist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no momentum from game to game,'' he maintains.
``There's momentum within a game. We are going to have to be ready
to play very well right from the start, and sustain it throughout
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He needn't add that history favors the home team in Game 7s, and
not by just a little. Expect to hear one of the NBC gang say, ``You
play all season to have Game 7 at home,'' one or two times Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing you might hear Sunday is that when New York and
Miami play, every possession matters. Someone will add that the
difference in the game will be a possession here or there, and that
things like a stray offensive rebound, a bad turnover or a hustle
play might decide the game. Well, maybe, maybe not. It helps to
make a shot every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a Game 7 is a masterpiece. Witness Boston-Atlanta
1988. Sometimes it's an artistic dud. But they are always
emotional, and you seldom hear a losing coach accuse his team of
being, you know, ``flat,'' in a Game 7. The key is to find the
proper emotional pitch, wherein you are juiced up, but still
rational. In other words, the trick is for enough players on each
side to emulate Bill Russell. If that happens, you get a great
game.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any Bill Russells in this game, but there are a
lot of pretty good players who have big hearts. The Knicks and Heat
are caught up in the tide of basketball history. No foes have ever
met four consecutive years in an elimination game. That's why they
should all feel privileged to be playing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But even if this were the Clippers and Nuggets, it would be
special. It is, after all, a Game 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
