<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-ALSORANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF LUCK FOR ALSO-RANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to the annual NBA Lottery or, as it's come to be known
around the league, ``My Lunch With Elgin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Clippers once again enter Sunday's drawing with
the most chances to get the first-round pick, not that it matters.
They had the same chances last year and ended up with the fourth
pick. This is an annual rite of spring for the Clippers and their
general manager, Elgin Baylor; his team has missed only three of
the lotteries since the system was instituted in 1985, although it
hasn't always had its own pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are trying a new approach. For the first time, they
are sending a player to represent them. Maybe it will change their
fortunes. Kenny Anderson, a New York playground legend, will cross
the river to Secaucus, N.J., to be the Celtics' representative. The
team has virtually no chance of moving off its 11th spot, which may
explain why coach Rick Pitino and GM Chris Wallace plan to be
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no luck in my two trips there, so we thought it would be
good for a change,'' Wallace said. ``There's some numerology here,
which may help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Well Anderson does wear No. 7 and this will be the Celtics'
seventh visit to the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Each team is assigned a number of four-digit combinations, with
the Clippers getting the most combinations (250) and the Magic
getting the fewest (five). However, it's rare that the team with
the worst record actually gets the first pick. Only New Jersey
(1990) and the Clippers (1988) have done so since the lottery was
weighted to give the worst team the best chance. (Philadelphia
selected Allen Iverson in 1996; it had the second-worst record, but
Vancouver, which had the worst, was not eligible for the No. 1
pick.)
</P>
<P>
   The lottery determines only the first three positions; after
that, the drafting order is set up by record, worst to best.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics will have nine chances in 1,000 to get the first
pick. Their chances increase slightly for the second pick (1.07
percent) and third pick (1.30 percent). Last year, Charlotte went
into the lottery with the fewest Ping-Pong combinations and still
came away with the third overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   The big drama, however, will focus on the Bulls and the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Michael Jordan is not expected to represent his
new team, which would have meant sitting on the same stage with
nemesis Jerry Krause, the Bulls' general manager. Moreover, the
Wizards must surrender their pick to Chicago unless it falls in the
top three (an 8.26 percent chance).
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's own pick should be in the top three. Thus, the Bulls
could walk away with two of the top six picks in addition to having
serious cap room to pursue free agents this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just keeping my fingers crossed that Michael doesn't get
lucky and land a top-three pick,'' Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf said
last week. ``I saw him and told him I would be very upset if he got
lucky and took that pick away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy buffs figure the NBA will rig it so Jordan does get a
top-three pick to help him in his rebuilding of the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Krause is planning on wearing the same clothes he wore last
year, when he came away with the No. 1 pick. He also will have the
same lucky pennies in his pockets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
