</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO STAY IN FIRST, INDIANS NEED FIRST AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians general manager John Hart was sitting in his
office last Thursday with assistant general manager Mark Shapiro
when the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a half-hour, we had three phone calls,'' Shapiro said.
``Boom. Boom. Boom. A bad day for the Tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Three calls, three pitchers on the disabled list. Charles Nagy,
who won 15 games or more in each of the last five seasons, needed
surgery for loose bodies in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Jaret Wright, who just two weeks earlier had pitched what
Shapiro called his best game ever against the Yankees, went on the
DL with a strained muscle in his right shoulder, the same injury
that landed him on the DL twice last season.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthanded reliever Ricardo Rincon went on the DL with a bone
spur in his left elbow. Surgery is likely and he may not be back
for another couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   With Wright and Nagy out, the Indians were forced to call up a
kid pitcher, Paul Rigdon, to make his big-league debut against the
Yankees Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an average fastball and average life,'' Shapiro said,
``but we felt we needed a strike-thrower against those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of spring for the Indians, which is as good
a reason as any to explain why they didn't lock up the American
League Central by Mother's Day, as they customarily do. The Tribe,
considered by many (including yours truly) as the team most likely
to end the Yankees' grip on the World Series, have been beset by
health problems since camp opened in Florida, when new manager
Charlie Manuel was stricken with diverticulitis and missed 11 days
after 8 inches of his colon was removed.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel missed another 15 days while having his colon reattached,
then returned to work Thursday, just in time to hear the bad
tidings about his pitching staff. The Indians already have had
eight players on the disabled list this season, including such key
performers as catcher Sandy Alomar and center fielder Kenny Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this continues a trend for the Tribe. Last season,
even as they ran away with their fifth straight division title,
they had their regular lineup together for only four games.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said the latest setbacks may not be as dire as they
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles wasn't pitching well, so it's good to see there was a
reason for it,'' Shapiro said. ``He's been a pretty consistent, key
guy for us. We think he'll be back around the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaret should be back with no problem before the end of the
month. It's a minor muscle strain. Rincon is a little bit of an
enigma, but this will give some of our young kids a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Star second baseman Robbie Alomar has been bothered with a
sore triceps, Shapiro said, but has been coming around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on a 12-game hitting streak and has been playing pretty
well,'' Shapiro said, agreeing that when the Red Sox were in town
at the start of the month, Alomar clearly was not himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, winners of five of six on their homestand prior to
the arrival of the Yankees, overtook the White Sox for first place
in the division last week. And the recent efforts by pitcher
Bartolo Colon, who was on the DL last month, have added credence to
the argument that with the addition of free agent Chuck Finley,
plus Wright throwing the way he did as a rookie (righthanders were
hitting just .146 against him when he went on the DL), the Indians
have a rotation that can compete with any in the league. And with
veterans Nagy and Dave Burba on the back end, they're deeper than
most.
</P>
<P>
   Colon struck out a dozen Tigers in seven innings last Wednesday,
and after the game, Detroit coach Bill Madlock, the four-time
batting champion, was comparing his stuff to that of Tom Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting on the bench saying he was playing around
until he gets into trouble, then he adds 4-5 miles per hour on his
fastball,'' Madlock said. ``And the way his fastball moves, if he's
throwing 99, it's like 101.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit manager Phil Garner said it was the best game thrown
against the Tigers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bartolo keeps taking it to the next step,'' Shapiro said. ``I
thought he was even better in the start before, against Kansas
City. But Colon, Finley, and Wright, that gives us a formidable
three.''
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest question marks for the Tribe this season? One is
the bullpen, which no longer has Mike Jackson. Steve Karsay is the
closer and Paul Shuey the setup man. Most nights they've been fine.
But on a recent visit to Minnesota, the bullpen blew leads of 5-0
and 8-1 on back-to-back nights.
</P>
<P>
   The other question mark revolves around Manuel, who is a
baseball lifer but a rookie manager, one whose health has hindered
his efforts to put his stamp on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``His health should be a nonissue,'' Shapiro said. ``He looks
better now than he did before the first time he went down. And he
didn't rush back like he did the last time. I told him, `Charlie,
you need to come back as a leader, not as a presence.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the Red Sox adjust their pitching rotation to
the off-day scheduled after Pedro Martinez's scheduled start next
Sunday against the Yankees in The Stadium, the Indians may see
Martinez again in Boston June 8, the makeup date for one of the
rainouts last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' Shapiro said. ``We're professionals. They're
professionals. Hey, the guy has dominated us every time he's
pitched against us. You can't take anything away from the guy. But
what he did was still b.s.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, of course, was referring to the chain of events that
occurred last month, when Martinez came up and in on Einar Diaz,
Nagy responded by throwing at Jose Offerman, and Martinez hit
Alomar with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love guys who pitch inside,'' Shapiro said, ``but you don't
throw at his head. That's his lifeblood. It's like you can
intimidate somebody in business, but you don't try to destroy a
human being. That's not what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mondy, Mondy
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, where the Blue Jays routinely drew 50,000 fans as
recently as seven years ago, SkyDome was less than half-full even
with a marquee attraction like Martinez providing the opposition.
GM Gord Ash took some major hits in the winter for trading former
Cy Young Award winner Pat Hentgen to St. Louis and outfielder Shawn
Green to Los Angeles for outfielder Raul Mondesi, a disgruntled
.253 hitter last season. But Mondesi has been anything but a
problem child for the Blue Jays. If he keeps playing the way he
has, he may wind up being credited for rejuvenating the franchise.
Mondesi began the weekend hitting .292 and was one of four Blue
Jays (with Carlos Delgado, Tony Batista, and Jose Cruz Jr.) with 10
or more home runs. He also was successful on 12 of his first 13
stolen-base attempts. Mondesi is just one of eight players to have
two 30-30 seasons. ``He's been tremendous in the outfield and he's
displayed everything you want to see in the clubhouse,'' said Dave
Stewart, the Blue Jays' assistant general manager. Stewart said he
was not scared by Mondesi's run-ins with Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson or an arrest for driving under the influence after a game.
``I knew him,'' Stewart said. ``For me, when a player gets in a
certain situation, in particular, a bad situation, sometimes the
rules aren't defined. I think that was the case last year in LA for
Mondy. I can't speak for going out after a game for drinks and
being caught. I'm sure everyone has done that, and those kinds of
things I can't make an excuse for, but it's human. But if you have
rules and guidelines that are defined and clear-cut, a player
usually stays within those guidelines. Maybe those guidelines were
not that clear for Mondy there, because he's been perfect here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pedro, then and now
</P>
<P>
   Has Martinez changed in the two-plus seasons since he left
Montreal to become a megastar in Boston? ``No,'' said Red Sox first
base coach Tommy Harper, who served in the same capacity with the
Expos and was close to Martinez in Montreal. ``He's still the same.
He was probably the biggest draw they ever had in Montreal. When he
pitched, we had our biggest crowds. Maybe he didn't get the same
national recognition there that he does now in Boston, but he's
pitching the same. Better now, if you can say that. He's stronger
and he's bigger than he was then.'' In his first year in Boston,
Martinez said he missed the relationships he had in Montreal, where
there were numerous Latin players and his manager, Felipe Alou, was
a fellow Dominican. Now, the Sox clubhouse has more Dominican
players, too _ Wilton Veras, Offerman, and Martinez's brother,
Ramon _ but Harper said that Martinez also learned to adapt. ``I
think he's learned to branch out,'' Harper said. ``In Montreal,
where there were so many Latin players and coaches, it was easy to
connect. But once here, it took people a little time to find out
what kind of person Pedro is. Pedro is Pedro. He has a good time
when he's not pitching. And when he's pitching, he's a different
guy. He's very sensitive, especially about headlines over that
headhunter stuff.'' Harper is one of Martinez's most ardent
defenders. ``This guy is not going to try and hurt people,'' Harper
said. ``Believe me when I tell you that. He's not going to hit
anybody around the head. Those kind of people, Pedro and Randy
Johnson, they know how hard they throw, and they're not going to
throw deliberately at people's heads.'' Harper scoffs at the
suggestion that Martinez was throwing at Diaz. ``If you slow down
the tape,'' Harper said, ``you'll see the rotation of the ball, and
it was rotating toward Diaz, who was moving toward the ball. If he
wanted to hit Diaz, do you think he would have thrown the pitch so
it would be moving from the middle in, instead of just throwing
right at him? What do you think, man, that a guy who throws a 97
mile-an-hour fastball can control it like a ballistic missile? Just
dial it, and it goes right there?'' Harper said that because of his
past reputation, Martinez is singled out. ``Did you see Greg
Vaughn? Two pitches were thrown over his head, and you don't even
know who threw them,'' Harper said, chiding a reporter. ``But if it
had been Pedro, we'd be seeing it on TV over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into the cause
</P>
<P>
   Hear, hear for the Yankees cutting off beer sales in the
bleachers, which had come pretty close to being unfit for human
habitation. How long do you suppose it will be before Friendly
Fenway takes steps in the same direction? But the Dodgers players,
though understandably enraged when a fan grabbed the cap of catcher
Chad Kreuter, made a mistake when they went into the stands last
week at Wrigley Field, escalating a situation that probably could
have been defused relatively quickly by security. ``It's your worst
nightmare, players going into the stands,'' said Cubs manager Don
Baylor. ``They throw beer, they say things, but that's one of those
unwritten rules: Stay out of the stands. If a guy comes onto the
field, that's a different story. If you go into the stands, you're
asking for trouble.'' Dodgers GM Kevin Malone blamed the booze.
``Let's get to the real issue: it's public intoxication,'' Malone
said. ``If they weren't drunk, this wouldn't have happened. It's
not a Cubs problem, it's not a Wrigley Field problem, it's an
industrywide problem.'' . . . Rockies outfielder Larry Walker is on
the disabled list for the seventh time in his 12-year career. He's
expected to miss at least a month with what was described as the
beginning stages of a stress fracture in his elbow. The condition
has been bothering him since mid-April, one reason he has hit just
three home runs. ``Turns out it was a good thing I got a MRI
because from what I've been told, one more throw and maybe I could
have torn the ligament away from the bone,'' said Walker, who won't
pick up a ball for two weeks . . . When Wil Cordero left the
Pirates last week to go to Puerto Rico and wrest custody of his
kids from his estranged wife, Ana, who reportedly was arrested on
drug charges, he was in the midst of a 12-game hitting streak,
longest of his career. Cordero had been vilified earlier in
Pittsburgh for a lack of hustle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
