u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     05-20 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY STRAYED FROM WHAT WAS WORKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there were such a thing as baseball professors, they would
have met Saturday for lunch and bragged about their favorite
students. They would have been bragging about the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   One professor would have gossiped, telling the others that he
believes the Sox have a brighter future than those dull Devil Ray
kids from Tampa. Another professor would have marveled at their
numbers: lowest ERA in the (American League) class, fewest home
runs allowed (33), fewest times grounded into double plays (23),
and most shutouts (6). Another would have talked over them both and
excitedly shared her May attendance records.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 18 games this month,'' she would say, ``the Sox have gone
13-5. They have lost four of those five by one run. This
consistency is remarkable, especially with today's
score-a-touchdown approach to baseball. Now you even see guys like
Jermaine Dye popping homers with ease. Who's next? Jermaine
Jackson?''
</P>
<P>
   They would have entertained themselves a little longer with
feel-good stories. Then there would have been an interruption from
a sour-looking professor with a Sox cap nearly pulled over his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you guys are talking about,'' he would have
barked. ``I was just at Fenway Park watching the Sox play the
Tigers. They lost, 2-1. It was ridiculous! Your textbook students
played as if they were boycotting the books. I've seen more
practicality from Marilyn Manson.''
</P>
<P>
   The angry professor would have been correct. Saturday, the
usually bookish Sox took a day off. They were sloppy with their
detail work. They did not accept the gifts the Tigers tried to give
them. They were as disciplined as 25 students on the last day of
school. They did about 15 things that prevented them from winning
and taking a two-game lead over the Yankees in the AL East. But the
mistake that got the most attention was Brian Daubach's baserunning
lapse in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cost us the game,'' the first baseman said. ``There is no
excuse for that. I took away all our momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach is one of the most intense and aggressive Sox during
games. His first-baseman-as-middle-linebacker image is enhanced by
the thick eye black he smears on his face. It was his
aggressiveness that cost the Sox a run in the fourth, and that's
too bad. Usually, a professional athlete is criticized for being
too passive (I can see you, Pervis Ellison). Daubach will be
criticized by some for being too energetic. Why? Because he ran
when he shouldn't have.
</P>
<P>
   There was one out in the fourth and the score was tied at 1.
Trot Nixon was on third, Daubach was on second, and Carl Everett
was at the plate. Everett hit a long drive to left, deep enough to
score Nixon. It appeared to be headed off the Wall, just out of
Bobby Higginson's reach. Daubach, who is not fast, left second so
he could get an extra step. But Higginson caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
   This wouldn't have been a problem on a normal Sox day. Nixon
tagged and went home. He didn't run as hard as he could have _ some
press box comedians said he Trotted _ but it wouldn't have made a
difference on most days. Nixon didn't know that Daubach had
ventured too far from second. His back was turned to Higginson, who
threw a strike from The Wall to second. The throw arrived in second
baseman Jose Macias's mitt before Nixon arrived home. So, what
would have been an easy run was taken away.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the game, Daubach thought to himself that he
needed to do something to make up for his error. He couldn't do it.
He was sullen long after the play. He certainly didn't run well on
the bases, but there is no way he cost the Sox the game by himself.
It was a class project.
</P>
<P>
   There was Tim Wakefield's bad day. First, the pitcher allowed a
monstrous home run to Juan Gonzalez. I'm not kidding when I say
that I didn't see the ball land. If I had to guess, I'd say it's
somewhere in Cambridge right now. The solo homer gave Detroit its
second _ and winning _ run. Later, Wakefield had to leave the game
after being hit in the inner thigh by a Macias line drive.
</P>
<P>
   There was Everett's bad day. He was up three times with runners
in scoring position and couldn't produce an RBI. In the top of the
fourth, he played a Gonzalez Wall ball perfectly and would have
thrown the slugger out at second had he thrown the ball well. He
didn't. There was Pete Schourek's bad luck (four hits, one earned
run, no decision).
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to sit here and analyze the mistakes. Should Nixon
have been running harder? Should Daubach have known better? Should
Jimy Williams have sent Jason Varitek in to pinch hit for Donnie
Sadler?
</P>
<P>
   So many questions. But the truth is that the Sox are like most
good students. They have been so efficient that they have spoiled
their observers. Sometimes they get in their favorite chaise chair,
recline, and zone out when they shouldn't be zoning out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't robots out there,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. They're not robots. They are baseball intellectuals.
They'll resume their normal studies Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
