<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-RAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY WINS ONE FOR IRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In cold, overcast conditions, the reigning
champions of the rival Indy Racing League and Championship Auto
Racing Teams waged a heated battle Saturday for the pole position
for next Sunday's 84th running of the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 1/2 hours after CART champion Juan Montoya gained
temporary control of the pole with a blistering four-lap average of
223.372 miles per hour, IRL champion Greg Ray wrested it away. Ray
helped the IRL hold serve _ and save face _ on its home track with
an average of 223.471, bolstered by a fast lap of 223.658 on his
first of four tours around the Brickyard's 2.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting that, in a year in which CART owner Chip
Ganassi and his dominant Team Target Ganassi, winners of the last
four CART titles, were warmly received in their return to Indy, the
champions of both series duked it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep harping on this CART-IRL issue, but it's not a big
issue to me,'' said Ray, who waved off his first qualifying
attempt, then overcame a serious vibration in his
Oldsmobile-powered Dallara fielded by owner John Menard, who
captured his third Indy 500 pole in the last six years. ``It's just
nice to have a lot of good drivers here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray ruined Montoya's bid to become the third race rookie to win
the pole. Walt Faulkner won the pole in 1950 and finished seventh,
and Teo Fabi was the pole-sitter in 1983. Rookie Tony Stewart
started from the pole in 1996 after inheriting from teammate Scott
Brayton, who was killed in a crash during practice.
</P>
<P>
   In securing his first Indy pole, Ray, 32, of Plano, Texas, joins
Montoya, the precocious 24-year-old from Bogota, and A.J. Foyt
driver Eliseo Salazar, 45, of Santiago, Chile, who turned the
fastest lap of the month (223.964) during Saturday morning's
practice session, in the front row of the 33-car field.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 23 drivers qualified on the first day of time trials,
including 19-year-old rookie Sarah Fisher, the youngest woman ever
to make the race. Qualifying will conclude Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The four laps of qualifying here are the ultimate speed
event,'' said Ray, who started second in his previous two Indy
500s. ``I wish it was as easy as just holding on. You've got to
drive it for all it's worth. It's an event all itself. You do
everything you can to go fast. Once tonight comes, you put it out
of your mind. Four laps is one thing, 200 laps is another. You've
got to be careful on qualifying day. You want to get up to speed as
quick as possible without going over the line, especially on a day
like this when tire temperatures are 50, 60, or even 90 degrees
below their optimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray aborted his first attempt, on cold tires and a colder track,
when he realized on the first turn his car wasn't capable of
challenging for the pole. ``It was pushing way too much, and if you
pull off the throttle there's no way to get a pole,'' he said.
``It's hard to get heat up in big staggered tires, and on the first
lap I was committed into Turn 1 at 223 miles per hour and the car
went straight. I had to back off to keep it off the wall, and so
there was no point in continuing the run at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lyn St. James waved off her first attempt, the brash
Montoya took the track and proceeded to blister it, ripping off a
warmup lap of 221.626. Montoya then came around with an even hotter
223.636 on his first go-round, the fastest of his four laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy,'' Montoya said. ``It was very consistent
with all the laps in 223. I like the car. It's a really friendly
car _ fast and friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ray presented his car for a second qualifying attempt later
in the afternoon, with track and weather conditions virtually
unchanged. The only difference was the vibration his car had
developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was in the car, laughing to myself, `What else?' '' Ray
said. ``I was running a car that had no downforce, it was 65
degrees and it's cold and slippery on the track. Now all of a
sudden I've got a vibration. What can you do? I just kept my foot
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for our team and it's great for our sponsors, and
that's my job. For me personally, (winning the pole) means a lot.
It would mean a hell of a lot more to drink milk, though.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ray knows that is a Memorial Day tradition reserved only for
the Indy 500 winner, not its pole-sitter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
