<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BURR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT BURR, 78, ACTOR FAMED FOR SHAKESPEARE ROLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Burr, a stage actor who played many of
Shakespeare's most famous roles, died on May 13 in Los Angeles. He
was 78 and lived in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was emphysema, said his son, Robert Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With a chiseled jaw and a sturdy physique, Burr was a top-rated
amateur boxer _ he attended Colgate University on a boxing
scholarship _ before turning in the gloves for a more erudite
pursuit. Burr, a World War II veteran, began acting after the war
and made his Broadway debut in 1951 as a chorus member in the
musical ``The Cradle Will Rock.'' His career was sidetracked
briefly later that year when he left to fly helicopters as a Marine
pilot in the Korean War, where he survived three crash landings.
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning to civilian life, Burr plunged into acting,
appearing in supporting and understudy roles in productions of
``King Lear'' with Orson Welles, ``Romeo and Juliet'' with Olivia
de Havilland, and ``The Andersonville Trial'' with George C. Scott.
Between acting jobs, he supported himself and his family of five by
working in a frozen food factory in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   But in June 1964, Burr's life suddenly changed from that of a
bit player to a leading man. The play was ``Hamlet,'' which was
having two productions that summer; one, on Broadway, directed by
Sir John Gielgud, with Richard Burton as Hamlet, and a second at
the Delacorte Theater in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, Burr was Burton's understudy, an assignment that
looked to be an easy job, as Burton prided himself on never missing
a performance. On the morning of June 3, however, Burton woke up
suffering from an abscess on his tonsils and had to bow out of the
matinee, causing a panic at the box office as theatergoers rushed
to exchange their tickets. Those who stayed, however, watched as
Burr stepped into the role and made it his own.
</P>
<P>
   The audience gave Burr a standing ovation, and the producer,
Alexander H. Cohen, made a curtain speech lauding the actor's
bravery. After returning, Burton also addressed the audience at his
performance, saying Burr had performed ``one of most difficult
tasks in acting.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, later that same summer, Burr would again step into
the role of Hamlet, in Central Park, after Alfred Ryder came down
with laryngitis. On three hours of rehearsal, Burr took over the
role, and never let it go: the producer, Joseph Papp, decided to
keep Burr as Hamlet, starting a nasty feud between the producer and
Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   The performance made Burr's reputation, and the next year Papp
rewarded him with the title role in ``Coriolanus.'' ( Burr's son
Robert played Coriolanus' son.) Critics again applauded his
performance, with Howard Taubman of The New York Times calling Burr
``a performer of virile power and smashing intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr went on to appear in more Shakespeare in Central Park,
including the title role in ``Titus Andronicus,'' as well as major
roles in ``King John,'' ``King Lear'' and ``Henry IV, Part II.'' In
1975, he returned to ``Hamlet,'' this time playing Claudius,
alongside Sam Waterson, Ruby Dee and John Lithgow.
</P>
<P>
   Burr also dabbled in television and film, appearing in several
soap operas and opposite Shirley MacLaine in 1972 in ``The
Possession of Joel Delaney.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son Robert of Hewitt, N.J., Burr is survived
by his wife, the actress and director Jacqueline Britton; three
daughters, Juliet of Tarzana, Calif., Elizabeth of Los Angeles and
Laura of New York, and another son, Britt, also of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 2244EDT &QL; 
