<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS BEAT DEVILS, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils were searching for someone to
regain the confidence that was seriously shaken after allowing
eight goals in two consecutive losses. Instead, their confidence
suffered another blow Saturday night when Martin Brodeur was again
below his usually high standards, allowing another soft goal.
</P>
<P>
   That goal, scored by Mark Recchi, helped the Flyers to a 3-1
triumph and a two-game lead in the four-of-seven-game series. The
Flyers can eliminate the Devils from the Eastern Conference finals
on Monday night in Philadelphia, where the Devils won the opening
game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Many Devils were looking for redemption for losing Game 3 two
nights ago, but none more than Brodeur. But Brodeur never reached
the level to inspire his teammates. He made a couple of brilliant
saves, and 18 over all, but none timely enough in a game of
paramount importance.
</P>
<P>
   After Bobby Holik's second-period goal against Brian Boucher
matched Recchi's goal in the first, the Flyers broke the tie on
Craig Berube's deflection with 7 minutes 2 seconds left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   They secured their third consecutive victory in the series on
Simon Gagne's goal with 3:20 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some nights you have it, some nights you don't have it,''
Brodeur said Friday after a team meeting to watch videotape of Game
3, in which he allowed 4 goals on 21 shots in a game he called ``my
worst in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur did not have it two nights ago, and he did not have it
in the opening period Saturday night, either. He was responsible
for Recchi's sixth goal in the playoffs, which put the Flyers in
the lead with 3:53 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to clear the puck from near his goal, which has been his
strength, Brodeur gave the puck to Gagne in the left corner to the
right of Brodeur. With Brodeur on his way back to the goal, Gagne
took a shot from a sharp angle that Recchi deflected under
Brodeur's right arm. Judging by Brodeur's reaction on the play, he
appeared to be in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Recchi's goal stood until 12:13 into the second period, when
Keith Primeau of the Flyers turned the puck over in Philadelphia's
zone. Primeau's errant pass went to Sergei Brylin alone in the
slot. Brylin gave it to Randy McKay, who gave it back to Brylin for
a pass to Holik, who beat Boucher with a wrist shot from the slot
for his second goal in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The game became the fans' delight and the coaches' nightmare for
several minutes after Holik's goal. There was wide-open, end-to-end
action for several minutes before the teams settled down and played
positional hockey for the rest of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur also took the first penalty of the game, tripping Berube
behind his goal, but the Devils and Brodeur escaped unscathed from
the disadvantage. It meant the Devils had allowed just one goal on
41 manpower advantages for the opposition in the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
