<HEADER>
A1363 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-COLONIAL-LEDE-TEX     05-20 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINK ATTACKS COLONIAL, LEAVES FOES IN DUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Stewart Cink arrived Saturday morning
to finish his second round at the MasterCard Colonial, he saw
green-light, full-throttle conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The course, made soft by Friday rains that had postponed play,
was gleaming in warm sunlight, and the wind that had buffeted the
course Thursday was lying low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was there to be attacked,'' he said of Colonial's 7,080
yards, where he had fought the wind and rain to stand at 1 under
par when play was suspended Friday. He still had 13 holes to play
to finish his second round and was six behind Davis Love III, who
was among the 53 of the 106-man field to beat the rain Friday to
finish his second round at 7 under for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But no one took more advantage of Colonial's vulnerability
Saturday than Cink, who scored a ringer on the Horrible Horseshoe
when he birdied Nos. 3, 4 and 5 during a five-consecutive birdie
streak in the morning when he finished his second round with a 64.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a 21/2-hour break, Cink continued his roll with a
5-under 65 in the afternoon to race away from an early rush-hour
traffic jam to take a three-shot lead over Davis Love III with a
54-hole, 11-under 199 total.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot ride in Sunday's final round of the $3.3 million
tournament could provide a $594,000 present for Cink, who turns 27
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-one holes ... that's a lot of golf in one day, and it's
hot,'' said Cink, the 1997 PGA Tour rookie of the year who won the
MCI Classic the second week of April.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the flip side, though, it was a good day to come out with
your good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Cink had brandished his ``good stuff'' in the morning when he
started his drive to the top by rolling in the five consecutive
birdies, including the three at the horseshoe holes of 3, 4 and 5
that he says are the three hardest consecutive holes on the PGA
Tour. row like that. It's the anchor of the whole course,'' he
said. The key was hitting the fairways at the 476-yard par-4 third
and the 470-yard par-4 fifth to set up 20- and 8-foot birdie putts
and ``sinking a 50-footer'' on the 229-yard par-3 fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, he bogeyed No. 3, but other challengers,
including Love and Phil Mickelson, stumbled, too _ Love with a
bogey and Mickelson with a double-bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Among others giving chase before running into an assortment of
potholes included David Toms, who completed his second round
Saturday morning, carding a 66 to tie Love for the second-round
lead. Toms shot a 2-over 72 in the afternoon and is at 5 under.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples made a move, moving into a tie for the lead at 7
under when he birdied No. 6 but finished at 6 under. It wasn't long
before the rearview mirror included Mike Weir, Jeff Sluman, Rocco
Mediate and Scott Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap (67) finished one behind Love at 203, and Sluman (67),
Couples (68), Mediate (69) and Weir (69) are at 204.
</P>
<P>
   At one time on the front nine, Love, Toms, Mediate and Cink were
tied at 7 under, four others were within one shot of the lead,
three others were within two shots and five others were within
three shots.
</P>
<P>
   Those who veered out of sight included Mickelson, who was two
behind after five holes at 5 under, but who fell to 2 under before
rallying to finish with a 70 and finishing at 5 under.
</P>
<P>
   Cink, a 6-foot-4 Georgia Tech graduate, managed to avoid any big
bumps, mainly because he said his iron play has been exceptional.
He birdied Nos. 2, 7, 9, 10, 12 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of birdie opportunities,'' he said. ``But I'm
not going to think about when I tee off (in the final round). I'll
just keep attacking.''
</P>
<P>
   It will help his confidence, he said, that he can reflect on the
65 he shot in the final round to win the MCI Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 65 came at a better time because it was the last day. I
still have 18 holes to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It helps, too, that he's on a course he believes is one of the
best ``in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you pretty much have to fit your tee shots around the
trees ... and the slopes are all where they're supposed to be. I
think it separates the true players out here when you have to go
both ways off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he hopes he's one of them. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
