<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COLON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBEN D. COLON, 76, FOUNDER OF A CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Ruben Dario Colon, who founded one of the first
Lutheran churches in New York City to conduct services in Spanish,
died May 5 in Orlando, Fla. He was 76 and lived in Sebring, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was lymphatic cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Colon was chairman of the Puerto Rican Community Development
Project Inc., an antipoverty program for Hispanics in the 1960s,
and was appointed New York Police Department chaplain in 1988, the
first Hispanic to hold the post.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Rio Grande, P.R., he was ordained a Baptist minister in
1950. He worked for seven years as chaplain of the Mariner's Church
of the New York Port Society. He became a Lutheran in 1959 and
founded Resurrection Church, which held services throughout the
city before finding a permanent home in the South Bronx in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 53 years, Ramonita Orabona de
Colon; a sister, Lydia Colon de Rodriguez of Bayamon, P.R.; two
brothers, Eliezer Colon of Bayamon, and Agustin Colon of Rio
Piedras, P.R.; a daughter, Damaris Colon de Corchado of San Juan,
P.R.; two sons, Ruben Dario Colon Jr. of Columbus, Ga., and Levi
Colon of Brooklyn; and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
