<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-20 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1380 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     05-20 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 28)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; REPORTING VIETNAM: American Journalism, 1959-1975 &LR;  Library of
America, $17.95. This collection, culled from two larger volumes of
writing about the Vietnam War, includes the work of correspondents
as diverse as Hunter S. Thompson, David Halberstam, Michael Herr
and Doris Kearns, and is mainly concerned with the campaign waged
in the field, not the one at home. The pages are filled with
``pain, anger, sadness, failure and the despair that accompanies
the recognition that suffering will never be redeemed,'' Thomas
Powers wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999 of the
two-volume edition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A DANGEROUS FRIEND &LR; , by Ward Just (Houghton Mifflin, $13), is a
novel set in Vietnam in 1965. Its protagonist is a well-meaning
American aid worker whose efforts to do ``more good than harm'' run
astray when he tries to foster his moral and political values in a
land vastly different from his own. ``Just has a veteran war
reporter's eye for the telling detail,'' James McManus wrote last
year. ``He succeeds in evoking the dense, tactile weave of life in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIRST WORLD WAR &LR;  By John Keegan. Vintage, $16. The eminent
British military historian demystifies World War I by conveying the
feelings of the participants and explaining how it started, how it
was waged, why the Allies won and what its far-reaching
significance was for the century. His account, selected by the
editors of The New York Times Book Review as one of the best books
of 1999, ``is elegantly written, clear, detailed and omniscient,''
Tony Judt wrote. ``As a narrative it is outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PITY OF WAR &LR; , by Niall Ferguson (Basic Books, $17), takes a
contrarian view of the war's causes, maintaining that had Britain
kept out, the Germans would have won but the world would have been
spared much of the grief that followed 1918. Last year the reviewer
V.R. Berghahn, called this ``an illuminating synthesis of current
knowledge'' with ``plenty of fresh information and challenging
ideas on the conflict's most important aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE GREAT WAR AND MODERN MEMORY &LR; , by Paul Fussell (Oxford
University, $14.95), which won a National Book Award when it was
first published in 1975, the war is portrayed as a profound
cultural event that in its carnage spelled the end of innocence and
reshaped the modern imagination. Frank Kermode wrote that the
result is a ``skillful and compassionate'' study of the war and
``an important contribution to our understanding of how we came to
make it part of our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VERDUN &LR; , by Jules Romains (Prion, $17.95), is a fictional
re-creation of the battle in 1916 in which more than 500,000
Germans and French were killed or wounded. ``Through the minds of a
skillfully chosen group of soldiers, officers and fighting units,
we see both the general character and the momentary progress'' of
the clash, Gilbert Highet said in 1939. ``The composition of this
battle piece is one of the greatest technical achievements in the
history of the novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HITLER. 1889-1936: Hubris &LR;  By Ian Kershaw. Norton, $21.95. In
chronicling Hitler's remarkable rise from obscurity, a history
professor tries to explain how Germany came to embrace the
leadership of a social outcast and beer-hall agitator. ``Kershaw
successfully illuminates the strange and at times ecstatic dance in
which Hitler and Germany engaged,'' Walter Reich wrote in 1999. He
``is able to clarify, perhaps better than any biographer who
preceded him, what made Hitler's dictatorial power possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CRUEL SEA &LR; , by Nicholas Monsarrat (Burford, $18.95), is a
1951 novel about combat in the North Atlantic between British
escort forces and Nazi U-boats. ``Its vivid action scenes, survival
episodes and smooth writing sustain the book at a high level of
excitement,'' W.J. Lederer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VILLAGE OF A MILLION SPIRITS: A Novel of the Treblinka
Uprising &LR; , by Ian MacMillan (Penguin, $12.95), is a harrowing
account of the daily operations of the infamous Treblinka
concentration camp in Poland, and the 1943 revolt by hundreds of
Jewish prisoners. The ``shifting tableaux of horror and
helplessness in the camp are devastating,'' Zofia Smardz wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKOUT: The Chosin Reservoir Campaign, Korea 1950 &LR;  By Martin
Russ. Penguin, $14.95. In November 1950, Chinese forces opened an
attack on U.S. troops in North Korea, ending Gen. Douglas
MacArthur's ``home by Christmas'' offensive and setting the stage
for a brilliantly executed withdrawal operation by three surrounded
Marine units. This ``engrossing account'' of the campaign relies on
the ``vivid, at times powerful'' recollections of ground-level
combatants, Ronald H. Spector wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOVEMBER 1916: The Red Wheel/Knot II &LR;  By Aleksandr
Solzhenitsyn. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $17. This huge, overstuffed
novel is set during the Great War in the months just before the
Bolshevik Revolution, when ordinary Russians were beginning to feel
that the old system had let them down. Solzhenitsyn ``achieves
something exceedingly rare among novelists dealing with history,''
John Bayley wrote last year. ``He makes the reader realize that
anything can happen at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued the opening volume in the
author's historical cycle,  &UR; AUGUST 1914: The Red Wheel/Knot I &LR; 
($25), a close study of the military fiascos of imperial Russia as
witnessed by several groups of characters. In 1989, Irving Howe
found this to be a flawed work but said there are ``some good
pages'' nonetheless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-00 2351EDT &QL; 
