u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      05-20 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL HAS MANY REASONS TO REMAIN WITH DETROIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grant Hill has been visiting team employees at the Palace of
Auburn Hills, talking often with Joe Dumars, a Pistons executive
and former teammate, and basically enjoying life in Detroit while
he recovers from foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   None of this guarantees that Hill, an All-Star forward, will
remain a Piston in the off-season. But the notion that he is fed up
with the franchise and wants to relocate soon is hardly accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Lon Babby, Hill's agent, has said Hill plans to visit other
teams when he exercises a clause in his contract to become a free
agent in less than two months. Unless his feelings about leaving
change quickly, Hill will most likely sign a one-year deal with
Detroit for $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   After the 2000-1 season, he will have seven years of experience,
which could help him secure a deal worth more than $100 million
from the organization and about $95 million from another team. If
Hill does not sign for one season, he can now qualify for only an
$83 million deal from Detroit and about a $76 million deal
elsewhere, based on his six years of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who along with Shaquille O'Neal has taken over Michael
Jordan's endorsement throne, has often said money is one of the
smallest considerations in his decision. He desperately wants to
play on an elite team. He is also proud enough not to want to have
the lasting image of the Hill era in Detroit of an injured All-Star
kicking his foot in frustration during a first-round sweep by
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He believes in Dumars' ability to find the right people. The
outside possibility that the Pistons can lure Jalen Rose home to
Michian and away from Indiana has also piqued Hill's interest.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, with the Pistons in turmoil after the firing
of Coach Doug Collins, Hill told a confidant he could see himself
playing in New York. Who knows if the Knicks, if unsatisfied with
their performance in the playoffs, would try to upgrade by trying
to move either Latrell Sprewell or Allan Houston for the right
player?
</P>
<P>
   Hill is one of the top four commodities in the National
Basketball Association, in the class of O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Tim
Duncan. Unless the Pistons' hand is forced, the idea that they
would accept anything less than one of the top 10 players in the
league for Hill is disrespecting the intelligence of their front
office.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if salivating executives from other teams have not
contributed mightily to the Hill-is-unhappy rumors spreading
throughout the league. If he stays, it is not as if his value will
go down or he is an aging veteran trying to find a championship
team before it is too late. The feeling is, Hill will give Detroit
one more season to build a bona fide contender. But not any
longer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POSTSEASON FRENZY
</P>
<P>
   A Western Conference general manager recently heard an
intriguing rumor: that Sonics point guard Gary Payton, fed up with
playing for Seattle, was going to issue a trade demand Friday night
on TNT. ``And if Duncan bolts for Orlando, all of a sudden, we're
in good shape,'' the general manager said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Payton did not go on the air and ask to be traded, just as Tim
Duncan was not about to leave San Antonio and sign with the Orlando
Magic. But such is the climate this time of year, when every
eliminated team starts to wonder how it can make itself better.
</P>
<P>
   Some other scuttlebutt is making the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas is supposedly coveted by every team with a vacant
head-coaching position. That may be stretching the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Byron Scott now appears to be Atlanta's No. 1
candidate, and that is if he does not wind up in Indiana. Thomas
would like to coach the Pacers, but that will probably not happen
if Larry Bird remains with the team in some capacity. Bird prefers
Rick Carlisle, his longtime friend and Pacers assistant, to take
over.
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle, by the way, has an in for the Vancouver job. He was on
Chuck Daly's staff in New Jersey. Daly was recently hired by the
Grizzlies as a consultant. (Read: Dick Versace needs help hiring a
coach.)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' best bet may be with the Nets, who want a marquee name.
</P>
<P>
   That does not explain why Kenny Smith, studio analyst for TNT,
said the Nets were interested in talking to him. At any rate, as
Thomas or Doc Rivers could tell Smith, why get genuine coaching
experience on a bench when you can increase your profile taking
other coaches apart on television?
</P>
<P>
   Payton may move from Seattle, but not unless another team will
give up comparable value. The Knicks will not tear up their team to
acquire Payton, no matter how badly they appear to need an elite
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We value him so highly, it's hard for me to envision we could
get back what he means to us,'' said Wally Walker, Seattle's
general manager. ``We'll always listen, but our respect for Gary's
talent level would prevent us from probably doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando's John Gabriel was not selected executive of the year by
his peers last week because the Magic did not make the playoffs
this season. Beyond having enough salary cap room to sign two free
agents to the maximum contracts, the Magic has a good chance of
securing the Nos. 3, 10 and 13 picks in Sunday's draft lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Michael Jordan has got to be hoping for a good bounce
of the Ping-Pong balls in the lottery hopper. If the Washington
Wizards receive one of the top three picks, they get to keep it
while giving Chicago an unconditional first-round pick next season.
If they fall below No. 3, the pick automatically reverts to Chicago
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Chris Webber, eight years after he was drafted,
will be responsible for the maneuvering of at least two of the top
seven picks. The Magic's first pick is courtesy of Golden State,
which gave up the pick when it traded Webber for Anfernee Hardaway
on draft day 1992.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Washington's pick is tied into their acquiring
Webber in 1994. That is the same pick the Warriors held the Wizards
hostage over when Jordan tried to hire Rod Higgins at the end of
January.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a time-release bomb. The Wizards and the Warriors are
still suffering from their Webber association.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where it drafts, the Magic is high on Iowa State's
Marcus Pfizer, whose scoring savvy dwarfs any other
offensive-minded player in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   A RILEY-RIDER COMBO
</P>
<P>
   No matter how far Pat Riley takes Miami this season, the Heat
need some sort of offensive upgrade next season. Having tried to
acquire players like Mitch Richmond and Latrell Sprewell, Riley and
Randy Pfund, the Heat general manager, understand the need for more
point production.
</P>
<P>
   That is where America's No. 1 trouble-making basketball player
comes in. Imagine, Isaiah Rider cloaked in Miami red and black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would consider it, with certain conditions,'' Riley said
recently, regarding the possibility of acquiring the oft-troubled
but incredibly talented shooting guard. ``You just never know. I
believe people can change and somewhere they really do see the
light and they see their career passing right in front of them. I
don't know. We'll come to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said acquiring a player like Rider, whose penchant for
being tardy and whose play to the beat of his own drum are among
his litany of transgressions, would depend on how well a player
like Rider adapted to playing for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for giving players opportunities, but when they come
here they know there are no compromises there,'' Riley said. ``And
especially with somebody who has his track record.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said a bigger problem than Rider's fitting in might be
changing people's perception about him. ``A guy like that, he's on
call all the time,'' Riley said. ``He's on notice all the time.
That even creates even more pressure. He can't even then be an
innocent human being, so if he does something innocently wrong,
he's measured. That's what he's created for himself. Those players
have to be above and beyond reproach now. They have to at least
have to try to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley has a reputation for getting malcontents to buy into his
system, but you wonder if he might not be going too far with Rider,
who was released from the Atlanta Hawks earlier this season after a
series of team violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control the injury factor, but you can control the
personality factor,'' Riley said. ``You don't let anybody get into
the way of that. You're always going to have conflict. There's an
ongoing tension in this league between coaches and players. It's
always going to be there. Because my job _ and this is going to
sound cliche _ my job is to get those guys to do the things they
don't want to do in order to achieve what it is we all said we
want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
