<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, May 21. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MEXICO-BORDER (AGUA PRIETA, Sonora) _ The furor over the ``hunt for
illegals'' in southern Arizona is receiving enormous attention in
Mexico, where it has been front-page news all last week and has
been given dramatic coverage in national television reports. ``This
is pure racism at its worst,'' said Mario Hernandez Olivas, a
supervisor at the Mexican office of migration. ``All the Mexicans
do is walk on the land. They don't even take bread or tortillas
from those people, yet they are being treated like they are
criminals.'' Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
REFORM-BUCHANAN _ Pat Buchanan, the presumptive presidential
candidate for the Reform Party, on Saturday said he supports in
theory a work-permit program that would give some kind of temporary
legal status to migrant workers who now cross the border illegally.
Buchanan was in town to address the Arizona convention of the
Reform Party, which elected eight members and eight alternates to
attend the national convention in Long Beach, Calif., in August. &QL; 
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHELTER-WOMEN _ Faith House, a domestic violence shelter that is
one of the Valley's oldest charities, is on the brink of insolvency
because of apparent financial mismanagement. The Glendale charity
opened an elaborate $2.8 million shelter for abused women in
January. But three months after it opened, the shelter ran out of
money and was shut down. An interim director brought in to sort out
Faith House finances found an organization so poorly managed that
some of its books may never be reconciled. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COL _ Dear Commissar Hull: I write now to be telling you
that I am pleased as borscht that in state of Arizona the law still
treats communists in a way to make late Sen. Joseph McCarthy most
proud. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and `K''
categories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
