<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ FOILS BLAZERS' STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _The spotlight of the Western Conference finals was
flipped on Saturday afternoon, and the glare suddenly,
embarrassingly, illuminated every blemish in the Lakers'
complexion. Every abrasion, every scar, every hairy mole, exposed
to the world.
</P>
<P>
   The weak bench. The powerless power forwards. And the go-to guy
who can't be gone to in the fourth quarter because he can't shoot
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   All of it, showcased and exploited by the Portland Trail
Blazers. But the Lakers found some beauty in their own presumed
shortcomings and forged a win out of their weaknesses, as they
survived hack-a-Shaq and other indignities for a 109-94 victory in
Game 1 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal was fouled intentionally 12 times in the final
5 minutes, 27 seconds as the Blazers tried to scrap their way back
from a double-digit deficit. But O'Neal made 12 of 25 free throws
in that span to secure a win that was satisfying for the Lakers, if
not altogether enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the arena, including both benches, were sitting
there watching a free-throw exhibition,'' groused Rick Fox.
``They'll go to any length to find a way to win. And is that wrong?
Maybe not, but it's absolutely boring to watch, or be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, time-consuming - the game lasted 2 hours, 48 minutes. And
the duel between Portland coach Mike Dunleavy and O'Neal also
detracted from other, more aesthetic impressions left by the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   They showed they could win with bench play, as Robert Horry
scored 12 points to lead a 28-point effort from the reserves. They
withstood constant defensive pressure on O'Neal, but he pulled
through for 41 points (13 on foul shots), 11 rebounds, seven
assists and five blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   And they won despite a mere 13 points from Kobe Bryant, limited
by aggressive double teams and a bit of foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the lasting image was not of a 94-foot game of movement.
Just a 19-foot game between a coach and an opposing center with one
glaring flaw in his game.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed six free throws in a row but settled down to make
seven straight, often accompanied by a glare at Dunleavy. With each
swish, O'Neal's confidence and the volume of the crowd increased.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, he had made 13 of 27 free throws in the
game and set NBA playoff records for attempts in a quarter (25) and
a half (27).
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of knew that they were going to do that,'' O'Neal said.
``I think it's the ultimate respect to my game when there's two
7-foot, 330 (pound) people playing back-to-back, but one had to
have two of his teammates come down and help him. I just think it's
a total respect for my game.''
</P>
<P>
   The other 7-footer was Arvydas Sabonis, who went scoreless in 33
minutes against O'Neal but supplied four of the fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he handled it quite well,'' Lakers coach Phil
Jackson said. ``It's easy to get down, but he stayed relatively
positive, his teammates gave him support. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tactic you have to deal with. Mike is playing
percentages, and the odds are in (his) favor. ... But it stops the
ballgame, and it's tough to run sets every time you come down, and
if your defense gets set, you're pretty good sometimes. And I think
that helped us play some defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, down 24 in the first half, had pulled to within 12
points when the hacking began. Even with O'Neal missing, they never
got closer than nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq stepped up and made the foul shots, and that made
everything look kind of stupid,'' said Scottie Pippen, who led the
Blazers with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if we get down in a game, I don't think it's a bad
strategy,'' Dunleavy said. ``From my standpoint, had we scored
better, we would have put ourselves in a chance to win the game. So
I can't not do what I think from a strategic standpoint is the
right thing to do because people are going to miss their cocktail
reservation or something.''
</P>
<P>
   But the game was rarely in doubt in the second half, despite a
Laker letdown in the third quarter that reduced a 21-point halftime
lead to a 13-point game by the start of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shot 53.5 percent for the game and made 9 of 19 shots
from 3-point range, including 8 of 12 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers adjusted to slow down the Lakers' perimeter game
in the second half, leaving O'Neal to score 27 of the Lakers' 46
points in the third and fourth. Bonzi Wells came off the bench to
score all 17 of his points in the second half to lead the Blazers
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned the game into more of an uptempo, they pressured a
little more full-court, got the ball out of the hands of the
guards, and we didn't settle into our offensive sets,'' Fox said.
``That's why Shaq obviously did most of the scoring for us. They
decided, `Enough of this unsung bench coming off and hurting us,
let's go guard them,' and then Shaquille was able to do his
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
